<HEADER>
A4859 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SKATING-WOMEN-HNS     02-14 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SKATING-WOMEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Kwan overwhelms inexperienced field
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SALT LAKE CITY _ She was almost perfect. Before her last jump, the
question wasn't so much whether there would be any 6.0s, but
whether she had left room for anything less.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, almost would have to do, though Michelle Kwan
didn't seem to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when that happens, you get back up quick,'' she said,
recounting her one late mistake with a smile. ``What if the judges
blink?''
</P>
<P>
   If they had, they might have missed about the only flaw in
another championship performance from figure skating's current
leading lady.
</P>
<P>
   Suffering a late spill on a triple lutz, the 18-year-old
Californian nevertheless claimed her third United States Figure
Skating Association championship Saturday night at the Delta Center
without much of a threat from a young and thin field.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Nari Nam, 13, from Irvine, Calif., finished second,
followed by Angela Nikodinov, 18, of San Pedro, Calif. But the
world team that will travel to Helsinki, Finland, next month will
look a little different because Nam is ineligible to go because of
her age.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, that opens a spot for another 13-year-old,
fourth-place finisher Sarah Hughes of Great Neck, N.Y. Hughes is
eligible because of her second-place finish in the recent junior
world championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really worried about not going to worlds,'' Nam said.
``I'm just happy I skated my best.''
</P>
<P>
   Her coach, veteran John Nicks, was less diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a travesty of age discrimination,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the fall Saturday night, Kwan was the runaway winner,
earning seven 5.9s for artistic merit from the nine judges.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't quite as emphatic a statement as the eight 6.0s she
pulled in winning the title in Philadelphia a year earlier, but she
was well on her way to duplicating the feat before the lutz went
awry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had it,'' she said with a shrug. ``I'm not sure
what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter. The defending champion was in good form otherwise,
and she enjoyed every minute of it, particularly a triple
toe/triple toe early in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to do that,'' she said. ``I haven't done it in
a year or more.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Andrea Gardiner, who suffered a broken hip in July,
struggled again after finishing 17th in Tuesday night's short
program. Hoping for a top-10 finish, the 18-year-old Robert E. Lee
High School senior had to settle for 15th in the long program and
15th overall.
</P>
<P>
   The basically lost season will be chalked up as a learning
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot from this competition,'' she said. ``What I
need to do before I go out to skate just little things.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardiner, the 1997 national junior champion and eighth-place
finisher in last year's seniors, heads back to Houston today to
pick up training, finish high school and ``come back stronger next
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2002 Winter Olympic Games in Salt Lake City remain a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a rough year,'' her coach, Megan Faulkner, said.
``She's never been injured before. It's a really hard thing to come
back from.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some letdowns here this week, and as she said, most of
them were mental. The nerves took over a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwan, by contrast, was under little pressure here. To no one's
surprise, the 1998 Olympic silver medalist and defending world
champion was by far the class of the field. And while another shot
at Olympic gold is three years away, it clearly was on Kwan's mind
as she finished her performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, when I looked up, I thought, `Wow. In a couple of
years, this is where they're going to have the 2002 Olympics,'''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   This time out, at least one of the hopefuls looked at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
