<HEADER>
A4861 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BASEBALLECONOMICS     02-14 1810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL </SLUG>
 ECONOMICS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Dismantling a winner becomes baseball's economic Catch-22
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ALAN TRUEX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're a baseball fan in most major-league cities, you may
believe the worst thing that can happen to your favorite team is
that it wins a pennant. Nothing destroys a team faster.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be winners tended to stay together; it was the losers
who rebuilt. But in the last two years, the Florida Marlins and San
Diego Padres went for the ring and then when they had it, they
broke up.
</P>
<P>
   It was not romantic, it was economic. And not especially
historic. Baseball champions have been breaking up as far back as
1915, when Connie Mack dismantled the Philadelphia Athletics after
their fourth American League pennant in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Finley tore apart his powerful Oakland A's in the 1970s,
but this sort of thing happens with increasing regularity in the
'90s. Minnesota started losing players soon after winning the '91
World Series. Pittsburgh purged after finishing first, for the
third straight time, in '92.
</P>
<P>
   And now it has happened, back-to-back, with Florida and San
Diego. It's even happening in basketball to the Chicago Bulls,
coming off their sixth NBA title of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The 1914 A's lost the World Series, but winning it couldn't
preserve the '97 Marlins. One who got away was Kevin Brown, who
pitched the Padres into last year's World Series. Then he jumped to
Los Angeles _ for $105 million, which is $45 million more than the
Padres said they could afford.
</P>
<P>
   If Brown and the rest of an $88 million-salaried roster can
return the Dodgers to postseason glory, Rupert Murdoch's media
empire will have what it wants: a loss leader into its Fox network
programming. What's $88 million to a corporation that earns $90
billion a year?
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lucchino, president of the Padres, saw this coming, but
too late. When Brown signed with the Dodgers, Lucchino screeched:
``The apocalypse is upon us.''
</P>
<P>
   When it came time last year to vote on letting Murdoch and Fox
into their henhouse, the major-league moguls realized they had
gotten in there long before, tying owners up, one by one and
collectively, with various cable contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers unquestionably are raising the salary bar, but
Lucchino's prophesy is not only tardy but self-fulfilling. The
Padres recently traded 50-home-run hitter Greg Vaughn, thereby
lopping $2 million off their player payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Times are changing rapidly. Payroll is becoming increasingly
critical. Minnesota won the '91 Series with the 17th-highest salary
expense in the majors. But then, $27 million separated the biggest
spenders, Oakland, from the smallest, the stripped-for-sale Astros,
whose salaries totaled $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   In this new age of disparity, the difference between the
Dodgers' payroll and Montreal's is almost $80 million. Montreal's
revenues last year were $140 million less than those of the New
York Yankees, whose $80 million from local broadcasting was 10
times what the A's received from theirs.
</P>
<P>
   The free-agency market is becoming an exclusive shopping center.
Of the $1.05 billion committed to free agents in this offseason, 70
percent was spent by six teams: the Dodgers, Arizona Diamondbacks,
Anaheim Angels, Yankees, New York Mets and Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The elite players have become so expensive that most clubs
cannot afford even one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you have a payroll of $60 million or more,'' Astros
general manager Gerry Hunsicker said, ``it probably doesn't make
economic sense to invest $10 million in one player.''
</P>
<P>
   So here is baseball, heading to spring training, strangely
somber after a magical season in which Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa
blew past Roger Maris and Babe Ruth in the long-elusive home-run
record chase.
</P>
<P>
   The light dims when the focus switches from home-run races to
pennant races. The gap between the filthy rich and the merely rich
draws ever wider, and the imbalance is showing on the field. No
club with a payroll less than the Astros' $48 million played
postseason ball last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dollars don't guarantee anything, but not spending at a
certain level all but guarantees you will not be competitive,''
said Hunsicker, the 1998 National League Executive of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Added Sandy Alderson, Major League Baseball vice president of
operations: ``Fans of 15 to 18 teams will be buying tickets to
watch clubs that can't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Most baseball owners want to change this situation, but therein
lies the greater danger: a nuclear explosion similar to 1994, when
a labor war brought cancellation of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The current labor agreement expires after 2001. Before signing a
new one, the owners may seek a salary cap similar to what was
recently accepted _ after half a season was lost _ by the players
of the National Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that will prevent owners from locking us out
(in 2002) is they have to get a 75 percent vote to do it,''
Milwaukee Brewers third baseman Jeff Cirillo said.
</P>
<P>
   The owners can make a stronger case for a cap now than they
could in '94, when Montreal had the best record in the majors and
middle-income Philadelphia was the defending NL champ.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the clubs realize that selling the players' union on a
salary cap will be about as easy as selling fleas to a collie.
Hunsicker, a former agent for players (former Astros slugger Glenn
Davis was a client), is well-tuned to their labor views. And he
does not see a salary cap in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you're talking about baseball or the steelworkers,
it's very difficult to ask a union to take something back that they
have bargained for,'' he said. ``In most industries, when those
concessions are granted it's under the umbrella of bankruptcy,
significant layoffs or job losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always seems to take a catastrophe to get people's
attention. That's human nature. Most people don't make difficult
decisions unless they're forced to. Unless some clubs go under,
which would mean jobs are lost, you won't get the employees'
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   No ballclubs have ceased operations in recent decades, and it's
doubtful they will. Baseball has enough revenue sharing and
national television income to allow any club to scratch out a
profit if it keeps player costs under $15 million a year, which
several are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't draw three million people, you've almost
guaranteed a financial loss,'' Hunsicker said, ``unless you're
going the other way, stripping your team to make a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   While most baseball owners want more revenue sharing, the
Yankees' George Steinbrenner argues that won't help competitive
balance if the have-nots refuse to use their subsidies to acquire
players. Montreal's payroll last year was less than the $12 million
it received in revenue sharing.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker sees Steinbrenner's point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pirates and Montreal are making money, and that's a
joke,'' he said. ``You've got most teams losing money in an effort
to be competitive, and they're subsidizing teams that are making a
profit by putting uncompetitive teams on the field. That's not fair
to the rest of the teams and certainly not to the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   The small-market teams answer that they must hoard their limited
cash and spend when the boom-or-bust cycle is right. Timing is
everything. The Brewers last year raised their payroll from $22
million to $35 million without improving their record. They found
the middle ground to be no-man's land.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for answers and taking care not to inflame the union,
commissioner Bud Selig has appointed a task force to devise ways of
changing baseball's economic system.
</P>
<P>
   The think tank includes former Senate majority leader George
Mitchell, former Federal Reserve Board chairman Paul Volcker, and
author and TV commentator George Will.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be more creative than the people who came before
us,'' Selig said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's full-time commissioner, Selig is showing some
creativity himself, vowing to enforce the little-known ``60-40
rule'' that prohibits a club's liabilities from exceeding 40
percent of its assets.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 teams are believed to be violating this rule,
including the Dodgers, who were purchased by Murdoch for $315
million and are in debt to Brown alone for one third of that
amount.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Selig or his task force will find a way to keep the
heavyweights from crushing everyone else. But for now there's
little consolation for fans of the Marlins, who have only four
players remaining from the world champions of 16 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Padres' purge, it's out of character for John Moores,
the team's owner and a University of Houston alumnus. This was the
free-spender who wants ``to own the Padres the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he appears to be selling out the 1999 season, after the last
one brought droves of bell-ringing fans through the turnstiles and
victories in the playoffs over the favored Astros and Atlanta
Braves. Enough Padres fans also made it to the voters' booths to
pass a referendum for a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing, owners tend to spend more on ballplayers when
they're seeking public funding for ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Huizenga turned the Marlins to minnows and sold the team
when he couldn't obtain financial aid for a proposed stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But even a stadium on the way wasn't enough to comfort the
Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Lucchino claimed the new austerity had no connection to the
stadium referendum, that ``last year we were at the end of a cycle.
We had players who were aging and near free agency, and we had to
make a run then. You cannot stay static, especially if you're a
small-market team.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker empathized: ``You make major investments for veteran
talent to go with your young players, and then if your young
players are successful, salary arbitration hits you. So if you're
trying to maintain a mid-level payroll, it's virtually impossible
to keep the team together.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, San Diego is accepting the loss of Brown,
Vaughn and free agents Steve Finley and Ken Caminiti. Padres
general manager Kevin Towers said bringing all of them back would
make his payroll $80 million, which is more than the club's
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres insist they're not giving up on 1999, that the
payroll will approach $50 million, that the up-and-down,
33-year-old Vaughn may never be as good as he was last year and
that this is no Florida Fire Sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '96, nobody picked us to win,'' Towers said, ``and we did.
This year we're going to do the same damn thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Marlins and Padres fans is that most of the
breaking up is over. What's left of these teams probably will stay
together. At least, until they win again. Nowadays, that's about
all most baseball fans can expect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
