</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC STUNS NO. 6 STANFORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD _ Point guard Brandon Granville, frustrated over USC's
penchant for narrow losses, decided to speak up as the Trojans
gathered at midcourt prior to tipoff against Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``We huddled before the game and I told the guys, `It's about
time for the ball to bounce our way,' '' Granville said.
</P>
<P>
   He had no idea he could be so right.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every USC player found a bounce to his liking Saturday.
Brian Scalabrine made the first 3-point shot of his college career.
Elias Ayuso said he hit the two biggest free throws of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman forward Sam Clancy had the most important blocked shot
of his budding career.
</P>
<P>
   Granville simply turned in the best game of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Put it together, and the Trojans stunned No. 6-ranked Stanford
in overtime 86-82 before 7,391 at Maples Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   How significant was the victory? It was the Trojans' first win
over a top 10 opponent on the road since they defeated No. 2 UCLA
86-82 in 1992. The Trojans had not defeated a top 25 team on the
road since beating No. 19 Nevada-Las Vegas 90-74 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   It also may have salvaged a season that quickly deteriorated, as
the Trojans (12-10, 4-9) dropped nine of their first 12 Pac-10
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does make up for a lot,'' Ayuso said. ``Beating the No. 6
team in the nation. That's big on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It rates with the Arizona game last year,'' said USC coach
Henry Bibby, referring the Trojans' 91-90 upset of the
second-ranked Wildcats at the Sports Arena. ``That win was great.
Today was bigger because we did it on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   USC silenced the normally rambunctious sellout crowd at Maples
Pavilion by doing all the things Bibby usually singles out as the
team's shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans played stifling defense, holding Stanford to 39
percent shooting, including 24 percent on 3-pointers. USC also made
its own shots, shooting 48 percent from the field and eight of 21
of its 3-point shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along we have to make shots to win games. The
defense has come around. It's a young team and we haven't given
up,'' Bibby said. ``For us, any win has been good. It doesn't
matter if it's Stanford or the Boys Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, which only two weeks ago was pondering an undefeated
Pac-10 season, was searching for explanations over how it could
lose to USC at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out and thought we would run over them,'' point guard
Arthur Lee said. ``They were making shots. Man, they made every
shot they took, it seemed like.''
</P>
<P>
   None were bigger than Scalabrine's desperation 3-pointer from
the top of the key with two seconds left on the shot clock, and 56
seconds left in overtime. It gave the Trojans a 79-74 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't have a choice,'' Scalabrine said. ``We tried
to run a play. It kind of broke down. That's more thanking the Lord
than my skill. I'm not a terrible shooter but making it over a 6-8
(Mark) Madsen is a lot of luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford (20-5, 10-2) still felt it had plenty of time, and cut
the lead to 82-80 on Lee's drive with 25 seconds left. But
Scalabrine (a team-high 22 points) hit two free throws with 19
seconds left to give USC a four-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Young made a 15-foot jump shot to bring Stanford within two
points (84-82) with four seconds left. Then Ayuso calmly sank two
free throws to seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to make them understand that 'SC could beat us,''
Stanford coach Mike Montgomery said. ``But maybe they didn't get
it. To 'SC's credit, the played great.''
</P>
<P>
   Although USC led 59-48 with under 10 minutes to go, the Cardinal
kept rallying. Lee scored nine straight points, and Stanford
trailed 59-57 with 7:06 left.
</P>
<P>
   Young's 3-point play gave the Cardinal their first lead, 64-63,
with 4:09 remaining. But the Trojans never folded. Scalabrine hit a
15-footer with 1:13 left that tied the game, 70-70.
</P>
<P>
   Then Clancy made a crucial defensive play. Madsen had the ball a
few feet from the basket with 53 seconds left, and tried to shoot,
but Clancy blocked it and USC regained possession.
</P>
<P>
   Granville and Lee badly missed 3-point shots in the final
seconds to send the game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   It was a one of Granville's few poor shots. The 5-foot-8
freshman had 21 points and seven assists in a career-high 43
minutes, and made five 3-point field goals.
</P>
<P>
   The players admitted that the adrenalin from playing the No. 6
team in the country prevented them from experiencing fatigue.
Besides Granville's 43 minutes, Scalabrine and Clancy (12 points,
10 rebounds) each played 42.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say it makes our season, but it puts us on the
right track,'' Scalabrine said. ``I'm not going to say we're going
to the tournament or anything, but maybe the NIT.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
