<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NILSMARK HAS LPGA LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE _ There is a young, talented Swede leading the way
after two rounds of the Valley of the Stars Championship, but it's
not who you think.
</P>
<P>
   Catrin Nilsmark, who often has been overshadowed by the exploits
of fellow Swedes Annika Sorenstam, Helen Alfredsson and Liselotte
Neumann, set an Oakmont Country Club course record with a
brilliant, 7-under-par 65 on Saturday for a 36-hole total of
11-under-par 133. It was good for a two-shot lead entering today's
final round.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsmark said she isn't bothered by the lack of recognition. In
fact, she takes it good-naturedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wished I've been from Norway or something,'' she said
with a smile. ``I've done that, but not anymore. I'm just happy
being from Sweden.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Lowe, who held the lead for most of the day Saturday,
is two strokes behind at 9-under 135 after a solid 67. Then there
is Sorenstam, who struggled with her putter and settled for a 70
and a two-round total of 7-under 137.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsmark, on the other hand, hardly struggled at all. She did
have two bogeys, but she also had seven birdies (including three on
her first three holes). All except one, a 10-footer on the par-4,
360-yard 16th hole, were inside 10 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're playing well,'' she said, ``birdies should be
within a few feet''.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsmark closed her round in spectacular fashion. She put her
second shot in a greenside bunker on the par-5, 440-yard 18th hole
and holed her effort out of the sand for an eagle 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to hit it all the way up there, not leave it
short,'' she said of the 40-foot blast. ``If it wasn't the best,
it's up there as one of my best bunker shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Nilsmark's 65 broke the course record held by Terry-Jo Myers,
Leta Lindley and Sorenstam, who said she was not surprised by
Nilsmark's performance. She played with her in last year's Solheim
Cup at Muirfield Village and was impressed by what she saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a streaky player,'' Sorenstam said. ``She really rises
to the occasion. I think she's one of the best putters coming down
the stretch. Except on No.18, when she didn't have to putt. But she
would have made it if she had to.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a great player, and she showed it today.''
</P>
<P>
   Nilsmark hit a long drive and was in-between clubs for her
second shot. She knew a five wood would be too much and a
three-iron might not be enough, so she went with the shorter club
and aimed away from a menacing bunker well short and to the right
of the green. If she mis-hit it short or off-line, she said, she
wanted to go left.
</P>
<P>
   Her effort out of the sand landed about 15 feet short of the
hole and rolled in, dead-center.
</P>
<P>
   ``She played well all day,'' Lowe said of Nilsmark. ``She played
a great bunker shot on 18. It looked like it was going to be close,
whether it went in or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Geddes, who won at Oakmont CC in 1987 when the tournament
was called the GNA/Glendale Federal Classic, had a 2-under 70 and
is all alone at 5-under 139. Another stroke behind were defending
champion Dale Eggeling (second straight 70) and Cindy Flom (69).
</P>
<P>
   Dottie Pepper, who once challenged for the lead in Friday's
first round, had an even-par 72 and is tied with La Canada's
Alfredsson and Neumann at 3-under 141.
</P>
<P>
   Se Ri Pak, who opened the tournament with a three-over 75, came
back with a 70 and is in a large group at 145 that included Pat
Bradley, Emilee Klein, Pat Hurst and Alison Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   The cut was made at 6-over 150. Among the casualties were
Michelle McGann (79-151), Sherri Steinhauer (73-153) and Jan
Stephenson (79-153).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
