<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRONGER'S ROLE IS AS CHECKING CENTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ The newest King wasn't able to make it to Los
Angeles in time to play in Saturday night's game, but coach Larry
Robinson already has a role in mind for Sean Pronger, who was
acquired from the New York Rangers on Friday for left wing Eric
Lacroix.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said he plans to try the 6-foot-2 Pronger as a checking
center, a role that could free No. 1 center Jozef Stumpel to
concentrate on offense and relieve him of tiring penalty-killing
duties. Pronger is expected to be available to make his Kings debut
Monday at the Forum against the Mighty Ducks, one of his former
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember him from Anaheim,'' Robinson said. ``They said in
New York they didn't think he had a good enough first step, but he
seems to be a good skater. He has good offensive skills and he's
good on faceoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have a wealth of centers on their current roster:
Pronger, Stumpel, Olli Jokinen, Ian Laperriere, Ray Ferraro and
Yanic Perreault, who was a healthy scratch Saturday night for the
second consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   Perreault, who has scored six goals in his last 45 games, said
he was not worried about his role on the team even with Pronger's
addition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to focus on what my job is,'' Perreault said.
``If they need me, I'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacroix leaves again: Lacroix cleaned out his locker Saturday
morning before leaving to join his new team. Among his final acts
was writing a note to his former teammates on the marker board in
the dressing room: ``Boys, Good luck tonite. See you soon, E.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the board,'' center Ian Laperriere said. ``Not too
many guys who were traded would write that down. I know I didn't
write that down when I was traded twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, according to Robinson, Lacroix had asked to be traded
about two weeks ago because he was disappointed by his lack of
playing time. Robinson said Lacroix's lack of speed was a liability
on a Kings team lacking overall quickness.
</P>
<P>
   Courtnall honored: Center Russ Courtnall, who on Wednesday
became the 135th player in NHL history to appear in 1,000 games,
was honored before the game. His teammates gave him an engraved
watch, and the Kings' organization gave him and his family a trip
to Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 1, after appearing in his 1,000th game, defenseman Garry
Galley's wife decorated their home with 1,000 roses. Courtnall's
wife, Paris, had one of her husband's sticks bronzed to commemorate
his 1,000th game.
</P>
<P>
   Murray setback: The Kings' hopes of having right wing Glen
Murray in the lineup for Monday's game against the Mighty Ducks
took a hit when Murray did not skate Saturday because he had a
cold. Murray has been sidelined since Jan. 2 with a knee injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
