<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCARY TIME FOR SORENSTAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE _ The Sports Illustrated swimsuit shoot was a one-foot
uphill putt for golfer Annika Sorenstam.
</P>
<P>
   The three-time Player of the Year is the cover girl for the 1999
LPGA media guide, so you could say she's used to the exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, it was a little strange, baring a lot of her body for
an SI spread that includes some of the world's most beautiful
women. But at least it wasn't scary.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind how she, uh, stacks up against the comely Heidi Klum.
Nothing can compare to the discomfort Sorenstam felt when she
opened a Christmas card sent by strangers and her picture was
splashed all over the front of it.
</P>
<P>
   That happened this past year. The card was sent by a creepy
couple that came to tournaments all over Europe, finagling media
credentials so they could get that much closer to snap rolls of
film of their favorite player. Sorenstam imagines the couple has
taken so many photographs of her by now, ``they might have me as
their wallpaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there are others where those two come from.
Sorenstam, 28, and her husband David Esch have set aside a ``weird
file'' to keep track of the worst of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten several scary letters and have been approached by
weird people,'' the softspoken Swede said Saturday after the second
round of the Valley of the Stars Championship at Oakmont Country
Club.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam, who led after the first day, added a 2-under-par 70
to her opening 67 and stands third. She is four shots behind
countrywoman Catrin Nilsmark and two behind Stephanie Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   There were 128 other golfers on the 6,276-yard layout, though
you never would have known it. So many people were following the
pairing of Sorenstam, Nilsmark and Lowe, it's a wonder every putt
on the course didn't break toward the threesome.
</P>
<P>
   If the galleries tilted in their favor, Sorenstam's chaste pose
with Esch in the most ogled magazine that doesn't come wrapped in
brown paper might have had something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   There was the fan who saw Sorenstam and screamed to his buddy,
``There she is, the swimsuit girl!'' and then there were others who
let Sorenstam know, more subtly, that they saw what she did in
December.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten a lot of positive reaction,'' said Sorenstam, who
admitted ``I wasn't too keen on doing it at first.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam has been involved in five playoffs in her six years on
the LPGA Tour and won back-to-back U.S. Opens and none of that
rattled her as much as the prospect of posing in a bathing suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf is a very traditional sport and I'm a very traditional
person,'' Sorenstam said. ``For me that was kind of being crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the screwballs to consider. Was Sorenstam
inviting more trouble by exposing herself to a wider audience?
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the more well known you get, the chances increase
of people following you around and acting (inappropriately),''
Sorenstam said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the strange letters that Sorenstam receives are
intercepted by Esch, who is not shy about alerting the proper
authorities. Some of the ones Sorenstam has seen have left her
shaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scares you when these people become so into you that they
know more about you than you know about yourself,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Golfers have more reasons to worry than most professional
athletes. A gallery rope is about all that separates them from
their fans. And sometimes there's no barrier at all.
</P>
<P>
   To get from the fifth green to the sixth tee here, for example,
players have to cross the same bridge used by spectators. There are
no volunteers manning the area; hence, no one save the players'
caddies to keep enthusiastic fans at arm's length.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf is the only sport where you can get really close to a
player,'' Sorenstam said. ``Someone could easily do something and
there's nothing a player could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Moira Dunn, who survived the second-day cut by one stroke,
realized just how vulnerable players are at a tournament in Old
Hickory Tennessee last May. During one of her rounds she heard
something that sounded like a car backfiring.
</P>
<P>
   Then she felt something whistle past her ear and rustle the
leaves on a nearby tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I realized it was a bullet,'' Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   She and her playing partners never did find out who fired the
shots. The best they could figure is that someone oblivious to
their presence on the course was doing a little target shooting in
the adjacent swamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of scary when it comes down to it,'' Dunn said.
``Something like that kind of makes you think.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider that a member of Tiger Woods' gallery at a tournament
in Phoenix last month was found to be carrying a concealed weapon
and you realize there potentially are more hazards out there for
golfers than sand and water.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Sorenstam spots the couple that sent her the Christmas
card or any of the other strange characters who come around to
tournaments, ``My heart stops beating,'' she said. ``You have this
feeling of `What are they going to do now?' It scares me. I see a
lot of movies.''
</P>
<P>
   So far no one has made Sorenstam feel like Wesley Snipes'
character in ``The Fan.''
</P>
<P>
   You can understand, though, if any of the players cringed when
they saw the paper fans that a certain discount store passed out to
spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Each one had a target on it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
