<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-KINGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS KEEP CONTROL OF PACIFIC THEATER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Another trip to the greater Los Angeles area and
another four points for the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars continued their dominance over Southern California
last night with a 3-2 victory over the Kings at the Great Western
Forum. When combined with Friday's 3-2 victory over the Mighty
Ducks in Anaheim, the Stars now are 5-0-1 this season against their
new Pacific Division rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars move their NHL-best record to 32-10-8 and stay four
points ahead of the Phoenix Coyotes for first place in the Western
Conference. The Coyotes, 4-1 winners over the Colorado Avalanche
yesterday, have played two more games than the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Stars pushed their undefeated streak against
the Kings to 15 games (9-0-6), raised their record against all
Pacific Division teams to 11-2-2, and improved their road unbeaten
streak to seven games (6-0-1).
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 goalie Roman Turek, meanwhile, pushed his record to 9-1-2.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great end to a week in Southern California in which the
Stars soaked up some sunshine, played some golf and prepared
themselves for a lot of hockey. They play four games at home in the
next seven days.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars started the scoring, getting the first goal on a Brett
Hull rebound shot at the 12:13 mark of the first period. It was the
30th time in 50 games the Stars scored first and pushed their
first-period scoring advantage on opponents to 52-36. In games in
which the Stars score first, they are 22-3-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars then pushed that to 2-0 on a beautiful play by Joe
Nieuwendyk and Pat Verbeek. Nieuwendyk swooped in behind the net
and fed Verbeek, who was sneaking into the slot. Verbeek buried a
one-timer for his 12th goal of the season and his first in the past
eight games.
</P>
<P>
   But just as the Stars seemed to have complete control of the
game, the Kings came roaring back, scoring twice in a span of 40
seconds to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Ferraro's impressive solo effort beat Turek at the 4:34 mark
of the second period. Ferraro, worked his way around two Stars
players, drifted into the left circle, faked one shot and then
slipped a wrister over Turek's pad.
</P>
<P>
   Kings winger Matt Johnson then beat Stars center Tony Hrkac to a
long rebound that Turek had left sitting about 15 feet from the net
and Johnson slapped in the game-tying at the 5:14 mark.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars immediately rallied. They began dominating shifts,
earned a clear advantage in shots (12-7 in the second period) and
regained the lead on a hard-working shift from the line of Guy
Carbonneau, Brent Severyn and Dan Keczmer.
</P>
<P>
   Keczmer and Severyn outworked two Kings defenders behind the net
and came up with control of the puck. Severyn then fed Carbonneau
driving to the net and Carbonneau scored his second goal of the
season at the 13:25 mark of the second period. It was Severyn's
second assist in 14 games this season and Keczmer's first in 20
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings ended up outshooting the Stars, 26-22, on the strength
of a 12-3 shots advantage in the third period. But Turek held his
own, and the Stars penalty killer proved strong down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also caught a break when Donald Audette's third-period
goal was disallowed on review. Audette struck the puck just inches
above the cross-bar, a high stick infraction that negated what
would have been the game-tying goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
