<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-ALL-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISS THE ALL-STAR GAME? HERE'S YOUR FANTASY REPLACEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHAKEADELPHIA _ You haven't died, just gone to Hoops Heaven.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not the 1999 NBA All-Star Game originally scheduled
Sunday to culminate a festive weekend at Philadelphia's First Union
Center. The lockout sent those relatively mundane plans the way of
the peach basket months ago.
</P>
<P>
   In its place, here is the ultimate dream game featuring the
ultimate dream teams in an All-Millennium Game. This dream is
spiced with the 20th Century's best players, coaches, referees,
announcers and fans from the East and West, featuring Michael
Jordan vs. Jerry West, Bob Cousy vs. Magic Johnson, and Johnny Most
vs. Chick Hearn and will surely atone for fans missing another
Sunday of Kobe Bryant waving off screens from his peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worth using my .1 percent loophole to return,'' said
Jordan, refreshingly without Ahmad Rashad in his ear or even in the
arena. ``Finally, let's settle the debate about who is the
greatest.''
</P>
<P>
   In this All-Time, All-Star Game, only the best of the best
earned invitations.
</P>
<P>
   Most and Hearn, the legendary voices of the heated rival Celtics
and Lakers, are yacking oblivious to one another along press row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious the East will reign supreme because of the
influence of the Celtics' greats and Celtics' ghosts,'' gravels
Most. ``The only shame is that they didn't have time to turn this
floor into parquet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He Got Lame,'' retorts Lee, a finger in Nicholson's face.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the sold-out arena are the league's most respected
referees, Darrell Garrettson, Mendy Rudolph and Earl Strom,
followed by none other than Dr. James Naismith, set to toss the
ceremonial jump ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dr. looks taller in person,'' says East coach Red
Auerbach, flanked by assistants Phil Jackson and Chuck Daly.
</P>
<P>
   ``So does that Dr.,'' says West coach Lenny Wilkens, pointing
out East forward Julius Erving to assistants Pat Riley and Jack
Ramsay. ``I hope we can match-up. There's a lot riding on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Only if you consider bragging rights for 100 years significant.
</P>
<P>
   Like Miss America pageant losers in one of those half-hearted,
pre-Finals routines, wannabes Alonzo Mourning, Chris Webber and
Allen Iverson warm-up with never-weres Charles Barkley and Patrick
Ewing for their part in the halftime entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry guys,'' says East guard Isiah Thomas as he strides
toward the court, ``but it don't mean a thing unless you win a
ring. Or two.''
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive and well-decorated collection of players to
ever grace a court form two 15-member teams sporting an incredible
73 championships, 38 MVPs, 67 All-Defensive Team selections and 323
All-Star appearances.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be the 30 greatest players of the century, but moreso
each conference's top three players by position based on individual
statistics, team achievements, and off-court ambassadorship of the
sport. Barkley, for example, has Hall-of-Fame numbers, but wasn't
invited to the All-Millenium gathering because he has more arrests
than championships.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens, the NBA's all-time winningest coach, and Auerbach,
owner of nine rings, have three five-man teams to play in the first
three quarters. In the fourth, they are free to substitute any
combinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear players saying all the time they'd play the game for
free,'' says East forward Larry Bird. ``I bet a bunch of us would
pay to play in this one.'' THE LINEUPS
</P>
<P>
   Buzz in the building before tip-off centers on the
first-quarter, first-unit matchups. Johnson figures to use his
6-foot-9 to 6-1 size advantage to take Cousy into the low post,
while Auerbach will counter by isolating Jordan on the step-slower
West on the perimeter. At small forward, it's Bird's savvy against
Elgin Baylor's speed, though Wilkens is hinting that he might put
Baylor on Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elgin was Michael Jordan before Michael Jordan could even
spell N-B-A,'' Wilkens said. ``It's the matchup everyone wants to
see. If anyone in the history of basketball has the size and
agility to stop Michael, it's Elgin.''
</P>
<P>
   In the paint, power forwards Elvin Hayes and Karl Malone will
trade fallaway jumpers over each other, while Bill Russell and Wilt
Chamberlain renew their legendary rivalry under the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best team Wilt has ever played on,'' Russell grins, ``and he's
still gonna lose to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The second-quarter lineups seem to favor the West with up-tempo
scorers Clyde Drexler, James Worthy and Bob Pettit, but no unit all
day will be able to top the East's pizzazz of Isiah Thomas, Pete
Maravich and Julius Erving. Near halftime, the West to goes to a
two-man game of Oscar Robertson and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar with the
East countering with rugged defenders Jerry Lucas and Moses Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to predict Jabbar's points, fouls and turnovers against
him, Malone grumbles, ``Fo', five, fo'.''
</P>
<P>
   The third quarter features intriguing matchups of gritty point
guards Walt Frazier and John Stockton, scrappy small forwards in
John Havlicek and Rick Barry, punishing power forwards Kevin McHale
and Nate Thurmond and wily centers Robert Parish and Hakeem
Olajuwon. The contrast comes at shooting guard, where the East's
Hal Greer will try to muscle West scoring machine George Gervin.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I can't let him do,'' says Greer, ``is finger
roll.''
</P>
<P>
   At the tense pregame press conference, Auerbach promises only to
keep the ball in the hands of Jordan and Bird down the stretch,
while Wilkens plans a 12-minute fast break led by Johnson, Drexler,
Worthy, Baylor and Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Bellows public address announcer Michael Buffer, ``L-l-l-l-et's
Get Ready to Ruuuuummmmmbbblllllle!''
AND THE WINNER IS ...
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to the fourth quarter, long after Bird swished his
final money ball to edge Maravich in the 3-point Shooting Contest,
Erving launched himself a toenail farther than Jordan to win the
Slam Dunk title and Chamberlain honored himself with a plaque
commemorating his 20,000th point.
</P>
<P>
   The score is tied 98-98, 36 seconds remaining and the West has
possession:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Showtime,'' Riley says. ``Magic, feed the big guy.
Kareem, one more sky-hook. Nobody's stopped it yet this century.
And remember, no rebounds, no rings.''
</P>
<P>
   Though hounded by Frazier's trademark hand-check in the small of
his back, a smiling Johnson lobs a pass to Jabbar on the right low
block against Moses Malone. With Johnson and Robertson cutting
through the lane and Gervin and Baylor spotted-up on the 3-point
line, Abdul-Jabbar instead dribbles once and spins to his left for
a 16-foot sky-hook.
</P>
<P>
   Shoved one foot out of his automatic range by Malone's brute
force, the shot clangs off the front rim. Hayes momentarily grabs
the rebound, but is stripped in the lane by Robertson. After a wild
scramble that sends Malone and Johnson sprawling to the hardwood, a
bloodied Havlicek crawls from the scrum calling an East timeout
with :12 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   While Jackson frantically hums a Zen meditation and diagrams a
triangle and Daly screams about playing like ``Bad Boys,'' Auerbach
pulls something from his suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to light this damn cigar!'' Auerbach says calmly.
``Havlicek bring it up. Parish set a screen for Bird, and Larry,
bury it and let's get out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As usual,'' Bird shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   As Bird gets the ball on the wing, however, he is trapped by
Worthy and Pettit. Somehow, he dives and sneaks a pass through
Pettit's legs to Jordan, who finds himself isolated at the top of
the key against Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan waves off a Parish screen, then winks at teammates Bird,
Havlicek and Maravich, each finding an open area for a possible
game-winner. Tongue wagging, Jordan head-fakes Baylor into the air
with :05 on the clock. After two dribbles he is met in the lane by
Olajuwon and Robertson. After faking a handoff pass to a cutting
Bird, Jordan vaults backward toward the free-throw line, sending a
high-arcing fadeaway over four outstretched hands.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the game's greatest players go crashing the boards as
the buzzer sounds. But their effort is wasted, as Jordan's
12-footer has swished through the basket to give the East a 100-98
victory and solidified his stature as the greatest player ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had to save my best for last,'' Jordan smiles while puffing on
Auerbach's stogie.
</P>
<P>
   Irritated on the floor by the trash-talking of Bird and Malone,
Johnson rushes the victory podium and whispers something in
Jordan's ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best two of three?''
</P>
<P>
   THE BOX SCORE
</P>
<P>
   East 100, West 98
</P>
<P>
   WEST 24 23 31 20 _ 98
</P>
