<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN BRINGS DIFFERENT SHOWTIME TO L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the department store of sporting cliche, the Lakers have
dragged their game to that elusive ``next level.''
</P>
<P>
   And that level is Women's Wear.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, Dennis Rodman this and any other planet's foremost
rebounding mercenary is reportedly about to become part of a proud
tradition. Prepare for roll call: Baylor, West, Chamberlain,
Goodrich, Abdul-Jabbar, Johnson, Worthy, Nevitt (gotcha) ... and
Rodman. Adding the Worm to this crew would be about as historically
incongruous as carving the mug of Jerry Springer into Mount
Rushmore.
</P>
<P>
   The deciding factor may be that $3 million endorsement windfall
promised by Converse, a company that - in its association with
Rodman - has gone from Chuck Taylor to Rip Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   But is it the right move for the Lakers?
</P>
<P>
   Well, those poorly dressed men who seem to be twisting in agony
from having acid splashed on their faces are, in fact, local
sportswriters dancing (badly) in the streets. From an impurely
professional point of view, we are thrilled about the possibility
of Rodman joining the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, this rascal still threatens to play his last game in
the altogether, which should re-define the hackneyed concept of
``Showtime.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Dennis refuses to favor us with pithy post-game
commentary at the Great Western Bacon Cheeseburger Forum, we can
track him down at some grotesquely hip Hollywood saloon. If his
kamikaze-inspired comments sound a bit detrimental to crucial team
harmony, we can macarena on over to the table of Lakers owner Dr.
Jerry Buss for clarification.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. According to sources beyond our control, Rodman
and Buss get thirsty in the same neighborhood. According to
unrelated sources, Clippers owner Donald T. Sterling has been
touring Detroit-area taverns in an attempt to bump into Grant Hill.
Oh, the Rodman story is just dandy news for the Clippers, who get
less ink in an entire season than Dennis has etched into his skin.
</P>
<P>
   It also should be noted that having Rodman in the lineup means
Shaquille O'Neal may not be the sole fourth-quarter target of foul
play. Can Dennis stop Utah's Karl Malone on the ol' pick 'n' roll?
Gee, he might, if he decides to actually assist the teammate being
screened instead of hanging back to pad his rebounding stats.
</P>
<P>
   Does any of this mean we dance-challenged scribes will be
covering the NBA Finals? Truthfully, most of us would have been
more comfortable had the Lakers landed Tom Gugliotta, but when
Pavarotti's not available, you make a go of it with Little Richard.
</P>
<P>
   Who cares if Rodman's fondness for makeup earns him the title of
the NBA's first powder forward? He rebounds with more zeal - not to
mention panache - than anyone this side of ``Melrose Place.''
</P>
<P>
   And let's not forget something else Rodman brings to bear (or
bare). If the Lakers can't win the championship with O'Neal, Kobe
Bryant, Eddie Jones and the Worm, reporters won't look upon the
team's coach as good ol' Del Harris.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be Del Nino.
</P>
<P>
   ALL-STAR (FAST) BREAK
</P>
<P>
   Stupid's arrow remains jammed in the heart of Philadelphia,
where the lockout wrecked today's regularly scheduled all-star
game.
</P>
<P>
   Because the league has been up and running for only nine days,
it would be foolish to name an all-star team. So here goes:
</P>
<P>
   For the West, our forwards are Gugliotta and Chris Webber, who
deserves to be Player of the Week. Shaq gets the nod at center,
with Gary Payton at point guard and nobody at shooting guard. Oh,
we have to have a shooting guard? Well, since Bryant is playing
small forward, let's select Michael Finley of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   For the West, we begin and end with Hill (Grant) at small
forward. From there, it's a crapshoot, which explains why Michael
Jordan's retirement brings all of the intrigue over to the Western
Conference. OK, let's try any Hardaway and Atlanta's Steve Smith in
the backcourt, with Keith Van Horn at power forward and ... pick
your favorite Georgetown poison at center.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Shaq is the only center averaging 20 or more
points per game thus far.
</P>
<P>
   FREE ADVICE
</P>
<P>
   This space is reserved to saddle someone with the World B. Free
Award, presented (in spirit) to the NBA player who is making a name
for himself.
</P>
<P>
   This week's honoree is Sacramento rookie point guard Jason
Williams. Unless you were an NBA scout or some get-a-life
sportswriter named Hill who happened to catch Williams on ESPN2
last year before he (Williams, not Hill) was kicked off the Florida
team for using a joint on the pick 'n' roll, this guy was a just
rumor.
</P>
<P>
   What he has turned out to be is Bobby Hurley with far superior
size, quickness, jumping ability, passing instincts and shooting
skill. Otherwise, they're virtually the same player.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES OF THE WEAK
</P>
<P>
   We would like to use this space to inform you that the coaching
lives of Mike Dunleavy and George Karl will be captured in a film
called ``You've Got Male-Pattern Baldness.'' But that would be a
lie.
</P>
<P>
   What we can tell you is the life of Clippers rookie Michael
Olowokandi may become a film project for DreamWorks, which has
something to do with Steven Spielberg and nothing to do with Hakeem
Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   Suggested titles: ``Citizen Kandi Cane'' or - exploiting the
crosstown-rival angle ``Kandi-Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   SHOT-CLOCK VIOLATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota point guard Stephon Marbury is reported to be a
virtual lock to sign with Chicago before next season. Let's see.
He'd team up with Toni Kukoc and Brent Barry for a grand total of
three dribble-happy perimeter players, necessitating a change from
the triangle offense to the wreck-tangle offense. ... Six former
Celtics are NBA head coaches, but a former Celtic is not the coach
of the Celtics. ... Charles Barkley was fined $5,000 for making
``obscene comments'' to Forum fans. According to witnesses, Barkley
shocked and infuriated Lakers fans by accusing them of paying face
value for their tickets. ... Marv Albert is not yet in mid-season
form in his return to Knicks' broadcasts, but should be fine once
he gets a few kinks out. ... Latrell Sprewell's recent injury means
that, for two years in a row, he will be sidelined by an
unfortunate incident involving a heel. ... Speaking of P.J.
Carlesimo, how 'about them Warriors? ... Milwaukee's Ray Allen
dumped his agent and hired Johnnie Cochran to eyeball his new
contract offer. This does not mean the same strategy will be used
by Gary Payton, whose nickname is the ``Glove.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 0122EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
