<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4883 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-REPORT-TEX     02-14 1453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENS A FINAL LINK TO NHL'S PAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it's the walk up Yonge Street, Toronto's eclectic
boulevard of people-watching that looks a little like a spilled bag
of Skittles.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the pale, yellow bricks of the block-long building
that strike you when you turn onto Carlton Street, the same kind of
bricks they used in building your old elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the smell of the hot dogs sold by the street vendors
or the steam from their carts or the simple doughnut shop and
pancake house that bustles with action across the street before and
after a game.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the fact you can close your eyes and go back to a
time when people wore topcoats and hats to a hockey game, when the
working class could be distinguished by their short jackets and
Dickeys, when a cup of Joe and a doughnut cost about the same as a
seat in the Greys.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, just maybe, that's why last night's closing of Maple Leaf
Gardens is so emotional. You see, the old outdated building in the
heart of downtown Toronto has small seats, a maze of halls and a
serious lack of parking. But what was great about Maple Leaf
Gardens is it was our link to the past. A trip to the old building
took you back to 1931 or '45 or '57 or '66. Whenever you had fond
memories of youth, of sports, of a better life, that's what the
Gardens was _ your own personal time machine.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it seats less than 16,000 in cramped little uncomfortable
seats that weren't unlike your Aunt Doris' folding chairs, the ones
they made you sit in when you weren't big enough for the adult
table. But along with those small seats came an NHL bench that had
no walls. That's right, through the years, fans sat right next to
King Clancy or held the door so Maurice Richard could make a line
change. Gordie Howe rubbed elbows with the fans, so did Wayne
Gretzky. It was quite possibly the neatest seat in all of sports.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you couldn't get seats on the glass, you could sit
in the reds or blues or greys _ the seats really are those colors.
That's not all. The building is an inefficient rectangle _ with
seats climbing straight up a wall in each end zone. What's more,
the designers built it strangely high, almost twice as high as the
seats reach, giving it the real feel of a barn in which canvas was
draped from the ceiling for the spring dance.
</P>
<P>
   Maple Leaf Gardens is all that and more, a wonderfully
inconvenient, classically beautiful structure that simply could no
longer survive in the high-dollar business of hockey. The Air
Canada Centre is twice as big and twice as nice. Many in Toronto
say it'll make you forget the Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   But that would be a shame. The oldest building in hockey is now
the Pittsburgh Civic Arena, a futuristic design that looks far
newer than its 1961 birthdate. There are no more time machines
left.
Spotlight on Jaromir Jagr
Jagr's future not cemented, but role with Penguins solid
</P>
<P>
   The hair gets you right from the start _ either you love it or
you hate it.
</P>
<P>
   It has that kind of Michael Bolton-Fabio effect that gets people
to form an opinion almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not how Jaromir Jagr should be taken. That would be
like slamming a cognac instead of sniffing it. No, the Pittsburgh
Penguins captain needs to be savored.
</P>
<P>
   Captain? That's right. You might have missed it, but Jagr was
named captain in the summer after center Ron Francis left for the
Carolina Hurricanes in free agency. Believe it, the long-haired,
insubordinate black sheep Jagr is running the show in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Kevin Constantine couldn't have made a better choice.
Jagr, who turns 27 tomorrow, has embraced his leadership and has
still not changed all that much. He doesn't like Constantine's
defensive system and isn't shy about saying so publicly. He
recently said an all-European team wouldn't have the right
``stuff'' to win the Stanley Cup. And he groused about a move onto
a line with the mostly inexperienced Jan Hrdina and Kip Miller.
</P>
<P>
   And after he griped and groused, Jagr went out and scored and
scored and scored _ enough to lead the NHL and take the Penguins on
a hot streak that has some believing they can win in the playoffs.
Now that's being a leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who else is going to do it?'' Jagr asks confidently. ``I know
I have to be that guy now. I was a troublemaker. When I wasn't
happy, I would scream. Now, I can't afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jagr has played so well, his team might not be able to afford
him. The Penguins are in bankruptcy, and Jagr is slated to make $9
million next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the owners and general manager think they have to trade me,
that's their decision,'' he said. ``I love to play in Pittsburgh.
If they can't afford me, then I would love to play in LA or New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   Ya gotta give the guy credit for honesty.
Quick hits
BARGAIN BASEMENT
</P>
<P>
   Here's the most outlandish statement you'll read in a while: The
Panthers got a bargain on Pavel Bure's new five-year, $47 million
deal.
</P>
<P>
   At $8, $9, $10, $10, $10 (all in millions, of course), Bure is
under contract for the long-term at a time when megastars Paul
Kariya and Eric Lindros will be negotiating new deals.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Bure (for basically expendable players) and
the subsequent signing could be the deal of the NHL season for
Panthers general manager Bryan Murray.
JAWS ROAD TOUR
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks so far are taking on their league-record 10-game
roadtrip with the style of their coach, Darryl Sutter _ they're
chewing it up and spitting it out. So far, the Sharks are 3-2 on
the trip, including a 5-1 whipping of the Blues on Thursday.
NEW TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   Never let it be said that hockey is being left behind on the
technology front. Players every day are experimenting with carbon
fibers and and metal composites. The new gimmick is a stick with a
slightly bent neck where the shaft meets the blade. The principle
behind the technology is it puts your hands in better shooting
position.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, didn't that same technology fail in softball bats about 20
years ago.
TEAM IN TURMOIL
</P>
<P>
   Detroit has been known for cars and killings, and the climate
last week had some thinking the Red Wings might be involved in the
latter.
</P>
<P>
   Red Wings GM Ken Holland returned from winter meetings to find
coach Scotty Bowman had challenged his top players (Steve Yzerman,
Sergei Fedorov and Brendan Shanahan), combined them on the same
line and then chastised them when they didn't perform well. Fedorov
was most upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two of them have to work it out, and they will,'' Holland
said of Fedorov and Bowman. ``You don't win Stanley Cups in
February or March.''
</P>
<P>
   No, but you can lose them then.
PLENTY OF WIND
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Blackhawks coach Dirk Graham is resorting to the whip, a
move that will either shape up Chicago's moribund Blackhawks or
beat them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are desperate games and the efforts we've been getting
from some people are a joke,'' Graham said of his veterans,
including Tony Amonte and Chris Chelios. ``I think you've been
hearing the same story for the past three years. Nothing's
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
AROUND THE LEAGUE
</P>
<P>
   The five-game suspension of Coyotes tough guy Jim Cummins for
elbowing the head of Blackhawks' defenseman Brad Brown was the
NHL's first major suspension for a hit to the head in two months.
Is it just coincidence that the league's best players are having
their healthiest season? ... Add the Sabres to the list of teams
saying they're losing money. Even with a new building, Buffalo's
management claims potential losses of $15 million. ... So is this
good news or bad news? Lightning goalie Daren Puppa and his sore
back will not need surgery, a doctor said last week. However, they
still have no idea when he might be ready. Lightning coach/GM
Jacques Demers said Puppa is out of the picture in Tampa. ... When
the Flames stopped the Avalanche winning streak at 12 (sixth
longest in NHL history) it was the second time this season Calgary
had been a streak-stopper. The Flames also halted the Stars'
franchise best unbeaten streak at 15 games. What's more, the Flames
own three victories over the Red Wings. ... Blues goalie Grant Fuhr
is out 4-6 weeks after surgery on his right knee. The on-a-budget
Blues will wait until the summer to decide if they need goalie
help.
THE WEEK AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   Today: Flyers at Avalanche _ The two hottest teams in the NHL
meet for one of only two times this season. Thursday: Capitals at
Hurricanes _ A key battle in the Southeast Division, where maybe
only one team will make it to the playoffs. Saturday: Canadiens at
Maple Leafs _ A new beginning, the Air Canada Centre opens.
</P>
</TEXT>
