<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS DEFEAT KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ROGER PHILLIPS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ This time, the rally fell short.
</P>
<P>
   Two nights after a dramatic last-second victory over
Philadelphia, the Kings spotted the Dallas Stars a two-goal lead
Saturday night, then started making like ``Comeback Kids'' once
again.
</P>
<P>
   They tied the score, and had the Forum crowd of 12,702 roaring.
</P>
<P>
   But a blown coverage by defenseman Rob Blake cost the Kings a
goal late in the second period, and the Stars made it stand for a
3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never seem to panic or run around,'' said center Ray
Ferraro, who scored the Kings' first goal. ``If you dig yourselves
a hole, you've got a lot of work.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was a job the Kings could not complete, though they came
close in the third period. But an apparent power-play goal by
Donald Audette was disallowed with 13:04 to play, and the Stars
held on.
</P>
<P>
   Audette appeared to score on his own rebound, but the video goal
judge ruled that Audette, who stands 5-foot-8, had his stick above
his shoulders when he knocked the puck out of the air and into the
net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I hit it good,'' Audette said, though replays
vindicated the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The news in the standings wasn't good for the Kings (20-30-4),
with an Edmonton victory again leaving them six points out of a
playoff berth with 28 games remaining. Dallas (32-10-8) improved to
3-0 against the Kings this season.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tough night for Blake. On Dallas' first goal, Brett
Hull scored when he fired the puck home after Blake had blocked the
initial shot. On the second, Blake was caught between Joe
Nieuwendyk, who centered the puck, and Pat Verbeek, who fired it
into the net.
</P>
<P>
   And on the game-winner, with 6:25 left in the second period,
Blake failed to check Guy Carbonneau in front, and Carbonneau
scored off a centering pass from Brent Severyn.
</P>
<P>
   When it was mentioned to Blake that he'd played more than 29
minutes, he said, ``It was 29 minutes too many for me, the way I
played.... I just got beat. (Carbonneau) passed by me and beat me
to the net. It's pretty simple.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Stars took their 2-0 lead, the Kings fought back with
the goals 40 seconds apart early in the second period by Ferraro
and Craig Johnson. But Dallas doesn't often blow two-goal leads,
and when the Stars regained the lead, they protected it as they
usually do so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think they are in first place by mistake,'' said
Kings assistant coach Jay Leach, who spoke to reporters because
Coach Larry Robinson has laryngitis and left immediately after the
game. ``There are no riders on that team. For us, we had too many
fluctuations in our game to play consistent and beat a team like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also were caught short on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, the Kings announced that Steve Duchesne was ill
and would not play, and 10:49 into the game, Doug Bodger left with
bruised ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Then 8:04 into the second period, the Kings lost Sean O'Donnell
for 17 minutes when he received a fighting major, an instigating
minor and a 10-minute misconduct after a fight with Grant Marshall.
O'Donnell had skated past Marshall moments after Marshall had hit
him with a hard check.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of banged the glass with my stick (after being
checked),'' O'Donnell said. ``(Referee Kerry Fraser) thought that
me skating to (Marshall) was me trying to start a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell said he'd simply been headed to the bench. Instead, he
and Marshall squared off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no intention of fighting,'' O'Donnell said. ``But I let
my emotions get the better of me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
