<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA SHOWS HIS METTLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The left eye was bruised and closing, and Oscar De
La Hoya was wobbling around the ring trying to keep his senses
intact in the sixth round Saturday night after he got decked by a
vicious left hook thrown by Ike Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Golden Boy looked so vulnerable, so beatable, so
near to suffering a most humiliating setback.
</P>
<P>
   This was the most challenging moment of Oscar De La Hoya's
career that has been so glamorous and so free of such danger until
Quartey's punch bounced wickedly against his jaw.
</P>
<P>
   Could he survive?
</P>
<P>
   Could he stay in a vertical position against a fierce-punching
opponent not faintly reminiscent of any of his previous 29 victims?
</P>
<P>
   Could he emerge from such an ominous predicament and show that
he indeed is a fighter of legitimate greatness, as Rocky Marciano
once did with that thundering right hand that decked Jersey Joe
Walcott when it seemed Marciano was destined for failure, as Sugar
Ray Leonard once did with one eye closed shut when he dispensed a
miraculous rally against Thomas Hearns, as Ali did each time he
faced certain doom from the punishing fists of Joe Frazier?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Oscar De La Hoya not only survived to earn a deserved
split 12-round decision over Quartey at the Thomas &AMP; Mack Center,
but did it with a flourish that earned him afterwards more respect
and praise than he did for all those easy victories against the
Julio Cesar Chavezes and Macho Camachos and Genaro Hernandezes and
all those other setups.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being handicapped the final six rounds with a badly
swollen eye that had to impair his vision, De La Hoya proved to be
even more aggressive than the too-cautious Quartey, even sending
Quartey sprawling to the canvas in a 12th round that he dominated
so thoroughly during the first two minutes that there were some
observers who thought the referee, Mitch Halpern, should have
stopped it.
</P>
<P>
   Wisely, Halpern didn't, and the equally heroic Quartey, who gave
the 26-year-old De La Hoya by far his most grueling test, was in
pursuit of De La Hoya for the final 60 seconds amid the
reverberating roar of the 16,000 spectators.
</P>
<P>
   What we found out about Oscar De La Hoya in this one is that his
heart is just as exceptional as his boxing skills which he used
adroitly throughout the evening, constantly beating his slower
opponent to the punch with his quick jabs and left hooks.
</P>
<P>
   What we found out about Oscar De La Hoya is that he can react
well in a crisis and isn't timid about mixing it up even when he
seems on the threshold unconsciousness.
</P>
<P>
   What we found out about Oscar De La Hoya is that he deserves to
be ranked among the best pound-for-pound fighters in the world and
that right now he is the best welterweight on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the other renowned practitioner in De La Hoya's
division, Felix Trindad, has never faced anyone as formidable as
Quartey, who fought heroically himself during a most competitive
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Two judges, Ken Morita (116-112) and John Keane (116-113), had
De La Hoya the clear winner, while another arbiter, Larry
O'Connell, had Quartey ahead by a 115-114 count.
</P>
<P>
   I had De La Hoya a 116-113 victor, scoring six rounds in his
favor, four for Quartey and calling two even in a match that wasn't
easy to tabulate because both men fought tactically and cautiously
for long periods of it.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, if Quartey had stepped up his attack in that sixth
round when he himself had risen from the canvas after being floored
by one of De La Hoya's left hooks, he might have been able to pull
off a most unexpected conquest.
</P>
<P>
   He had De La Hoya badly hurt, but didn't exactly displayed a
killer's instinct as he took his time and let the retreating De La
Hoya regain his composure.
</P>
<P>
   And in the fight's late stages, Quartey relaxed too often,
allowing De La Hoya to steal several rounds that he had no business
stealing considering the shape of his eye.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzied crowd was, as always, overwhelmingly in favor of De
La Hoya, who once again inspired a huge contingent of Hollywood
types to make appearances, including Jack Nicholson, who shows up
at more events than Magic Johnson, who, of course, was present and
would show up at a mall opening in Anchorage, Alaska, if he were
invited.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Arum was an animated presence at ringside, dripping with
pride over another successful De La Hoya promotion that that this
time actually had tense drama and excitement in it.
</P>
<P>
   There are dark rumors afloat that De La Hoya, with
behind-the-scenes cajoling from his financial adviser, Mike
Hernandez, might soon detach Arum and begin promoting his own
fights, a risky venture at best.
</P>
<P>
   All Arum has done is shrewdly choreograph De La Hoya's
professional career in a textbook perfect manner, from marketing to
matchmaking it so flawlessly that De La Hoya's private worth
exceeds $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   The talk on the street is that Hernandez, wealthy owner of an
East L.A. car dealership, thinks Arum is earning too much of the
profits generated by De La Hoya, and it's not a coincidence that
Arum consented to a 50-50 split in Saturday night's match.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, it seemed Oscar De La Hoya's fistic stock would take
a severe crash, but he reached into the deepest recesses of his
heart to somehow overcome Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   Ike Quartey never backed down.
</P>
<P>
   But neither did Oscar De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when he was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when he seemed destined for serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when it came time to prove that he is one special
fighter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
