r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-LA-LADN     02-14 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-LA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENE TIES WORLD RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following his world-record performance in the men's 50 meters
Saturday night in the L.A. Invitational indoor track and field
meet, Maurice Greene showered the Sports Arena crowd of 6,005 with
T-Shirts which read: ``Something like a pheno-Mo-nom.''
</P>
<P>
   His start en route to his record run was nothing but phenomenal.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, 24, got off to a lightning start in the men's 50 meters
to win in a world-record-tying 5.56 seconds. Greene's time, which
equaled Canadian Donovan Bailey's 1996 standard, also dipped under
the American record of 5.61 seconds set by Andre Cason, and
eclipsed James Sanford's 1981 meet record of 5.62.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say? Not too much,'' Greene said about his start.
``I knew from the gun nobody was going to catch me. In the 50
meters, it's reaction time, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Greene's coach John Smith put it: ``Well-timed.'' Either
way, Greene had already left a stellar field behind by 30 meters.
Jon Drummond and defending national 100-meter champion Tim Harden
finished well back in second and third in 5.63 and 5.67 but equaled
the eighth- and tenth-best performers of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``His reaction was great because of the shortness of the race,''
Smith said. ``We're trying to take that finesse outdoors. It's like
going through the eye of a needle to get that composure. If he does
that, he can be the sprinter everybody wishes to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, the UCLA sprint coach who also coaches Drummond and 1997
World 200-meter champion Ato Boldon, called it Greene's best legal
start ever. Smith believes a similar start in the 100 meters by
Greene could result in taking down Bailey's 100 record of 9.84
seconds set in the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Greene came agonizing close after wind-aided efforts of
9.79 and 9.84 seconds. Greene said he felt capable of extending
Saturday's effort to a full 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 50-60 meters, I am just getting started,'' Greene said.
``It hurt a little bit to not get the (100) record, but I have
dealt with it. I just have to be patient and everything will come
together. I am not worried about records. I am thinking about
running technically correct.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the women's 50-meter match race between Inger
Miller and Chryste Gaines went down to the wire. Miller squeaked by
Gaines in the final 10 meters to win, 6.15 to 6.16. Miller and
Gaines, members of the U.S. 1997 World Champion and American
record-setting 400-meter relay, moved into a tie for fifth and
seventh on the all-time U.S. list.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Morrison won the women's 50-meter hurdles in a
meet-record 6.81 to break Jackie Joyner-Kersee's 1996 record of
6.82 and become the second-fastest American of all-time.
</P>
<P>
   In the men's 50-meter hurdles, Reggie Torian, national 110-meter
high hurdles champion, defeated Mark Crear, the world's top-ranked
hurdler, to win in 6.43.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Jacobs, the American 5,000-meter record holder and
seven-time national 1,500-meter champion, stepped down to the 800
meters to win in 2:07.60.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Adkins, the 1996 Olympic 400-meter intermediate hurdle
champion, turned back Tyree Washington to win the men's 500 yards
in 56.75. Jeff Hartwig, American record-holder in the pole vault,
turned back former record-holder Lawrence Johnson to win at 19-0\.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's Jess Strutzel was a surprise winner over four-time U.S.
Olympian Johnny Gray in the men's 800 meters. Strutzel held off a
furious surge from the 38-year-old American outdoor record holder
at the wire to win, 1:49.37 to 1:49.39.
</P>
<P>
   Other winners included Tisha Waller in the women's high jump at
6-3\ and Kevin Toth in the men's shot put at 66-5}.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
