<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-CLIPPERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLUTCH WHEN IT COUNTED  
 CHAPMAN EARNS REDEMPTION IN OT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Just when the 19,023 fans at America West Arena were
starting to think Rex Chapman had turned into Mr. Klutz, he
returned to Mr. Clutch.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting only five of 19 shots in regulation, turning the
ball over five times and looking skyward for redemption a dozen
times, Chapman bailed the Suns out when they needed him most
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   He scored 12 of his 22 points in overtime and the Suns escaped
the Los Angeles Clippers _ barely _ 107-104.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, the Suns (3-2) came out of a four-game
homestand with two wins and and face three games in three nights on
the road starting Monday night in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   After the Clippers' Lamond Murray, who led Los Angeles with 26
points, missed badly on the first shot of overtime, Chapman
connected with one of his patented runners from 14 feet. He added a
pair of free throws a moment later, then connected on his second
three-point basket of the game with 2:36 to go in the extra period
for a 100-93 Phoenix lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns, who blew a nine-point fourth quarter lead, nearly let
the Clippers survive again in the overtime. James Robinson's
three-point field goal with 1:40 remaining got the winless Clippers
(0-4) within two.
</P>
<P>
   It was still two with 45 seconds to go after Sherman Douglas's
running shot, but the Clippers were called for an illegal defense
with 29 seconds to go, and Chapman hit the resulting technical foul
free throw. The Suns had the ball and a three-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers were forced to foul, and Chapman missed the first
of two free throws with 27 seconds to go. But he made the second to
ice it.
</P>
<P>
   It was a terrific ending for what had been a long night for
Chapman, who has been struggling since returning from a hamstring
injury that caused him to miss training camp, the preseason and the
regular-season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Zeke's game for some pointers today,'' Chapman said,
referring to his 6-year-old son. ``His team won 40-16 and he had 28
(points). At halftime, it was 20-6. Zeke had 20. They wouldn't let
him play in the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Suns Coach Danny Ainge might have had similar thoughts about
Zeke's dad, but even on his worst nights, Chapman is the Suns best
player when defenses turn up the heat.
</P>
<P>
   And he came through in the overtime.
</P>
<P>
   But give forward Clifford Robinson an assist. He put the Suns in
position to win the game without an overtime or help from Chapman.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's defensive activity sparked the Suns going early at
the start of the fourth quarter, and he scored 14 of his 23 points
in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   A former NBA Sixth Man Award winner, Robinson started the first
three games at small forward. But Ainge moved him to the bench for
defensive purposes behind center Luc Longley and power forward Tom
Gugliotta.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson played all three front-line spots against the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns trailed by a point going into the fourth quarter, and
they were down two when Robinson converted a three-point play,
driving to the basket on Jason Kidd's feed and drawing a foul.
</P>
<P>
   That started a 22-11 Phoenix spurt that put the Clippers in a
nine-point hole with 3:41 to play in the game. It was still a seven
point lead with 1:52 to go, but the Suns let the Clippers off the
hook.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles closed to within one on Lamond Murray's jump shot
with 42 seconds to go. Kidd's driving layup attempt was blocked by
the Clippers' Lorenzen Wright, and Los Angeles had a chance to take
the lead with possession of the ball and 22.3 seconds on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gugliotta's foul sent Maurice Taylor to the free throw line
for two shots with 11.3 seconds to go, and Taylor tied it with his
first shot.
</P>
<P>
   But he missed badly on the second.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who finished with 25 points, made amends, hustling to
the other end to block Robinson's shot on a drive to the basket
with just over three seconds to go, and the game went to overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman went 0-6 in the first quarter and missed his first four
attempts in the second before finally hitting a three-point shot
with 6:05 to go in the first half. He curled off a screen to hit
another jump shot from about 18 feet with 7.8 seconds on the clock
that got the Suns within 45-44 at halftime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
