<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4893 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-QUARTEY-     02-14 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-QUARTEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA EARNS SPLIT TO KEEP BELT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ It was a night worthy of an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   For Oscar De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya survived Saturday night against Ike Quartey. Nothing
more. Nothing less. But nothing could be more telling. In the end,
fighters are defined by survival. It's not an ability. It's an
instinct.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody really knew whether De La Hoya was born with anything
more than good looks.
</P>
<P>
   Until Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   The African challenger forced him to get up, forced him to fight
with a welt that nearly closed his left eye and, in the end, forced
him to prove that he, too, had the instincts to be among boxing
greats.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya picked himself up after hitting the canvas for only
third time in his career to win a split decision over Ike Quartey
at Thomas &AMP; Mack Center.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya (30-0, 24 knockouts), still the World Boxing
Council's welterweight champion, was down in a wild sixth round,
just moments after he had floored Quartey (34-1-1, 29 KOs).
</P>
<P>
   In an equally wild 12th, De La Hoya knocked down Quartey, who in
the bout's final seconds fought desperately with his back to the
ropes and defeat on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   It was Quartey's last stand. One judge's card indicated it was a
worthy one.
</P>
<P>
   Larry O'Connell had Quartey leading by three points by three
points going into the final round. Despite the the 12th-round
knockdown, Quartey still was a 115-114 winner on O'Connell's card.
</P>
<P>
   But Quartey couldn't convince the other two judges. For Ken
Morita, it was De La Hoya, 116-112. For John Keane, it was also De
La Hoya, 116-113.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw the fight,'' Quartey said. ``The world saw the fight.
I knew I couldn't win a decision in Las Vegas. I thought I did
enough to win. I think I surprised him.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Quartey stunned him and scared more than 12,000 of
De La Hoya's adoring fans.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, it looked as though De La Hoya was in for
another easy victory. He looked sharp in the opening round with
body shots that punctuated the crisp jab that has always been the
fundamental skill in his repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Ouartey grinned, almost with contempt. If he
respected De La Hoya, it wasn't evident. But where there wasn't
respect, there was rust. Quartey hadn't fought in the 16 months
since he struggled to a draw with Jose Luis Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya decided to test him early in an apparent attempt to
see whether inactivity had eroded the African's skills. In the
second, it looked as if De La Hoya's decision would pay dividends.
He landed a right hand that rocked Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   The early moments belonged to De La Hoya. But the third round
did not. Quartey was considered dangerous, and, suddenly, he showed
why.
</P>
<P>
   He landed a big hook that momentarily seemed to hurt De La Hoya,
whose cheekbones already were beginning to redden from a jab that
landed with stinging precision and power.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Quartey began to stage what looked like might end
in upset. But, first, he would hit the canvas. A big left hand from
De La Hoya put him there.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Quartey countered with an uppercut that put De La
Hoya on the seat of his black trunks.
</P>
<P>
   His left eye began to swell. His fans began to murmur.
</P>
<P>
   It was a complete departure from the moments before the opening
bell.
</P>
<P>
   The cheers for De La Hoya started early and lasted long. Before
the start of the third round in Oba Carr's bruising decision over
Frankie Randall, he appeared like a matinee idol on video screens
above the ring.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd erupted. Oscar was in the building.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Ike Quartey. Far from his native Ghana, he was a stranger
on a different continent. The boundaries, culture, people and
language belonged to DeLa Hoya. Only Oscar was spoken here.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey almost slipped into the ring unnoticed. He wore a gold
robe trimmed in the red and green of Ghana's national flag. A song
about a lion pounded on the speakers.
</P>
<P>
   But who was listening? Who cared? Quartey, the obscure
welterweight, was the invisible challenger as he danced a few
hesitant steps past a mariachi band that was waiting to serenade
the man who would step into the ring like a king unto his throne. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
