<HEADLINE>
WRITETHRU _ DISREGARD EARLIER VERSION 
 CLUTCH WHEN IT COUNTS  
 CHAPMAN EARNS REDEMPTION IN OT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Just when the 19,023 fans at America West Arena were
starting to think Rex Chapman had turned into Mr. Klutz, he
suddenly returned to Mr. Clutch.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting only five of 19 shots in regulation, turning the
ball over five times and looking skyward for redemption about a
dozen times, Chapman bailed the Suns out when they needed him most
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   He scored 12 of his 23 points in overtime and the Suns escaped
the Los Angeles Clippers _ barely _ 107-104.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't normally like praying for shots to go in,'' Chapman
said. ``It was frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with Chapman missing, there was little doubt he would
be on the floor at the end if the game's outcome was in question.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the kind of guy you don't give up on,'' said Suns Coach
Danny Ainge. ``He's huge for our team, and he showed it down the
stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Chapman won so many games last season with late-game heroics,
``USA'' ``Today'' dubbed him the the new ``Mr. Clutch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to stick with him no matter how many shots he misses
until he's 50 years old,'' said Suns guard Jason Kidd. ``I know
he's going to make them sooner or later, and he'd do the same thing
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, the Suns (3-2) came out of a four-game
homestand with two wins and now face three games in three nights on
the road starting Monday night in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   And they probably never should have needed overtime to get by
the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns led by nine in the fourth quarter and still had a
seven-point lead with 1:52 to go after Chapman hit a jump shot on
an assist from Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clippers reeled off seven points in the final 1:07, with
Maurice Taylor sending it to overtime by hitting one of two free
throws with 11.3 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   After the Clippers' Lamond Murray, who led Los Angeles with 26
points, missed badly on the first shot of overtime, Chapman
connected with one of his patented runners from 14 feet and the
game was on.
</P>
<P>
   He added a pair of free throws a moment later, then connected on
his second three-point basket of the game with 2:36 to go in the
extra period for a 100-93 Phoenix lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns, who blew a nine-point fourth quarter lead, nearly let
the Clippers survive again in the overtime. James Robinson's
three-point field goal with 1:40 to go got the winless Clippers
(0-4) within two.
</P>
<P>
   It was still two with 45 seconds to go after Sherman Douglas's
running shot, but the Clippers were called for an illegal defense
with 29 seconds to go, and Chapman hit the resulting technical foul
free throw. The Suns had the ball and a three-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers were forced to foul, and Chapman missed the first
of two free throws with 27 seconds to go. But he made the second to
ice it.
</P>
<P>
   It was a terrific ending for what had been a long night for
Chapman, who has been struggling since returning from a hamstring
injury that caused him to miss training camp, the preseason and the
regular-season opener.
</P>
<P>
   He went to watch his 6-year-old son Zeke play earlier for
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Zeke's game for some pointers today,'' he said.
``His team won 40-16 and he had 28 (points). At halftime, it was
20-6. Zeke had 20. They wouldn't let him play in the fourth
quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Ainge might have had similar thoughts about Zeke's dad, but even
on his worst nights, Chapman is the Suns best player when defenses
turn up the heat. Shawn Respert played most of the fourth quarter,
and played well. But Ainge went back to Chapman.
</P>
<P>
   And he came through in the overtime.
</P>
<P>
   But give forward Clifford Robinson an assist. He put the Suns in
position to win the game without an overtime or help from Chapman.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's defensive activity sparked the Suns going early at
the start of the fourth quarter, and he scored 14 of his
season-high 23 points in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give the Clippers credit,'' Robinson said.
``They're a good young team, and they fought hard. We just made a
few more plays at the end. Rex hit some big shots for us in
overtime, and we pulled it out.''
</P>
<P>
   All the Suns have been trying to keep Chapman loose during his
struggles, a nd Robinson couldn't resist one jab.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took enough shots, he should have been able to get the
cobwebs out,'' Robinson said, laughing.
</P>
</TEXT>
