<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-OWNER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURKE ANTICIPATES BIG LOSS ON COYOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Coyotes will lose $10 million this season,
according to owner Richard Burke, who is expecting total financial
losses of at least $50 million by the time the NHL team's lease
expires at America West Arena in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we've got to remain highly competitive just to stay
alive until then,'' said Burke, who is trying to eventually pull
out of the downtown arena and build a 20,000-seat hockey arena in
south Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Burke contends the Coyotes' lease arrangement at the arena, with
its obstructed-view seats and limits on revenues to be made at the
site, makes the red ink inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said Saturday that the hard cash losses likely will
preclude General Manager Bobby Smith from actively seeking a
high-priced player by next month's trading deadline. He also said
the team will make only a ``minor dent'' in lost revenues if the
Coyotes advance beyond the first round of the playoffs for the
first time in 12 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to lose a huge amount of money again this year, an
unaffordable amount, really, over the long term,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That being said, we have the sixth-lowest payroll in the
league and, as (NHL) Commissioner (Gary) Bettman pointed out, we
have more wins per dollars-spent than anybody in the league. That's
a real credit to the front office. Plus, we're 25th in non-payroll
expenses (the third-lowest in the 27-team NHL), which is a tribute
to the other half of the front office (for keeping spending
down).''
</P>
<P>
   In a change from comments made Thursday night, Burke said
Saturday that he has no plans to move the team out of the state,
regardless of the outcome of the proposed $624 million Los Arcos
Mall redevelopment plan, which would feature a 20,000-seat hockey
arena for the team, in addition to a conference, retail and
entertainment complex on 92 acres at Scottsdale and McDowell roads.
</P>
<P>
   A public referendum on the project is scheduled for a May 18
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable it will get done,'' Burke said. ``I have been
from the first time we looked at it. The reasons are the same now
as then. One, it's the right place to put it. This is a piece of
commercial property, an arena, that will make the project good for
everybody _ the community, our fans, the city of Scottsdale and
us.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Burke had mentioned ``Plan B'' _ considering a move
out of state _ if the referendum didn't go the Coyotes' way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a Plan B. This is it,'' Burke said Saturday. ``We
don't have any expectations that it isn't going to work. We are not
going to look elsewhere. We're committed to being here.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke said about 40 percent of the $10 million in losses the
Coyotes are bracing for is directly related to the loss of revenue
from 4,500 sight-obstructed seats at America West Arena, which sell
for about $10 apiece. Hockey capacity at the arena is 16,210.
</P>
<P>
   Burke blames himself and Jerry Colangelo, the city-appointed
landlord of the arena who lured him to Phoenix. He said Colangelo
was not truthful about the number of quality seats for ice hockey
at the arena. He also said his group should have done a better job
of checking it firsthand before signing a five-year lease agreement
there after purchasing the Winnipeg Jets and moving them to Phoenix
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their financial shortcoming off the ice, the Coyotes
have cruised to the second-best overall record in the Western
Conference and are challenging Dallas and Philadelphia for best
record overall. However, Burke said fans probably can forget about
the club going after a superstar like Calgary's Theo Fleury before
the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby's put together a strong team and I think we're as good
as anybody,'' said Burke, whose club improved to 29-13-10 with a
4-1 victory Saturday over red-hot Colorado. ``But (trading for a $4
million-$6 million player) is not realistic. There simply are
limits in our case.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if Bob needs to make a responsible move at the trading
deadline to get this team over the top, I've told him he can do it.
That doesn't mean taking on somebody with a $5 million salary. But
if it's something reasonable, my guess is he'll do it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
