<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON, MANNING STAR IN SUNS' 6TH MAN ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA may have to change its Sixth Man Award to something
different, like the Sixth Men Award.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have last season's Sixth Man winner,  &UR; Danny Manning.
And another Suns forward,  &UR; Clifford Robinson, won the same award
for the 1993 season.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson started the first three games this season at small
forward, but Suns Coach  &UR; Danny Ainge moved him to the bench to
provide defense and scoring behind center  &UR; Luc Longley and power
forward  &UR; Tom Gugliotta.
</P>
<P>
   And Manning also is coming off the bench while recuperating from
a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was particularly instrument in the Suns 107-104
overtime victory against the Clippers. He scored 14 of his 23
points in the fourth quarter to help the Suns build a nine-point
lead in regulation that the Clippers ultimately overcame to force
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to knock down the shots when I had open
opportunities and be more aggressive when I had the ball,''
Robinson said. ``The last couple of games, I haven't been as
aggressive as I usually am. I was just trying to make things
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He started it with his defensive play, and guarded three
different front-line positions at different times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny (Ainge) told me he might have me guard five different
guys, so be ready,'' Robinson said. ``I'm always going to be ready
to play defense. That's part of my game. I wouldn't feel
comfortable being out there and not being a force on defense.'' &QL; 
McCloud out &QL; 
Forward  &UR; George McCloud missed the game after his sprained right
ankle failed to respond well enough to treatment. Ainge said it
wasn't just a precaution to get McCloud ready for a
three-games-in-three-nights trip that starts Monday in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might not even play in the next three games,'' Ainge said.
``It's that sore. I don't think it's a two-week type of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   With McCloud out, Ainge started  &UR; Chris Morris at small forward
because he wants to keep Robinson and Manning in their roles off
the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Morris responded with seven points and five rebounds in only 15
minutes. &QL; 
Kandi Man &QL; 
 &UR; Michael Olowokandi, the first player taken in the 1998 NBA draft,
made his first career start for the Clippers and finished with nine
points and seven rebounds in 34 minutes. He got into early foul
trouble and wasn't much of a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted Michael in there because (the Suns) start Luc
(Longley) at that spot,'' said Clippers Coach  &UR; Chris Ford. ``It
would be easier for him to guard Luc.''
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi said nothing has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because I was starting didn't mean that I was going to
play more of a role,'' he said. ``It was mainly to match up against
Longley.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
