<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4898 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-QUARTEY-     02-14 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-QUARTEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUARTEY PUTS UP A FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ In the end, the man who wanted to win more did.
</P>
<P>
   At the finish of a close and painful confrontation, Oscar De La
Hoya dropped his relentless challenger, Ike Quartey, with a
crushing left hook to the chin in the opening seconds of the 12th
round, sending the former World Boxing Association champion
skidding on the seat of his pants into the ropes and skidding over
the cliff of defeat.
</P>
<P>
   When Quartey got up, De La Hoya went after him with a relentless
fury, pinning him on the ropes and bombing him with at least 20
unanswered punches. Quartey refused to go down again but he was out
on his feet, wobbling back into the ropes in search of an emergency
exit no boxing ring contains.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time he was done, so was De La Hoya, who had punched
himself out in a furious search for the knockout that might have
quieted all of his critics and had nothing left to finish his
challenger with. Both spent the final minute of one of the best
welterweight fights in years walking around without punching, a
quiet concession that each had spent all his armaments in the
effort to win the World Boxing Council welterweight title.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, De La Hoya (30-0) won a split decision, with judge
Larry O'Connell of England having Quartey a 115-114 winner while
John Keane, also of England, had De La Hoya winning, 116-113, and
Ken Morita of Japan had De La Hoya a 116-112 victor. The Globe card
also had De La Hoya in control, 116-112.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Quartey (34-1-1) claimed the usual fiction that he
had won, saying, ``You saw the fight. You know I won the fight, but
you knew I couldn't win a decision in Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   Quartey gave De La Hoya his toughest 36 minutes in the ring, a
battle that led the champion to say he had no interest in a
rematch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' De La Hoya said. ``There are bigger and
better fights out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Also easier ones, as De La Hoya surely knows.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey's jab immediately began to redden De La Hoya's face, but
the champion retaliated with some solid body shots that left
Quartey smiling and unmoved. The fight remained a cat-and-mouse
game until Quartey hit him with a solid right hand late in Round 2
that De La Hoya answered with a toe-to-toe confrontation that
Quartey won at the bell.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya finally made his presence felt late in the third
round when he landed a blistering left-right combination that took
the smile off Quartey's face and kept his punches well short of the
mark for the next 45 seconds. Late in that stanza Quartey dropped a
hard right and a harder left on De La Hoya and the champion quaked
for an instant, but he came back in Round 4 and had Quartey
retreating.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey had openings late in the next round to land two right
hands but was short with both. Round 6 proved De La Hoya's
prediction that both men could do damage was true when he dropped
Quartey with a left hook seconds in, then grew too bold and was
dropped by a Quartey left hook after De La Hoya missed with an
uppercut.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey's powerful jab and hammering right had begun to do
damage to the champion's face, which no longer had the Golden Boy
looks. By Round 9, De La Hoya's left cheek was turning blue and his
nose was swollen, but the fight remained close because De La Hoya
was busier longer, even though it was clear Quartey's heavy punches
were more effective.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey landed his best punch of the fight late in Round 9 when
he blasted home a right hand that snapped the champion's head back.
But when De La Hoya returned fire the next round with a solid
combination, Quartey backed off and did not come forward again.
</P>
<P>
   His slowing pace would continue until he ran into the blistering
punch that dropped him a second time. That one will be the punch
fight fans remember and Ike Quartey would like to forget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
