<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA SHOWS HIS HEART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ This wasn't how Oscar De La Hoya was supposed to
prove his greatness.
</P>
<P>
   He was supposed to dazzle Ike Quartey with his
once-in-a-lifetime skills, wear down the challenger and then knock
him out in the late rounds here Saturday, or so many believed.
Then, having thrashed the fighter deemed his first serious
challenge, he'd walk away unmarked and seemingly invincible.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen that way. Not by a longshot.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, De La Hoya took a giant step toward superstardom with
something that isn't learned over years in the gym _ his heart _ in
what turned out to be an unforgettable battle of wills that
could've gone either way in the end.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth round, Quartey, who had just risen from the canvas
himself, knocked down De La Hoya with a right hand. As he got up,
it seemed as if he might be easy prey for the challenger. He was
hurt, his left eye was nearly closed and his confidence seemed
shaken.
</P>
<P>
   Each and everyone in a packed Thomas &AMP; Mack Center, almost all
on the side of De La Hoya, was thinking the unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya's response?
</P>
<P>
   A display of inspiring courage. As he said afterward in a
monumental understatement _ ``I'm no quitter'' _ and set about
proving it.
</P>
<P>
   It took him a few rounds, but he shook off the effects of the
ill-fated sixth, dug in and seized victory in a way that would've
made the greatest ring warriors in history proud.
</P>
<P>
   In the deciding rounds, the 10th, 11th and 12th, it was De La
Hoya who threw and landed more punches. It was De La Hoya who
seemed to have more energy. It was De La Hoya, not Quartey, who
decided he wasn't leaving the ring a loser.
</P>
<P>
   The final round will go down as one of the greatest in boxing
history.
</P>
<P>
   With the fight apparently in doubt, De La Hoya landed his best
punch: A picture-perfect left hook that sent Quartey to the canvas
and brought the crowd to its feet for the remainder of the contest.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was sheer mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   The two stood in Quartey's corner and exchanged blows for what
seemed to be a solid minute until they both ran out of steam. De La
Hoya got the better of it and, his fans hoped, he did enough to
win.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, De La Hoya won all three rounds on all cards
to claim a split-decision victory and retain both his title and
perfect record (30-0).
</P>
<P>
   Again, it wasn't the dominating performance we've come to expect
from De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   But remember who Quartey is. He was !ital!not!off! an opponent
handpicked to make the champion look good, as so many were in the
past. He was recognized as one of the best fighters in the world, a
ferocious power-puncher with excellent boxing skills and absolutely
no fear.
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of many, he's a monster. And he looked it on
Saturday. No one stands up to the Golden Boy the way he did unless
he, too, has uncommon courage.
</P>
<P>
   That's what makes the manner in which De La Hoya won so
remarkable and so unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   Had he won easily, he would've taken a monumental step in what
is turning out to be a monumental career.
</P>
<P>
   However, he wouldn't have made the statement he made on
Saturday. People admire sheer talent, which De La Hoya certainly
has, but they cherish someone who can overcome adversity against a
worthy adversary and emerge victorious, as De La Hoya did so
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, De La Hoya hasn't risen to the level of a Roberto
Duran or a Sugar Ray Leonard. All the ingredients are there,
though: The God-given ability, more experience with every fight
and, perhaps most important, the guts.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, he has great performances in his future. Fighters
like Felix Trinidad, like Jose Luis Lopez, like Fernando Vargas or
like David Reid probably will bring even more out of De La Hoya.
After all, he's only 26 years old.
</P>
<P>
   But it's going to be difficult to top Saturday, the night De La
Hoya chose victory over defeat. When we look back on De La Hoya's
career, it might be his defining triumph. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
