<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-CANUCKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS SINK DEEPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ The good ship Boston Bruins is
taking on water.
</P>
<P>
   After a shutout victory in Edmonton Tuesday night, the Bruins
appeared in decent shape at one game above .500. That all changed
in a hurry as the team suffered back-to-back losses to Calgary
Friday and the Vancouver Canucks, 3-1, Saturday night at GM Place.
After falling to two of the worst teams in the Western Conference,
the Bruins are back to one game under .500 with a sorry road mark
of 9-15-3.
</P>
<P>
   As troubling as their subpar play is, injuries also are
mounting. The Bruins lost defenseman Darren Van Impe to a shoulder
separation Tuesday night, left wing Sergei Samsonov to a charley
horse Friday and Saturday night, checker P.J. Axelsson sprained his
right wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The score probably should've been more than what it was,''
said coach Pat Burns, who had little to say after the disappointing
defeat. ``We weren't that much in the game. We circled the wagons
for a while, but we just didn't have enough elements tonight to put
on a better fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins didn't come out nearly as confident as they had a
night earlier in Calgary. They struggled mightily in their own end
and were very fortunate to be tied, 1-1, heading into the first
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Mogilny, who has endured a prolonged scoring slump
this season, put the Canucks on the board at 7:16 with his sixth
goal of the year. Mogilny, who had gone into the game with one goal
in 21 games, took a pass from Dave Gagner and fired a quick wrister
from the left circle that sailed over goalie Rob Tallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins actually received a huge assist from Vancouver in
scoring their goal on the power play. Anson Carter tried to send a
backhand pass across to Joe Thornton. Fortunately for Boston,
Canucks defenseman Bryan McCabe swept his stick across and put the
puck into his own net past goalie Garth Snow to tie the game at the
11-minute mark.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver, playing without captain Mark Messier (knee injury)
and defenseman Ed Jovanovski (broken foot), outshot the Bruins,
10-5, in the period with several decent scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The Canucks took the lead early in the second period on a truly
astonishing goal by left wing Todd Bertuzzi, likely to be seen on
highlights for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   The mammoth forward _ listed at 6 feet 3 inches, 230 pounds,
took a pass from defenseman Mattias Ohlund and skated through
virtually the entire Boston lineup on his way to the net. Just
before arriving, he met up with defenseman Hal Gill and stiff-armed
Gill to the ice, kept control of the puck, and smacked a forehand
shot into the top corner for the 2-1 advantage at the 33-second
mark. It was the fourth goal in the last five games for Bertuzzi,
whom the Canucks are hoping will take up the offensive slack with
Messier out a month or more.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins lost Axelsson for a time in the middle period when he
was pitchforked into the boards by former Bruin Jamie Huscroft at
2:48. Axelsson returned later, playing a total of five shifts in
the period, but left again and didn't play in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Boston had its chances in the second, the best a point-blank
shot by Carter after he took a centering pass from Antti Laaksonen
at 11:48 on the power play, but Snow turned it away. The Bruins'
fortunes took a turn for the worse early in the third when center
Dave Scatchard converted a Bill Muckalt rebound at 4:38. Tallas
stopped Muckalt's bid but Scatchard put a backhander through his
legs for the 3-1 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
