r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-OSCAR-WRITETHRU-L     02-14 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-OSCAR-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOSE CALL FOR DE LA HOYA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MORALES  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Oscar De La Hoya wondered if Ike Quartey was good
enough to stand up to a man who would stand up to him.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey was able to stand up to De La Hoya on Saturday, but not
enough to dethrone a man who now could be considered the best in
the world, pound-for-pound, even by those who have refused to adorn
him with that label.
</P>
<P>
   In a thriller that indeed matched the Suqar Ray Leonard-Thomas
Hearns welterweight title bout in 1981, De La Hoya retained his WBC
welterweight title with a split decision over Quartey of Ghana on
at the Thomas &AMP; Mack Center.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey won on Larry O'Connell's scorecard 115-114 but De La
Hoya took the other two, 116-113 and 116-112, on the scorecards of
John Keane and Ken Morita, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The 12th-round was one for the books, and it was all De La Hoya,
who flattened Quartey with a wicked left hook early, then
pulverized him on the ropes for 40 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey, who fell to 34-0-1, somehow stayed on his feet. Referee
Mitch Halpern somehow restrained himself from stopping the bout.
But Quartey showed his mettle, and once De La Hoya ran out of gas,
Quartey even connected with a decent right hand coming off the
ropes.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, 26, is now 30-0. He will meet Oba Carr on May 22 in
what will be his seventh defensive bout; Saturday night was his
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want action-packed fights, and I gave it to them,'' De
La Hoya said. ``He was a very tough opponent. He gave me a good
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Quartey was bitterly disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won the fight,'' he said. ``You saw the fight, the world saw
the fight. You saw the decision. I thought I did enough to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I knew I couldn't win a decision in Las Vegas. You have to
respect Oscar. He is the champion, but I thought I did enough to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps boxing analyst Gil Clancy said it best regarding De La
Hoya's performance, in which he showed he can take a big punch from
a big hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the greatest welterweight title fights I've
ever seen,'' Clancy said. ``Oscar proved he is a great champion.''
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of punches landed in the first five rounds,
but the real fireworks didn't begin until the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya dropped Quartey with a right-left combination within
the first 20 seconds of the round. Quartey was up quickly, then
flattened De La Hoya with a left uppercut. De La Hoya also rose
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   But Quartey continued the assault and won the round by landing
some of his hard jabs and a couple of rights.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey applauded De La Hoya's ability to take his best punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``That did not surprise me,'' Quartey said. ``He is a champion
and he came to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Said De La Hoya: ``This guy hits hard. He is a very powerful
puncher. But I said to myself, `Hey, I'm going to come right back.'
I'm no quitter. I proved to the world I can go up against the very
best.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya seemed to get back on track in the seventh, though he
did not win the round convincingly. However, in the eighth round,
after having absorbed some punishment, De La Hoya staggered Quartey
with a powerful jab, snapping back the challenger's head.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya opened the ninth with a five-punch combination, then
quit throwing punches for some time. Quartey began to score with
his jab, although he also was short on several. De La Hoya
responded with a combination, but Quartey landed two rights.
</P>
<P>
   In the twelfth, De La Hoya connected with the big left hook,
dropping Quartey with a thud, and it looked like De La Hoya might
stop Quartey. But Quartey, with heart to burn, was once again on
his feet in just seconds.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya went for the kill. During the long beating he gave
Quartey on the ropes before De La Hoya became tired, Quartey took
several more hard shots to the head.
</P>
<P>
   Twice Halpern edged toward the fighters, as if he were going to
stop it, but he pulled away. De La Hoya suddenly stopped punching,
and Quartey landed a light right.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 12th round I was surprised Ike was didn't go down
again,'' De La Hoya said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Clancy: ``I was worried that Oscar was going to kill him.
He landed some left hooks that I have never seen anybody be able to
take.''
</P>
<P>
   Quartey was not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did everything,'' he said. ``Oscar did nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Dino Duva, Quartey's promoter, said Quartey's reaction is
normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ike is very upset,'' Duva said. ``He thought he won the fight.
After a war like that, he has the right to be upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, De La Hoya laid claim to best in the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he said, ``I am the best pound-for-pound fighter in the
world.'' &UR; !end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
