<SLUG> BC-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KWAN COASTS TO TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
 FIGURE SKATING-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Maybe she should have just mailed in her
practice tapes from Lake Arrowhead and saved on the airfare. Nobody
but Michelle Kwan was going to beat Michelle Kwan here Saturday
night _ and nobody did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't really matter who I compete against,'' the
18-year-old Kwan shrugged after she'd blown away 13-year-old Naomi
Nari Nam and Angela Nikodinov inside the Delta Center to win her
third US women's figure skating title in four years. ``It was just
one of those performances where you just went out there and let it
go. It didn't matter what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody since Jill Trenary (1987, 89-90) had won three crowns and
this one was never in doubt. With Olympic gold medalist Tara
Lipinski gone pro and former champion Nicole Bobek absent with an
ovarian ailment, Kwan's main challengers were middle schoolers.
Probably not since 1975, when Dorothy Hamill defeated Wendy Burge
and Kath Malmberg, had a defending titlist faced less of a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Kwan saw it that way. ``I don't think I'm dominating
skating in any way,'' she insisted, even though she hasn't lost an
event since the Olympics. ``You never know who's going to come up.
You know there are people out there. You always have to keep on top
of your game and keep improving. Because you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwan knew about Nam, the 4-foot-6-inch dervish who resembles the
Kwan of five years ago. ``Adorable,'' declared Kwan. ``Very cute.''
She knew about the 18-year-old Nikodinov, who'd been fifth last
year. And she knew about Sarah Hughes, the US junior champion who
finished fourth here.
</P>
<P>
   Making the team for next month's world championships in Helsinki
was a dream for Hughes, an impossibility for Nam. Though
13-year-olds are banned from the worlds, where the minimum age is
15, Hughes gets to go because she's a world junior medalist.
</P>
<P>
   So even though Nam finished second, she stays home. And she'll
stay home again next year unless she can make the world junior
podium. ``It's a deplorable instance of age discrimination,'' said
John A.W. Nicks, Nam's coach.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for Nam, who fell in Thursday's short program, whacking
her head on the ice and straining her neck, it was enough to skate
cleanly Saturday night and steal the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sort of nervous, but I just had to block it out of my
mind and not think about what I did Thursday,'' said Nam, who was
skating in the novices only two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Though Nam had the easiest program among the contenders _ only
five triple jumps and no lutz among them _ she zipped through it
with grace and verve and brought the crowd to its feet with the
night's most rousing ovation. ``I just wanted to stay out there,''
said Nam. ``I wish I could just stop time and freeze.''
</P>
<P>
   The only question after that was whether Nikodinov could climb
out of sixth place and grab the third spot for Helsinki. She was
far from stellar, breaking off a combination and doubling a triple
lutz. But it was enough to vault her past Hughes and 16-year-old
Erin Pearl of Scarborough, Maine, who performed nicely in her
senior debut.
</P>
<P>
   That was the only suspense on a night that Kwan owned merely by
showing up. She had breezed through the year, winning six open
events including the world professional title, and came here as the
heaviest women's favorite in two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Once she landed her triple lutz combination and the triple
toe-triple toe that she hadn't tried in two years, Kwan was off and
winging. By the time she flopped on her triple lutz near the end,
they already were getting another gold medal ready.
</P>
<P>
   For Kwan, this was merely a dress rehearsal for the 2002
Olympics, which will be held in the same building. ``I didn't get a
chance to skate in Nagano before the Olympics,'' she said. ``It's
good to know my way around the place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
