<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK FOR DODGERS IN CACTUS LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It really wasn't that long ago that the Cactus League was
basically on a respirator. There was growing talk of every club
moving its spring training headquarters to Florida, where many
cities were making pitches to lure the eight clubs that trained in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's moving from Tucson to Florida after the 1992 Cactus
League season was seen as a possible start of the migration to the
Sunshine State. Thankfully, those ideas quickly disappeared thanks
to some forward-thinking people who decided to revamp the spring
training landscape in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's addition of the Maryvale complex, home to the
Milwaukee Brewers, was the latest in a series of renovations and
new stadiums being built in the state. In recent years, Arizona has
seen a new complex built in Peoria (home to Seattle and San Diego),
Tucson (home to the Diamondbacks and White Sox), Scottsdale
(Giants) and complete renovations done in Mesa (Cubs), Tempe
(Angels) and Phoenix (Athletics).
</P>
<P>
   In Anaheim's  &UR; Mo Vaughn and Colorado Manager  &UR; Jim Leyland, two
giants in the game will arrive for their first Cactus League spring
this year. But those two will pale in comparison if the Cactus
League is able to lure the biggest name ever next year.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus is that the Los Angeles Dodgers will finally make
the financially sound move to relocate their spring training from
Vero Beach, Fla., to the Valley, probably in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   With that move will come yet another new spring complex and the
belief that other clubs may follow in the years to come. All of
which would be great news to baseball fans in Arizona. &QL; 
Short-term memory loss? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Diamondbacks starter  &UR; Willie Blair, last seen with a 4-15
record the day he was traded to the New York Mets on July 31, seems
happy and content to be back in Detroit, where he enjoyed his
finest season in 1997, winning 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't expect it would happen, though,'' Blair said
of his off-season trade from the Mets to the Tigers. ``I was very
surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair emphasized that his leaving Detroit last year had
everything to do with economics. Arizona offered Blair a three-year
deal worth $11.5 million, while Detroit came in at $10 million for
the same length.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anyone faced with that decision would have made the
same one I did,'' Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's financial situation may have been set up in Arizona, but
little else. He started the season 0-7 and it soon looked like he
was headed toward becoming a rare 20-game loser.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got to be a joke among our pitchers,'' Blair said. ``If I
didn't throw a shutout, I didn't win the game. My numbers were bad,
but they were deceiving.''
</P>
<P>
   True, the Diamondbacks offense was near the bottom in the
league, but that doesn't mean he got jobbed every time out. In his
four victories, the D-Backs averaged nearly eight runs per game.
However, Blair did allow at least five runs in nine starts. And his
27 home runs allowed came in just 23 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Detroit, I was a lot more relaxed because the Tigers were
scoring some runs for me and I got on a roll. But with Arizona,
every pitch I made was the biggest pitch in the game.'' &QL; 
Trivial question &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's pretty much a no-brainer to know Baltimore's  &UR; Cal Ripken
has played the most games in the 1990s. Ripken enters this season
having played 1,389 games this decade. Who is next on the list? &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Texas first baseman  &UR; Rafael Palmeiro, who will start the season
having played in 1,368 games this decade. Palmeiro, a teammate of
Ripken's the last five years who has never been on the disabled
list, has missed only 22 games in the 1990s. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; The time's they are definitely
 &UR; a-changing: For the first time since their days at Brooklyn's
Ebbet's Field, the Dodgers will advertise on their outfield walls.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; On the other hand, it won't be all bad: Dodgers players will be
able to select a commemorative patch of a past Dodger hero to wear
on his uniform.  &UR; Eric Karros will wear one of  &UR; Gil Hodges and  &UR; Eric
Young is one of a few who have picked  &UR; Jackie Robinson. Wonder if
anyone will take  &UR; Steve Sax?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Freddie Patek.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What's the message, go find a lake? The 1999 Florida Marlins
pocket schedule has a white background with nothing but a fishing
cap filled with pins on it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; My bad: Thanks to all who called to let me know  &UR; Tom
 &UR; Seaver is not 58. Nonetheless, he will turn 55 this year and that
still sounds too old for Mr. Met. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
Seattle, the overwhelming choice to win the AL West last year,
returns only 12 players to spring camp who were on the opening day
roster a year ago. And if  &UR; Bobby Ayala is traded or released, as
expected, the number will be reduced to 11.
</P>
<P>
   They can talk all they want about being a younger, quicker club
in 1999. The reality of the Baltimore Orioles is they will remain
one of the oldest clubs in ball. Catcher  &UR; Charles Johnson (27) will
be the only regular under 30 on the opening day roster. Of the 25
projected players on the roster, 21 will be at least 30.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dennis Martinez retired last week, telling a reporter in his
native Nicaragua the news. The Atlanta Braves, who gave Martinez
his lone chance to become the winningest Latin-born pitcher, were
not happy, at least privately. The Braves wanted to invite Martinez
to become a coach. At the very least, they wanted to hold the
retirement press conference.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sparky Anderson was voted into the Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame
last week. Anderson guided the Big Red Machine to four World Series
appearances and two titles during a seven-year span in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis slugger  &UR; Mark McGwire will appear on the Feb. 22
episode of ``Mad About You.'' McGwire, who will play himself, is
the object of  &UR; Helen Hunt's character's affections in the show.
McGwire will appear bare-chested in the show.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bill Mazeroski, arguably the greatest defensive second baseman
ever, will rejoin Pittsburgh as a spring training coach. Pirates
infielders, who made 95 errors last season, could use the help.
Mazeroski, who won eight Gold Gloves, is expected to be named to
the Hall of Fame by the veteran's committee on March 2. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
Should  &UR; Wil Cordero win the everyday designated hitter's job during
spring training, Cleveland might be willing to listen to offers for
highly-rated prospects  &UR; Richie Sexson,  &UR; Alex Ramirez or  &UR; Jacob
Cruz. The price would be a starting pitcher. Listen up,
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly a long-shot, but don't discount the possibility
of Seattle having 19-year-old flame-thrower  &UR; Ryan Anderson in its
opening day rotation. When asked of the possibility, Manager
 &UR; Lou Piniella said, ``Let's see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia appears to be cooling on the idea of signing  &UR; Orel
Hershiser to a 1999 contract. The biggest reason is trying to
justify giving Hershiser $2 million and not opening up that
rotation spot for one of the Phillies young pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   With Minnesota facing an $18 million payroll heading into spring
training, the club is facing the task of dealing away closer  &UR; Rick
Aguilera and outfielder  &UR; Marty Cordova to reach the desired $11
million level.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego closer  &UR; Trevor Hoffmann, who was close to signing a
three-year $15 million deal several months ago, has changed his
mind after watching events in the past few weeks. Hoffman now wants
a four-year deal for $32 million and he wants a no-trade clause.
</P>
<P>
   If the Brewers get off to a bad start, Milwaukee's
 &UR; Phil Garner is the first to recognize he may be the first manager
fired this year. He will not, however, tolerate that as an excuse
for poor play from his players. ``I'm not worried about losing my
job, so they shouldn't be, either.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
