<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEONARD REPRE SENTS WHAT DE LA HOYA WANTS TO BE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Officially,  &UR; Sugar Ray Leonard was part of the
promotional team for  &UR; Oscar De La Hoya's welterweight clash
Saturday night with  &UR; Ike Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   Symbolically, Leonard was much more.
</P>
<P>
   He represents what De La Hoya hopes to become.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard faced a string of tough opponents _  &UR; Roberto Duran,
Thomas
 &UR; Hearns, Marvin Hagler and  &UR; Wilfredo Benitez. He defeated most of
them. More important, he was confronted with adversity in a loss to
Duran and eventually prevailed with a victory in the rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Until the confrontation with Quartey, De La Hoya had yet to
withstand Leonard's trial by fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very blessed to have had a Benitez, Duran and Hearns,''
said Leonard, who was joined by Hearns in promotional work. ``The
only way to be considered great is to fight great fighters.''
</P>
<P>
   A postscript: Hearns and Leonard fought to a controversial draw
in a rematch of Leonard's classic victory in the first bout.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, Leonard concedes what has always been argued:
</P>
<P>
   Hearns won the second fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Ray Leonard, I accept that,'' Hearns said. &QL; 
Hostile takeover
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya's move from marquee fighter to boxer-promoter figures
to be official sometime after Saturday night's bout.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marc Ratner, executive director of the Nevada Athletic
Commission said the state's attorneys first have to review an
agreement for De La Hoya to join  &UR; Bob Arum in co-promotion of
future bouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure exactly how Oscar can be a partner in a
promotion,'' Ratner said.
</P>
<P>
   Arum said the agreement is for only one fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it works, and works well, we'll extend it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The joint venture has been fueling speculation that De La Hoya
eventually will leave Arum.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Spanish-speaking media, a misunderstanding
over an Arum option for a rematch with Quartey angered De La Hoya.
It was later explained that Arum retains that option for most
fights in the event of an upset.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, De La Hoya kept the rumor mill working overtime by
saying: ``I told them jokingly I am going to get rid of Bob Arum
and re-sign him as a partner.'' &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   On the undercard: World Boxing Council super-bantamweight champ
 &UR; Erik
 &UR; Morales (32-0, 26 KOs) of Tijuana threw a beautiful right hand for
a second-round knockout of Puerto Rican challenger  &UR; Angel Chacon
(24-3, 14 KOs).
</P>
<P>
   Featherweight  &UR; Mia St. John, a former Playboy model, fought
motivation and  &UR; Amanda Skelton on Saturday night's undercard. Her
fold-out looks are her opponents' biggest target. ``They're
jealous,'' said St. John, who won a decision. ``They think I've
gotten where I am because I was a model.''
</P>
<P>
   Quartey trained at the Pensacola, Fla., gym that is home for
light-heavyweight champion  &UR; Roy Jones, Jr., who is De La Hoya's
rival in the ongoing pound-for-pound debate. ``People in Ghana know
who De La Hoya is,'' Quartey said before the opening bell. ``I'm
not that well-known in the U.S., but people will know my name
whether I knocked him out or not.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
