<HEADLINE>
NAU COASTS PAST MONTANA  
 LUMBERJACKS STILL IN BIG SKY HUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RORY FAUST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ It was senior night in the J. Lawrence Walkup
Skydome Saturday night, but the NAU seniors are hoping Saturday
night's 74-53 thrashing of Montana won't be their last home game of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lumberjacks (18-5, 10-2 Big Sky) fare well on their
season-ending four-game road trip, they could host the Big Sky
tournament for the third year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   NAU coach Ben Howland said the win was also important because
the Grizzlies had been playing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been playing tough lately,'' Howland said. ``They beat
Weber State (which is second in the Big Sky) handily last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael McNair led the Lumberjacks with 15 points and Casey
Frank added 12 points and six rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Montana cut NAU's 12-point halftime lead to 11 on a Cory Reiser
three-pointer five minutes into the second, but the Lumberjacks
widened the margin to 16 one minute later on Kawika Akina's three.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 47-34 with just over 12 minutes left, Montana
implemented a full-court trapping press in hopes of getting back
into the game, but Frank shattered those hopes with a dunk, which
widened the Lumberjacks advantage to 15 with 15:55 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way you want to break a trap,'' Frank said. ``That
made them get out of (the press) real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank's dunk sparked a 9-2 run, which put the Grizzlies away.
Ross Land's three pointer put NAU up 52-34 with 10:30 left, and
Akina's eight-foot leaner capped the run and increased the lead to
20 with seven minutes remaining in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Lumberjacks opened up their largest lead of the game, 71-44,
on Matt Gebhardt's fast break layup with 1:48 left.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams looked sloppy in the first half, but NAU managed to
pull away because of Montana's cold shooting. The Grizzlies shot 29
percent from the field in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Land's three-pointer with 8:27 left in the half gave the
Lumberjacks an 18-8 lead, and six minutes later Land's alley-oop to
Frank put NAU up by 15, 30-15.
</P>
<P>
   The teams traded free throws in the final two minutes of the
half, and NAU took a 32-18 into the break.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Olson, who scored all but six of Montana's 18 first half
points,finished with 16 points and five rebounds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
