<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ASU-ARIZONA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNOVERS DOOM DEVILS IN OVERTIME LOSS TO CATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Arizona State's guards held their own against
Arizona for 40 minutes Saturday night, giving the Sun Devils a
chance to snap their 11-game losing streak in the women's
basketball rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Then came overtime, the second consecutive OT game for ASU at
Wells Fargo Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The guards who committed just six turnovers in the first half
gave up six in the five-minute extra frame, UA scored the first
nine points in winning 76-67, and the streak now is a full six
years long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guards were hesitant (in overtime) and boom the game is
over,'' said ASU Coach Charli Turner Thorne, working four days
after giving birth to her first child. ``It was definitely an
experience issue. The bottom line is the team that was more
aggressive was going to win, and we got cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats (13-8, 8-4 Pac-10) opened OT with a three-pointer
by junior guard Lisa Griffith. Then sophomore guard Reshea Bristol,
replaced last week in the starting lineup by freshman Julie Brase,
took over.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Pickney stole Natalie Tucker's inlet pass for Rachel
Holt, resulting in a layup by Bristol, who sprained her right ankle
late in the first half. Bristol followed with a steal at half-court
and scored on another layup. Angela Lackey then batted a Tucker
pass to Griffith, who fed Bristol again for a 68-59 lead with half
of overtime gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like coming out after halftime,'' Bristol said of the
overtime burst. ``To have a 9-0 lead is unbelievable. We had to be
the aggressor.''
</P>
<P>
   Bristol finished with 20 points, the combined total for Griffith
and Felecity Willis. Lackey added 16.
</P>
<P>
   The win is critical to UA's drive for a third consecutive NCAA
Tournament berth. Even with a split of their three remaining
series, the Wildcats might be able to qualify although Coach Joan
Bonvicini thinks a minimum 4-2 finish is necessary. The stretch run
includes games against the Pac-10's top three: No. 12 UCLA, Oregon
and Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``We control out own destiny,'' Bonvicini said. ``Our strength
of schedule helps us. The tournament (committee) looks at the last
10 games, and we've won eight.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU (10-11, 4-8) must win four of its final six to register its
first winning season since 1992-93. That would require an upset of
one of the league's Big Three, but might be possible if freshman
forward Theresa Jantzen continues at her conference Player of the
Week level.
</P>
<P>
   Jantzen had season highs of 24 points and 16 rebounds, her third
double-double, and scored 13 consecutive ASU points in the second
half to help the Devils overcome a 12-0 run that put the Wildcats
up 54-43 and threatening to run away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still real young,'' Jantzen said. ``We know we can beat
them so easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not so easily, but realistically some day soon. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 0322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
