<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 03:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4909 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ARIZONA-LSU-AZR &LR;      02-14 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-LSU-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LSU PLAYS LIKE TEAMS OF PAST, SCARES UA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ It seemed like a good idea at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Coach Lute Olson takes advantage of the weeks of games
against Arizona State to schedule nationally televised games
against top-25 opponents, since the Wildcats have just the one
Pac-10 game those weeks. It doesn't hurt recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   When Olson and Dale Brown, then coach at Louisiana State, agreed
to play a home-and-home series, LSU was an annual fixture on the
national scene and was about to get _ it thought _ center Lester
Earl.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Brown has been forced out. The program has faced the
threat of NCAA sanctions over, among other things, the manner in
which Earl was recruited. He transferred to Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Tigers, under new coach John Brady, limped into
McKale Center on Saturday a game below .500 and on a five-game
skid, it seemed the game had lost its luster.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, LSU played like the team Olson expected to see when the
contract was signed, extending the 10th-ranked Wildcats to the
closing minute before they saved their 28th straight home win,
78-71. With it, the 10th-ranked Wildcats moved closer to their 12th
straight 20-win season and 15th straight NCAA Tournament bid.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Arizona's players seemed far more concerned with what
had happened to those teams that were playing Pac-10 games on
Saturday _ and for the Wildcats the news was good.
</P>
<P>
   The team just ahead of it, Stanford, and the one just behind it,
UCLA, lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched the Stanford game at home before we came over,''
said UA center A.J. Bramlett. ``That was big for us. We're now back
in control of our destiny in the Pac-10 and that's pretty
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   UA point guard Jason Terry, who tied a school record with seven
three-point baskets that carried him to 25 points, described the
turn of events as ``extra motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry acknowledged that it didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're right back in it,'' Terry said. ``We want to win
the Pac-10 title. Anything is still possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this game shows us that we still play to the level of the
team we're playing, and we can't do that. We came out lazy at both
ends. It was a lax effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Terry's three-pointers, which quieted each LSU rally
attempt, was one from two steps across midcourt that banked in and
gave UA a nine-point halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   The featured match-up between UA freshman power forward Michael
Wright and LSU's Stromile Swift was everything expected of two
players who were judged to be among the 15 best high school seniors
in the country last season.
</P>
<P>
   Swift, who scored 21 points _ the third straight game he has
established a career high _ and grabbed nine rebounds, cut
Arizona's lead to five when he tossed a jump hook over Wright with
2:47 to play.
</P>
<P>
   But Wright (15 points, 11 rebounds) retaliated by rebounding a
miss by Bramlett and scoring with 37 seconds left to give Arizona a
seven-point edge, all it needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the better players I've played against so far,''
Wright said. ``I played against him in high school and he's only
gotten better.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson had recruited Swift before learning that he had academic
difficulties. Olson then turned to Wright, who has become the
leading freshman scorer and rebounder in the Pac-10, and a possible
Freshman All-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``LSU had talked about canceling when the program went into a
bit of a decline and with the threat of sanctions,'' Olson said.
``Now Coach Brady has built it back up with a great freshman class
and they'll be in good shape when they get more experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
