<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Husband copes with loss of loved one, long romance
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At age 56, Jim Webster talks about his wife Marianne
with the passion of a 25-year-old. His eyes glisten when he recalls
the last time they biked together _ on a Florida beach, last
Easter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a oneness we felt that morning,'' he said, ``and we
talked about it. Our marriage was about sharing _ and not because
of any contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Five days later, on April 17, Marianne was biking in her
Dunwoody neighborhood when her totebag got tangled in the spokes of
her bicycle wheel. She took a fatal fall.
</P>
<P>
   For 30 years, they had done everything together _ sports,
cooking, kids, travel. But it was the routine everyday things that
lost meaning without her. No one to make the coffee for each
morning _ no one to share the newspaper. No one to tell him he's
loved. And the plants _ why isn't she there to water the darn
things?
</P>
<P>
   Webster still hasn't emptied the bedroom drawers, hasn't touched
the cosmetics on the dresser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see them and it's a sameness I'm not ready to leave. I don't
want anything to feel empty.''
</P>
<P>
   Marianne was in a coma after her accident. Webster made the hard
decision to remove the artificial life support. He and the two
grown children stayed by Marianne's bedside after they moved her to
the hospice. She died three days later. Daughter Emily discovered
early-blooming purple flowers outside the French doors to
Marianne's room moments after her death and brought some in. None
of them will ever forget that.
</P>
<P>
   Webster can smile now, laugh even, as he remembers his long
romance _ the times they flew kites with the kids, the fierce
tennis matches with each other (Marianne was a 1998 Atlanta doubles
champion), the music they liked, the making up after little spats.
</P>
<P>
   They both enjoyed classical works, Bach especially, but they had
favorite pop singers too. Once Webster and Marianne were listening
to Celine Dion's ``No living, No Loving Without You.''
</P>
<P>
   Marianne placed her hand on him gently. ``If you ever leave
me,'' she said. ``This is the way I'm going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Remembering makes him cry.
</P>
<P>
   Webster loved seeing Marianne find her own identity after years
of devoting herself to family. Men and women are on different life
cycles, he says. A CPA with his own firm, he'd arrived at a time
when he didn't want ``those 500 clients'' anymore. He wanted to
wind down. But Marianne was just getting started, and he admired
her new-found confidence. In addition to her run for the
Legislature, she was president-elect of a national women's
organization, Women in Action for New Directions (WAND).
</P>
<P>
   Webster finds comfort in his work on ``Marianne's Fund,''
started by WAND and the Webster family to raise money for the
issues Marianne cared about, the reduction of nuclear weapons,
environmental preservation and women in leadership. The fund has
$150,000 and an equal amount pledged. WAND has chapters all over
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Webster runs and works and savors time with close
friends. And spring will bring good things _ visits with Emily, a
University of Georgia graduate who works in Washington, and son
Jacob, who graduates from medical school in May. He'll be a
grandfather soon, too. Jacob and wife Susy don't know if it's a boy
or a girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either way,'' Jim says, `` I'm going to see a lot of Marianne
in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
