<HEADER>
A4945 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN15-COX     02-14 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For the good it does for some, it saps others' education
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ What's wrong with TAAS? Nothing may be more
emblematic than the reprimand a student received recently _ for
reading a history book.
</P>
<P>
   He and classmates were penned up for a TAAS chalk talk.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills. As academic
futures are pinned to it in Waco, all eyes will be trained on the
chalk, even the eyes of students like the reprimanded one who will
ace the test in half the time some peers need. Then this student
and others will fidget in silence, not even a restroom break, as
precious seconds tick away from their education.
</P>
<P>
   In Waco schools, this happens not just in tests but in practice
tests. That means some students who master TAAS get extra practice
in not fidgeting, and not learning.
</P>
<P>
   As my son says about every TAAS-related thing, ``We now
interrupt our regularly scheduled learning for...'' Ask teachers.
Ask students. They will say TAAS is 9.9 parts interruption, .01
part learning.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, many students need to spend extra time on the basic skills
and to feel comfortable with TAAS.
</P>
<P>
   But even with improvements aimed at ``higher-order'' skills over
the years, TAAS is far too basic to be considered a sufficient
challenge for large numbers of students.
</P>
<P>
   Texas should stop the interruptions, or commit itself to
minimizing them.
</P>
<P>
   Texas children should be able to test out of TAAS drudgery.
</P>
<P>
   They should be able to say, ``I'm ready to ace it'' on Day 1 of
school, or Day 2, to take it, dispense with it and never over the
next nine months have to endure any more interruptions and TAAS
chalk talks.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are considering broadening the state student
assessment, including an 11th-grade exit test and testing more
students on social studies and science. A big problem, however, is
what's attached: A price tag of $100 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has a reasonable means of reducing those costs. Let
students ``test out'' of TAAS or whatever Texas calls its
successor. Let them, at a time of their choosing, log on to a
computer and pull the trigger. Let them do it the week before
school starts, after school, before school.
</P>
<P>
   Schools have had it exactly backward in the students they've
shackled with TAAS and those they've exempted. Until a state
crackdown, schools were exempting hundreds of thousands of
academically challenged students, the very children who most needed
the emphasis on the basics. Meanwhile, students who had the basics
down were subjected to mind-numbing TAAS review and all those
lovely interruptions to learning.
</P>
<P>
   I'm imagining the benefit of children knowing that they can
prepare to pass TAAS before school starts, meaning they'd not have
to worry about it during school. I'm imagining students so juiced
by that prospect they'd actually review a TAAS workbook in August
and then line up to be tested at the first opportunity so as to
spare themselves TAAS prep in September, October, November,
December, January, February, March, April and May.
</P>
<P>
   Making every child spend a whole year prepping for TAAS is using
a tomato mallet to hammer every brain into the same jar.
</P>
<P>
   The legislature did something good in 1997 when it made it
possible for students who passed end-of-course tests in Algebra I,
English II and either biology or U.S. History to forgo TAAS. But
reforms now in the hopper in Austin would revoke that option.
Everybody back to TAAS. Is this necessary? The answer is no, but it
fits in with one-size-fits-all education fixes.
</P>
<P>
   Unquestionably, no one should be graduating from high school or
even advancing to the next grade without grade-level skills. But
Texas' fixation with ``the basics'' has fitted wings of concrete
onto many children capable of flight.
</P>
<P>
   When it's an academic offense for a boy to to read his history
book, Texas, you've done him wrong.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald. His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday.
E-mail: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
