A4950 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZULUREX15-COX     02-14 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZULUREX15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rex, Zulu to kick off Mardi Gras together
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Zulu, the historically black parading krewe, for
years has been the warm-up act and sometime nemesis of Rex, the
mostly-white group that is the centerpiece of Mardi Gras. On Fat
Tuesday, Zulu rolls its floats down St. Charles Avenue first _ and
often late _ followed by Rex, the king of Carnival.
</P>
<P>
   And the day before, on Lundi Gras, it is the king of Rex who
travels across the Mississippi River, meets the mayor in the French
Quarter and asks him to proclaim Mardi Gras an official holiday.
Then they toast the event with champagne. The king of Zulu also
crosses the river and meets the mayor, but it is a separate event,
and does not officially mark the beginning of the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, for the first time, Rex and Zulu will toast the
mayor together.
</P>
<P>
   It may sound like a small gesture, but for Zulu, who spent
almost 60 years marching on back streets because blacks weren't
allowed on the main parade routes, it is an important display of
mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was important that they toast each other and
meet the mayor together, to indicate to the community that we are
bridging the gap,'' said City Councilman Roy Glapion, who has been
a member of the Zulu krewe for 27 years. ``Certainly during the
days of segregation this would have been unheard of.''
</P>
<P>
   Rex, the only 19th-century krewe that still parades and the most
traditional of the 60 or so parading organizations, says this is
not so much about race as it is about marking two anniversaries.
This year is the 300th anniversary of Mardi Gras in Louisiana, and
the 50th anniversary of jazz legend Louis Armstrong serving as the
king of Zulu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anniversaries are very important in Mardi Gras,'' said King
Logan, a Rex official. ``A lot of people are very happy with what
Rex and Zulu are doing this year, but there are no commitments to
do this again.''
</P>
<P>
   Rex guards its traditions very carefully, Logan said, so change
doesn't come easily. That could be said of many of the traditional
krewes. In fact, some traditionalists proclaimed the death of Mardi
Gras when, in 1992, the city council passed an ordinance that
forced the krewes to integrate or stop marching. Several krewes
quit parading in protest; Rex continued to parade, allowing two
black members in 1992 and a handful more in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue still stings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is buried history, and we don't need to talk about
anything relating to 1992,'' Logan said.
</P>
<P>
   Glapion, on the other hand, said he thinks the ordinance eased
tensions between blacks and whites, and made the Lundi Gras toast
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``That caused some problems at the time, but I think we are
closer now as a result,'' Glapion said.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Hardy, a member of Rex and publisher of the Mardi Gras
Guide, said the meeting has little significance and has been
overplayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not front-page news,'' he said. ``Since 1992, there has
been nothing but cooperation. It's symbolic and a sweet moment, but
it's not a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Rex and Zulu couldn't be more different in style and history.
</P>
<P>
   Rex created the concept of day parades in 1872. That same year,
Rex decided on the official song for Mardi Gras, ``If I Ever Cease
to Love,'' and the official colors _ purple, green and gold. The
king, whose identity remains secret until Lundi Gras, is always a
civic leader, and his queen is a debutante. The king and his court
wear regal outfits that make them look like playing cards.
</P>
<P>
   Zulu was founded in 1909 by a group of black laborers in a
benevolent society called the Tramps. They changed their name to
the Zulu Social Aid and Pleasure Club after seeing a vaudeville
play called ``There Never Was and Never Will Be a King Like Me,''
about the African tribe, Zulu.
</P>
<P>
   That year, Zulu paraded through black neighborhoods and from bar
to bar on Mardi Gras, spoofing Rex by having a king of their own,
resplendent in a lard can crown and carrying a banana stalk
sceptor. In future years, members would take to wearing grass
skirts and blackface makeup. They throw spears along with beads,
and painted coconuts, one of the most prized throws of the Mardi
Gras season.
</P>
<P>
   The African motif drew sharp criticism during the civil rights
movement from blacks who said the get-ups were demeaning. The krewe
almost dissolved, but was revived in the late 1960s. The costumes,
the spears and the coconuts endure to this day.
</P>
<P>
   The Zulu parade, which hit the main parade route in 1968, is
wildly popular and always late. Rex can't start rolling until Zulu
does, because they both go down St. Charles Avenue. Last year, Zulu
enraged Rex by getting a late start and then suffering a two-hour
delay in the Garden District when a float broke down. The king of
Rex got so agitated he abandoned his float to go to a friend's
house along the parade route until things got moving again.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, Rex and Zulu will come together in the name of
.... tradition? Racial harmony? Both sides say not to read too much
into all this.
</P>
<P>
   For those who think grass skirts and spears are demeaning,
Glapion says, ``It's just for fun.''
</P>
<P>
   And for those wishing to read deep meaning into today's toast,
Logan says, ``This is Mardi Gras. Let's not take this too
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
