<HEADER>
A4951 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DORTCH-100BLACKMEN15-     02-14 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DORTCH-100BLACKMEN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dortch leads the way for young African-American males
 &HT;    By Peter Scott
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tommy Dortch's flair for leadership goes back years
ago when he was in college.
</P>
<P>
   As student government president at Fort Valley State College, he
came close to winning a seat to the Democratic National Convention
in 1972, losing by just 16 votes to then-Gov. Jimmy Carter. Two
years later, Dortch was named associate director of the Democratic
Party of Georgia. He has been climbing the leadership ladder ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   While Dortch, 48, was unable to unseat Carter, the daring he and
other students showed in challenging the state's political
establishment earned them community support. It also led to
hundreds of blacks in Fort Valley registering to vote and
subsequently electing that city's first black mayor, Rudolph
Carson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy carried himself as a leader. He was always involved,''
said Tom Palmer, former dean of students at Fort Valley. ``He was
never afraid to make a decision. If he felt something had to be
done, he made that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Dortch, who owns an Atlanta-based public relations firm,
finds himself leading another generation of young men.
</P>
<P>
   As president of the 100 Black Men of America, Dortch heads a
service organization that is developing leadership skills among
scores of young African-American males. The organization announced
last month plans for a new Youth Leadership Center it plans to
build about 45 miles southwest of Atlanta by the year 2000. Land
for the $7 million center stretches over 500 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Dortch's ``pull-yourself-up-by-the-bootstraps'' attitude was
instilled in him as a boy growing up in Toccoa, a closely-knit city
at the foot of the North Georgia mountains.
</P>
<P>
   While away at Fort Valley, Dortch became a contender for a
delegate seat at the National Democratic Convention at the urging
of former legislators Ben Brown and Julian Brown. If one more
busload of voting students had shown up, Dortch might have won the
seat instead of Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know I was running against Carter, but my parents
always instilled in me if you believe you could do something, you
could do it, and if you wanted something, go all out to get it,''
said Dortch.
</P>
<P>
   He did not lose politically. Former U.S. Sen. Sam Nunn picked
him to join his staff and, in 1990, Dortch became the first
African-American to serve as a state director for one of the
nation's senators.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Dortch's mother, Lizzie, served as a mentor to welfare
mothers, there were others who helped her son: educators such as
Betty Henderson, L.F. Thoma, Willie Mae Keels and Anna Canady;
barbers M.C. Scott and Robert Holley; electrician Clarence Wilson;
and funeral home director and former Mayor James Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Dortch keeps a busy schedule. TWD has as many as seven meetings
a day, often tied to the seven Fortune 500 companies Dortch counts
among his clients. Still, he finds time to practice what he
preaches. Atlantan Gabriel Miller, a 21-year-old intern who wants
to become an architect, is one of dozens of young people for whom
he is a mentor. Dortch and other mentors include interns in their
corporate meetings, conferences and social gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard much criticism that black males don't do this and
that. This (the institute) is an effort to take care of our own,
and that will benefit everybody,'' Dortch said.
</P>
<P>
   Dortch and his wife, Carol, head of the regional office of the
General Services Administration, have four children and are
preparing the two youngest to operate their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
   One son, Thomas III, is getting an early start. At 12, Thomas is
vice chairman of the board of directors for Dortch's TWD Inc. A
20-year-old daughter, Angel, is a secretary for the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people talk today about the village concept of raising a
child, that worked for me in Toccoa. Whether it was right down the
street or cross town, we had a full city of people who cared about
kids and looked out for kids. That's the kind of thing we need now
in order to succeed,'' said Dortch.
</P>
<P>
   Dortch grew up idolizing the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and
Supreme Court Justice Thurgood Marshall as heroes. Now he can put
youngsters in touch with successful black men like Gen. Colin
Powell, former Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young and and American Express
President and CEO Kenneth I. Chenault. The 13-year-old service
organization has provided mentoring to more than 60,000 youngsters
at its 84 chapters internationally.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
