<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-ECON-I (Undated) _ It is still not clear that the
financial upheavals, which began in Thailand in July 1997, will
ever damage the United States. But the collapse of Brazil's
currency in January and the jolt that it brought to markets
worldwide underscored the continuing risks of ``the most serious
financial crisis in a half a century,'' as Clinton called it in his
State of the Union address. This series of four articles is a
narrative of the worldwide financial crisis that over the last 20
months has toppled some governments and hobbled others. The crisis
illustrates how globalization increasingly stitches lives all over
the world into a single economic quilt. In the new economic
landscape that has emerged in recent years, the pool of
international investments has grown to dwarf the sums that
governments can muster, and money zips around the globe far faster
than ever before. The result is a world more prosperous; but also,
perhaps, a bit more wobbly. By Nicholas D. Kristof with Edward
Wyatt. 6,500 words, pix, graphics.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Paris) _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
meets European foreign ministers and reiterates that the threat of
air strikes remains real if Kosovo talks fail. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Undated) _ What IS the American interest in
sending troops to Kosovo? What tips it for the administration to
get involved? Does this presage further such deployments in areas
of no clear strategic value to the United States? By Serge
Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-CULTURECLASH (Jerusalem) _ 250,000 ultra-Orthodox Jews
demonstrated against the Supreme Court, swaying in prayer. A few
hundred yards away, a Woodstock-like gathering constituted a
counter-demonstration. The two rallies symbolized Israel's growing
cultural divide. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   UKRAINE-CORRUPT (Kiev) _ The arrest of Pavlo Lazarenko, a former
prime minister traveling on a Panamanian passport in Switzerland,
throws harsh light on corruption in this vast but impoverished
republic. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CLINTON (Merida) _ President Clinton arrives for a brief
visit. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-VOTE (Mexico City) _ Latest tally of last weekend's vote
for two state governors. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-POLITICS (Paris) _ As NATO's 50th anniversary looms,
Europeans increasingly chafe at American demands to do more and
Washington's reluctance to relinquish control. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-NAZIS (Undated) _ Poles are demanding a share of any
settlement of slave labor claims dating from World War II; the
shape of German plan for universal settlement becomes clear.
</P>
<P>
   RIO-CARNIVAL (Rio de Janeiro) _ Carnival parties and parades get
underway; the party spirit prevails over Brazil's economic crisis.
By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-POLITICS (Miami) _ At a meeting of Republican moderates,
leaders like Christie Whitman and John Rowland, as well as the rank
and file, speak bluntly about how badly they feel the party has
damaged itself and how much it needs to work on repair. By Kevin
Sack.
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-INDIANS (Undated) _ The Justice Department releases its
first study on crimes against Native Americans. Indians are victims
at twice the rate of the general population, and unlike other
groups, most of the crime is not Indian against Indian. By Fox
Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-POLITICS (Seattle) _ In the legal debate over the
future of Americans' high-speed connections to the Internet, some
public figures clearly think they have found a potent political
issue. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ Developments, and the talks shows. By
Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-POLITICS (Washington) _ A look at Al Gore's prospects, now
that the impeachment issue is history. By Richard L. Berke.
