   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   ROYAL-OPERA (London) _ For the last three years the Royal Opera
House has been a soap opera made for the tabloids. But an American,
Michael Kaiser, the former executive director of the American
Ballet Theater, arrived here in mid-November to sort out the
warring British, and now, just 10 weeks later, there are signs that
peace is breaking out. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-CUBA-EXCHANGE (Undated) _ The next few months may be
unprecedented in the cultural history of post-revolutionary Cuba as
a stream of American performers and arts organizations travel to
the island in the wake of the pope's visit last year and the
Clinton administration's easing of restrictions last month to make
cultural exchange easier. By Peter Watrous.
</P>
<P>
   EX-FRIENDS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt
reviews Norman Podhoretz's ``Ex-Friends: Falling Out with Allen
Ginsberg, Lionel and Diana Trilling, Lillian Hellman, Hannah Arendt
and Norman Mailer.''
</P>
<P>
   MISANTHROPE-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Ben Brantley reviews the
Classic Stage Company's production of Martin Crimp's contemporary
adaptation of Moliere's ``Misanthrope,'' starring Uma Thurman.
</P>
<P>
   MET-MUSIC-REVIEW (New York) _ Anthony Tommasini reviews Verdi's
``Il Trovatore'' at the Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   WEIR-MUSIC-REVIEW (New York) _ The Hanson brothers join Grateful
Dead guitarist Bob Weir and his bass-playing collaborator Rob
Wasserman at a concert celebrating the 10th anniversary of the
downtown club Wetlands. By Ann Powers.
</P>
<P>
   OPERA-CONNECTIONS (New York) _ Ed Rothstein's Connections
column: The subject of Arnold Schoenberg's opera, ``Moses und
Aron,'' in a new production at the Met, is also the opera's
ambition: to express something seemingly beyond musical expression.
So the fact that it fails is a kind of peculiar success.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   AMR-PILOTS (Undated) _ Airline pilots, some of America's best
paid and most highly respected workers, have become among the
nation's most militant, in part because of the central role that
they play in the airline industry and the past scorched-earth labor
policies of executives at major airlines. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   DILLER-LYCOS (Undated) _ As a television executive who has spent
most of the 1990s testing the edges of new media _ including last
week's deal to acquire the Internet portal Lycis _ Barry Diller has
been enterprising and ambitious, in many ways the personal
embodiment of the media ``convergence'' movement. But how have his
bold experiments fared so far? By Saul Hansell and Geraldine
Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-LANGUAGE (Undated) _ Microsoft is playing down a
report in a trade magazine that it has been briefing software
developers on a new programming language that would be similar to
Sun Microsystems' Java but free of technological or licensing
obligations to Sun. Microsoft said the idea was one of several
being discussed. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ-HALTS (New York) _ Frank G. Zarb, chairman of the
National Association of Securities Dealers, the parent of the
Nasdaq stock market, has asked the association's board to consider
testing temporary halts in the trading of shares that experience
extreme volatility. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   STERN-SNL (New York) _ When Howard Stern announced he was
turning his radio show to late-night television, he bragged he
would turn NBC's ``Saturday Night Live'' into ``Saturday Night
Dead.'' With the season half over, his show has barely dented
``Saturday Night Live'' except among men ages 18 to 34. By Lawrie
Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS-STANDARDS (Undated) _ In six weeks, the International
Telecommunication Union is scheduled to start approving
international standards for wireless technologies for the next
decade. But that process is being threatened by a general
reluctance to compromise on arcane technical standards and in
particular by intransigence on the part of Ericsson of Sweden and
Qualcomm Inc., of San Diego, two big communications manufacturers
that have feuded for years. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   INDUSTRY-VIEW-COLUMN (Undated) _ The EMC Corp. is to data
storage what Cisco is to routers. But few outside of Wall Street
and corporate data centers are familiar with this emerging
technology powerhouse. By Glenn Rifkin.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-CALENDAR (Undated) _ Key government figures this week.
</P>
<P>
   BOND-CALENDAR (Undated) _ The week's planned offerings.
</P>
<P>
   EQUITIES (Undated) _ Equity issues coming to market this week.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDEND-MEETINGS (Undated) _ Major meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column. By Sabra
Chartrand.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   (Coding varies.)
</P>
<P>
   AFTER-MONICA-MEDIA (Washington) _ Interviews with two dozen
reporters, news executives and scholars found concern about public
interest in news from the capital now that the impeachment trial of
President Clinton is over, as long as the economy flourishes and
American troops are not in harm's way. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   NBC-MERCHANDISE-MEDIA (Undated) _ After selling tens of
thousands of music CD's in conjunction with its recent mini-series
``The 60's'' and ``The Temptations,'' NBC executives believe they
have found a new source of revenue for the increasingly strapped
network television business: direct response sales of music through
toll-free telephone calls. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   SLATE-SUBSCRIPTIONS-MEDIA (Undated) _ Ten months after deciding
to charge readers $19.95 a year, the publisher of Slate, the
on-line magazine owned by Microsoft, announced in an e-mail to
subscribers that it would now be free. The publisher cited the
dynamic growth of advertising on the Web and the slow pace of paid
subscriptions for content. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
