u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ORTHODOX15-COX     02-14 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ORTHODOX15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RALLIES ILLUSTRATE ISRAELI RELIGIOUS RIFT
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A sea of ultra-Orthodox demonstrators in black hats
and dark suits packed a city street Sunday while counter-protesters
in sweatshirts and jeans filled a park nearby, accentuating
Israel's religious-secular cleft.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200,000 ultra-Orthodox were estimated to have turned
out at a major entrance to the city. Called by religious leaders,
their target was the Israeli supreme court, which has recently
eroded some special privileges held by ultra-Orthodox Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We demand from the judicial branch not to intervene in matters
of religion and to stop interfering in matters of (scriptures),''
said rally leader Rabbi Menachem Porush.
</P>
<P>
   A half mile away, about 50,000 secular Jews met to support the
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must understand this is a war, a war over the character of
our beloved country,'' Yossi Sarid, leader of the left-wing Meretz
party, told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations on the first day of the work week came off
without any of the expected clashes that had drawn 1,500 police to
ring the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   The rallies were probably the largest of the their type ever,
and they represented a crest in what many call a ``culture war''
within the small nation.
</P>
<P>
   Ultra-Orthodox Jews, though perhaps only 10 percent of the
population, have wielded a strong influence by serving as a
tie-breaking faction in the Israeli parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In a country without an official separation of religion and
government, ultra-Orthodox Jews have been able to win exemptions
from mandatory military service, government subsidies for lifetimes
of study in religious schools, and heavy funding for religious
schools.
</P>
<P>
   They see themselves as preserving the Jewish nature of the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   But as they have grown in number, their special status has
angered most Israelis, who are Jewish but do not practice organized
religion.
</P>
<P>
   American Jews have been angered at Orthodox efforts to exclude
those in less traditional forms of Judaism, such as Reform and
Conservative, from sharing power in government religious councils.
</P>
<P>
   As secular advocates have won recent court challenges against
the Orthodox, Orthodox leaders have lambasted the courts. They have
called the head of the court, himself Jewish, a ``persecutor of the
Jews'' and ``anti-semitic.'' Banners at the rally decried the
``judicial assaults on the Jewish faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The gathering Sunday was a mass prayer meeting _ toned down from
plans for a political rally at the request of Israeli leaders. With
the blowing of the traditional ram's horn, men gathered in the
streets and rocked back and forth in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the men wore the black fedoras or skullcaps, beards and
side curls distinctive of the ultra-Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with Orthodox traditions for segregated prayer, women
were kept to the sides of the protest, on balconies and a raised
street nearby.
</P>
<P>
   At the secular rally, a mix of male and female demonstrators
banged bongo drums and wore jeans and sweatshirts. Some bared their
midriffs on the unseasonably warm day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my country to be only a religious country,'' said
15-year-old Ganit(cq) Bendel, who came on a bus from her kibbutz, a
collective Israeli farm, and was wearing secular bumper stickers
across the front of her blouse. ``I want anybody to live the way
they want.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
