<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPERA-CONNECTIONS-NYT     02-14 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-CONNECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOSES UND ARON':   AN OPERA HINTS AT MOSES AS SCHOENBERG'S ALTER
EGO 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By   EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The queasiness is unrelenting. Revelation inspires a
form of nausea in Arnold Schoenberg's opera, ``Moses und Aron,''
now being given its first Metropolitan Opera performances. But that
nausea comes not from disgust, but from disorientation. The ear
canals are jostled and jiggered by the studious avoidance of
familiar harmonic guideposts. When there are echoes of familiar
dances _ a march, a waltz _ the stomping emphasis of the rhythms
lands on puddles of slippery mercury.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the opening of this brain-wrought rendering of the
Exodus story, when we hear God's voice from the burning bush, the
music does not bring us ear to ear with a transcendent power. There
is no sublime grandeur, no awe-inspiring mystery. Instead the
revelation is overwhelmingly weird, an unsettling combination of
six voices mixing song and speech and whine and whisper. The sound
is an eerie trace of something that lies beyond common experience.
We don't hear revelation. But we do hear its distorted residue.
</P>
<P>
   Which is probably pretty close to what Schoenberg wanted, since
this opera _ one of the musical landmarks of this century _ is
about futile attempts to express an idea that lies beyond
expression, an idea that is, as Moses solemnly chants, both
unperceivable and inconceivable. Moses, slow of speech, is granted
a vision of the ineffable, while Aron, who can give the revelation
voice and public meaning, distorts it along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The Met's new production by Graham Vick, which creates a mixture
of hauntingly beautiful images and stupefyingly banal distortions,
adds to the unease in a strange fashion. It inadvertently shows how
ill-understood the opera and its ideas remain, a half-century after
Schoenberg's death.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenberg, in his writings, left little doubt about what the
stakes were in this drama. For all his stature as a highly rational
modernist, in his views of artistry he was a religious Romantic,
opposed to what he called ``sterile faith in science.'' He kept
circling around religious dramas, while leaving them incomplete: an
oratorio about Jacob, a play, ``The Biblical Way,'' ``Moses und
Aron.'' He spoke of musical composition as a form of ``miracle''
and suggested that the artist ``feels as if what he does were
dictated to him,'' as if he were acting as a ``mouthpiece'' of a
higher power.
</P>
<P>
   This puts the composer in the position of Moses at the burning
bush. But Schoenberg argued that something wasn't right, that in
this century music's language was no longer capable of giving shape
to new revelations. Schoenberg in essence became a law-giver, a
Moses, constructing a musical system that would guide music's
future.
</P>
<P>
   But how would such a revelation be communicated? In the opera
Aron does the job. He is seductive, manipulative, translating the
gnomic proclamations of his brother into tenorial display that
might sway an audience as skeptical as any Schoenberg ever
encountered. The listeners doubt that Moses will return from the
mountain with their law. So Aron decides to give them what they
want.
</P>
<P>
   ``I return your gods to you,'' he says, ``and also give you to
them, just as you have demanded.'' The result is the golden calf,
which is celebrated in an extended musical scene of debauchery,
butchery and sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   This is nail-scratching, nail-biting music with a primitive
vitality and sweep. There may even be suggestions, in the midst of
the idolatrous bacchanal, of Schoenberg's early sickly
Expressionism along with music of composers who did not accept
Schoenberg's declarations of musical law: invocations of the
primitivism of Stravinsky (as in ``Rite of Spring'') and the
sensuous grotesqueries of Richard Strauss (as in ``Salome''). That
music, with its suggestions of energy and decadence, tapped into an
audience larger than Schoenberg's later compositions ever did.
</P>
<P>
   What happens when Moses/Schoenberg returns, severe and
unforgiving, with the revelatory law and its promise of salvation?
</P>
<P>
   Aron argues that Moses' pride is unjustified, that even those
laws are nothing but images, inevitably distorting, no better than
the calf itself. (Aron is not just a Romantic tenor, he is a
post-modern tenor). Moses smashes the tablets. ``Thus am I
defeated!'' he cries. ``O word, thou word, that I lack!''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenberg planned another twist, but his account of Moses'
rehabilitation _ and his own _ was never completed. Only a portion
of the originally planned libretto exists. In it Aron is condemned
by Moses for having betrayed ``the extraordinary to the
commonplace,'' having ``abandoned the wasteland's renunciation.''
</P>
<P>
   He is condemned for indulging in sensuous imagery, for pandering
to his people, for abandoning the rigors of modernist solitude. For
not being Arnold Schoenberg.
</P>
<P>
   I think the opera really was this personally urgent for
Schoenberg, which is why he had such trouble finishing it. At stake
were his very achievements as a composer. Was his compositional
system as arbitrary as Aron suggested? How could his music live
without the distortion of Aron? How could it survive intact without
the ruthlessness of Moses?
</P>
<P>
   The result of his modernist severity could only be a bizarre
isolation, in which everything falls short of the ideal. In
Schoenberg's unfinished play, ``The Biblical Way,'' a high priest
proclaims the futility of this quest, arguing, ``He who dedicates
himself to the idea should either renounce the temptation of its
fulfillment, or resign himself to a reality that he would rather
not have to live. This is why all those who are impelled to live
out an idea become martyrs to it.''
</P>
<P>
   What hope would any society have where the only choices were
resignation or renunciation? What opera could ever convincingly
reconcile these alternatives? How could such music even hope to
find an audience when finding an audience is seen as a compromise?
</P>
<P>
   Now that the orthodoxies of modernist visions like Schoenberg's
have passed, we might think we see things more clearly: Moses and
Aron offer incomplete visions, though both are needed. But
post-modern interpretations like Graham Vick's end up adding more
distortions.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the revelation is treated as something immutable,
inexpressible and inconceivable. There is no ideal. Aron's
interpretations can become ever more arbitrary, Moses' authority
more open to question. In this context, the bacchanal can hardly
seem like an outrage; there is no idea of order to be opposed.
</P>
<P>
   This is the problem with the production at the Met, which even
ends up importing political and cultural villains to inspire
disgust. The scene with the golden calf is staged as a series of
vignettes involving the nemesis of the 20th-century avant-garde,
the decadent bourgeoisie: models in luxurious furs (with blood on
the inside lining), hypocritical politicians, plastic surgeons and
their victims and even an array of Hasidim.
</P>
<P>
   Of course Schoenberg himself had no great love for the bourgeois
audience. But here familiar idols and villains are propped up and
left to make polemical and incidental points, while the mission of
Moses seems haplessly incidental to the chaos. The opera itself is
more ambiguous, more discomfiting and more confounding.
</P>
<P>
   It poses questions about the tensions between high art and mass
acclaim, hermetic systems and pandering entertainments, immutable
law and unfettered abandon. Its challenge _ that some Aron be brave
enough to give its flawed revelations public voice _ remains
unanswered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
