<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFTER-MONICA-MEDIA-2TAKES(1,100)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER IMPEACHMENT, IS THERE STILL WASHINGTON NEWS?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ky., Fla., Pa.) (Duplication notice: Also moving in `w' category.) 
 (nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Call Chris Matthews an optimist. In the brand new
studios of the CNBC show ``Hardball With Chris Matthews,'' where he
has spent the last year turning impeachment into entertainment,
Matthews says he is actually upbeat about the end of the scandal
that helped double his audience in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In its birth, my show is the same as ABC's `Nightline' was,''
he said. `` `Nightline' was born during the Iran hostage crisis.
They survived. We've been introduced as a program covering one big
ongoing story.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, he said, as the Year of Monica comes to a close, he is
prepared for the New Age. ``Jury nullification,'' he said,
gesturing toward an article in The Washington Post. Delivered with
the right insight and attitude, he said, talk about angry jurors
protesting the law by letting defendants go free can get just as
many people to tune in.
</P>
<P>
   His colleagues around Washington are not so optimistic, about
his prospects or their own. Interviews with two dozen reporters,
news executives and scholars found growing concern about the
general public's interest in news from the capital, as long as the
economy flourishes and American troops are not in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington and politics used to be the hub of the news
wheel,'' said S. Robert Lichter, president of the Center for Media
and Public Affairs. ``Now it's just another spoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington news increasingly attracts enthusiasts rather than a
general audience, said Thomas B. Rosenstiel, director of the
Project for Excellence in Journalism. ``Our mass media depends on
an audience that no longer exists _ a mass audience which is now
fragmented,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Niche audiences are the bread and butter of cable television,
with its channels for gardening and weather and now for Washington
news. CNN's ``Larry King Live'' scored its best ratings in 1998,
averaging 1.3 million households. ``Hardball'' reached an average
of 552,000 homes in 1998, up from an average of 252,000 in 1997,
its first year.
</P>
<P>
   Compare the effects of the scandal on the evening news
broadcasts of three major networks. In 1998, 44 percent of all the
Washington news reports on the evening broadcasts were about the
scandal, according to the Center for Media and Public Affairs.
Since September, these linchpins of the nation's general news
coverage have lost more than two million households a night _
roughly the same total as the audiences of ``Larry King Live,''
``Hardball'' and CNBC's ``Rivera Live'' combined.
</P>
<P>
   David Poltrack, vice president for audience research for CBS,
supervised those network audience calculations. ``For the past two
years, while network ratings in general were declining, the most
resilient ratings were those of the three evening newscasts,'' he
said. Since September, he added, those programs have lost almost 6
percent of their combined audience.
</P>
<P>
   The press corps that will now try to lure readers and viewers to
news of Washington government and politics has changed in some
fundamental ways in the last 25 years. When Richard Nixon resigned
in 1974, newspaper and wire service reporters in Washington
accredited to cover Congress outnumbered broadcasters almost 2 to
1. As the Lewinsky scandal ends, that ratio is now 3 to 2 in favor
of the radio and television journalists and technicians.
</P>
<P>
   Specialty reporting, mostly involving business and finance, has
blossomed, while more traditional beat coverage of Cabinet
departments like Interior, Transportation, or Agriculture is
increasingly episodic.
</P>
<P>
   The generalists have hardly disappeared _ the bureaus of Reuters
(with 55 staff members accredited to cover Congress during the
1997-1998 session) and The Associated Press (95) have near-record
staff levels. And television programs like ``News Hour With Jim
Lehrer'' on PBS provide wide-ranging and deep coverage (it had
nearly 50 staff members accredited to cover the last session of
Congress.)
</P>
<P>
   But more of the Washington press corps than ever covers news
tailored to the audience's business interests _ witness the rise of
the financial news services Bloomberg News (35 Congress
accreditations) and Bridge News (30). More journalists than ever
cover the city for a Washington-centric audience _ witness the rise
of the C-SPAN cable channels (135 journalists accredited by
Congress) and Hotline, the online daily Washington news bulletin
distributed by The National Journal.
</P>
<P>
   In this increasingly splintered universe, some general news
organizations are realigning. Peter Copeland, the new bureau chief
for the Scripps-Howard newspaper chain, is redirecting coverage to
new beats like consumer affairs and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   At the Knight Ridder bureau, the focus on daily coverage will
dwindle, bureau editors say. Instead of assigning nine of its 14
Washington reporters to daily coverage, the bureau will devote 10
reporters to in-depth coverage of subjects like health, economics
and science.
</P>
<P>
   At coming meetings, news executives and representatives from
CNN's 35 bureaus will discuss similar changes. Rick Kaplan,
president of CNN/USA, said he wanted to reorganize the network's
coverage, including Washington's, around ``nine major subjects'' _
education, religion, culture, family, money, saving cities,
changing world, health and the Year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
   This shift, he hopes, will reduce the network's dependence on
big stories.
</P>
<P>
   The press corps has changed in other ways. Senior journalists
who were sought out by top government figures once had a virtual
monopoly on conveying the gist of policy debates. Now those
officials can appear on cable programs and explain their views
without any filters.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Stacks, an executive editor at Time magazine who is
writing a biography of the late James Reston, a columnist and
editor of The New York Times, said columnists like Reston or Joseph
Alsop would have background briefings with presidents and senators,
ask hard questions, and then dissect government policy in print.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spin ethic, as opposed to the patient, off-the-record,
background explanation, has destroyed those people, destroyed the
need for them,'' he said. Other journalists, however, point out
that many officials still court influential journalists. It is just
that fewer influential journalists work for newspapers and more are
hosts of television programs.
</P>
<P>
   But if cable's rise has eclipsed some journalists, it has
elevated others with different, more television-friendly skills
such as coming up with well-turned quips that crystallize a
political situation. ``Now the value is edge and attitude,'' Stacks
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Edge, attitude and speed. Fast-forward from the 1960s to the
``Hardball'' set in 1999, to see some of the new permutations of
the journalistic craft. It is Monday, the beginning of the last
week of President Clinton's Senate trial. King Hussein of Jordan
has just died, but the talk of Washington's journalistic and
political circles this morning is journalist Christopher Hitchens.
</P>
<P>
   An affidavit from Hitchens recounting a lunch at which, he said,
the presidential aide Sidney Blumenthal called Monica Lewinsky a
``stalker'' is on the mind of Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-Fla., who is
scheduled to appear on the first segment of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews wants the latest news on his program; Adam Levine, the
senior producer, is trying to fit all the elements of the show
together. The bookers and producers fill his office as he rattles
off the plans for the program's six segments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we really have room for Hitchens?'' one of the assembled
producers asked. ``I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you're right,'' Levine replied. ``You can't bump Al
Haig.'' Former Secretary of State Alexander M. Haig Jr. is another
scheduled guest.
</P>
<P>
   In the final lineup, Graham's version of the impeachment news
got top billing, but Haig and the funeral of King Hussein got more
time. The show closed with an author talking about a new book on
Muhammad Ali. Such a show _ a mixture of subjects and pacing _ will
survive even without scandal, Matthews says.
</P>
<P>
   The point, he said, is not so much what the news is but how it
is presented. Matthews, who is also the Washington bureau chief of
The San Francisco Examiner, said he seeks to explain ``the subtexts
in political scripts.'' He sees ``Hardball'' as a direct descendant
of ``The Tonight Show'' of the 1970s. ``Johnny Carson brought
audiences into a backstage conversation about Hollywood,'' he said.
``This is a backstage conversation about politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Out in central Kentucky, where Jim Ogle is news director of
WKYT-TV in Lexington, which reaches about 500,000 households, the
audience wants no part of any such conversation. ``The anger that
people in my church and civic groups feel is intense,'' Ogle said.
``They're saying, `Please just stop telling us about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   In early November, he decreed that no report out of Washington
could be broadcast in the first eight minutes of his 90-minute
early evening news program. His ratings for November were the best
in that CBS affiliate's history. Since the change, the show has
captured 40 percent of the viewing audience, about half the size of
the average audience for ``Hardball'' in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Luecke, the editor of The Lexington Herald-Leader, was
somewhat friendlier to Washington news when she and editors of 30
other Knight Ridder newspapers were polled by the company late last
year about what kind of Washington news they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   A majority called for less daily coverage, with the editors of
The Philadelphia Inquirer strongly dissenting.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the scandal, Ms. Luecke said, she wants
``coverage out of Washington that will focus on how the government
is moving on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that the House and the Senate can get into meaty
issues like Social Security and Medicare, we could use some good
`explainers,''' Ms. Luecke said, referring to in-depth analyses of
policy.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Her tastes are traditional. Explainers are a staple of
newspapers and newsmagazines, of programs like ABC's ``Nightline''
and of correspondents like CNN's Jeff Greenfield. But they may not
be the stuff of Matthews' program.
</P>
<P>
   On the set of ``Hardball,'' after expressing his gung-ho
enthusiasm for the subject of jury nullification, Matthews
explained that his show needed to keep up a brisk pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a news program,'' he said. ``People aren't tuning
me in for news. They're tuning me in as an alternative to
`Friends.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
