``This is a backstage conversation about politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Out in central Kentucky, where Jim Ogle is news director of
WKYT-TV in Lexington, which reaches about 500,000 households, the
audience wants no part of any such conversation. ``The anger that
people in my church and civic groups feel is intense,'' Ogle said.
``They're saying, `Please just stop telling us about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   In early November, he decreed that no report out of Washington
could be broadcast in the first eight minutes of his 90-minute
early evening news program. His ratings for November were the best
in that CBS affiliate's history. Since the change, the show has
captured 40 percent of the viewing audience, about half the size of
the average audience for ``Hardball'' in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Luecke, the editor of The Lexington Herald-Leader, was
somewhat friendlier to Washington news when she and editors of 30
other Knight Ridder newspapers were polled by the company late last
