<SLUG> BC-MET-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IL TROVATORE': A VERDIAN CHALLENGE, A DREARY PRODUCTION
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite its familiarity, ``Il Trovatore'' remains one
of Verdi's most challenging, and hardest-to-cast, operas. It came
at a crossroads in the composer's career, when he was still imbued
with the bel canto heritage yet breaking new ground. So the main
roles want singers who can shape florid melodic lines, yet who have
dramatic depth and resplendent vocal presence. If it's difficult to
find a great cast for, say, ``La Traviata,'' it's difficult to find
any cast at all for ``Il Trovatore.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first ``Trovatore'' of its season, the Metropolitan
Opera's cast was always creditable, and often much more. Given the
demands of this opera, that is saying a lot.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian tenor Richard Margison, as the troubadour Manrico,
who is leading a band of warriors in 15th-century Spain against the
throne of Aragon, has a vibrant and sizable voice, with a bright
ping in the top range. But he lacks subtlety. He is a hefty-framed
man, and his singing can get pretty hefty as well. So for all the
charisma of his sound, he can be a bit bland. But there was
pleasure in hearing a genuinely gifted Verdi tenor take on this
role. He doesn't have much competition right now.
</P>
<P>
   When the American soprano Michele Crider made her Met debut in
1997 as Madama Butterfly, she seemed a very promising new artist.
Returning as Leonora, she still seems a singer just shy of being
completely comfortable. Still, her sound is luscious, and she ably
handled the role's coloratura flights, high-lying pianissimo
phrases and lurching melodic lines. But in her sometimes cautious
placement of notes, and her sometimes labored breathing, there was
a sense of not being quite in control. Still, hers is a beautiful
voice, and this was an affecting performance.
</P>
<P>
   The powerhouse Russian mezzo-soprano Larissa Diadkova was
commanding as the Gypsy woman Azucena, singing with throbbing
intensity yet solid musicianship. The high B-flat Verdi takes the
character up to is not a happy note for her. But this was an
impressive performance by an exceptional singer.
</P>
<P>
   It will take more hearings to know what the Mexican baritone
Genaro Sulvaran, who made his debut as the Count di Luna, is
capable of. He has an essentially robust, dark-hued voice and sings
with dramatic vigor. But he was more concerned with unleashing
fortissimo top notes than in shaping Verdi's elegant phrasing.
</P>
<P>
   He may have been confounded by the dreary 1987 Fabrizio Melano
production, dominated by a stage-wide staircase and massive, moving
black columns, all dimly lighted and veiled by a scrim. At times it
seemed as if Sulvaran was being subjected to some trial of
initiation: ``Go stand up on that stairway behind that screen and
sing `Il Balen.'''
</P>
<P>
   The production may have also hampered the young German conductor
Jun Maerkl in his Met debut. He is an alert, musical, technically
skilled conductor with an idiomatic sensitivity for the ebbs and
flows of Verdian lines. The occasional moments of poor ensemble may
have been a result of the singers' and chorus' being stuck in the
dark abyss of the stage, far removed from their conductor.
</P>
<P>
   The tireless bass Paul Plishka, who sang Ferrando, continues to
be a model of vocal, musical and dramatic professionalism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 1635EST &QL; 
