<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-DATA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA'S ACCIDENT PLANS CATALYZE AN INTERNET CONTROVERSY
</HEADLINE>
   ( nk ) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of the House Commerce Committee, Rep &UR; .
 &LR; Thomas J. Bliley Jr., R-Va., is considering legislation that would
put limits on the types of publicly released government information
that could be posted on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are the ``worst case scenario'' plans for handling
accidents that the Environmental Protection Agency is collecting
from the nation's 66,000 chemical plants and chemical storage sites
under the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   The information is to be released to the public in June, and the
EPA originally intended to post it on its World Wide Web site in
the form of a searchable data base. But Bliley and officials from
intelligence agencies began objecting last year, saying that the
EPA would be creating an Internet road map for terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups and community advocates, however, say easy
public access to the data is necessary to help prepare for a much
greater risk _ that of accidental spills of dangerous chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA has dropped its plans to post the data on its Web site.
But at a hearing on the matter last week, Bliley said he remained
concerned that environmental groups would obtain the information
through the Freedom of Information Act and post it on their own
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Bliley has not specifically said that he is considering
legislation to limit what can be posted on the Internet. But a
spokesman for Bliley said legislation dealing with the issue was
imminent. And the issue was clearly on his mind in calling the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Several of his supporters grilled witnesses from the EPA and the
FBI about terrorist concerns. And after the meeting, Bliley's
office issued a news release contending that an EPA official had
agreed the information ``should not be posted on the Internet by
the government or any other party.''
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of Internet advocacy groups has asked Bliley to
reconsider filing legislation, saying that any proposals to limit
the distribution of the data electronically would set a dangerous
precedent for limiting public access to nonclassified government
documents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
