<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Feb. 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Exceptionally dry air will cover much of the nation on Monday,
but a series of potent disturbances poised over the central and
eastern Pacific will move quickly east, causing a change to
unsettled conditions in many areas during the middle and latter
part of the week.
</P>
<P>
   After a cold dawn over the East Coast states, temperatures will
rebound above seasonal levels as high pressure moves off the
Atlantic seaboard. Sunshine will be abundant in most areas,
although a few high clouds will dim the sun at times in parts of
the interior Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south along the southern flank of the high, onshore
breezes will bring patchy clouds and isolated showers near the east
coast of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Breezes from the southwest will transport unseasonably mild air
from the southern and central Plains to the Mississippi and Ohio
valleys. Sunshine will mix with patchy clouds during the day as
moisture is gradually drawn north from the Gulf of Mexico. By
Monday night, showers will develop from northeast Texas to the
central Mississippi Valley as a cold front approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, clouds and patchy light snow will occur near low
pressure over the northern part of the Dakotas and Minnesota. The
snow will spread toward the northern Great Lakes on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, high pressure will keep most of the interior cold
and dry, despite some snow showers along west-facing mountain
slopes and near a jet-stream disturbance over northern New Mexico.
Meanwhile, rain will develop near the northwest coast and will
become heavier Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Money in the Bank
</P>
<P>
   Through Sunday, precipitation totals in parts of California were
averaging only 50 percent to 85 percent of the normal amount
expected at this point in the rainy season. While such rainfall
deficits may cause some concern, there is still money in the bank.
Most of California relies on mountain snow melt to replenish
northern reservoirs that supply water during the long, dry summer.
Here, recurrent moist winds have produced ample snow in the
mountains this winter. Some areas in the northern Sierra have had
several feet of new snow this month, bringing seasonal snowfall
totals near or above normal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
