<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-NAZIS-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLAND SEEKS ROLE IN SHAPING FUND FOR NAZI VICTIMS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Israel)   (jw) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poland is seeking a central role in shaping a financial fund
being set up by German companies to compensate forced laborers
during World War II and other victims of Nazi horrors.
</P>
<P>
   Wieslaw Walendziak, the chief of staff to Polish Prime Minister
Jerzy Buzek, said in a telephone interview Friday that some 2
million Poles were deported to Germany after the Nazis invaded in
1939 and subsequently worked under prison-like conditions in German
companies or on farms. He estimated that some 520,000 of them live
in Poland today.
</P>
<P>
   Since World War II ended, the German government has paid out 140
billion marks, or about $80 billion at current exchange rates, in
war reparations and aid, much of it to Jews who fled Germany or
suffered in concentration camps. But Walendziak said only 1 percent
of such funds have gone to former forced laborers living in Central
and Eastern Europe, which became part of the Soviet bloc after
1945.
</P>
<P>
   Walendziak flew to Washington for talks at the State Department
just days after a top aide to the German chancellor was in
Washington and confirmed the intention of Germany's government and
major corporations to compensate forced laborers and thus address a
wave of class action lawsuits over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Any such scheme must recognize obligations to Poles and other
non-Jews, Walendziak said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These issues must be resolved once and for all so that they
bring the issue to a closure, not to another problem,'' Walendziak
said. ``We certainly expect the results to be meaningful
compensation to people who were victims of forced labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Walendziak spoke after a two-hour meeting Friday with Stuart
Eizenstat, the State Department's undersecretary for business and
economic affairs, who has been extremely active in
Holocaust-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   Days earlier, Bodo Hombach, top aide to German Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder, was in Washington and said the German government
had agreed to establish a compensation fund financed by major
German manufacturers, banks and others intended to resolve
Holocaust-era claims against German industry.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, several class-action lawsuits have been
brought against dozens of German companies, including Volkswagen,
Siemens and Deutsche Bank. The lawsuits allege, among other things,
that the companies profited from the use of forced labor or assets
seized from Jews and other Nazi victims.
</P>
<P>
   Hombach did not discuss details of the plan, which is still
taking shape. But a translated copy of a discussion paper
circulated by German officials and obtained by The New York Times
states that the initiative is intended to respond ``to the moral
obligations'' of German companies and to create a basis for dealing
``with class actions in the U.S.A. and to scotch any plans for a
boycott.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the document, the German initiative foresees
devoting funds to compensation of Nazi victims, including forced
laborers, and to international ``remembrance'' programs involving
groups in Germany, the United States, Israel and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The compensation would give priority to those in need, the
document states. It says the money should go to victims of forced
labor deported by the Nazis from occupied countries and used in
German industry as ``concentration camp prisoners or under
prison-like conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The funds should provide them with a measure of moral redress
and material assistance,'' the proposal states.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``forced'' laborer typically applies to non-Jews
deported to Germany from Poland, Russia or other East European
countries. Concentration camp prisoners who were used by German
industry are generally referred to by historians as slave laborers.
</P>
<P>
   Forced laborers outnumbered slave laborers by about 10-to-1.
Many slave laborers, about half of whom were Jewish, starved or
perished otherwise during the war.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When announced by Hombach, the German initiative was greeted
warmly by leaders of the World Jewish Congress, a New York-based
group active in Holocaust compensation issues. But it may face
hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Both German companies and government officials seek to avoid the
protracted battle that Swiss banks engaged in before resolving
claims that they profited from the assets of Jews and other
Holocaust victims. But the Germans also face demands from a broader
class of claimants like forced laborers, and from Holocaust
survivors or their heirs seeking payments from German banks and
European insurers.
</P>
<P>
   The Polish government, for one, has closely allied itself with
several of the class-action lawyers who were active in the Swiss
banks litigation. Walendziak says he foresees a role for those
lawyers in any negotiations, which the Germans hope will result in
all class action lawsuits' being dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible that this is going to be resolved through
political negotiations,'' he said. ``But I emphasize that this is
going to happen with the assistance of attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Hombach and Eizenstat assured him the Polish position would
be taken into account, Walendziak said.
</P>
<P>
   Eizenstat said in a telephone interview that the German
initiative would address both forced and slave labor, although
immediate emphasis was on slave laborers.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing the financial need of various victims may slow
distribution of any funds made available by the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   For several decades, one group associated with the World Jewish
Congress, the Conference on Jewish Material Claims Against Germany,
has negotiated reparation payments for Nazi survivors based on
income levels. The group, which has a proposed role in the new
initiative, has been criticized by some groups for taking years to
approve payments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 1710EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990214.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBC-MERCHANDISE-MEDIA     02-14 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBC-MERCHANDISE-MEDIA-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC DISCOVERS NEW STRATEGY IN `THE '60S' 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After selling tens of thousands of music CDs in
conjunction with its recent miniseries ``The '60s'' and ``The
Temptations,'' NBC executives believe they have found a new source
of revenue for the increasingly strained network television
business: direct-response sales of music through toll-free
telephone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   And to keep the flow of revenue going, the network's movie
department is now picking some projects specifically for their
potential to generate albums that NBC can sell to its viewers. NBC
executives acknowledge that some of their programming decisions are
being influenced by the potential for merchandising profits.
</P>
<P>
   This means that viewers will be hearing a lot of rock 'n' roll
music on NBC and not only because of the strong ratings that ``The
Temptations'' and ``The '60s'' scored on the network. Lindy
DeKoven, the executive vice president of movies and miniseries for
NBC, said the network believed it had found in music-oriented
movies ``a new economic model'' for the network television
business.
</P>
<P>
   Network television, facing higher program costs and diminishing
market share, finds itself more than ever in need of ways to raise
revenues beyond the single source of advertising.
</P>
<P>
   At least three more music-oriented miniseries are in various
stages of development at NBC, including a follow-up to ``The '60s''
called ``The '70s,'' a fictional history of rock 'n' roll, and an
account of the lives and times of the three brothers that made up
the group the Bee Gees.
</P>
<P>
   During its broadcast of ``The '60s'' last week, NBC made on-air
announcements of a special toll-free telephone number set up for
sales of a CD of music from the movie, along with a videocassette
of the movie itself.
</P>
<P>
   NBC had sold more than 35,000 units of the $29.95 package by the
end of last week. That did not include what NBC will take in from
retail sales. The CD reached the top sales spot on Amazon.com, and
moved up from number 87 to number 65 in the Billboard album charts
the week the movie was on the air.
</P>
<P>
   NBC hopes for more sales in the summer when the miniseries will
be televised again, this time carried by both NBC and the cable
music channel VH-1, part of the MTV Networks unit of Viacom Inc.,
in a deal that will be announced Monday. VH-1 has already run
promotions for the show on its channel and will run direct-response
commercials for the soundtrack and home video each time it carries
the movie in August.
</P>
<P>
   NBC first tried the direct marketing approach in a significant
way last April when the network sold more than 100,000
videocassettes of another miniseries, ``Merlin.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Don Ohlmeyer, the head of NBC's West Coast
division, said the network would commit itself more and more to the
``direct transaction business'' as a way to ``devise other revenue
streams'' for the network. He predicted that NBC would find other
products to sell besides videos of shows. Music is the product the
network has identified as having the most potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very interesting way to sell records,'' said Jerry
Petry, the executive vice president of NBC Enterprises. ``We always
knew the reach of the network was very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC is now looking at the potential for ancillary profits from
the very start of its production planning, Ms. DeKoven said. ``Do
we think now about ancillary opportunities before we start up a
project?'' she said. ``The answer is yes.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she said, in initiating the idea that became ``The
'60s,'' ``we started out with a music supervisor picking out what
songs might be appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the ratings for the first part of the film arrived,
Ms. DeKoven gave the go-ahead for a follow-up miniseries, ``The
'70s,'' which is expected to be on next season.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And some preliminary discussions have been held about further
follow-ups to ``The '60s'' that could tell the story of ``The
'80s'' and ``The '90s.'' Ms. DeKoven said, ``We picked up `The
'70s' because it seemed like the period lends itself to music, and
so the ancillary opportunities would be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Petry said NBC had also experimented with direct marketing of
CDs on other NBC shows. Last fall, he said, the singer Jewel
appeared on NBC's ``Tonight'' show just as she was releasing her
new album.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a direct-response spot on the `Tonight' show,'' he
said. ``It drove their sales numbers up. We weren't in that for the
money. We were in it to say: Here's what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Petry acknowledged that the total revenue from direct sales of
the CDs and video from ``The '60s'' might not be impressive by the
standards of the television advertising business, which is measured
in billions.
</P>
<P>
   Even kicking in extra profits from shipping and handling costs,
and sales of another CD being offered with the deal, a collection
of Marvin Gaye's greatest hits, the direct-response revenue from
``The '60s'' might only reach $2 million to $3 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '60s'' was a new phase in NBC's effort to build additional
revenue, Ms. DeKoven said, because ``Merlin'' and ``The
Temptations'' were produced by outside studios.
</P>
<P>
   NBC produced ``The '60s'' itself and owns the film, so it does
not need to share profits from sales of the CD with a studio. But
Petry had to make a deal with a record label for the right to use
the music. He said he approached all the large labels, some of
which were reluctant to collaborate with a television movie.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from Mercury Records were most enthusiastic about the
project, Petry said, and agreed to work with NBC to produce the CD
for an equal share of its profits. Mercury was able to provide some
of the music itself but had to make deals with other labels for
songs the filmmakers wanted to use. The biggest deal came with Sony
for the use of Bob Dylan's ``Chimes of Freedom,'' which he
rerecorded for the film.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Petry said, with the sales of the CD from ``The '60s'' to
show to other record labels, ``I imagine it's going to be much
easier to convince them'' to sign on to NBC's future music-oriented
movies, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
