<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS COLUMN:   ATM'S LEAD TO OTHER INVENTIONS THAT REPLACE
CLERKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., S.C., N.J.) (rk) 
 By   SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before automated teller machines, transacting business at a bank
required a human teller working during business hours. The
automated machines have proved that it is faster and more efficient
for customers to serve themselves by punching buttons at a computer
terminal. Exploiting the computer kiosk idea, more inventors are
patenting similar ways to eliminate clerks from retail services.
Last week, several inventions won patents for replacing those
employees with do-it-yourself, while-you-wait computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Norris' idea displaces another staple of the banking
business, the loan officer. Applying for a loan might seem too
complicated for a kiosk, but Norris contends that all the necessary
steps can be processed while the customer waits. He has patented a
system for real-time loan approval that uses a computer terminal to
complete the application, underwrite the loan and transfer the
money being borrowed.
</P>
<P>
   Norris of Lexington, S.C., has designed a computer program that
requests loan application information, analyzes the request,
decides whether to approve the loan, authorizes electronic transfer
of the money to the applicant's account, and sets up a schedule of
automatic withdrawals from that account to repay the loan.
</P>
<P>
   The application information would come in part from the
applicant himself, but also from data bases that the computer could
tap, like credit reporting bureaus. The paperwork for the loan is
transmitted to the computer terminal, where the customer's copy can
be printed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a preferred embodiment, the applicant accesses the computer
from a kiosk where the complete transaction can take place as the
applicant waits,'' Norris wrote in his patent. He was awarded
patent 5,870,721.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Lawlor and Timothy Carmody received a patent for a
system that enables people to pay bills from portable computer
terminals. The terminals get access to financial information by
dialing up a central computer, which then transmits data over an
established automated teller machine network.
</P>
<P>
   To pay a bill, a customer would provide the name of the company
being paid, the amount to pay, and his or her bank account's
personal identification number. The payment is then deducted from
the bank account.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payments and transfers may be scheduled in advance, or on a
periodic basis,'' the inventors explain in their patent. They
received patent 5,870,724.
</P>
<P>
   Four Japanese inventors see computer kiosks as aids in grocery
shopping. Taichi Sugiyama, Yukio Akimoto, Takafumi Morimoto and
Yoshiyuki Tsuge worked together on a patent that belongs to
Hitachi &UR;  &LR; Ltd. Their idea is for a network of computers that
registers purchases, figures out how often items are purchased, and
notifies the consumer of what he needs to buy on his next shopping
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Their invention relies on a computer system of store terminals
that register purchases via electronic labels. A central computer
manages the data from the individual terminals and sends it to a
home computer, where the customer can review his or her shopping
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   The home terminal ``accumulates the item information from the
store terminal as history, determines a mean purchase interval of
individual items, and decides and notifies the items to be
purchased by the shopper'' during future trips to the store, the
patent explains. The four inventors received patent 5,870,716.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Oberg of Washington, Mo., hopes the kiosk idea will
simplify the process of framing photos or artwork. Oberg has
patented a computer program that analyzes a digital image of an
object to be framed, chooses a frame and mat, and produces a
prototype image of the finished product.
</P>
<P>
   The system uses a digital camera so customers can take photos of
the art they are hoping to have framed. The digital picture is
downloaded into the computer. Once it appears on-screen, the
consumer can crop or change it. The program analyzes the artwork's
color composition, and then searches its data base of frames,
moldings and mats to find a suitable frame. The customer can
experiment with the computer's choices, changing the frame's color,
shape, size or number of openings.
</P>
<P>
   The data base also offers information about framing products,
manufacturers and suppliers, model numbers and cost. Once the
customer is satisfied, the program will print out the composite
image for preview, and store the customer's choices for future
reference. Oberg received patent 5,870,771.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Spector of Union City, N.J., has designed a computer and
printer terminal that he hopes will simplify special occasions. His
kiosk offers custom-made greeting cards bearing a gift certificate.
</P>
<P>
   A buyer chooses graphics and a message addressed to a specific
person for the greeting card, and then selects a monetary figure or
an item as a gift to be included in the card. The buyer chooses the
store where the certificate can be redeemed, drawing from a list of
pre-approved retail outlets that have Internet sites. The card,
with the embedded gift certificate bearing the recipient's name,
gift description and store name, is then printed out. Spector
received patent 5,870,718.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
