<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUATEMALA15-COX     02-14 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUATEMALA15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bringing Government 301 to life: Texas and Guatemalan students
lead UT democracy project
 &HT;    By Angela Shah
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The bark from the family dog was a brief and
useless signal.
</P>
<P>
   As Magdalena, then 9, and her family slept in the cold night of
early spring, a group of soldiers stormed her one-story white house
in the rural Guatemalan farming town of Patzun. They bound and
dragged off her father. Her mother screamed in protest. Young
Magdalena watched, silent and stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day they took my father away was April 9, 1985, in a leap
year, when dawn comes more quickly,'' said Magdalena Jochula, now
23.
</P>
<P>
   For almost four decades, generations of Guatemalans watched as
friends and family members disappeared during an often brutal civil
war. Many, like Jochula's father, were taken for suspected
involvement in liberation theology, a Christian philosophy used to
free people from economic, social or political injustice.
</P>
<P>
   Most Guatemalans couldn't do anything to stop the military at
the time. But some, like Jochula, are attempting to prevent it from
happening again.
</P>
<P>
   Guatemala's young adults are at the forefront of an effort to
create a nation of their own, 175 years after Guatemala's
independence from Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Following guidelines in peace accords signed in 1996, about 80
students from the University of Texas and two Guatemalan
universities are helping the Guatemalan Congress of Deputies decide
which of the country's 12,000 laws to expunge, which to rewrite and
how to rewrite them.
</P>
<P>
   With a $3 million grant from the U.S. Agency for International
Development, UT is directing the Texas and Guatemalan students in
the Guatemalan Modernization Project. In addition to law making,
they are setting up the sometimes mundane apparatus that keeps
democratic governments functioning: budget boards, legislative
research agencies and the staffs to operate them.
</P>
<P>
   The student volunteers _ most of whom are between 20 and 25
years old _ are invaluable consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are midwives in the birth of a nation,'' said Reginald
Todd, a UT staff member who heads the program's operations in
Guatemala City.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Central American countries, Guatemala fought a
repressive Spain to set up a mostly repressive government of its
own. Other than intermittent spurts when Guatemala had a democratic
government, its history is ripe with episodes of peasant rebellion
against government oppression. The power has always lied with urban
elite, primarily the Spanish upper-class. This has fostered a deep
mistrust of government for the majority of Guatemala's 10 million,
largely indigenous residents.
</P>
<P>
   Guatemala has been ruled by a legal system imposed by Spain,
Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of Guatemala is the history of top-down rule,'' he
added. So, the ``country (is) governed more by tradition and custom
than by formal law.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the students believe they can help create a democratic
system of government. Todd likens the modernization program to an
incubator hatching different governmental bodies: a legislative
technical assistance unit, budget analysis group, legislative
committees and a ``delegislative'' group to eliminate conflicting
or obsolete laws.
</P>
<P>
   The students started creating a database last year of the
thousands of laws passed in Guatemala since 1871. Getting the
message out to Guatemalans, who speak more than 23 dialects, is
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us in the program are dreaming always that we can
change our country,'' said Ana Medina, a Guatemalan student who
oversees the legislative research organization. ``The laws are
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Students such as Medina, 26, research requests by Guatemalan
lawmakers that could lead to a bill being filed. Right now, they
have completed 70 legislative studies on potential bills and have
requests for 90 more. A third of those requests are aimed at
banishing Guatemala's ghosts. But there also are questions of how
to prosecute those guilty of torture, kidnapping or extra-legal
killing. Others deal with more practical concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many in the guerrilla movement moved to southern Mexico. Some
married Mexican citizens, had children born in Mexico,'' said Todd.
``One of the questions is what is the citizenship of those people
during those 36 years?''
</P>
<P>
   Jochula and another team of students will meet with local public
service agencies and international relief organizations to gather
input. For example, Jochula is working on drafting adoption laws,
which Guatemala doesn't have, and is talking with international and
regional groups that can provide expertise on such laws in other
Central American countries and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Todd said the most important thing supporting the students'
efforts is the eagerness of the Guatemalan government's support.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative project also opens up an exchange program
between the Guatemalan students and UT students studying law,
public affairs and other subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Sykes, a UT law and public affairs student who worked with
Jochula in Guatemala City last summer, said the students' idealism
is the key for making the democracy work.
</P>
<P>
   Lariviere agreed. ``We've sent some pretty tough and _ I don't
want to say jaded , let's say experienced _ faculty down there, and
every single one of them comes back full of enthusiasm, and a glint
in their eye they didn't have before,'' he said. ``It's that
idealism and that genuine belief that (the students) can do
something consequential that's infectious.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, 20 of the 80 students have been hired as full-time
staff in the Guatemalan Congress, Todd said. Another 10 have gone
on to graduate school, and 10 other students are working for
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative modernization program also gives Guatemalan
students the chance to study at UT and work in government jobs in
Austin. Medina has an internship in the Texas Senate office of
engrossing and enrolling to learn the mechanics of how bills are
processed and filed. The experience is also giving her the chance
to practice English, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jochula, who will finish law school next year, wants to become a
deputy in the one-house Guatemalan Congress. Self-effacing and
self-confident, she says she wants to be her country's president.
</P>
<P>
   Sykes said Jochula has inspired her.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything, I learned about the importance of strength
of character and perseverance,'' Sykes said. ``Magda has the most
incredible attitude that I have ever encountered. She finds the
positive in even the most tragic aspects of her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
