<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MEXICO _ Coverage of Clinton's Mexico trip.
(Deans/Ferriss, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ORTHODOX _ JERUSALEM _ In an ominous display of one of
Israel's greatest societal rifts, about 100,000 ultra-Orthodox Jews
are expected to protest against the Israeli Supreme Court, which
they have called ``anti-Jewish.'' The court has made several
rulings that go against the special status that Ultra-Orthodox Jews
have had. Counter demonstrations and violence expected. (Kaplow,
Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GUATEMALA _ At age 9, Magdalena Jochola watched the military
cart away her father, the first in a line of male relatives
kidnapped, never to be heard from again. For almost 40 years,
generations of Guatemalans watched friends and family members
disappear during an often-brutal civil war. In 1996, peace accords
were signed, leading the way for Magda and about 80 other students
to work toward preventing the brutality from happening again. With
a grant from the U.S. Agency for International Development, UT, two
Guatemalan universities and the fledgling Guatemalan government are
setting up the sometimes mundane apparatus that keeps democratic
governments functioning: budget boards, house research
organizations, etc. They are making recommendations to the
Guatemalan Deputies on which laws to expunge, which laws to rewrite
and how to rewrite them. The students _ most of whom are between
20- and 25-years-old _ are invaluable assistants to Guatemala's
modern-day founding fathers. They are, says the American chief of
party there, ``midwives in the birth of a nation.'' (Brooks, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   ZULUREX _ NEW ORLEANS _ Today, the kings of Zulu and Rex, the
black and white Mardi Gras parades, are meeting the mayor together
for the first time. Normally only Rex greets the mayor.
(Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-MEN-AMERICA _ As president of the 100 Black Men of
America, 48-year-old Tommy Dortch heads a service organization that
is developing leadership skills among scores of young
African-American males. The organization announced last month that
it is poised to groom scores more from Atlanta and around the
country through a new Youth Leadership Center it plans to build
about 45 miles southwest of Atlanta by the year 2000. Land for the
$7 million center stretches over 500 acres encompassing Coweta,
Meriwether, and Troup counties. ``We've heard much criticism that
black males don't do this and that. This (the institute) is an
effort to take care of our own, and that will benefit everybody,''
Dortch said. (Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GOP-LINCOLN _ WASHINGTON _ In the general election last fall,
the best any statewide Republican candidate could do among African
American voters was George Voinovich's 30 percent in Ohio's U.S.
Senate race. That was nearly three times the national average. And
the most prominent African American in the GOP, Oklahoma
Congressman J.C. Watt, believes it make take at least another
decade to get the Party of Lincoln up to just 20 percent. That is
likely to spell political problems for the party in the 2000
presidential and congressional races. (Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MOVED in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ What's wrong with TAAS? Nothing may
be more emblematic than the reprimand a student received recently _
for reading a history book. Texas should stop the interruptions, or
commit itself to minimizing them. Texas children should be able to
test out of TAAS drudgery. (John Young is opinion page editor of
the Waco Tribune-Herald.) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Jim Webster remembers his wife,
Marianne, the love of his life. (Ezzard, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
