</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFILING TO FIX CODING 
`MONICA'S STORY' UNFOLDS IN FLATIRON BUILDING
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the landmark Flatiron building, which houses St.
Martin's Press, elevators move with all desultory speed so there
was plenty of time last week for the various occupants to discuss
sightings of the fabled ``she.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is she still there?'' one employee asked another on the
downward descent from the 16th floor to the lobby. No first or last
names needed. Everyone seemed to know that Monica Lewinsky and her
new literary confidante, Andrew Morton, were ensconced in an
office, plotting the delicate strategy for the promotion of the
tell-more title, ``Monica's Story.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's, a division of Macmillan Publishers Ltd., is still
planning on a late February publication date for the 288-page
portrait of the former White House intern by Morton, if a
court-imposed order of silence on Ms. Lewinsky is lifted. (``We're
just taking it day to day,'' John Murphy, a St. Martin's spokesman,
said.) But the book is apparently so eagerly anticipated (or
reviled) that potential readers started posting early reviews and
lewd critiques on the online bookstore, Amazon.com, which
eventually removed them.
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's, which is initially printing at least 400,000
copies, is casting the book as a tale of a ``generous-hearted, but
troubled young woman'' who was betrayed by her friend, Linda Tripp,
and thrust as a pawn into a power struggle between President
Clinton and the Office of the Independent Counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Left unsaid is that Ms. Lewinsky got her book deal while Ms.
Tripp was still searching for sympathy, public rehabilitation and,
perhaps, a curious publisher. Ms. Tripp professes that she has no
plans for a book, although she does not rule it out.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the top publishing houses that could offer a
generous advance are unlikely to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her chances are less than zero,'' said an executive at a top
New York publishing house, who insisted on anonymity. ``She is
truly seen as the true harridan of this whole ghastly experience, a
woman who engenders no sympathy from either side of the
controversy. The perception here is that she is such an
unsympathetic figure and so unlikable that there would be an unduly
small number of people interested in her book.''
</P>
<P>
   Publishing well may be the best revenge.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
<P>
   FALWELL TAKES ON THE TELETUBBIES
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jerry Falwell provoked laughter last week when he
chastised ``Teletubbies,'' a popular public television program for
children under the age of 3, accusing one of the cuddly, cooing,
antenna-topped characters, the purple one named Tinky Winky, of
``modeling the gay lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenn Viselman, the man responsible for promoting the
British-made show in the United States, can laugh all the way to
the bank. An estimated $800 million worth of Teletubby products _
toys, videos, pajamas and the like _ were sold in 1998, with PBS
getting a cut, said Jim Silver, the publisher of The Toy Book, a
toy industry trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the show did not make its PBS debut until April, and
products did not go on sale until June, the best-selling item in
the preschool plush-toy category for 1998 was the Talking Teletubby
(when squeezed it says, ``Eh-oh,'' for hello, and ``Bye-bye'').
</P>
<P>
   The Falwell furor happened to erupt during the week-long annual
Toy Fair in New York, which ends Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At the fair, Viselman presented the newest Tubby plush toy, one
with a rudimentary Microsoft computer in its tummy.
</P>
<P>
   An article in the February edition of Falwell's publication,
National Liberty Journal, argues that Tinky Winky is meant to be
gay because he has a boy's voice yet carries a red purse, he is
purple (``the gay-pride color'') and his antenna is a triangle
(``the gay-pride symbol'').
</P>
<P>
   On the ``Today'' show on NBC last week, Falwell told Katie
Couric that to have ``little boys running around with purses and
acting effeminate and leaving the idea that the masculine male, the
feminine female is out and gay is OK'' is something ``which
Christians do not agree with.''
</P>
<P>
   Viselman, who was also on the program, countered: ``We're
talking about a show for 1- to 4-year-olds. If we had homosexuals
in it, they wouldn't even know it,'' adding quickly, ``but we
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   After a busy day at Toy Fair, Silver said last Friday that
Falwell had probably helped the Teletubbies' business.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he's done is make a mockery of himself, and if anything
put more attention on Teletubbies and increases sales,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Lawrie Mifflin
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA BUYERS WORRY ABOUT THE TIMING AT TALK
</P>
<P>
   The announcement last week that Talk magazine would arrive on
newsstands in August _ the offspring of Miramax Films, which is
owned by the Walt Disney Co., and Hearst Magazines _ caused a
flurry of discussion in several industries.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of advertising, media buyers said that they were
concerned with what they perceived to be the late start in selling
ad pages for Talk. Roberta Garfinkle, the director of print media
at McCann-Erickson, a unit of the Interpublic Group of Cos., said
she would have liked to have seen Talk sell its ad pages earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``With an August launch, I think March is a little bit on the
late side to start selling advertising,'' she said, referring to
need of media buyers to plan yearlong schedules. ``Is it going to
hurt them substantially? No. But I think that there may be some
instances where budgets have been committed and it's too late to
make changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Writers wondered about pay days. Hiring writers at Hearst may
not prove as easy as it was with Conde Nast, a company known for
being extremely generous with writers' salaries. Ms. Brown said
that she was negotiating to hire a dozen writers away from other
publications, but was not able to announce who she was hiring yet.
``Their bosses don't know,'' she said. But writers who have been
approached by Ms. Brown's magazine have said that they were
surprised that salaries were not as high as expected.
</P>
<P>
   And in Hollywood, there had been rumors that Michael D. Eisner,
the chairman of the Walt Disney Co., did not know about Miramax's
involvement with Ms. Brown until very late in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, Eisner said, ``I have been trying to make a
deal with Tina for several years.'' As to whether starting a
magazine was risky, he said, ``I measure high risk by talent, and
Tina Brown is so talented that it puts a conservative bent on the
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with Ms. Black, Ms. Brown, Ron Galotti, the
publisher of Talk, and Harvey Weinstein, the co-chairman of Miramax
Films, Weinstein said that he was certain Ms. Brown and Galotti
would not be wasteful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been out to dinner 10 times with Ron, and he's never once
picked up the check,'' Weinstein said. ``He's frugal, I
guarantee.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Alex Kuczynski and Geraldine Fabrikant
</P>
</TEXT>
