</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASIC DIVISIONS IN NATO PIT EUROPEANS AGAINST U.S.
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The NATO alliance, as it approaches its 50th anniversary
celebrations in Washington in April, is hardly one big, happy
family.
</P>
<P>
   While the latest squabbles have been over how to share the
burdens of placing troops in Kosovo, the division is bigger than
any single issue, running to core of the future mission of the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The European allies are complaining about American
highhandedness, the elevated place of what the French call American
hyperpower and what Europeans see as a growing tendency by
Washington to go it alone.
</P>
<P>
   American officials answer that they welcome a more active role
for the Europeans, but that the Europeans are incapable of taking
the lead, even when the United States offers it to them.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side really seems to believe that the other side means
what it says. Some military officials even worry that Congress may
eventually get so fed up that it will wash its hands of the whole
mess.
</P>
<P>
   The discord is such that France, the loudest voice of European
complaint, now seems to spend nearly as much time trying to counter
American power as to cooperate with it.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the Europeans are demanding more say in fashioning a
new purpose for the alliance, and American officials are
increasingly concerned about French-led efforts to make European
defense less dependent on American leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States of America today predominates on the
economic level, on the monetary level, on the military level, on
the technological level, and in the cultural area in the broad
sense of the word,'' the French Foreign Minister, Hubert Vedrine,
said in a recent speech in Paris. ``It is not comparable, in terms
of power and influence, to anything known in modern history.''
</P>
<P>
   While French leaders since de Gaulle have chafed at American
dominance, both President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin's government have been saying since last summer that
multilateral institutions, from the International Monetary Fund to
the United Nations, should be strengthened to offset American
influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire foreign policy of France, among other objectives,
is aimed at making the world of tomorrow composed of several poles,
not just a single one,'' Vedrine said. Chirac, a few weeks earlier,
said avoiding ``unilateral temptations'' should be the first
principle of the multipolar international order.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac plans a short working visit to the United States starting
on Thursday, a week after a visit by German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder, who has himself raised similar concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That there is a danger of unilateralism, not by just anybody
but by the United States, is undeniable,'' Schroeder said at the
Munich Conference on Security Policy, a gathering of allied
officials and strategists, early this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a new Europe for a new NATO,'' he said, ``and we want
a new NATO for a new Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The German foreign minister, Joschka Fischer, also in Munich,
added that the ``growing tendency to avoid multilateral solutions''
should be seen by Europe as ``a challenge to build up its own
political authority.''
</P>
<P>
   The Germans have also irritated the United States by calling on
NATO to say it would not be the first to use nuclear weapons in
conflict with any adversary who also has them, a proposal rejected
by almost all the other allies but welcomed by Canada.
</P>
<P>
   European policymakers, an American official said recently,
apparently did not realize how much some of the sounds coming out
of Europe these days, particularly from Paris, have irritated
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The United States still hopes to get the allies, in their visits
to Washington, to redefine ``collective security'' to include
threats from missiles and weapons of mass destruction from outside
NATO's traditional turf. The French, however, are leading the fight
to keep the alliance's new strategy down to earth.
</P>
<P>
   The French defense minister, Alain Richard, warned those present
at the Munich forum, ``Approach with caution any new formula
implying that one of the essential tasks of the alliance ought to
be to make it the `policeman of the world,' with the mission of
dealing with crises all over the globe.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same gathering, Secretary of Defense William Cohen
challenged the European allies to put their money where their mouth
was. The United States, he said, had plans for $112 billion in
additional military spending over the next six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it may not be possible for all alliance members to seek
and secure dramatically increased defense budgets, we believe that
if the alliance is to exist in word and deed, in fighting capacity
as well as political appeal, then, at a minimum, defense budgets
cannot be reduced further,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Europe is tired of being an economic power but a
political and strategic dwarf, as it has been for most of the last
50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Even Britain, which alone among the European allies has joined
the United States in bombing Iraq over Russian objections, went
along with France in early December with a call for the European
Union to have ``the capacity for autonomous action, backed up by
credible military forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain's defense secretary, George Robertson, assured his
American colleagues in Munich, ``America has nothing to fear from a
European defense identity within the Atlantic Alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   The French, however, are unhappy with the degree of increased
authority the United States is prepared to give Europe within NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since President Kennedy, we've been hearing from people on the
other side of the Atlantic about a European pillar for the
alliance,'' Vedrine said. ``In reality, this pillar is never
built.'' The reason is that NATO is built on a ``hierarchical
foundation with a strict subordination of all participants'' to the
United States, which he conceded, insures the ``credibility of the
whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander R. Vershbow, the American representative to NATO,
reassured the Europeans in Munich that the Clinton administration
would not try, at the Washington NATO summit meeting, to drag the
allies into following the United States wherever it wanted to go,
from Iraq to North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that there is going to be a radical widening of
alliance responsibilities is a misreading of the situation,'' he
said. ``The new strategic concept is really going to reflect the
changes NATO has already undergone in the past 10 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
