<SLUG> BC-INDUSTRY-VIEW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETING HELPED TURN SMALL COMPANY INTO A POWERHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Calif.) (rk) 
 By GLENN RIFKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Much has been written about Cisco Systems Inc. and
how it rose from obscurity to market prominence by providing the
switches and routers that form the plumbing of the Internet. But
there is another, more obscure, player that has reaped Internet
rewards by producing a fundamental piece of technology.
</P>
<P>
   The EMC Corp. is to data storage what Cisco is to routers. But
few outside of Wall Street and corporate data centers are familiar
with this emerging technology powerhouse. Based in Hopkinton,
Mass., on the far western reaches of metropolitan Boston's Route
128 high-technology belt, EMC dominates the $10 billion market for
large data storage systems _ a market it wrested from IBM.
</P>
<P>
   EMC, which had revenue of $4 billion last year, provides the
storage systems for corporate computer systems _ not only
mainframes but also the power network server computers through
which corporate America uses the Internet. And America Online, as
well as seven of the other 10 largest Internet service providers,
employ EMC storage systems as their main data repositories.
</P>
<P>
   Although EMC was founded 20 years ago, it was only in the 1990s
that the company rose to the leadership of the large data storage
market _ a category encompassing both hardware and software that is
expected to reach $35 billion by 2001, according to the Dataquest
research house. With the Internet creating a seemingly insatiable
appetite for storage, and with corporate computing needs growing
apace, EMC has seen its annual profits surge from $30 million in
1992 to nearly $800 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Its stock _ which closed on Friday at $102.375, down $1.75 _ has
been the second-best performer in the S&AMP;P 500 in the 1990s, with a
return of more than 32,000 percent, second only to Dell Computer's
50,000 percent. Its stock market value, more than $50 billion, is
larger than for companies like American Express, Boeing and
Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   Part of EMC's success lies in its having embraced an approach
that might be called radical marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Radical marketers emphasize listening to customers; creating a
community atmosphere among customers who are served by employees
and salespeople who are expected to take a missionary's zeal to
their work. Marketing is also made one of the top priorities of the
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Successful organizations in a wide range of endeavors _
including Harley-Davidson Motorcycles, Providian Financial and Iams
pet food _ have employed radical marketing techniques to overcome
the larger advertising budgets and giant marketing machines of
their bigger competitors.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of EMC, the tone was set by the co-founder and
chairman, Richard J. Egan, and the chief executive, Michael C.
Ruettgers, who joined the company in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1990, EMC had no measurable share of the market
for mainframe data storage. At that time, IBM owned three-quarters
of the market, in which the prevailing wisdom among information
technology professionals was the aphorism that ``no one ever lost
his job by buying IBM''
</P>
<P>
   How quickly things can change. Today, EMC owns 35 percent of the
market for large external storage systems, compared with a 22
percent share for the market's No. 2 company, IBM, which has now
focused much of its attention on building smaller computer disk
drives rather than the large data storage systems in which EMC
specializes.
</P>
<P>
   How did EMC do this? To begin with, EMC helped convince
customers that the data storage system was no longer a mundane
peripheral to corporate computers but a technological weapon which
the customer could put to strategic business use.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the catalog merchant LL Bean, an EMC customer,
found that it could process transactions sufficiently faster to add
a full day _ and tens of millions of dollars in sales _ to its
holiday shopping season and still promise delivery by Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   EMC's rise came on the wings of its Symmetrix storage systems, a
product line that was introduced in 1990 and that drastically
shifted the technical assumptions about data storage.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than follow IBM's model of writing millions of lines of
complex software microcode to run these refrigerator-size
electronic file cabinets, EMC engineers built storage devices made
up of hundreds of small, off-the-shelf disk drives. The engineers
were able to make these devices work together with a simple bit of
microcode, and the company packaged them as smaller, cheaper,
faster, more powerful and _ as it turned out _ inherently more
reliable storage devices.
</P>
<P>
   That pioneering technology was known as RAID (redundant array of
independent disks). And though it was invented at the University of
California at Berkeley, EMC developed it into a commercially viable
product that processed data faster than conventional storage
devices and took up less floor space, too.
</P>
<P>
   IBM had reaped 70 percent profit margins by selling ``one size
fits all'' systems, much to the chagrin of corporate
information-technology managers, who had long felt hampered by such
limited and restrictive offerings _ and were often hard pressed to
afford the systems, which might sell for $700,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   EMC aimed to address such frustrations, seeking the advice of
corporate computing managers and inviting them to a visitor center
at EMC headquarters, where customers could regularly meet with
engineers, see work in progress and offer suggestions. And to turn
visitors into customers, EMC put the new systems into client sites
at no charge for a few months of testing.
</P>
<P>
   The Unum Corp., a large insurance company, used the free trial
to process its year-end data, an enormous number-crunching effort
that traditionally took two full weeks of computer time. Using
EMC's system, the company completed the task in three days. The
customer was sold.
</P>
<P>
   EMC executives referred to these as ``puppy dog sales.'' Once
the cute puppy was home, few cared to return it to the pet shop. It
didn't hurt that initially at least, EMC's prices tended to be
hundreds of thousands of dollars below IBM's.
</P>
<P>
   And over time, EMC learned to concentrate on the customers that
could implicity help the company market its products. For example,
some 9,000 banks in the United States spend nearly $20 billion each
year on information technology.
</P>
<P>
   EMC knows that the top five _ BankAmerica, Chase Manhattan,
Citigroup, JP Morgan and Banc One _ account for nearly 40 percent
of that spending. All are EMC customers. Winning them has helped
the company turn the other top 25 banks into EMC customers today,
and more of the nation's smaller banks are coming into the EMC fold
each month.
</P>
<P>
   Grab the leaders and the rest generally follow. It's one of the
premises of radical marketing _ the technology marketing model for
the 21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
