u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASDAG-HALTS-NYT &LR;      02-14 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASDAG-HALTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ REVIVES PROPOSAL TO TEST TRADING HALTS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With continued volatility in Internet stocks, Nasdaq
regulators are now moving to temporarily halt trading of the most
wildly unstable shares.
</P>
<P>
   Frank G. Zarb, chairman of Nasdaq's parent, the National
Association of Securities Dealers, has asked the association's
board to consider testing trading halts for one year. A proposal to
institute the use of trading halts was rejected just two weeks ago
by a Nasdaq committee of market makers and brokerage firm officials
that had studied the issue as a possible remedy to large daily
price swings in Internet-related shares.
</P>
<P>
   But in the wake of recent warnings about online trading by the
Securities and Exchange Commission's chairman, Arthur Levitt, and
the disclosure by the New York attorney general, Eliot L. Spitzer,
that he would investigate the Internet trading industry, Zarb will
now ask the association board to consider allowing halts.
</P>
<P>
   Association officials said the plan, which would also require
SEC approval, would allow Nasdaq to halt trading in a stock
immediately ``when there appears to be significant corporate news
or when a company's security is experiencing extraordinary
volatility, either of which is impacting the fairness and
orderliness of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The enormous level of recent trading activity, Zarb said in a
statement, has created ``new issues of volatility and trading
practices, issues that must be addressed by the exchanges and
member firms to preserve the fairness of the market for
investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates say that trading halts have worked at the New York
Stock Exchange and that they would stem the sharpest price moves of
Internet-related stocks. But opponents contend that halts could
increase volatility by causing investors to rush to make trades
before a halt.
</P>
<P>
   A key issue that has not been resolved is what specific criteria
Nasdaq officials would use before halting trading in a stock, said
Bernard L. Madoff, a leading Nasdaq market maker and head of the
Securities Industry Association trading committee. ``It's something
long overdue, and I think it would be a sensible way to deal with
some of the volatility occurring in the marketplace,'' said Madoff,
who expects that officials of both the association and the SEC will
approve trading halts.
</P>
<P>
   While the idea has been dismissed before, he said, ``I think the
circumstances in the marketplace today are such that there is so
much volatility, and so many small public orders coming in, that it
makes more sense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 1855EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
