<HEADLINE>
A TEST OF HONG KONG'S AUTONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late last month Hong Kong's final court of appeal made a
landmark decision. It ruled that children of Hong Kong residents
could legally live in Hong Kong and did not require Beijing's
permission to do so.
</P>
<P>
   It was without doubt the single most important affirmation of
Hong Kong's legal autonomy since ``one country, two systems'' came
into effect with the turnover to Chinese sovereignty in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was important not so much for what it said about
immigration and residency rights in the former colony but because
it in effect overruled the National People's Congress on the
subject, affirming the independence of Hong Kong's judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   An independent judiciary is the touchstone of Deng Xiaoping's
``one country, two systems,'' for without it there would be only
one system. An independent judiciary is also not a concept that
Chinese officials are comfortable with, though they are making baby
steps in that direction, because an independent court system means
that there is a higher authority than the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   This week there have been rumblings out of China that Hong
Kong's courts must be brought to heel. ``This is a very serious
matter,'' said Zhao Qizheng, a minister of information for the
Chinese Cabinet. ``The decision needs to be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Beijing's Law Daily, an official publication, quoted Xiao Yang,
president of the Supreme People's Court of China, as saying that
``courts of all levels throughout the country must strengthen their
contact with the people's delegates'' to the National People's
Congress ``and actively accept the supervision of the NPC.'' In
other words, in China the party's wishes should be the law.
</P>
<P>
   It is up to Hong Kong to remain firm on this matter. If the Hong
Kong courts can be intimidated and overruled by the party bosses in
Beijing, then the carefully constructed local autonomy that is
supposed to guide Hong Kong for the next 50 years will be rendered
a fraud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 1859EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
