<SLUG> BC-AMR-PILOTS-2TAKES(920)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMONG PILOTS, A LONG HISTORY OF DEEP DISTRUST
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Texas, Colo., Ill.)  (Duplication notice: Also moving `a' category code.) 
 (jw) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A senior pilot at American Airlines works about 14 days a month
and can earn more than $200,000 a year. Forced by federal law to
retire at age 60, that pilot receives a lifelong pension and a
lump-sum payment that in some recent cases has reached $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Yet hundreds of American pilots called in sick last week to vent
their rage at the airline's management, forcing the cancellation of
thousands of flights and inconveniencing hundreds of thousands of
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Their anger was not unusual. In September, striking pilots
grounded Northwest Airlines for nearly three weeks. And pilots at
Federal Express threatened for a time to disrupt the peak Christmas
delivery season.
</P>
<P>
   So why are some of America's best-paid and most highly respected
workers among its most militant? Some answers can be found in the
pilots' central role in the airline industry and in past labor
conflicts that have left the pilots with a deep distrust of
management.
</P>
<P>
   But it is just as important to look at the character traits of
the pilots themselves. Members of a highly skilled elite, pilots
both individually and as a group often exhibit a self-confidence
that some industry executives say borders on arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really think that they are at the center of the
universe,'' said an executive at a major airline who regularly
negotiates with the pilots and therefore insisted on anonymity.
``They are people who are trained to think in terms of right and
wrong. They are not trained to tolerate ambiguity.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of American's pilots returned to work Sunday after a
federal judge cited their union for contempt on Saturday for
disobeying his order to end the sickout and ordered the union to
set aside $10 million to pay for damages. American was forced to
cancel fewer flights Sunday and the disruption appeared to subside
at many major airports.
</P>
<P>
   But the union and the airline, which plan to hold a negotiating
session Monday, are still far from reaching a settlement over the
main issue in the dispute: how American will integrate Reno Air, a
small airline it bought in December to expand its presence in the
West. Some pilots said the airline's operations were likely to
continue to suffer because many pilots would strictly adhere to
work rules by refusing to fly overtime until an agreement was
reached.
</P>
<P>
   In his scathing ruling, U.S. District Judge Joe Kendall in
Dallas trivialized the pilots' differences with management and
called the sickout a ``shakedown'' worthy of organized crime. But
while the judge found the union responsible for the damage to
American and its passengers _ and seemed determined to make them
pay for it _ the pilots and their defenders saw things very
differently.
</P>
<P>
   To the pilots, American's handling of the Reno Air purchase was
the latest in a series of deceitful moves by the company designed
to squeeze more work out of them and erode their job security. They
accuse the airline of violating the fundamental protection in their
contract that guarantees that all flying at American will be done
by members of their union, the Allied Pilots Association.
</P>
<P>
   The 300 pilots at Reno Air, which has 25 planes, are represented
by the rival Air Line Pilots Association and earn much less than
their counterparts at American.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great job and I love it, but I don't want it to become
a bad job,'' said one American pilot who enthusiastically
participated in the sickout and spoke on the condition that he not
be identified. ``If we don't hold the line here on the heart of our
contract, then we will travel down a slippery slope.''
</P>
<P>
   Antipathy between pilots and airline management is almost as old
as commercial aviation itself. The first pilots strike was in 1932,
a year after the Air Line Pilots Association was founded. The
union, which is the industry's largest, now has 52,000 members at
51 airlines and is one of the richest and most powerful members of
the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   In those early years, flying was much more dangerous than it is
today. Pilots resented that airline owners forced them to fly too
many hours, often in foul weather. ``They felt these people were
making money exploiting them,'' said George Hopkins, a professor at
Western Illinois University who has written two books on the
history of pilots unions. ``They saw these people as little more
than profiteers.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude has not changed much.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the pilots themselves have never been an easy
group for airline executives, or anyone else, to deal with. Many
learn to fly in the military, where even early in their careers
they are part of an elite corps. By the time they are given the
controls of a commercial jet worth $30 million to $170 million and
the responsibility for the lives of hundreds of passengers, many
have developed outsized egos, their critics say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you gave the company to them to run,'' said Michael Boyd,
an aviation consultant in Evergreen, Colo., whose father was a
captain at American, ``they would say, `I can't run it with this
amount of money. Give me more.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And to a large degree, their exalted status is reinforced by the
traveling public. One major airline recently did a survey on public
attitudes toward pilot pay and found that most people were not
offended that airline pilots were making $200,000 a year. Those
surveyed felt that pilots, like heart surgeons, should be well
compensated because they wanted to see those professions attract
the most competent people.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As the industry has grown in recent years, the pilots' position
has became more pivotal. ``They occupy a good square on the
board,'' said an executive at a major airline who has faced them
across the negotiating table. ``Alone among the large work groups,
they can shut down the airline and it is not practical to replace
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet at the same time, the job itself has become more mundane.
Commercial jets have become more automated, requiring less actual
flying skill. In any case, airline pilots cannot rise on merit.
They move from second officer to first officer to captain, earning
progressively higher pay, based on their years at the airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are for the most part overachievers, but they can't show
their skill,'' said a second airline executive who insisted on
anonymity for fear of jeopardizing relations with the pilots at his
carrier. ``They can't move to another airline because of seniority.
All they can do is sit around and complain about `their deal.' The
deal becomes the way they measure their progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilot groups have often had trouble even getting along with each
other. The Allied Pilots Association split off from the Air Line
Pilots Association in 1963, becoming an independent union, because
of a complex set of events that boiled down to a personality clash
between two pilot leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Even though American's pilots now appear to be demanding higher
pay for pilots at Reno Air, the latter are unhappy because the
Allied Pilots Association has suggested putting the Reno pilots at
the bottom of its seniority list. The Reno pilots want some credit
for their years at the airline and they complain that the American
pilots have refused to negotiate with them.
</P>
<P>
   But by far the most friction remains between pilots and
management. Some of the bitterest battles took place after the
airline industry was deregulated 20 years ago. Several venerable
airlines, including Braniff, Eastern and Pan American, filed for
bankruptcy and ultimately went out of business, forcing many pilots
with years of experience to start over at the bottom of the ladder
at other carriers. Many of the airlines that survived demanded that
pilots roll back wages and make other concessions. Then, when the
industry turned around, they found that management opposed raising
their wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pilots see themselves as having been completely taken by
management since the era of deregulation began,'' Hopkins said.
</P>
<P>
   That has certainly been the case at American, even though the
airline has emerged from deregulation as one of the industry's
strongest competitors. The pilots feel that they had to fight with
Robert Crandall, American's combative former chairman and chief
executive, for everything they now have.
</P>
<P>
   Many American pilots are still bitter about a two-tier wage
scale introduced by Crandall in the mid-1980s that paid newly hired
pilots less than those already flying. They also remember cutbacks
and layoffs in the early 1990s that they say enabled Reno Air to
get its start. And they are still angry about their brief strike
two years ago, which was ended when President Clinton ordered them
back to work.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton then appointed a special emergency board, which helped
the union and the airline work out a tentative contract. Many
pilots felt they had no choice but to ratify the agreement;
otherwise, Congress could have imposed a contract on the union.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, many pilots stopped volunteering for overtime,
forcing American to cancel a modest number of flights, after it
discovered that the airline was placing more American passengers on
Canadian Airlines, one of its foreign partners, than was allowed in
an agreement with the union. Many pilots are also angry that a new
system for scheduling flights is not as flexible as the airline
promised.
</P>
<P>
   All this was in the background, when the union learned on Dec.
28 that American had taken full control of Reno Air. American said
that it discussed the Reno Air purchase with leaders of the pilots
union and that they raised no objections. But the airline closed
the deal without first reaching an agreement with the union over
how it would merge the two carriers.
</P>
<P>
   American later said that it would take as long as 18 months to
combine the two airlines because it needed to refit Reno Air's
airplanes and retrain crews at the two airlines. The pilots suspect
that the company is dragging out the integration so that it can
continue to pay Reno Air pilots at lower rates. It is worried about
setting a precedent for future acquisitions, perhaps of much larger
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The union has said that the 150 jobs as captains at Reno Air now
belong to pilots at American and that the company should begin
paying every American pilot as if the transition had been
completed. American responded that doing that would give immediate
raises to 2,000 pilots as the promotions rippled through the ranks,
costing $50 million in 1999 alone. The two sides tried to negotiate
a resolution for five weeks before the exasperated pilots began
calling in sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than signing a transition agreement with APA that would
allow both completion of Reno's integration as well as compliance
with our basic contract, AMR has so far stonewalled APA's
negotiators on this important issue,'' Richard LaVoy, the union's
president, said.
</P>
<P>
   American says it has not violated the pilot contract and does
not understand what all the fuss is about. ``We intend to pay Reno
pilots American Airlines wages, and we intend to offer promotion
opportunities to APA pilots who will benefit from the airline's
expansion on the West Coast,'' the company has said.
</P>
<P>
   But to the many pilots who stopped trusting American executives
a long time ago, promises are not enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
