<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SUVS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TANKING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Falling gasoline prices are a boon for consumers and the US
Treasury, which collects 18 cents a gallon in taxes, but they are
reshaping tastes in ways that require some careful thinking. This
is the right time to start addressing serious problems of urban
congestion and a degraded environment.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thought gasoline would never again be available for
less than a dollar a gallon has had a pleasant surprise. It is
commonplace to see off-brands for 95 cents or even less. In fact,
gasoline prices are now at their lowest level ever when adjusted
for inflation, according to the American Petroleum Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that automobiles have become more
fuel-efficient, averaging more than 20 miles per gallon today
compared with 14 miles a gallon in the early 1970s, consumption has
risen to about 8 million barrels a day now compared with 6 million
then.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key factors has been a surge of interest in sport
utility vehicles, which are exempt from federal gasoline
consumption rules.
</P>
<P>
   Federal gasoline taxes were 4 cents a gallon in the early 70s
and are 18 cents a gallon today, so receipts have gone from $10
million a day then to more than $60 million today _ $22 billion a
year. The Department of Transportation estimates that the figure,
thanks to added consumption, will rise by about $1.4 billion above
recent projections.
</P>
<P>
   Most of that pays for road and bridge projects like the massive
Big Dig. But more of these revenues should be used to address
longer-term transportation problems. Bigger vehicles take more
space on the roads, as anyone who has been sandwiched between two
SUVs can attest. They are adding disproportionately to emissions
and take more space when they park.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the extra revenue should be used to offset those impacts
by going back to additional rail and bus service, to research on
improved efficiency, and to getting a handle on the road gluttons.
Otherwise we may all drown in gasoline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 1908EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990214.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5091 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WOMEN-NYT &LR;      02-14 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S GROWTH IN SOCCER NOTED IN WORLD CUP DRAW
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Kim Sun Hui was already 17 years old when she
first touched a soccer ball with her instep. Before that, women
were not encouraged to play soccer in her country, North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when many nations are promoting soccer as the major
team sport for female athletes, Kim made the transition from track
and field to soccer. Sunday she was here from Pyongyang, playing in
an all-star game to promote the Women's World Cup of soccer that
begins four months from now, and will be played at stadiums around
the United States June 19 to July 10.
</P>
<P>
   The North Korean team was one of the 16 nations (14 qualifiers
plus the United States as the host nation and Norway as the
defending champion) placed in the draw at halftime Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of football is feminine,'' is the operative slogan
from Joseph (Sepp) Blatter, the head of the world soccer body known
as FIFA.
</P>
<P>
   As soccer grows in popularity among women _ an estimated 30
million now play _ many of them tell the same story about facing
stereotypes that soccer is a tough-guy game, not suitable for
tender females.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, `the women should be home in the kitchen,' '' said Ulrika
Karlsson, the goalkeeper from Sweden, surely one of the more
advanced nations for the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Other nations are catching up, trying to catch up in the huge
swell of interest since the first Women's World Cup in China in
1991 and the second in Sweden in 1995. North Korea has come from
virtually nowhere to qualify _ the first time any soccer team from
that nation has reached a World Cup since the mysterious men's team
inflicted considerable pain to established nations in the classic
1966 World Cup in England.
</P>
<P>
   Kim did not begin the way many other of Sunday's all-stars did _
playing against boys in her neighborhood. She was trained as a
defender, is quite proud of her ability to intercept passes near
the goal, but said, through a translator, ``I am very pleased to be
in the vanguard, but I am always hoping I am not too late to learn
soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of her teammates Sunday have a full decade of experience on
her. Mercy Akide of Nigeria, a rangy midfielder, said that she grew
up playing with boys. ``They called me Tomboy,'' she said with a
big smile, but she said that the women's game has become popular.
</P>
<P>
   Graziele Grazi of Brazil, a lithe 17-year-old known only by one
name in Brazilian soccer fashion, spoke openly about the old
stereotype: ``In Brazil there was a lot of bias against women
playing soccer. Some people thought that only lesbians played
soccer. But now this is not as much of an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of attitudes Graziele describes, women's soccer in
Brazil has developed slowly, despite that country's being the
emotional center of the men's sport. In the team brochure, the
players list their soccer idol and Graziele lists Denilson and most
of her teammates list Zico, Romario or Ronaldo or other male stars,
but two women do list their teammate, Sisleide Lima do Amor, known
as Sissi.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of talent in Brazil,'' Graziele said. ``Our
men's team did not win the World Cup in France so maybe we can win
in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Some all-stars have come through an established club system,
like Sue Smith of England, whose country did not qualify for the
World Cup. Smith is from Liverpool, and grew up playing against
boys in a park _ not on Penny Lane, she replied patiently.
``Everybody asks me that.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith joined a local club called Tranmere Rovers that has
recently beaten the women from both Liverpool and Everton, the two
civic powers. Born into a family that roots for Everton, Smith
sheepishly admits that as a left wing she emulates Ryan Giggs, the
Welsh left wing for Manchester United.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you switch on the telly, that's what you see,'' Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   But this summer the women will be on the telly _ all 32 games
shown by ABC and ESPN and many available around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, which won the 1996 Summer Olympics
tournament, is the favorite, and has been seeded into a host slot
for games in Giants Stadium in East Rutherford, N.J., on June 19,
Soldier Field in Chicago on June 24 and Foxboro Stadium in
Massachusetts on June 27.
</P>
<P>
   Norway, the defending champion, hopes to meet the United States
in the final in the Rose Bowl on July 10. The Norwegians will have
a bicoastal schedule in the first round, and could be affected by
the heat as well as the jet lag.
</P>
<P>
   Then, consider the team seeded fourth in Group C _ Foxboro on
June 20, Civic Stadium in Portland, Ore., on the night of June 23,
then back to Giants Stadium for a noon game on June 26 _ grueling
conditions even for millionaire males in professional basketball.
</P>
<P>
   This may not be a consolation for weary female athletes, but
perhaps these brutal schleps around this huge country are a sign
that women's soccer is reaching the big time. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
