A5092 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-MIRANDA-BOS     02-14 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MIRANDA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRANDA WRONGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On television a defendant's Miranda rights have the healthy life
that they deserve as a pillar of American democracy. In real life
they are being destructively chipped away.
</P>
<P>
   Fictional police, to convey irony, anger, or pleasure, rely on
the Miranda chant: ``You have the right to remain silent. You have
the right to an attorney. You have the right to have an attorney
appointed if you cannot afford one. Anything you say can be used
against you in a court of law.''
</P>
<P>
   This drill sprang from a 1966 Supreme Court ruling on the cases
of Ernesto Miranda, charged with rape and kidnapping, and other
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   It was not, as the ruling explained, an ``innovation.'' Miranda
bundled already existing rights to address a history of unjust
interrogations that stretched back to pre-Colonial days in England.
The ruling also pointed to 1930s America, with its police violence
and infamous use of the ``third degree.'' With an eye for human
weakness, the court cited the ``temptation to press the witness
unduly, to browbeat him if he be timid or reluctant.''
</P>
<P>
   But this week, a bruising attack waged by a federal appeals
court in Virginia threatens to degrade Miranda from a
constitutionally &UR;  &LR; based right to merely a good but not always
necessary idea.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia court cited a 1968 law saying confessions could be
admissible in court if they were given voluntarily. In other words,
33-year-old Miranda was overruled 31 years ago. It is fine, said
the court _ and should have been for decades _ for federal
prosecutors to ignore Miranda.
</P>
<P>
   This finding is outrageous. It may technically adhere to the
1968 law _ one the Justice Department has never enforced _ but it
is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In 15 seconds a police officer can state Miranda rights,
providing a key democratic and American protection with almost no
effort. This can hardly be a barrier given today's sophisticated
investigatory and technological tools.
</P>
<P>
   If protecting Miranda means repealing the 1968 law, Congress
should do so. Otherwise the fulfillment of the Bill of Rights _
from its protection against self-incrimination to the right to
counsel _ will be changed from groundbreaking history to a historic
waste of time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 1917EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
