<HEADER>
A5095 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-WEEK15-COX     02-14 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-WEEK15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Luxury fabrics in drab brown, olive slink down Fashion Week
runways
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At this point, the news from Fashion Week that might
matter to the most people is also the least exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Brown _ not fuschia, not periwinkle, not even gray, for goodness
sake _ has been the most prevalent color shown by designers so far
during previews of their fall/winter collections. News of the
second most-often shown color _ olive _ is equally drab.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the question of color, some interesting patterns that the
masses might not be ready to embrace are taking shape.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the clothes for the last cold-weather season of
this century are taking a stance of pre-millenial preparedness.
More often than not, they're being rendered in the luxury fabrics
commonly associated with the rich and pampered. But stylistically,
they present a look that asserts, ``I'm strong, confident and savvy
enough to withstand whatever follows that fated stroke of
midnight.''
</P>
<P>
   JOHN BARTLETT
</P>
<P>
   In this collection, Bartlett offered a vision of 21st-century
pioneers. His models _ male and female, since this is the first
time New York has combined its men's and women's fashion weeks _
wore their clothes like body armour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boiled'' cashmere, ``bonded'' wool, ``iron'' cotton and
``oxidized'' gabardine were among the fabrics. Outfits for both
sexes featured deep-pocketed aprons, and most clothes were fitted
to showcase all the alluring things about our bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett clings to the ``utility'' trend; he affixed
militaristic terms to shirts (``CPO''), pants (``sailor'') and
coats (``field''). But he helps utility evolve by making it
precious: His capes were glorious collages of distressed, colored
leather; his sweaters were bundles of joy; his slinky dresses would
look seductive even on hangers.
</P>
<P>
   JOSEPH ABBOUD
</P>
<P>
   Two factors were missing from this show: telejournalist Bryant
Gumbel, who normally sits front and center at Abboud's shows and
wears his next-door neighbor's designs routinely, and the attitude
of understated elegance that has been Abboud's trademark. Neither
was particularly missed.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than work its way up to the formal wear segment, as most
shows do, Abboud's kicked off with an intimidating display of what
the boldest among the beautiful should be wearing on New Year's
Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Menswear is Abboud's top priority, but his velvet halters and
satin pants topped by wrap vests proved that one great evening look
is all a stylish woman needs. For day, Abboud put women in suits
made for walking: elongated coats, trim pants, low-heeled shoes.
</P>
<P>
   His clothes for men demand to be touched, insist on being seen.
Formal wear consisted of velvet robes and paisley dinner jackets
and suede pants. Clothing was tailored to show a lot of the tie,
the cuffs, the shoes. Thanks to an extensive use of stripes and
plaids and paisley, everything looked bright.
</P>
<P>
   Considering its restriction to a gray, ivory and bronze color
scheme, Abboud was right in calling the collection ``artistry.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
