<HEADER>
A5100 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-POSTCARD15-CO     02-14 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-POSTCARD15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Orange accessories shine in the Big Apple
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Common things _ such as arriving at a runway show
only to find some shifty-eyed gate-crasher sitting in the chair
assigned to you _ are what make people chronically standoffish
during Fashion Week.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness for the oddball things _ like Atlanta-based
Kleinberg Sherrill's luxury handbags _ that bring people together.
</P>
<P>
   An orange alligator-skin purse and matching, silver-buckled belt
by Kleinberg Sherrill was one of 38 orange items being auctioned
over the weekend at the Look Art Gallery in the East Village as
part of a ``Celebration of Accessories'' exhibition. And it's the
Kleinberg Sherrill purse and belt that the Atlantans, as well as
the thousands of others gathered here this week to critique
clothes, gravitated to during the opening gala.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bag? It's chic and glamorous and luxurious, like
something the Europeans carry,'' said Daphne Shirley, a publicist.
``And the matte color of it is certainly left of center. Everything
else here is like the color of SunKist. This is more like a
tangerine.''
</P>
<P>
   Orange, incidentally, is starting to look like one of the key
accent colors for fall/winter 1999-2000. And luxury leathers
apparently are going to play an even more important role in the way
fashionable women dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``My business is skyrocketing,'' said Page Bondurant, director
of sales for Trussardi, a luxury leather goods company. ``That's
all the stores want nowadays: leather, leather, leather. Leather
pants, leather T-shirts. And colored leathers especially. Purple.
Green. Pastel pink.''
</P>
<P>
   Time Life publicist Carolyn Burnette was delighted to see the
Kleinberg Sherrill bag and belt, and made an opening bid of $500
for the duo. She thought they would make a great gift for her
sister Adrienne. What she didn't realize was that the minimum bid
was $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bag is something that'll live past this trend with the
color orange,'' Burnette said.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving fashionably late for the exhibition _ wearing a
bright red ``Afro'' (think big and fuzzy) coat, with 3 1/2-year-old
daughter Anabelle in tow _ Marcia Sherrill explained that the
orange pieces were ``slight modifications on bags and belts in our
existing collection.''
</P>
<P>
   She seemed much more interested in cornering Kevin Knaus, chief
of the career counseling agency InsideFashion, and dishing the dirt
on friends back in Atlanta. And she served up this tidbit of her
own: New York magazine is doing a feature on Anabelle's room in its
March 15 issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why I came here tonight,'' Sherrill said. ``For the
chance to see friends from home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
