<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-SIDE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Engine problems slow Stewart, Labonte
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ For his very first Winston Cup race,
rookie Tony Stewart felt the pain of a veteran and, as bad luck
would have it, the veteran he could most identify with is his
teammate in the Joe Gibbs garage, Bobby Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart started on the outside pole in Sunday's Daytona 500 but
quickly drifted back into the pack with a faulty engine. He fought
the bad motor all day and finished 28th in the No. 20 Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte started third, led 20 of the first 42 laps and then
faded to a 25th place finish in the No. 18 Pontiac because of a
misfiring engine.
</P>
<P>
   ''We spent so much time in the pits because we were trying to
figure out why the motor wasn't running,'' Stewart said. ''We lost
a cylinder. We probably won't know for certain till we get back to
the shop, tear the motor and find out. We for sure lost one
cylinder. Nothing you can do about it. If it was something I did,
that would be one thing. You're just kind of a victim out here
riding around. It happened to Bobby, too. All we can do is go out
there and make laps and try to gain as many points as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte was singing the same blues.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were really strong early on and were able to take the lead
and get our five bonus points out of the way quick,'' Labonte said.
''Then it developed a miss pretty early and I kept falling slowly
back. We still don't really know what it was. Tony had a
similar-type miss, too. It's disappointing because we showed from
the start we were one of the cars to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Stewart's debut in a Winston Cup car after a successful
career in Indy cars. He was impressed. ''It's definitely the
biggest stock car race in the world, that's for sure,'' he said.
''To come here today and see all the fans out here, it's similar to
the Indy atmosphere just with a different style of race car and
different type of fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of education was gained on the track.
</P>
<P>
   First, he had to learn about drafting on a speedway. ''I'm
learning (about the draft),'' he said. ''There's still a lot of
knowledge to be learned out there. I think we learned enough in the
125 (qualifying race) to at least keep up us semi-competitive
today. We got shuffled back a little bit, got back in line and
start picking our way back up through there. I feel like we a
pretty good boost for the next time we come back here or Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not telling anybody what we learned about drafting. It's
stuff I've learned that most of these other drivers already know.
But the ones that don't, I don't want to help them out. We learned
a lot. We brought the car back in one piece, and that was our main
goal. We wanted to finish the race higher, obviously, but all
things considered that was out of our control. So we're kind of
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
