<HEADLINE>
AN AIRBRUSHED JACKSON POLLOCK? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Tuesday, February 16, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The US Postal Service took the cigarette out of Jackson
Pollock's mouth for his portrait on a new 33-cent stamp. While a
spokesman insists this was a ``design decision'' that had nothing
to do with the government's antismoking campaign, the change is
unsettling because it tells a lie, albeit a small one, about this
master of abstract expressionism.
</P>
<P>
   Pollock was a chain-smoker who worked with his trademark
cigarette dangling from his lips as he squatted down next to a
canvas on the floor, dripping and swirling paints into his
fantastic designs. That was exactly how photographer Martha Holmes
snapped him for a 1949 cover story in Life magazine. But an
artist's rendering of that photo for the 1999 stamp eliminates
Pollack's bad habit _ and sucks the tension out of the pose.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Smeraldi, press officer at the Postal Service, notes that
the stamp is part of a ``Celebrate the Century'' series and is
supposed to commemorate abstract expressionism in America rather
than being a tribute to Pollock. He says eliminating the cigarette
was no big deal: ``It was a minor element and didn't have to be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes it did. That ``minor element'' was a part of who Pollock
was, and anything commemorating the art should not divorce itself
from the artist. Similarly, no portrait of Edward R. Morrow is
complete without the cigarette, which was as much a part of the man
as a microphone, although neither appears on his 1994 US postage
stamp. Smoking blues guitarist Robert Johnson was also forced to
quit cold turkey on a 1994 stamp.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting that President Franklin D. Roosevelt got to
keep his long, upturned cigarette holder in a 1982 Postal Service
rendering, although Smeraldi wasn't sure why. Presidential
privilege, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   No one is condoning smoking here. The mountain of research on
that subject is clear. But revisionist history on legends is often
murky. Little things, good or bad, say a lot about a person and the
America in which he or she lived. They should not be air-brushed
away _ not even in miniature in the corner of an envelope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 1944EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
