<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5124 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MEXICO-HNS &LR;      02-14 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT AND FIRST LADY MARK VALENTINE'S DAY WITH GIFTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERIDA, Mexico _ President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton
put their mutual affections on public display Sunday by seeking out
reporters aboard Air Force One to offer Valentine's Day wishes and
show off a gold-colored, heart-shaped pin that the president gave
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The first couple's visit with reporters aboard the presidential
aircraft was so unusual after months of arms length dealings during
the impeachment fight that reporters aboard the plane telephoned
reports of the rendezvous to news organizations back in Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The couple appeared in the press cabin shortly after takeoff to
pass out chocolate candy from a large heart-shaped box.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy Valentine's Day,'' the president said. ``Isn't this the
biggest heart you ever saw in your life? This is a better kind of
heart of darkness.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heart of Darkness,'' written by the 19th century writer Joseph
Conrad, chronicled the ill-effects of heat, deprivation and
isolation on a 19th century European colonist in Africa, leading to
the colonist's eventual breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton was wearing a gold-colored pin shaped like a heart
on her dark suit. Asked if the jewelry was new, Mrs. Clinton
replied: ``Brand new.'' She then pointed toward her husband and
smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said the box of candy was a gift from one of her
brothers. Her brothers, Tony Rodham and Hugh Rodham, her mother
Dorothy Rodham, and her nephew Zack Rodham, joined the Clintons at
the White House last week during the climax of the impeachment
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The president and Mrs. Clinton made their way quickly through
the press compartment at the rear of the specially equipped Boeing
747 jumbo jet to distribute holiday candy to passengers in other
parts of the 75-seat plane.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons' trip to Mexico on Valentine's Day meant a return
to the country where they spent their honeymoon in 1975. Then, they
vacationed in Acapulco on the Pacific coast of Mexico after their
wedding in Fayetteville, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons arrived here on the Yucatan peninsula late Sunday.
The president began private meetings with Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo, Mexican government officials and some opposition members
of parliament during a 23-hour visit taking place two days after
the Senate acquitted Clinton on impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &LR;  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials have already signaled that the
White House will seek to ease the greatest tension in U.S.-Mexican
relations by certifying to the U.S. Congress that Mexico continues
to cooperate with joint counternarcotics' efforts. The deadline for
the annual certification is March 1.
</P>
<P>
   National Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger said
recertification would ``receive a great deal of attention'' during
the summit, adding that U.S. officials will look at the extent of
cooperation ``fairly, without either inventing or inflating
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger, tipping the president's hand, added: ``It's important to
remember what the purpose of certification is and what it is not.
It is not to measure the extent of Mexico's problems. It's intended
to assess the extent of its cooperation with us in overcoming
them.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials cited a variety of milestones underscoring
Mexican progress, including Mexico's announcement on Feb. 4 of
``total war'' against narcotics trafficking, with $400 million in
new spending to buy ships, aircraft, radar, X-ray equipment and
other equipment.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials also pointed to Mexico's steps criminalizing
money laundering by requiring reporting for cash transfers of more
than $10,000, tighter screening of an elite antidrug force to weed
out endemic corruption and extraditing U.S.-sought drug dealers to
the United States for trial.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials estimate that 70 percent of illegal narcotics
smuggled into the United States cross the U.S.-Mexican border.
Mexican authorities point to Americans' consumption of cocaine and
marijuana as an equal source of the international drug challenge.
</P>
<P>
   A loss of White House certification would cost Mexico millions
of dollars in U.S. assistance. Three presidents have certified
Mexican cooperation with antidrug efforts over the 12-year period
since Congress mandated the annual review.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo is ``clearly trying to establish a clean government and
respect for the rule of law,'' Berger told reporters last week.
``He has described drugs as the number one national security threat
to Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   The scope of corruption has been revealed largely because of
``Mexico's own efforts to uproot it,'' Berger added.
</P>
<P>
   James Dobbins, the National Security Council's senior director
for Inter-American Affairs, said, that U.S.-Mexico cooperation has
``made a lot of progress over the last year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said they expected Mrs. Clinton to strike
a higher profile now that her husband's impeachment trial is over
on charges stemming from a sex-and-cover-up scandal involving
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is weighing whether to seek the Democratic
nomination for the U.S. Senate seat in New York being vacated by
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   White House Chief of Staff John Podesta, appearing on ABC News'
``This Week'' on Sunday, said that a number of people ``have been
really urging her to run, and I think she wants to hear them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan told questioners on NBC News' ``Meet the Press'' that
Mrs. Clinton would be ``welcome and she'd win.''
</P>
