<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5126 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SKATING-WOMEN-HNS     02-14 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SKATING-WOMEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SALT LAKE CITY _ She has seen the future, and it looks awfully
familiar.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A fresh, young face. A look of wonder in the eyes. And all those
reporters buzzing around, ready to anoint the new kid as figure
skating's next great thing.
</P>
<P>
   Been there, done that, Michelle Kwan says amiably enough. And if
somebody new makes for a bigger crowd and sharper elbows around the
medal podium well, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember skating next to Nancy (Kerrigan) in 1994,'' Kwan,
just 13 back then, said Saturday night after claiming her third
United States Figure Skating Association championship. ``I was in
awe, definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, another 13-year-old was soaking it all in, much
as Kwan had done five years earlier as an Olympic alternate for the
Lillehammer Games. Naomi Nari Nam won't go to next month's world
championships _ the U.S. runner-up is too young, of all things _
but she has made her presence felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's good,'' Kwan said. ``I admire her.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwan should appreciate the work in progress. Part of Nam's
development, as it turns out, is the result of some tips by an old
hand. For the past three years, Nam has spent weekends at Lake
Arrowhead, Calif., where Kwan trains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to help her,'' Kwan said. ``When you see a little girl
struggling with her jumps ''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Nam isn't quite so little or struggling so much.
Kwan was the class of the field and a clear winner Saturday night,
but Nam was pretty good, too. As such, a competition that opened as
a one-woman show produced some intrigue after all.
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry isn't of Kwan-Tara Lipinski proportions just yet,
but in figure skating, things change quickly. Kwan has detected a
few indications it might no longer be lonely at the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see it in their eyes, if they have it,'' she said. ``She
definitely has it in her.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Kwan, who plans to attend college next year on
at least a limited basis, is ready to step aside at the ripe old
age of 18. The appearance of a potential rival might be a good
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone's better, they're better, right?'' coach Frank
Carroll said. ``It's up to us to be better. I think it's a
positive. It keeps you improving.''
</P>
<P>
   For the long-term outlook, Nam's emergence might have been the
best bit of news to emerge from a largely dreary week at the figs.
Better skating has been seen during an Aeros penalty kill, and
prospects for next month's worlds appear bleak.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan, of course, is the defending champion and will be favored
to win again, but Nam's ineligibility leaves the United States
sending the Nos. 3 and 4 skaters from a thin field to face the
world in Helsinki. Neither Angela Nikodinov nor Sarah Hughes
appears ready for that just yet, though the 13-year-old Hughes (who
goes, despite her age, as a result of a second-place finish in
junior worlds this year) might benefit from the experience.
</P>
<P>
   Among the men, prospects are more tenuous. Michael Weiss, who
won his first U.S. championship here, is the best hope, but his
international background is spotty. Weiss was seventh in the 1998
Olympics and sixth at last year's world championships. The prestige
of being the top American might get him some benefit of the doubt,
but Weiss must perform at a level he has yet to reach if he is to
medal in Finland.
</P>
<P>
   More is at stake than image and bragging rights. In order to
keep three spots in the following year's worlds, the top two
skaters must combine for no more than 13 placement positions. For
instance, if Weiss were to come in third, one of the other two men
_ Trifun Zivanovic or Timothy Goebel _ would have to finish 10th or
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm going with the idea of protecting our spot,'' said
Goebel, who didn't inspire confidence by falling twice in his long
program here. ``I think we can do it, too. I feel good about our
chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Protecting positions in the field is the immediate concern, but
figure-skating eyes are beginning to sneak a peek at 2002, when
America's attention again will focus on an Olympic season.
</P>
<P>
   Will Kwan be there? That's her plan at the moment, but three
years is a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I still have that flame burning inside, I'll be here,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll isn't sure, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she wants to do it, she can do it,'' he said. ``It won't be
up to me or her parents or anyone else. Whether she stays in it
will be totally up to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Nam might actually help in that regard. Skating insiders
wondered if boredom might overtake Kwan in the absence of a
Lipinski to motivate her. The idea of being pushed aside by another
young up-and-comer might stir the competitive juices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it helps having somebody close by,'' Kwan said. ``I
already know that people are out there. You can't let anything go.
You have to keep improving, or you're going to stop and people are
going to pass you.''
</P>
<P>
   The impetus might have arrived in the form of a diminutive
fellow Californian even Kwan calls ``cute.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to see how this little girl develops,'' Carroll said.
``She has a lot to go yet, but she's darling, and she has the
talent.''
</P>
<P>
   So it appears. And just like that, the road to 2002 got a little
more interesting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
