<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-VALENTINE-2T     02-14 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-VALENTINE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOBBY VALENTINE: THE MAN WHO KNOWS EVERYTHING EXCEPT THE WORDS `NO
COMMENT'  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
( ATTN:   Conn., Mo. Ga., Texas)  By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ Strolling into Bobby Valentine's Sports
Gallery Cafe here is like opening a gigantic scrapbook of his life.
There are newspaper clippings about a national dance competition he
won at 13, about how he consumed 120 pancakes in college to win
another contest and, of course, about his accomplishments as a
major league baseball player, including frame-by-frame shots of him
crashing into a center-field fence and fracturing his right leg
and, ultimately, his career.
</P>
<P>
   In the bar, where the walls are adorned with sports magazine
covers, there is a shrine to Valentine's high school football
exploits. Encased in a glass frame are about two dozen recruiting
letters that the running back at Rippowam High School received from
the top college football teams in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine is a hero here. That is especially true in this
restaurant, where waiters and waitresses wear Mets jerseys bearing
Valentine's No. 2, pictures of Valentine are everywhere and,
periodically, Valentine himself is there as owner, ambassador and
manager. He is always a manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great day, isn't it?'' he gushed as he sat in a
corner booth beneath an autographed Stan Musial jersey recently.
``I love days where I've got a lot to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine likes to be busy and he likes to be liked, and he
found both work and love here.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the restaurant asked if Valentine had anything to do
with the dismissal of the Mets announcer Tim McCarver this month.
If there were comments about it, they were simply to reiterate
Valentine's opinion that the theory was ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   No one asked about Valentine's poor relationship with Todd
Hundley. If there were observations offered about it, they were
made on the side of the man known here as Boss.
</P>
<P>
   No one questioned why he used Mel Rojas against Paul O'Neill,
who subsequently hit a three-run homer, last June, and it would be
hard to find anyone here who believes that he glared at the press
box after the left-hander Bill Pulsipher allowed a hit to O'Neill
the next day.
</P>
<P>
   This is home, and Valentine is temporarily away from Flushing,
Queens, and the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrown into the middle of everything that happens,''
Valentine said. ``I don't think that's where I am. I'm a manager. I
care about everything that is involved with my group. I accept
rather than control.''
</P>
<P>
   The tanned Valentine was relaxed on this day. He feigned a frown
when asked some personal questions, but then freely discussed what
he called the misconceptions about him, about his inability to
muzzle himself and about his failure to reach the post-season in
1,541 games as a manager. As confident as Valentine is _ and he is
extremely confident as he approaches his third full season as the
Mets' manager _ a smidgen of insecurity is evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to speculate, but there are people who have
decided that they have worked too hard at trying to make me look
how they want me to look,'' he said. ``I don't know why they waste
time doing it. I'm not the greatest guy in the world or an angel,
and I'm not the worst guy in the world or the devil. It's better to
write the bad side because the good side is not news. I understand
it and it's confusing. I'm trying to figure that out.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Leiter is also trying to figure it out. He said he was
guarded when the Marlins traded him to the Mets because Kevin
Brown, who played under Valentine in Texas, warned him that the
manager ignored slumping players. But Leiter said he had not
witnessed ``the bad stuff'' he had heard about and called it ``a
complete joy'' to play for Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where Bobby gets a bad rap is people don't know him and he
doesn't let them into his world,'' Leiter said. ``There are worse
managers than him, believe me. I told him that he needs to hire a
p.r. firm. Something's not right. He's not getting his message out.
Some people don't like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to figure Valentine out is a pastime of many people in
and around baseball. Even Valentine acknowledges he can be
confusing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people he doesn't like, and some people who
don't like him,'' said Joe Valentine, Bobby's father, a retired
carpenter. ``You live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine is a complex man who is designing two computer
Web sites and is comfortable calling for the hit-and-run with a
pitcher batting. He has a brilliant baseball mind and is eager to
mold the new-look Mets and surpass last season's victory total of
88, but the 48-year-old with the graying hair and nonstop smile is
often one comment or curious action away from obscuring what his
well-prepared teams do.
</P>
<P>
   Even Valentine conceded there had been six to eight incidents
that had tarnished his two-plus seasons with the Mets. Whenever
anything occurs with the Mets these days, there is a tendency to
wonder what role Valentine played in it
</P>
<P>
   Did he help get McCarver banished as a Mets announcer after 16
years? Why did Valentine ever publicly discuss Hundley's sleeping
and drinking habits? Did he undermine Joe McIlvaine, the former
general manager whose exit he discussed with reporters before the
news conference to announce it? Some angst could have been avoided
if Valentine had kept quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I wish I had the `no comment' in me,'' Valentine
said. ``It's probably a character flaw. My teachers and friends
will tell you I like to contribute. I don't have `no comment' in me
often. That's a problem. Sometimes that becomes a know-it-all
situation. And maybe I am a bit of a know-it-all when it comes to
those conversations.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Wilpon, who praised Valentine's intelligence, preparation skills
and teaching abilities, said: ``I've had conversations with him
right after he didn't use the edit button. I've told him, `You have
to take one or two more seconds before you answer.' He understands.
He can't always do it because he's under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, who became ensnared in an ugly battle with Valentine
after the manager criticized his sleeping patterns during a session
with reporters in 1997, chuckled when asked specifics about their
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to let that ridiculous relationship we had go
with me to L.A.,'' said Hundley, who was traded to the Dodgers in
December. ``I don't know if it's a grudge, but I won't forget what
happened soon. But I'm not going to let him play in my world at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said he did not badger Hundley about the issue and
added, ``I didn't think it was a big thing when it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine can be engaging and regale his listeners with
interesting stories, but he can be abrupt with reporters who are
unprepared and he especially does not like to be second-guessed.
His disenchantment with McCarver's critiques were well known, but
Valentine called talk of a rift between the two gossip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the McCarver thing epitomized me being put into
something and even reached the level that it could now be going
downhill,'' Valentine said. ``It's so ridiculous. Maybe now people
will say this stuff has gone too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs that thing you tell your children, `When you get mad,
count to five, take a deep breath,''' said Tom Grieve, the former
Texas Rangers general manager who lives a few houses from
Valentine's off-season home in Arlington, Texas, and still
considers Valentine a friend even though he fired him as manager in
1992. ``There have been times where you say to yourself, `I hope he
didn't say that.' If he did, I wish he'd thought before he said it.
You don't need to say it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Valentine sometimes says it and sometimes regrets it,
although he emphasized that most of his miscues had quickly blown
over. While the Hundley soap opera stretched on for more than a
year and his dispute with former Mets pitcher Pete Harnisch also
lasted for a while, Valentine said he publicly criticized McCarver
only once, that his dispute with a fan behind the dugout last year
lasted only a few minutes and that his glare at the press box last
season lasted only a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, I blame myself, probably for every one of them,''
Valentine said. ``All of those things, I wish I didn't do them. But
how the heck do you do that? There's a real high standard set when
I deal with the press. I have no protection. I get frustrated when
nothing is allowed to slip. Don't be human and have any emotions
going when you talk. I understand it. I'm not complaining because I
don't expect it to change. Just don't ever mess up.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine cannot mess up this year. Not after the Mets invested
$164 million to retain Leiter, catcher Mike Piazza and reliever
Dennis Cook and to sign third baseman Robin Ventura and outfielder
Rickey Henderson. But Valentine, who has a career record of 769-772
and a 188-167 mark with the Mets, lighted up when he was asked
about shaping this Mets team.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I do best is teach,'' Valentine said. ``I
love it. I know it. I will go toe to toe with anyone in the world
on what really happens when you play the game. I can sit on that
panel. People get upset when I say that, but I have a master's in
baseball. I've been educated by the best. The things I didn't know
I went out to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Grieve agreed, saying: ``I played for Joe Torre, Ted Williams,
Billy Martin and Whitey Herzog, and, when it comes to knowing
different facets of the game inside out and having an overall grasp
of baseball, no one is better than Bobby. I don't think anyone else
is close.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Valentine's confidence can be construed as arrogance.
Valentine said he knew that St. Louis Cardinals Manager Tony La
Russa did not like him, but added that he could care less. Atlanta
Braves Manager Bobby Cox compared defeating Valentine to defeating
the Hall of Fame managers Casey Stengel and John McGraw last year,
but Valentine said he considered the comments competitive, not
sarcastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bobby doesn't like me, he's a phony because he makes like
he's my good friend every time I'm with him,'' Valentine said. ``If
there's a reason he doesn't like me, he should have let me know a
long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets win, Valentine will be praised. But if the Mets
sputter, there will be heightened scrutiny on a manager who is
already in the glare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would much rather have a litany of things, 50 times when I
looked up at the press box, 50 quotes about Tim McCarver,
documented run-ins with all these players I supposedly didn't want,
than a little one-liner here and a little glance there,'' he said.
``I wish I didn't do all those things. There's no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine paused. Unable to resist, he added, ``It would only
mean that I'm doing better than I'm capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine stopped speaking, letting his last remark sink in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
