<HEADER>
A5130 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MEXICO15-COX     02-14 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEXICO15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIRST LOVEBIRDS FLY TO MEXICO
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERIDA, Mexico _ President Clinton, romancing the press with
chocolates and the first lady with gold on Valentine's Day, sought
a post-impeachment thaw in relations strained by a year of scandal.
</P>
<P>
   En route from Washington aboard Air Force One to a presidential
summit with Mexican leaders, the Clintons made a rare appearance
Sunday in the press cabin, where the president passed out
chocolates from a large heart-shaped box.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy Valentine's Day,'' Clinton said to a dozen astonished
reporters and photographers. ``Isn't this the biggest heart you
ever saw in your life?''
</P>
<P>
   Backing the rhetoric of reconciliation with a symbol of romance
rekindled, the first couple showed off Clinton's Valentine's
present to his wife: a heart-shaped gold pin.
</P>
<P>
   ''Brand new,'' Hillary Rodham Clinton beamed when reporters
asked about the pin. Then she pointed to her husband and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has sentimental symbolism for the first couple. They
honeymooned in the resort city of Acapulco after their 1975
wedding.
</P>
<P>
   The chocolates were a gift to Mrs. Clinton, but not from her
husband. They came from her brother, Hugh Rodham, said White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons' appearance in the press cabin was a surprise.
During a year dominated by Clinton's sex-and-deception scandal, he
has assiduously avoided reporters, including those traveling with
him aboard the presidential aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   After his effort to sweeten relations with a sometimes sour
press corps, Clinton quickly retired to his cabin, leaving
reporters to wonder whether he might be intending more regular
contacts with the media after being acquitted of impeachment
charges in the Senate on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's next scheduled press conference is Friday, when he
meets at the White House with President Jacques Chirac of France.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons arrived in this city on the Yucatan Peninsula on
Sunday night, greeted by President Ernesto Zedillo of Mexico and
his wife, Nilda Patricia Velasco, as the national anthems of both
countries played.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, the Zedillos played host at a dinner for the
Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Monday will be devoted to meetings on anti-narcotics efforts,
trade and environmental issues. Clinton is scheduled to return to
Washington on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has two weeks in which to certify to
Congress that Mexico is fully cooperating with U.S. efforts to stop
the flow of illicit narcotics northward into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Decertification would trigger reductions in U.S. aid that could
damage the fragile economy in Mexico, the second-largest U.S.
trading partner behind Canada.
</P>
<P>
   While Mexico remains the largest trans-shipment point for
cocaine destined for the United States, the Clinton administration
has already begun making the case for certifying Mexico's
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president has not made a decision,'' national security
adviser Samuel Berger told reporters Friday. ''We will look to the
extent of the cooperation between us. We'll look to it fairly
without either inventing or inflating progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger stressed, though, that the administration is more
interested in encouraging progress in Mexico than in punishing
failure.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, this is a tremendous problem for Mexico, but one
that they are tackling head-on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important to remember what the purpose of certification
is, and what it is not,'' said Berger. ''It is not to measure the
extent of Mexico's problems. It's intended to assess the extent of
its cooperation with us in overcoming them.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
