<HEADER>
A5132 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VAUGHN-LADN     02-14 1767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VAUGHN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ANGEL VAUGHN MAKES COMMITMENT TO CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kim Courtemarche used to live in the neighborhood that surrounds
Boston's Fenway Park. From her apartment, she could see the Fenway
Park scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   But there were parts of every game when she didn't have to go to
the window to find out who was batting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could hear the crowd chanting `Mo, Mo, Mo,' '' she said.
``He was a hero there.''
</P>
<P>
   Many players across the country have their names chanted at
ballparks, but that hardly makes them worthy of hero status.
Maurice ``Mo'' Vaughn, however, was just that to many in Boston. He
was arguably the city's most popular player since Ted Williams.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so much that Vaughn was the American League's Most
Valuable Player in 1995, or that he averaged 36 home runs and 111
RBIs in his past six seasons, or that he has a .304 lifetime
average covering eight years in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   It had more to do with Vaughn's roots in the city and his desire
to make a difference in the lives of children.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was born and raised in Norwalk, Conn., and was sent to
Trinity-Pawling, a private boarding school near the New
York-Connecticut border, during high school. He was a three-time
All-American at Seton Hall and has a home in Easton, Mass. Before
signing with the Angels the day before last Thanksgiving, he had
played his entire career in the Red Sox organization.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, 31, is flashy and flamboyant. He stands 6-foot-1 and
weighs 240 pounds. He wears expensive jewelry, including a ring
that spells out his jersey number, 42, in diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   But Vaughn has a heart for helping children, and he wears it on
his sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of former Dodger Mike Piazza made sure to call
the Los Angeles media whenever the catcher made a visit to
Children's Hospital. In contrast, Vaughn quietly began working with
area children on the bottom floor of an ordinary brick building in
Dorchester, Mass., five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn started the Mo Vaughn Youth Development Program in 1994,
based in Dorchester, not far from his home in Easton. He hired a
couple of his childhood friends to help run it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents worked with kids a long time, so I've been involved
even before I got to the major league level,'' Vaughn said. ``You
feel kids out. Working with young kids, you're seeing their
reactions. You find out if you have the ability to make a
difference. If you don't have the ability to communicate, you won't
be able to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seven original kids are about to go to college,'' Vaughn
said of his program's original students. ``We've touched hundreds
of kids. ... It's nice, but it's a long road.''
</P>
<P>
   LONG ROAD TO ANAHEIM
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 25, the Angels announced they had signed Vaughn to a
six-year, $80 million contract. At the time, his $13.3 million
average annual salary was the highest in baseball history. Since
then, Kevin Brown's seven-year, $105 million deal with the Dodgers
-- averaging $15 million per season -- has surpassed Vaughn's.
</P>
<P>
   But Vaughn's commitment to children began long before he was
making millions as a professional baseball player. One might even
say it's in his blood.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's parents, Leroy and Shirley, were teachers. Leroy also
was a high school football coach and later became a principal. They
know the value of education, and instilled that in Vaughn from an
early age.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn learned discipline and order from other teachers, those
at Trinity-Pawling. Everything -- from breakfast to study hall
after dinner -- was carried out by the book. Classes were held six
days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I hated it in the beginning, it was a stepping
stone in my life,'' Vaughn said. ``I had to learn to live with
other people. We would eat, sleep, go to class together, living in
a dorm situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living with people, you abide by the rules, and you also
execute your own rules. I was doing that at 15, 16 years old. So by
the time I went to college, I was already prepared. It's why I did
so well my freshman year (at Seton Hall). And in the minor leagues,
riding buses ... well, I had already been riding buses. I had
already learned to take care of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   THE MAJORS CAN WAIT
</P>
<P>
   Education obviously has been as important as anything in
Vaughn's life. It continued at Seton Hall after his graduation from
Trinity-Pawling.
</P>
<P>
   At Seton Hall, Vaughn decided to focus on baseball after also
having played football and basketball in high school. He enjoyed a
stellar three years, being named an All-American three times and
being voted the Big East Conference player of the decade. And he
can thank his mother for insisting on college.
</P>
<P>
   The Vaughns received a phone call from the Phillies during Mo's
senior year at Trinity-Pawling. It was Vaughn's mother who took the
call, but instead of negotiating a big-money signing bonus, she
told them not to bother drafting him -- he was going to college.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn didn't learn of the phone call until years later, but
doesn't hold it against his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never miss what I never had,'' he said. ``The way my mom
looked at it was if I was a third-round pick at 18, at 21 I'd be a
first-round pick. Plus, I got three more years of education. I'm
glad it worked out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   YES SIR, NO SIR
</P>
<P>
   There were a couple of men who had as much influence on Vaughn
early in his life as anybody, other than his parents. One was Miles
Hubbard, the athletic director and basketball coach at
Trinity-Pawling. The other was Mike Sheppard, Seton Hall's baseball
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my coaches had a great influence on me,'' Vaughn said.
``(Hubbard) taught me the importance of knowing there was an
academic side and an athletic side, and it took a lot of effort to
succeed in both. He told me the difference between doing the right
thing and the wrong thing might only take five more minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sheppard, he's an ex-Marine. He believed you don't make
excuses for whatever went wrong. He believed if he hammered you
long enough, it would make you a better player. He didn't want you
to like him, he wanted you to respect him. You played so hard
because you didn't want to hear his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he made me understand that no matter what level you're at,
guys still need to be led.''
</P>
<P>
   LEADER OF THE PACK
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn has been a leader on every athletic team he's ever played
for. Many of his Red Sox teammates felt Vaughn was the one player
they could not afford to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, voiced their feelings
publicly during negotiations between Vaughn and the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Vaughn is about to step into the Angels clubhouse as the
new guy. But he already commands respect. The Angels have been
waiting for someone like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times you get guys in here and you hear their voices,
but it turns out to be nothing but hot air,'' said veteran Angels
pitcher Chuck Finley. ``But Mo is somebody who goes out and does
what he says. The last three or four years, we've been one key
player away from going to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you don't know how good you can be. And it doesn't
show until somebody like Mo says he wants to play for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said being a leader simply is part of who he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watch other players and it comes because you care about
other people,'' he said. ``When I first came up in the big leagues,
young players didn't get a lot of attention from veteran players.
So I do what I can because I remember what it was like when I was
young.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a leader all my life. I don't know how it
transpired, it just has. I want to make my team believe it can be
as good as anybody, and can beat any team. I'm going to make the
Angels believe because we are a very, very talented team.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walk onto the field in spring training on Day One,
people are going to know we are the team to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels general manager Bill Bavasi said he has admired Vaughn
since Vaughn became a big leaguer in 1991. When Vaughn became
available, he became the Angels' first choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we embarked on the offseason, we wanted to make sure we
were real specific on the type of player we were trying to
pursue,'' Bavasi said. ``We felt the club was good enough to where
only the best would do. We feel we've done that.''
</P>
<P>
   A NEW CHAPTER
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn repeatedly has said he is excited about turning the page
in his career and in his life. He has purchased a home in the
Newport Beach area and plans to get involved in community programs
in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Vaughn really didn't have a choice. He said he felt
slighted when the Red Sox told him they couldn't improve on a
three-year, $30 million contract extension the two sides were
negotiating following the 1997 season, then turned around and
signed pitcher Pedro Martinez for $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   He also didn't feel the Red Sox supported him off the field.
When Vaughn was arrested for drunk driving in January of 1998, no
Red Sox representatives attended his trial, at which a jury found
Vaughn not guilty. But when Red Sox infielder Wil Cordero went to
trial on charges of spousal abuse, the team sent several
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy I made the decision I made,'' Vaughn said. ``I've
played eight years in the big leagues and I love playing baseball.
If I stayed there six or seven more years, I would have left the
game angry and I didn't deserve that. It was time to make a move.
Now, when I leave the game, I'll leave with a smile on my face.''
</P>
<P>
   EVERYONE LOVES A WINNER
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn expects to enjoy Southern California after spending his
entire life on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's going to be different,'' he said. ``But what's got
to be understood is that the baseball situation is what it's all
about. If we play well, it'll be great. If we play poorly, I'll be
disgusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a different mentality out there than in Boston.
But I'm happy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   California's laid-back reputation won't bother Vaughn, unless it
creeps into the Angels' clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see a time to keep the positive things rolling, I'll
make sure they keep rolling,'' he said. ``I want to help the team
play with the right intensity. I might put up numbers, but I don't
know what they're going to be. I was fortunate enough to be the MVP
in '95 and start an All-Star game. But the biggest asset I bring to
a team is to keep the team concept rolling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nomar (a Whittier native) said it's laid back out there. Well,
maybe we've got to up the tempo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
