<HEADLINE>
MAJOR FINANCIAL NEWS ITEMS IN BRIEF
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HISTORY OF BAD BLOOD HARDENS POSITION OF PILOTS
</P>
<P>
   Airline pilots, some of America's best-paid and most highly
respected workers, have become among the nation's most militant, in
part because of the central role that they play in the airline
industry and the past scorched-earth labor policies of executives
at major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   But just as important are their character traits. Pilots both
individually and as a group often exhibit a self-confidence that
some industry executives say borders on arrogance. For decades,
many of them have felt they have been exploited by the airlines.
</P>
<P>
   BACK TO WORK
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines pilots returned to work in greater numbers.
</P>
<P>
   SLATE BECOMES FREE AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Ten months after deciding to charge readers $19.95 a year, the
publisher of Slate, the online magazine owned by Microsoft,
announced in an e-mail to subscribers that it would now be free.
The publisher cited the dynamic growth of advertising on the Web
and the slow pace of paid subscriptions for content.
</P>
<P>
   TICKETMASTER ENDS MICROSOFT SUIT
</P>
<P>
   Ticketmaster, a unit of USA Networks Inc., has settled its
two-year-old lawsuit against Microsoft. Executives said that
Microsoft had agreed to no longer link Sidewalk to pages deep
within the Ticketmaster site. The Sidewalk guides will now point
visitors who want to buy tickets directly to the Ticketmaster home
page _ and its advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ MAY TEST TRADING HALTS
</P>
<P>
   Frank Zarb, the chairman of the National Association of
Securities Dealers, the parent of the Nasdaq stock market, has
asked the association's board to consider testing temporary halts
in the trading of shares that experience extreme volatility.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT PLAYS DOWN JAVA REPORT
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is playing down a report in a trade magazine that it
has been briefing software developers on a new programming language
that would be similar to Sun Microsystems' Java but free of
technological or licensing obligations to Sun. Microsoft said the
idea was one of several being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   BILL CONSIDERED FOR ONLINE DATA
</P>
<P>
   House Commerce Committee Chairman Thomas Bliley, R-Va., is
considering legislation that would put limits on the types of
publicly released government information that could be posted on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   FEUD OVER FUTURE OF WIRELESS
</P>
<P>
   In six weeks, the International Telecommunication Union, a U.N.
agency, is scheduled to start approving international standards for
wireless technologies for the next decade. But that process is
being threatened by a general reluctance to compromise on arcane
technical standards and in particular by intransigence on the part
of two rivals, Ericsson of Sweden and Qualcomm, based in San Diego
and led by Irwin Mark Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   STERN MAKES SLOW HEADWAY
</P>
<P>
   When Howard Stern announced he was turning his radio show to
late-night television on Saturdays, he bragged he would turn NBC's
``Saturday Night Live'' into ``Saturday Night Dead.'' With the
season half over, his show has barely dented ``Saturday Night
Live'' except among men ages 18 to 34.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. MARKETS CLOSED
</P>
<P>
   All financial markets in the United States, as well as banks and
government offices, are closed today in observance of Presidents
Day. Most markets overseas are open.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
