<DOCNO> NYT19990214.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5139 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-MAIN15-COX     02-14 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-MAIN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon not intimidated
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The 1999 NASCAR season started much like
the way last year's ended: With two-time defending Winston Cup
champion Jeff Gordon in victory lane.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Gordon became the seventh driver to win more than one
Daytona 500, holding off a furious threat from defending champion
Dale Earnhardt in one of the most thrilling finishes in the 41-year
history of the Great American Race.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, the '97 Daytona 500 winner, collected more than $2.1
million in winnings, which includes a $1 million Winston ``No Bull
5'' bonus. It was Gordon's third straight victory dating back to
last season, and his 21st consecutive top-10 finish in points
events.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who led only 17 of 200 laps in the race, became the
first driver to win the Daytona 500 from the pole position since
Bill Elliott in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Daytona on the last lap, that's not the kind of black you
want to see,'' Gordon said. ``That black race car can flat get
around here. Dale really had a very strong car all day. Keeping him
behind me was one of the toughest things I've had to do in a race
car. ... That is a dream come true to race Dale down to the final
finish, all the way down to the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt tried to move past Gordon on the final lap, letting up
on the accelerator in turn 4. Earnhardt tried to go inside before
the finish line, but Gordon blocked the move.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt finished second for the fifth time, moving him past
Cale Yarborough on Daytona's all-time list for runner-up finishes.
Kenny Irwin, last year's rookie of the year, was third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't really muster much on Jeff,'' Earnhardt said. ``His
car was stronger from the center of the corner than mine was. I
just never could get to him. If I could have got to him, I could
have got a bumper under him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Earnhardt didn't get to Gordon until after they passed the
flag stand, where ``The Intimidator'' gave Gordon a shove well
after the checkered flag had dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't pull up beside me,'' Gordon said. ``He drove into
the side of me. I guess he was saying, `If they're going to put
your car into Daytona USA (exhibition where winning cars are
housed), I'm going to leave my mark on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was Earnhardt who helped Gordon get to the front
of the pack to set up the furious finish. Following a four-lap
caution through the 178th lap, Earnhardt teamed up with Gordon _
and not teammate Mike Skinner _ in drafting to begin their assault
on the team of Rusty Wallace and Jeremy Mayfield, who led all but
32 of the final 143 laps between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty surprised, although I think I had the preferred
line,'' Gordon said. ``I had the bottom groove and the bottom
groove was the way to go all day long. Dale had a tough choice
there. He had a teammate, his buddy Rusty in the middle and me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he would have gone with the other two long before he
went with me, but I think he knew he had a fast race car and he
could race with anybody. Maybe he wanted to race me for the
finish.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened in the final 11 laps. Shortly after the
green flag fell, Gordon and Earnhardt took a wild, daring ride
through the pack, moving up from the eighth and 10th spots,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt passed Mayfield for second place with only 16 laps to
go, catching Wallace's bumper. Earnhardt stayed in Wallace's
rear-view mirror for three more laps, but then Gordon got a push
from Skinner to move into second, with Earnhardt falling to fifth
as they finished lap 188.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get up there with Dale,'' Gordon said. ``It seemed
like once I did, we started making some moves and that's when it
started coming back in my mind. Once we got up there to the leader,
I didn't want to push him past the leader because I knew I'd never
pass him.''
</P>
<P>
   Two laps later, only 11 laps from the finish, Gordon made a
daring move to pass Wallace. Toward the first turn, Gordon went
inside Wallace on the apron and squeezed past the lapped car of
Ricky Rudd at nearly 190 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner then moved next to Wallace on the outside and the cars
moved side by side into turn 3. Gordon finally took the lead at the
flag stand, with Wallace and Skinner trailing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gordon just got me on the apron down there,'' Wallace said.
``I couldn't block him off enough. I thought I had him blocked off,
but he kept on going. I thought he was going to run right in the
back of Rudd on the apron. I had him pinned down there, but I
wasn't going to try to wreck a bunch of cars. I pulled up and he
got me, but I just didn't think I'd get freight-trained that
badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who led more than half of the race, got squeezed out of
the front draft and finished eighth. He is now winless in 17 career
starts in the Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one probably hurts the most because I thought I had the
best car,'' Wallace said. ``I'm just so heart-broken that happened.
I can't believe it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's last hope was getting a push from Skinner, but he
was stuck in fourth behind Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to get some help,'' Earnhardt said.
``(Irwin) and (Skinner) were trying to race each other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally, you're a little frustrated,'' Skinner said. ``It's
hard to watch people draft with your opponents instead of your own
team, but that's the way it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt and Skinner weren't the only teammates that struggled
on Sunday. Irwin hit teammate Dale Jarrett in the rear during the
134th lap, causing a 13-car pileup between turns 3 and 4. The
accident knocked Jarrett out of the race after he led 14 of the
first 56 laps. The wreck also eliminated contender Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, who was running second at the time of the accident,
wouldn't assess blame after the wreck, although television replays
showed Irwin's car made contact with Jarrett's No. 88 Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Irwin) was in the mix there, but I have no idea,'' Jarrett
said. ``He was back there. A couple of cars had passed me coming
off of two and down the backstretch, and I was the guy in the
middle and I was just trying to hold there.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin was apologetic after the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very bad about it,'' he said. ``If I could have made it
not happen, I would have made it not happen. I honestly don't know.
I didn't feel anything.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
