u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-RDP-NYT &LR;      02-14 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS SHIFTING TO ISSUES AND THE 2000 CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With President Clinton's acquittal behind them,
senators of both parties Sunday turned to issues like Social
Security, taxes and foreign policy, while another Republican
announced he was taking steps to seek his party's presidential
nomination next year.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the Senate concluded the trial of the president,
the Sunday morning talk shows were notable for showcasing how eager
the nation's political leaders are to move beyond the impeachment
struggle that consumed Congress for five months. Senators quickly
shifted to the legislative arena and sounded the opening notes of
the policy battles that are likely to shape the presidential and
congressional races in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in particular, who have seen their approval ratings
sink across the past months, worked to show that their party stands
for more than investigating Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very much in the president's interest, and the
country's interest to put the impeachment trial behind us,'' said
Sen. Don Nickles, an Oklahoma Republican who is the majority whip,
in an appearance on ABC's ``This Week.'' ``That's over now, and
let's go on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans have to have an agenda,'' said Sen. Pete V.
Domenici, a New Mexico Republican, appearing on ``Fox News
Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   To drive home the point that they do have an agenda,
congressional Republicans are planning to hold scores of town
meetings during the week-long recess on such issues as Social
Security, Medicare and tax-cutting.
</P>
<P>
   A critical question in the wake of the impeachment struggle is
whether Clinton and Congress can overcome the anger and partisan
bitterness and work together.
</P>
<P>
   John Podesta, the White House chief of staff, said on ABC's
``This Week'' that for the second consecutive day the president
spoke with the congressional leadership about the possible troop
deployment in Kosovo and domestic issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talked about Medicare and Social Security,'' he said,
``how we can get to the table to begin to do the people's
business.'' Podesta also said the president suggested to the new
House speaker, Rep. Dennis Hastert of Illinois, that the two men
meet soon on policy.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, a Democrat who has
often been at odds with Clinton, said on NBC's ``Meet the Press''
Sunday, ``I wouldn't expect a great deal in terms of
presidential-congressional working together, but the Congress could
do a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., both warned that Clinton would
make a mistake if, as part of the Democratic drive to recapture the
House next year, he mounted an all-out political campaign against
those, such as the House managers, who had worked hardest to remove
him from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has opportunities, but he will squander them if there's any
note of vengeance,'' Moynihan said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said, ``We just can't work well together if you know that
they're mounting some kind of specific vengeance-minded program
which is different from the normal electoral cycle we go through.''
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers of both parties did agree on one outcome of
impeachment: that the Independent Counsel Act, which expires this
summer, will be substantially revised or eliminated entirely. The
law, under which Kenneth Starr was commissioned, was passed in the
aftermath of the Watergate scandal to guard against situations like
the so-called Saturday Night Massacre of 1973, when Richard M.
Nixon ordered his attorney general, Elliot Richardson, to fire the
Watergate special prosecutor Archibald Cox. Richardson resigned
rather than do so.
</P>
<P>
   `This law needs to terminate,'' said Sen. Mitch McConnell, a
Kentucky Republican, on CNN's ``Late Edition.'' ``I don't want it
to be amended. I want it to be ended.''
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan said the law, which created independent counsels, was
``a post-Watergate liberal notion, and it was a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   The two political parties now plan to turn their attention to an
overhaul of the Social Security system, a battle over how to use
federal budget surpluses, education and foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have made a sweeping, across the board tax cut a
centerpiece of their agenda this year while Clinton had advocated a
series of tax credits targeted to specific social purposes.
``Targeted tax credits don't help all the people,' Domenici, the
chairman of the Senate Budget Committee said. ``And they don't help
the economy. An across the board tax cut does both.''
</P>
<P>
   The same theme was struck by Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, the House
Budget Committee chairman, who announced on ``Meet the Press'' that
he would file papers Monday with the Federal Election Commission to
set up a presidential exploratory committee, joining a crowded
field of Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Tax-cutting, he said, ``is about power flowing from the people
rather than running America with a handful of people deciding out
to spend our money, how to plan for our retirement''
</P>
<P>
   In foreign policy, another area where the Republicans want to
highlight their differences with the Democratic president, McCain,
another of the Republican presidential contenders, reluctantly
supported Clinton's decision to send troops to Kosovo. But he
criticized Clinton for failing to prepare the American people for
the deployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the United States a few weeks ago gave an
hour and 17 minute speech to the American people,'' he said on
NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' referring to the State of the Union
message. ``There was one line about Kosovo. The president and his
advisers knew very well that this was a looming crisis, where
people are gouging out other people's eyes, innocent people's eyes,
and we have no exit strategy, we have no concept of how we want to
settle this situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 2009EST &QL; 
