<HEADLINE>
RECENT DECISIONS MAY HURT JETER IN ARBITRATION CASE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Derek Jeter is scheduled to have his arbitration
hearing here Monday, and recent history may be working against him.
Jeter, the Yankees' ll-star shortstop, is asking for $5 million,
while the Yankees' proposed figure is $3.2 million. Another
shortstop in Jeter's service-time class, Mark Grudzielanek of Los
Angeles, lost his arbitration case and will make $1.9 million,
rather than the $2.6 million he wanted. In fact, the owners have
won all five cases that have gone to arbitration this year. Frank
Casey, who argued two of those cases successfully, will represent
the Yankees on Monday, before a panel of three arbiters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to say we have a slam-dunk case because
anything can happen,'' one Yankee executive said. ``But we're in a
good position.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, said Sunday that
there had been no contact in recent days between him and Casey
Close, the agent for Jeter. The shortstop made $750,000 last
season, the same as the closer Mariano Rivera, whose arbitration
case will be heard here Wednesday. Rivera is asking for $4.25
million, while the Yankees are offering $3 million; some baseball
officials believe there is a good chance Rivera will settle or even
reach the multiyear agreement that the Yankees have been hinting
about in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman and other Yankees players and officials attended the
Florida State Fair on Sunday, and David Wells was among them. The
pitcher, whose girth has been an issue with the club, ``looks fine
to me,'' Cashman said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I wasn't measuring him up, to be honest, but he
looked like he did to me in October.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
