<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF CRITTERS GOT YOU STEWIN', BON APPETIT! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Jasper, Alberta, the town pet is the elk. However, local
residents spell it with an ``s'' as in pest.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors are enthusiastically supportive of the resident herds,
which hang around the city parks or dig through the snow to munch
on fairway grass at the Jasper Park Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Seattle's Ballard locks used to applaud Herschel the
Sea Lion when he appeared, gulping down a salmon sandwich. Local
fishermen were not amused.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? The people of Jasper have developed a master plan.
They intend to ship most of the resident elk to Saskatchewan. We
can only hope they will not use the same delivery service that
transported Herschel and friends to California. The sea lions
returned faster than a 250-pound anvil mailed with a two-cent
stamp.
</P>
<P>
   During a typical week, Jasper Park Lodge will play host to
wildlife lovers from Japan, Germany and France; to cross-country
skiers from South Carolina, Hawaii and Virginia; to ice skaters,
ballroom dancers and to Canadian immigrants like those who recently
celebrated the Ukranian New Year in the lodge with a few splashes
of vodka.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, representatives of the Alberta Elk Breeders
Association took over the place. Ground elk antlers are highly
valued in Asia but you didn't have to travel to Bangkok to buy elk
velvet nutritional tablets. They were on sale in the lodge lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are brisk markets for venison and elk skins in
North America, and perhaps the breeders also rent out elk to safe
crackers. A cross-country skier from Corvallis, Ore., claimed elk
had opened the cooler on his cabin deck and consumed almost
everything inside during a late-night refrigerator raid.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, some of us suspected raccoons.
</P>
<P>
   Cabin neighbors with a partiality for gin and tonic were above
suspicion. The only items left by the midnight raiders were two
limes.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I were treated to close-up views of a wolf, a moose
and a few dozen future residents of Saskatchewan. However, we did
not come away from Jasper with any regional recipes requiring two
limes and a half ton of elk meat.
</P>
<P>
   This alternate recipe is great for venison, beef or buffalo. Who
knows? It might even work with raccoon.
</P>
<P>
   Critter Stew
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds cup flour
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds round steak, in one-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   2 cups beef broth
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon dill, crushed
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon marjoram, crushed
</P>
<P>
   2 14-ounce cans artichoke hearts
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh mushrooms, sliced
</P>
<P>
   On a sheet of waxed paper combine one-third cup flour, 2
teaspoons salt and one-half teaspoon pepper. Add the meat cubes and
toss with your hands until coated.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet or heavy pot heat the oil and brown the meat
cubes on all sides, adding garlic the last 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into the pot the wine, beef broth, dill and marjoram.
Simmer covered 90 minutes or until the meat is tender. Add the
artichoke hearts (drained and quartered) and the mushrooms. Simmer
10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In a small jar mix the remaining flour with one-half cup water.
Shake or stir until you have a smooth paste. Stir this into the
pot, cook another 10 minutes then serve over buttered noodles.
</P>
<P>
   This should feed six to eight.
</P>
<P>
   Ground venison also works well in spicy breakfast sausage. So
does lean ground beef and even ground turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Jalapeno Turkey Patties
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno pepper, seeded
</P>
<P>
   One-half small onion
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ground meat
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 beaten egg or egg substitute
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon crumbled sage leaves or 2 tablespoons fresh chopped
sage
</P>
<P>
   Dump the jalapeno pepper, onion and garlic into a food processor
or meat grinder. If you don't have fresh jalapenos, use about 6
slices from a jar of pickled and sliced peppers. Well, don't just
stand there, process, unless you decide to grind.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl combine the ground meat and all other
ingredients. Moosh thoroughly with your hands.
</P>
<P>
   Form into 6 patties and saute in a pan with a small amount of
oil. Cook just until the middle is no longer pink.
</P>
<P>
   According to Asian importers, powdered elk horn is treasured as
``a cure-all and aphrodisiac.''
</P>
<P>
   Gin and tonic is probably cheaper. I think there are a couple of
limes left in the cooler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 2012EST &QL; 
