<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-CONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE WILL BE WATCHED CAREFULLY BY YANKEES' STAFF  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is the best of times for free-agent pitchers.
Kevin Brown won 18 games last season and was rewarded by the
Dodgers with a seven-year, $105 million contract. Randy Johnson
collected 19 victories and negotiated a four-year, $52.4 million
deal with Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone garnered a league-high 20 victories for the Yankees,
who last year won more games than any team in history. He led the
Yankees in strikeouts, and his ratio of walks to strikeouts was the
best in his 13-year career. But the Yankees offered Cone a
one-year, $8 million contract, and he accepted _ evidence of his
priorities, at age 36, and of the Yankees' wariness about the
condition of Cone's pitching arm, even after his superb season.
</P>
<P>
   Catchers and pitchers report to the Yankees' training camp in
Tampa, Fla., on Wednesday, Cone among them. The Yanks won 114 games
last season, in large part because their starting pitching was the
most consistent in the American League. Their rotation was
responsible for 72.9 percent of the team's innings, the highest
rate in the league. David Wells compiled a career-high 18
victories, Andy Pettitte won 16 games, Orlando Hernandez 12 and
Hideki Irabu 13.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom will tout the Yankees as favorites to
successfully defend their World Series championship. But unless the
Yankees' rotation offers a similar contribution, they will be
vulnerable. Whether the Yankees approach the standards they
established in 1998 will depend almost entirely on how the starting
pitchers respond in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Cone, therefore, will be watched closely by the Yankees' staff.
Again.
</P>
<P>
   They will watch how far he extends his right arm as he throws _
shortening his arm would be to suggest a problem. They will watch
his command, and see if he can throw his fastball past hitters high
in the strike zone, something he was able to do most of last
season, before fading. They will monitor his wellness and, Manager
Joe Torre said recently, reduce his workload if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely going to keep an eye on Cone,'' Torre said.
``But we did last year, because he was coming off surgery. What we
might be looking at this year, depending on how he feels, is maybe
stopping him after five innings or skipping a start.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone pitched effectively in the post-season, no-hitting San
Diego for five innings in Game 3 of the World Series, even when his
fastball lacked energy. But he required extensive treatment for his
final starts, and tired quickly _ and that, Cone understands, is
probably why the Yankees would not give him anything more than a
one-year deal. If he had wanted more, he would have had to sign
elsewhere, with the Mets, Los Angeles or Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Cone has thrown more than 90,000 pitches in his major league
career, accumulating roughly 8,500 tons of force on his shoulder.
He has been willing to take the ball even when his arm has ached
and to pitch on shortened rest, and he has fought to stay on the
mound as long as possible. There will be a time when attrition ends
his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they are worried about my health,'' Cone said, ``and
I'm sure that's what they were thinking when we negotiated, and I
don't have any problems with that. At this point in my career I'm
willing to take it year by year, and I'm willing to prove myself.
If I can have another good year, then maybe we can talk about
another one-year deal. I have no problems with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in my career, control over where I wanted to
play is more important than trying to maximize my value on the
free-agent market. It's really important for me to stay where I'm
at. Last year was so good that I just didn't want to give it up,
and I was going to do anything I could to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone believes he tired late last season because he started his
preseason preparation unusually early, as he recovered from
shoulder surgery. Bears and pitchers have similar life cycles: in
the winter, most pitchers are virtually dormant, resting their arms
completely. Cone normally will not touch a baseball from October
until sometime in January, when he will begin tossing lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Leading up to spring training last year, Cone had been throwing
resolutely for two months, wanting to prove to Torre and the
pitching coach, Mel Stottlemyre, that he was healthy and ready to
open the season. ``He was auditioning,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time spring training came around I was way ahead of
schedule, and I was probably peaking too soon, but it was
inevitable because of what I had been through,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   This winter, Cone returned to his normal off-season routine,
relaxing and spending some time on his charitable organization, the
David Cone Foundation. In recognition of his fine season, community
service and return from adversity, he was given the Hutch Award two
weeks ago, named in the memory of Fred Hutchinson, the Cincinnati
manager who died of cancer in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Cone started throwing only a couple of weeks ago, and he has yet
to throw off a mound. ``I'm hoping it'll make a difference to start
a little later, and peak a little later,'' he said. ``I feel good
about being able to get full rest this winter. Right now my arm
feels great _ I haven't really tested it, and I haven't gotten on
the mound and aired it out, but going into spring training I feel
really good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been told that now, more than a year removed from his
surgery, his shoulder may be stronger. That explosive fastball he
had in the warm weather of June and July last season might be
sustained through this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Cone's frustration manifests itself in self-lament. When his
face reddens with anger, when the lines on his face are taut, he
usually is castigating himself. He was discouraged with his slow
start last April, worried in September and disgusted when he nearly
blew a large lead against Cleveland in Game 6 of the AL
Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in February, he is confident. He was one of only four
pitchers to win 20 games last year, held opponents to a .237
batting average _ fourth lowest in the league _ and made more
starts (31) than in any year since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all speculation at this point, but I feel like last year
is still a pretty good indication of what I have left,'' Cone said.
``This year could be just as good or better.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
