 CHRON - FINBUDGET  
 
These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business section
plans to move for Monday, Feb. 15, on the New York Times wire. If
you have any questions, please call Georgie Dennison at (415)
777-6055.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BIOPASS  &LR; _  &LR;   &LR; Arthur Kaye lay perfectly still on the surgical bed
at the UC San Francisco Medical Center last week, while
cardiologist Tony Chou threaded a catheter through the clogged
arteries leading to Kaye's heart. Through that tube Chou shot an
experimental fluid that represents one of the most ambitious
research efforts in biotechnology: the attempt to grow new blood
vessels in hearts too weak to repair using traditional techniques
like bypass surgery or angioplasty.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists call the growth of new blood vessels angiogenesis,
and the search for drugs to stimulate this process has sparked a
race. Bay Area biotech giants Chiron and Genentech are among the
firms vying to discover ways to stimulate the heart; in essence, to
grow a bio-bypass around clogged arteries. By Tom Abate
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; HEWLETT-PACKARD  &LR; _ Hewlett-Packard is good at a lot of things, but
exploiting the Internet has not been one of them. Now, however, the
computer and electronics giant is vowing to catch up quickly and
become a force in electronic commerce. A profitable Internet
strategy could help reinvigorate HP, which has suffered through
more than two years of financial disappointments. And it would make
a hero of Ann Livermore, who is spearheading the effort. By David
Einstein
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE NET FILES  &LR; _  &LR;   &LR; Amazon.com misled the public and paid the price
with a public relations shellacking. But did it commit an
unpardonable sin on the wild, wild Web, where the lines between
advertising and editorial content are frequently fuzzy? Hardly. By
Jon Swartz
</P>
