<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5149 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-ART-2TAK     02-14 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT BRINGS FOES FACE TO FACE AT KOSOVO TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMBOUILLET, France _ Alternately threatening and cajoling,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright brought the two warring sides
in Kosovo together in talks here for the first time on Sunday but
came away unconvinced that a settlement could be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not be able to say that the path to agreement is clear
or that success is in sight,'' she said Sunday, before she was
expected to report back to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Empowered with Clinton's pledge of 4,000 U.S. troops to police
an eventual peace settlement in Kosovo, Albright journeyed to Paris
and then to the 14th-century stone chateau 30 miles southwest of
the French capital to try to galvanize the Serbs and Albanians into
reaching an accord this week.
</P>
<P>
   Despite invocations of fond childhood memories as a diplomat's
daughter in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, Albright encountered a
recalcitrant Serbian delegation.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs' ultimate leader, President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia, has remained at home. His surrogate and close ally,
President Milan Milutinovic of Serbia, flatly ruled out accepting
NATO troops on his territory _ considered a key part of any accord
_ and seemed impervious to Albright's renewed threats of airstrikes
by the alliance if the Serbs refuse an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanians, who have been fighting for the
independence of Kosovo, a province of southern Serbia, recognized
the plan to offer them autonomy as a ``fair deal,'' Albright said.
But so far, only they seemed ready to sign a peace agreement at the
end of the conference, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Contact Group of six nations _ the United States, four
Western European countries, and Russia _ whose foreign ministers
met in Paris on Sunday to review the negotiations set a deadline of
noon next Saturday for ending the talks.
</P>
<P>
   It was possible that Albright would return before the weekend
deadline, officials said. She would come back for ``closure or a
showdown,'' one said. But it was also highly probable, he added,
that the peace deal would have to be taken by the negotiators
directly to Milosevic in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Albright used a variety of arguments, from the highly personal
to the downright political, to tell Milutinovic why he should
encourage his boss, Milosevic, to accept foreign troops. NATO
envisages a force of some 28,000 troops to enforce an eventual
peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   An aide recounted that she told the Serbs on Sunday: ``I know
you all think that I'm anti-Serb but my father said if he hadn't
been a Czech first, he would want to be a Serb.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright spent part of her childhood in Belgrade, where her
father was a senior Czechoslovak diplomat. But her exhortations,
including remembering a Serbian lullaby, appeared to leave her
listeners unmoved.
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic, who dropped into the talks two days ago and is
expected to report to Milosevic on Monday, said the Serbs remained
opposed to the imposition of an outside force in Kosovo, the key
element of the peace proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very much against it,'' Milutinovic said in a statement
broadcast on government-controlled Serbian television. ``The
differences boil down to what happens at the end. If an agreement
is reached, who should implement it? We are of the opinion that we
should implement it, that we have the strength do that.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the Russians, traditional allies of the Serbs but
part of the foreign team overseeing the talks, ``are in full
agreement with us'' on the issue of foreign troops. Russia's
foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, was expected at the Rambouillet
talks on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said she stressed to Milutinovic during their meeting
at a Paris hotel that the foreign troops did not represent an
invasion. ``There's a big difference between if troops invade or
are invited,'' she said at a news conference. ``There are many
places in the world where troops are invited to enforce the
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright said she was encouraged by the response from the ethnic
Albanians, in contrast to that of the Serbs. Besides meeting the
16-member delegation, she spoke privately with one of the group,
Hashim Thaci, a leading member of the Kosovo Liberation Army rebel
group that has battled Serbian security forces for almost a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave me every indication that they will be ready to sign
on'' to the peace accord, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats here say that little progress has been made so far in
the talks, where the ethnic Albanians _ representing 90 percent of
Kosovo's estimated population of 2 million _ and 13 Serbian
delegates have been ensconced for the last week.
</P>
<P>
   Progress is likely to remain difficult to assess, because the
final decision rests with Milosevic in his palace in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The brunt of Albright's arguments with the Serbs centered on
Milosevic's opposition to allowing foreign troops in Kosovo, a
province of Serbia. Milosevic and his surrogates argue that foreign
troops represent a breach of sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   In the draft plan that has been presented to both sides at the
talks, Kosovo will become autonomous for three years, with its
future after that undecided.
</P>
<P>
   During the three years, a parliament, a judicial system, police
and other institutions are to be developed. The aim is to give the
ethnic Albanians control over their lives, but also to afford
``protection'' to the minority Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   While their security forces have ruled Kosovo harshly since
Milosevic stripped away the province's autonomy in 1989, ordinary
Serbs in the region say they fear domination by the ethnic
Albanians, who speak a different language, practice a different
religion and live almost entirely separately. The Serbs are
Orthodox, and the Albanians mostly Muslim. The two communities go
to different hospitals, schools, places of worship and
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Albright tried to impress on the Serbs, she said, that national
sovereignty toward the end of the 20th century didn't always mean
what it meant 100 years ago. She cited as an example arms-control
agreements between great powers who decided to cede portions of the
armaments they could produce ``for the greater good.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary also stressed that if Serbia did not accept an
agreement for autonomy, Kosovo would descend into an even worse war
that the Serbs could not win.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the elegant rooms of the castle, Albright achieved some
measure of success by bringing the leaders of the two delegations
together.
</P>
<P>
   They had not formally met in their seven days of talking, eating
and sleeping inside the chateau. The high point of the face-to-face
encounter, according to an aide who was present, was the offer by
the leader of the ethnic Albanian delegation, Thaci, who turned to
the Serbs and said he wanted to find a way that they could live
together. In reply, one of the Serbian leaders said they would like
to be constructive, the aide recounted.
</P>
<P>
   Because Thaci had been open-minded, Albright took him aside and
encouraged him to think about the example of other militant groups
that had given up their weapons. As a model, she suggested Gerry
Adams, leader of the political wing of the Irish Republican Army,
who had forsworn arms for peaceful leadership, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Some diplomats have suggested that Milosevic is resisting
foreign troops because it would be a ``humiliation'' for him to
explain allowing outsiders on Serbian soil, particularly in the
province that is at the heart of the Serbian national myth and was
the site of Milosevic's first attempt to keep all Serbs in one
state as the old communist Yugoslavia disintegrated.
</P>
<P>
   But others point out that Milosevic has the ability to explain
anything he wants to his population, particularly through his
control of key media.
</P>
<P>
   On April 23, last year, for example, Milosevic organized a
referendum in which a majority of Serbs agreed that there should be
no foreign interference in the conflict in Kosovo. Less than three
weeks later, the Clinton administration envoy, Richard Holbrooke,
the most prominent foreign mediator, met with Milosevic in Belgrade
to try and get a peace process started.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
