<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOPASS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOTECH FIRMS ARE RACING TO HEAL A BROKEN HEART 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - BIOPASS   By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Arthur Kaye lay perfectly still on the surgical bed at the UC San
Francisco Medical Center last week, while cardiologist Tony Chou
threaded a catheter through the clogged arteries leading to Kaye's
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Through that tube Chou shot an experimental fluid that
represents one of the most ambitious research efforts in
biotechnology: the attempt to grow new blood vessels in hearts too
weak to repair using traditional techniques like bypass surgery or
angioplasty.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists call the growth of new blood vessels angiogenesis,
and the search for drugs to stimulate this process has sparked a
race. Bay Area biotech giants Chiron and Genentech are among the
firms vying to discover ways to stimulate the heart; in essence, to
grow a bio-bypass around clogged arteries.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is a share of the multibillion-dollar market for
remedies to treat the 5 million Americans afflicted with angina _ a
condition in which a shortage of blood to the heart causes severe
chest pain.
</P>
<P>
   Angina patients like Kaye are the first possible beneficiaries
of angiogenesis. Today, when angina strikes, patients pop
nitroglycerin pills to relax their arteries, temporarily increasing
blood flow to the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Angiogenesis aims to provide permanent relief by growing new
canals to irrigate parched heart muscles. Kaye was the first
patient out of 300 who will take part in Chiron's Phase II clinical
trials during the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech has already completed Phase II human trials. Both
companies still face a third _ and more rigorous _ phase of human
trials before seeking Food and Drug Administration for their drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming nothing goes wrong, it could still be three to five
years before either company completes this process. But Chou is
guardedly optimistic these tests will one day lead to drugs to
safely repair the sickest hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a ray of hope,'' he said. ``But we really don't have
the final answer.''
</P>
<P>
   When Chou threaded the catheter into Kaye's heart last week,
neither doctor nor patient knew whether the tube dispensed Chiron's
drug or a placebo. The 67-year-old San Franciscan volunteered
knowing he might be a control subject, denied treatment so
scientists can later tell whether drug-treated hearts show better
blood flow than untreated ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through two bypasses and seven angioplasties, and I
still have angina,'' Kaye said. ``I'll take any chance I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the race to develop angiogenic drugs has been driven by
the growing numbers of patients like Kaye, who have been kept alive
by treatments like bypass surgery and angioplasty, but still have
clogged arteries and chest pains.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some extent we're the victims of our own success,'' said
Dr. Tim Henry, a cardiology professor at the University of
Minnesota. ``We've kept so many people alive who would have died of
heart attacks in the past, that we're growing patients who've
exhausted all the other options.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry, who has tested both the Genentech and Chiron drugs, said
at some point surgeons can no longer splice in another new artery
to bypass blockages to relieve heart pain. Clogged blood vessels
eventually become so weak their walls collapse, rendering
angioplasty useless as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angiogenesis is the next evolutionary step in heart
treatment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Henry will unveil the most comprehensive experimental
data so far gathered on angiogenic drugs in a presentation before
the American College of Cardiologists in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Henry's data will show whether Genentech's drug, vascular
endothelial growth factor, or VEGF, improved blood flow in a trial
involving 178 patients, some of whom got placebos.
</P>
<P>
   Though unable to divulge the results in advance, Henry explained
the similarities and differences between Genentech's VEGF test drug
and Chiron's candidate, fibroblast growth factor or FGF.
</P>
<P>
   Both test drugs are administered through a catheter threaded to
the heart. The drug (or placebo) is released inside the blocked
blood vessels and allowed to seep toward the areas where blood flow
is restricted.
</P>
<P>
   Henry said earlier research has shown that when the heart
becomes parched for lack of blood, the muscle tries to repair
itself through natural angiogenesis. The damaged heart tissues send
out signals, called receptors, that attract the VEGF and FGF that
our bodies normally produce.
</P>
<P>
   The hypothesis being tested in the current experiments is
simple: If doctors give the heart mega-doses of VEGF or FGF, will
the heart grow enough new blood vessels to irrigate the muscle and
relieve angina?
</P>
<P>
   Even if the tests show mega-dosing works in this way,
researchers will also have to prove _ to the FDA _ that it's safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern is that you're introducing compounds that might
cause unwanted vascularization (blood vessel growth) elsewhere in
the body,'' explained Chou at UCSF.
</P>
<P>
   The hypothetical danger is that these growth factors will escape
from the heart and find tiny tumors _ which need blood to expand _
and unwittingly fuel cancer growth.
</P>
<P>
   Chou said researchers will be alert for this and for hints that
these growth factors might grow unwanted blood vessels in the eye,
which could lead to blindness.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at Genentech and Chiron believe their drugs will
eventually prove safe and effective, but since they still have so
far to go in the FDA approval process, they can do little more than
keep their fingers crossed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, each company _ Genentech is based in South San
Francisco and Chiron in Emeryville _ subtly touts its supposed
advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech clinical scientist Ted McCluskey cq &LR; noted that his
company's completed second stage VEGF trials put it perhaps a year
ahead of Chiron's FGF.
</P>
<P>
   McCluskey said Genentech is hopeful that the molecular structure
of VEGF will lessen any likelihood the compound will roam the body
causing mischief. He said VEGF seems to bind to a protein called
heparan, &LR;  cq  &LR; which is present around blood vessels. The hope is
that the most of the VEGF dripped into heart arteries will be
captured as it flows through, leaving little to circulate through
the body.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron clinical physician Bruce Scharschmidt cq  &LR; said his
researchers also hope to show that FGF has a molecular
``stickiness'' to heparan, binding most of the chemical to the
heart arteries where it is introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Scharschmidt said the body's own processes should protect it
against any FGF that does circulate through the system. Remember
that angiogenesis begins when blood-starved areas send out receptor
signals. In the absence of signals, researchers hope any escaped
FGF will be ignored by normal tissues that aren't blood starved.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chiron may lag in the race, Scharschmidt believes FGF
has certain advantages because it seems to grow arterial blood
vessels, which are larger in diameter than the thinner capillaries
stimulated by VEGF. This suggests FGF might prompt more blood flow,
thus greater relief, to the heart.
</P>
<P>
   With years of research ahead, such conjectures remain
unanswered. UCSF's Chou said experiments could ultimately show that
the heart needs both VEGF and FGF to promote angiogenesis, and that
patients might benefit from a cocktail of the two drugs. Or they
might not work at all.
</P>
<P>
   But for the millions of people like Kaye who live with angina,
the research _ indeed the race _ holds out the prospect that
science could one day provide a way to relieve the pounding chest
pain that can be precursors to heart failure or death.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, volunteering is a kind of payback for all they've done
to keep me going,'' he said. ``This may be a total waste of time
for me, but somebody will eventually benefit from the research.''
</P>
</TEXT>
