<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5154 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEWLETT-PACK-SFCHRON-     02-14 1538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEWLETT-PACK-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON - HEWLETT-PACKARD  
 HP's Heir Apparent Leads Internet Push  &HT;     By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hewlett-Packard is good at a lot of things, but exploiting the
Internet has not been one of them. Now, however, the computer and
electronics giant is vowing to catch up quickly and become a force
in electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   A profitable Internet strategy could help reinvigorate HP, which
has suffered through more than two years of financial
disappointments. And it would make a hero of Ann Livermore, who is
spearheading the effort. In fact, industry observers say she could
end up running the Palo Alto company _ and become the most powerful
woman in technology.
</P>
<P>
   Livermore, a 17-year company veteran with heavy experience in
marketing, runs the Enterprise Computing Solutions Organization,
which was created in October to put HP's corporate hardware and
software under one roof. The group boasts 44,000 workers and
accounts for some $15 million in annual sales _ both nearly a third
of the company's totals.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge facing Livermore is to lift HP to the same level
in the minds of customers as IBM and Sun Microsystems, both of
which have done a much better job of positioning themselves as
Internet companies. IBM has grabbed the high ground with television
ads touting its expertise in e-business, while Sun's image has been
enhanced by the popularity of Java, the Internet programming
language it developed.
</P>
<P>
   HP, meanwhile, has been flailing about, trying to craft a
cohesive Internet strategy that integrates its online business and
security products.
</P>
<P>
   The problem can't be blamed on HP's technology and products,
which are lauded for their quality and reliability. Instead, the
company has been badly out-marketed by its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in our DNA to build great products, but there are other
areas such as customer relations in which we could be doing a
better job,'' said Duane Zitzner, the general manager of HP's
personal computer and workstation business.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the technology,'' analyst Daniel Kunstler of J.P.
Morgan agreed. ``They just haven't been able to pull it into the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Livermore means to change all that. Last Thursday, she told an
analysts conference in New York that HP will unveil, in the next
three months, Internet software that will let a broad range of
computers and other electronic devices communicate with each other
online.
</P>
<P>
   HP hopes the software, along with alliances it also plans to
announce, will lead to a new kind of Internet portal offering
comprehensive services in areas such as banking and travel. Such a
service, for example, could notify a car rental company or hotel
when an expected customer's plane is late, said Nick Earle, vice
president of marketing for Livermore's organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``HP will provide software technology to build the services, and
over and above that, we'll offer to manage them,'' Earle.
</P>
<P>
   Livermore's appointment effectively elevated her to the No.2
position at HP behind Lew Platt, the avuncular and media-shy chief
executive who has done little to sharpen the company's focus since
taking command in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Platt's inability to articulate a vision for HP _ especially its
plan for the Internet _ is cited as one of the company's most
glaring weaknesses. The omission has allowed its rivals to take the
high ground in the fight for the fast-growing e-commerce market.
</P>
<P>
   During Platt's tenure, HP has gone from a company hitting on all
cylinders to one that's been stalling at every street light. In
1995, earnings rose at an annual clip of 51 percent and revenues
grew by 26 percent. Last year, profits fell by 6 percent to $2.9
billion and revenue increased by just 10 percent to 47.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   HP's stock, once one of the steadiest performers in the
technology sector, sat out the great tech rally of 1998, rising in
value just 10 percent for the year. It has been rising lately,
however, largely on anticipation of the new Internet strategy. It
closed up $1.19 at $76.44 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In Platt's defense, HP may be one of the most difficult
companies in the world to run. It boasts five semiautonomous groups
that turn out a wide range of products from handheld calculators to
enterprise servers, as well as printers, scanners, test equipment
for chipmakers, and medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that mix competitive price pressures coming from all
directions as well as economic turmoil in Asia, and you have the
recipe for a financial malaise, not to mention a king-size headache
for the person at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Given all the bad news, it's only logical that the media have
been hunting around for a possible successor to Platt, who in three
years will reach HP's retirement age of 60. One candidate seemed to
be Rick Belluzzo, who ran HP's computer organization, but he left
about a year ago to take the top position at Silicon Graphics.
Since then, there has been no heir apparent until Livermore jumped
onto the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every company should have two or three people it's grooming as
possible successors,'' she said, adding, ``I'd have to say I'm in
that camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Livermore, 40, is a Stanford MBA with a reputation as a
hard-nosed but likeable manager. And compared to the bland Platt,
she's positively charismatic. Just the kind of person HP needs to
compete for headlines with people like Lou Gerstner of IBM or Sun's
Scott McNealy.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's initial reaction to Livermore has been positive.
Several analysts have upgraded HP's stock, confident that she will
be able to jump start the company with her Internet initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Milunovich, an analyst with Merrill Lynch, expects HP to
create an Internet division aimed at bringing together what until
now has been a fragmented effort. ``Creating a unified Enterprise
Computer Systems Organization under Ann Livermore was a prelude to
a cohesive Internet push,'' he wrote in a recent report.
</P>
<P>
   ``HP admits it missed the first wave of Internet computing but
believes the second (e-commerce) wave will be even bigger.'' he
wrote. ``HP may very well have all the pieces to become a leader.
In our view, the company's challenge will be packaging and
promoting its capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   While insisting that HP already has a solid Internet presence _
she noted that the company's OpenView software manages 70 percent
of all Internet servers _ Livermore acknowledged, ``We haven't been
too visible about it.''
</P>
<P>
   To correct that situation, she has elevated marketing to a top
priority in the person of Earle, who has become her right-hand man.
That's unusual for HP, which traditionally has pitched individual
products far more than corporate strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Livermore believes that an active campaign to improve the
company's image with customers also will serve to motivate HP
workers, whose morale has dropped during the financial downturn.
Last year, the company tightened up on travel and other expenses,
cut top executives' salaries and closed all its offices for a week
in December, giving workers an unpaid vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A key benefit of our getting out there and showing the flag is
that it will help inspire 44,000 people,'' said Livermore. ``We
think it will create a rolling thunder inside the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but it's unclear whether she will succeed in bringing the
rest of HP onboard. For one thing, the flat management structure _
six organization leaders reporting directly to Platt _ could make
for a struggle over succession.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, at least one HP group, the $8 billion Measurement
Organization, which makes devices for testing everything from phone
equipment to semiconductors, has been having real problems due
mostly to the Asian economic crisis and a downturn in the
semiconductor sector last year. In the fourth quarter, sales from
test and measurement equipment dropped 19 percent compared with the
year before.
</P>
<P>
   Edward (Ned) Barnholt, who sits atop the Measurement
Organization, said the Asian situation appears to have stabilized.
``We're seeing a modest increase in business there,'' he said,
adding, ``I wouldn't call it robust, but it's encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnholt declined to comment on reports that HP, believing
measurement no longer dovetails with its main computing business,
might decide to spin off the Measurement Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Critics argue that the decentralized nature of HP, which worked
to its advantage when it was smaller, is a liability for a firm
with revenues of nearly $50 billion that is trying to come up with
companywide strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Phil Rueppel of BT Alex. Brown said he thinks that given
HP's decentralized structure, as well as its historically cautious
attitude about change, ``The company may not be as adaptive and
flexible as it should be to deal with the new business
opportunities of e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, HP officials disagree, saying decentralization
actually makes the company more nimble. ``The value of the
decentralized culture at HP is the biggest strength we have,'' said
Antonio Perez, who runs the company's ink-jet-printer business.
``It will allow us to adapt a lot better than other companies to
changes in the industry's ecosystem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 2030EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
