<HEADLINE>
UCLA DOWN, BUT DAVIS IS UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As his team struggles, Baron Davis flourishes.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, UCLA's sophomore guard, is playing the best basketball of
his career and has emerged as one of the top point guards in the
country _ on equal footing with Arizona's Jason Terry and Utah's
Andre Miller.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bruins' two Bay Area defeats, Davis made 18 of 30 field
goals, 7 of 11 3-point shots and scored 50 points. He was the only
reason UCLA avoided humiliation in an otherwise lethargic
performance at Cal.
</P>
<P>
   Step back three weeks and Davis' numbers are equally impressive:
In his last seven games, Davis is shooting 56.6 percent from the
field, 52.1 percent from 3-point range and averaging 19.7 points,
with 41 assists and 19 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best he's played by a long shot, and it's not even
close in terms of the complete game,'' UCLA coach Steve Lavin said.
``In some ways, he's slowed his game down. In trying to do less,
what he's eliminated is the unnecessary forced shots. He's showing
patience, judgment and discretion.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis has not fully recovered from April surgery to repair a
torn anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee. Although he has
regained conditioning and can play 35 minutes without trouble, he
doesn't have the pre-injury bounce in his leg that produced his
spectacular play.
</P>
<P>
   But he has become a more cerebral player, thinking his way
through games, compensating for his knee, picking his spots to
shoot and score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can get my shot off at any point, but as a point
guard I've learned to keep everybody in the game,'' he said. ``I
just go with the flow, and I get easier looks at the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Second time's not a charm: It appears opponents have adjusted to
the Bruins' aggressive defense in the second half of league play.
</P>
<P>
   The teams UCLA has faced twice _ Oregon, Oregon State, Stanford
and Cal _ shot a combined 40.4 percent against the Bruins in the
first half of Pac-10 play, 46.4 percent the second time around.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso update: Freshman forward Jerome Moiso said it was his
decision to sit out Saturday's game because of tendinitis in his
right foot. Moiso hopes to return this week, but Lavin wasn't sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so tender, he has a hard time walking,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: In two games in the Bay Area, guard Earl Watson
made 5 of 15 shots and committed seven turnovers, and center Dan
Gadzuric made 6 of 15 shots and committed eight turnovers. . . .
Lavin plans to start Brandon Loyd and Sean Farnham against USC on
Wednesday and use Todd Ramasar as his sixth man. Combined, they
have scored 23 points in conference play. . . . Lavin sent his
apology letter not only to Washington but to all the coaches and
athletic directors in the Pac-10. Although he felt protesting
referee Terry Christman's sensitive whistle was necessary, a source
said, Lavin later saw replays of his Jan. 31 outburst and realized
he went over the line. . . . UCLA has not lost three consecutive
games since February 1992, when the Don MacLean-Tracy Murray team
lost to Notre Dame, USC and Duke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
