</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-NORTHRIDGE-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE LOOKS FOR BETTER OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A few days after Auburn surprisingly canceled its
football game at Florida State, Brian Swanson picked up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Swanson, Cal State Northridge's assistant athletic director for
external affairs, wanted to see if the Matadors could fill the hole
in the Tigers' schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Swanson was beaten to the punch. Appalachian State had already
filled the slot with Auburn. And CSUN is still looking for an
alternative to Southern Utah, the scheduled opponent in its Sept. 4
opener.
</P>
<P>
   The CSUN coaches do not want to play the Thunderbirds. They were
incensed when three starters went down with injuries, from what
they considered chop-blocks, which are illegal, when the teams
played last season.
</P>
<P>
   As of right now, however, head coach Ron Ponciano said there is
a ``90 percent'' possibility the Matadors will play at Southern
Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has any openings in that window that we would have an
opening,'' Ponciano said. ``We've done everything to get a game.
People are starting to flinch a little bit now. People aren't as
eager to play Cal State Northridge as they used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Swanson, who has been working the phones along with Ponciano and
interim athletic director Sam Jankovich, hasn't given up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two or three schools start dropping games and people start
falling all over themselves,'' Swanson said. ``There's so many
different scenarios out there.''
</P>
<P>
   One scenario has CSUN ``buying out'' Southern Utah _ probably
for $10,000 _ and hosting a game on Sept. 4. The travel costs to
Utah probably would run more than the buyout anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Swanson said he hopes to have the schedule, with or without
Southern Utah, finalized by the first week of March.
</P>
<P>
   Attacking the job: When Allison Lee was a soccer player at Cal
Poly Pomona, she looked for every opening in the defense, attacking
relentlessly.
</P>
<P>
   She became the school's all-time leading scorer. Now she's
making points in her bid to become CSUN's head women's soccer
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 26, has held the interim head coach title since Jan. 1,
replacing Brian Wiesner, who resigned after four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN is conducting a national search for a full-time
replacement, but it may not have to look far after the way Lee has
conducted herself in the last 1{ months.
</P>
<P>
   She has been a constant presence at high school games, and the
Matadors have already gotten commitments from two local standouts.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN has been criticized in the past for not recruiting local
talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I care a lot about this program,'' said Lee, who was Wiesner's
top assistant. ``There's no reason why the talented players in this
valley should be leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is the possibility Lee is assembling a talented
team for another coach. She doesn't mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've grown very attached to the team,'' she said. ``I want the
program to do well. I want (the team) to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN also is in the process of hiring a men's head coach. Both
openings should be filled by the end of next month.
</P>
<P>
   Magic number: The standard has been set in college basketball:
20 victories.
</P>
<P>
   To get that many in a season gives most college basketball teams
cause for celebration. The CSUN men have an outside shot at 20
wins, but the Matadors already accomplished one goal Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN earned its 15th win Saturday night, 83-62 over Montana
State, the highest win total in a season since the program went to
Division I in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this 15th win means a lot to us,'' CSUN head coach
Bobby Braswell said. ``We're heading in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking them home: Braswell shared this story Saturday night,
after senior guard Derrick Higgins played his last home game:
</P>
<P>
   ``The very first time I met Derrick Higgins, I was on my
interview here,'' Braswell said. ``I was meeting with the team and
he walked in with a towel on his head and he was holding a big,
long stick. He was calling himself Moses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought about that tonight in chapel. Moses led his
people to the promised land. Derrick has been a leader for us. He's
been just a great kid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
