<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXP-IMPEACH-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS SHIFTING TO ISSUES AND THE 2000 CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This article is part of TIMES EXPRESS. It is a condensed
version of a story that will appear in tomorrow's New York Times.) 
(ms) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With President Clinton's acquittal behind them,
senators of both parties Sunday turned to issues like Social
Security, taxes and foreign policy, while another Republican
announced he was taking steps to seek his party's presidential
nomination next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday morning talk shows were notable for showcasing how
eager the nation's political leaders are to move beyond the
impeachment struggle that consumed Congress for five months.
Senators quickly shifted to the legislative arena and sounded the
opening notes of the policy battles that are likely to shape the
presidential and congressional races in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in particular, who have seen their approval ratings
sink across the past months, worked to show that their party stands
for more than investigating Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A critical question in the wake of the impeachment struggle is
whether Clinton and Congress can overcome the anger and partisan
bitterness and work together.
</P>
<P>
   John Podesta, the White House chief of staff, said on ABC's
``This Week'' that for the second consecutive day the president
spoke with the congressional leadership about the possible troop
deployment in Kosovo and domestic issues.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, a Democrat who has
often been at odds with Clinton, and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
both warned that Clinton would make a mistake if he mounted an
all-out political campaign against those, such as the House
managers, who had worked hardest to remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has opportunities, but he will squander them if there's any
note of vengeance,'' Moynihan said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, the House Budget Committee chairman,
announced on ``Meet the Press'' that he would file papers Monday
with the Federal Election Commission to set up a presidential
exploratory committee, joining a crowded field of Republican
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, another of the Republican presidential contenders,
reluctantly supported Clinton's decision to send troops to Kosovo.
But he criticized Clinton for failing to prepare the American
people for the deployment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 2033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990214.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-PROVIDENCE-WELSH-     02-14 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PROVIDENCE-WELSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SMILING TIM WELSH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tim Welsh was just a few minutes removed from his Providence
College team's 84-57 blowout loss to St. John's last month when a
wistful smile crossed his face. He spoke of wiping the game off the
board by the next day's practice, so the negative feelings would
not linger.
</P>
<P>
   It was the sort of feel-good reaction the Providence players
have come to expect from their first-year coach, who nearly turned
down the job last spring because he dreaded saying goodbye to his
players at Iona so much that he canceled six meetings to announce
his resignation. Welsh, whose team faces St. John's again Monday
night at Alumni Hall, has resisted the tough love and histrionics
many coaches have adopted, weaving instead a personality that
combines the demanding work he learned from several coaches,
including his father, and the indulgence of his mother. While
others lead like Marines, Welsh sometimes sounds more like Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that scares me is we'll go into halftime down 6,''
said Providence's star forward, Jamel Thomas of Brooklyn, ``and
he'll be smiling. And I'm thinking, what's wrong with this guy? He
makes us feel good about our mistakes. He doesn't yell. His
assistants yell. When his assistants are yelling, he's smiling. I'm
telling you, this guy is crazy. Crazy in a good way.''
</P>
<P>
   Just one year after taking the eventual national champion,
Arizona, to overtime before falling in the final eight of the
National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament, the Friars
went 13-16 last season, a disappointment at a place that has
employed, among others, Rick Pitino. When Pete Gillen left to take
the head job at Virginia, Welsh became the Friars' fourth coach in
10 years, and they were picked by his Big East brethren to finish
near the bottom of the league.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Welsh, 38, using his brotherly demeanor _ after an
early-season loss, he insisted to his disbelieving team that it was
improving _ an up-tempo offense and pressure defense he learned
largely from Pitino, has turned Providence in the other direction.
Despite losing five of its past seven games _ three by lopsided
margins _ the Friars are 14-10 over all and 7-7 in the Big East.
</P>
<P>
   They have beaten North Carolina State, Purdue and, on the road,
Syracuse, a team coached by Welsh's mentor, Jim Boeheim, whose
frequently dour demeanor clearly did not rub off on Welsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my father's work ethic but a lot of my mother's
personality,'' Welsh said. ``I'm more relaxed. I can certainly lose
it, but only at points where it makes sense. Some kids need to be
yelled at more than others. Others need hugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players take on the personality of their coach. If I'm roiling
on the inside, they'll see through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, when Welsh looked at tapes of last season's
games, he did not think that Providence's circumstances were as
dire as his Big East colleagues did. But he also admitted that he
did not know how the team would respond to him after the departure
of the popular Gillen.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh's first lessons in relating to players were from his
father, Jerry, who won a Division III national championship and was
second three times in a 23-year career at Potsdam State. He
followed his father to practices, games and recruiting trips
beginning at the age of 3. Jerry Welsh has a picture of Tim, then a
fourth grader, at a coaching clinic in Saratoga Springs. Tim is in
a coat and tie, standing next to John Wooden.
</P>
<P>
   But Welsh also saw the strain the all-consuming coach's life
causes his family. After playing for his father at Potsdam State,
he became a salesman of air cargo space.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hours my father put in _ I wasn't sure if I wanted to
commit my whole life to what he did,'' Welsh said. ``I saw the ups
and downs, and the downs were really down. You saw the family pain.
It's a tough time, with a lot of traveling. It's not normal.''
</P>
<P>
   But he soon missed the rhythms of the season and, after
inquiring at many New York-area programs, became a volunteer
assistant to Pat Kennedy at Iona in 1985. Welsh made sales calls in
the morning and was at practices in the afternoon. He used vacation
time to go on road trips. His doubts erased, he followed Kennedy to
Florida State in 1986 and joined Boeheim's Syracuse staff in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Iona's athletic director, Rick Petriccione, who had been on
Kennedy's staff at Iona and Florida State with Welsh, wanted to
hire Jerry Welsh as Iona's coach in 1991, with Tim coming as the
assistant and heir apparent. Jerry Welsh was willing to make the
move for the sake of his son. Tim wasn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him no once,'' Tim Welsh said. ``I went back and felt
bad _ as a son _ and then I told him yes. You only have one father,
and you have a chance to be with him every day. This is the
twilight of his career and would you ever have a chance again to go
to the tournament with your father?''
</P>
<P>
   Iona went 30-26 in the Welshes' first two seasons, but had just
17 victories total in the next two seasons. Ten games before the
end of that fourth season together, Jerry Welsh was forced to
retire suddenly when doctors found a heart defect. Tim became the
head coach, finished 4-6 and then began a three-year run that
earned him a 70-22 record, two awards as Metro Atlantic Athletic
Conference coach of the year and a trip to the 1998 NCAA
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   When Welsh got to Providence, Thomas said, he told the players
that, because he was single and had no children, he would devote
all his time to them. Thomas was devastated when Gillen left and
thought briefly about quitting. Now, he said, ``I love Coach
Gillen, but I love Coach Welsh, too, even though I haven't known
him for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Welsh's smile rarely has cause to dim. Karim Shabazz, a
7-foot-2-inch transfer from Florida State, who also had been
coveted by St. John's, is in the fold, and Providence has surpassed
nearly all expectations and will very likely end up in the National
Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas and his teammate Corey Wright were talking one day,
wondering why their new coach was always laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask the players, `Why do you play the game?' '' Welsh said.
``It's not a job. A lot of coaches make it a grind. Not on purpose,
but because they feel the pressure. I do not want to make this a
grind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 2038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
