<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: KNOWING LOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Washington, Great Britain)  (rk) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first First Couple play a starring role beginning Tuesday at
the National Portrait Gallery in Washington where 25 depictions of
George and Martha Washington go on display through Aug. 8.
Commemorating the 200th anniversary of George's death, ``George and
Martha Washington: Portraits From the Presidential Years'' includes
the efforts by little-known and established artists, like Gilbert
Stuart, Charles Willson Peale, Rembrandt Peale and John Trumbull.
Information: (202) 357-2700.
</P>
<P>
   Fancy's Flights
</P>
<P>
   An airplane factory begins operation Tuesday at the Tate Gallery
in London. But it's not as if the home of the National Collections
of British and Modern Art had decided to abandon art for commerce.
The manufacturing complex in the Tate's Duveen Galleries is an
installation, ``When Robots Rule: The One-Minute Airplane
Factory.'' Created specifically for the galleries by the American
artist Chris Burden, this 20-foot-long robotic assembly line
transforms tissue paper, balsa wood and plastic into rubber-band
powered model airplanes in a sequence that ends with each plane
ascending some 60 feet and landing on the gallery floor. The planes
are sold for about $8 each. Having illuminated the principles of
mass production, the factory will close on June 6, after making
some 86,000 aircraft. Information: 011-44-171-887-8727.
</P>
<P>
   The Count
</P>
<P>
   ``Sesame Street'' is 30 years old, and in conjunction with that
anniversary a show of celebrities' art inspired by the show will
end a nationwide tour Tuesday in New York, its final stop. Among
the artists represented in ``Art From the Fuzzy and Famous,''
through March 11 at the Museum of Television and Radio, are Tony
Bennett, Barbara Bush, Kevin Kline, Rosie O'Donnell, Itzhak Perlman
and Julia Roberts. Information: (212) 621-6600.
</P>
<P>
   Scoreboard
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Spacey was named best actor when the Society of London
Theater handed out the Laurence Olivier Awards. Spacey was honored
for his performance in ``The Iceman Cometh.'' Eileen Atkins was
named best actress for ``The Unexpected Man.'' A revival of
``Oklahoma!'' was cited as outstanding musical. Its choreographer,
Susan Stroman, and its set designer, Anthony Ward, were also
honored, as was Shuler Hensley, for best supporting performance in
a musical. Nicole Kidman and Iain Glen of ``The Blue Room,'' now on
Broadway, were overlooked for acting honors, but its lighting
designer, Hugh Vanstone, won an Olivier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
