<SLUG> BC-AMR-PASSENGERS-546&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISRUPTION EASED AT AIRPORTS AS PILOTS RETURN  
 (EDS: SEE AMR-PILOTS)
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A day after a federal judge cited their union for contempt and
threatened to fine it $10 million, pilots at American Airlines
began returning to work in large numbers Sunday, easing the
disruption that has inconvenienced hundreds of thousands of
travelers over the last eight days.
</P>
<P>
   American said Sunday that it expected to cancel 260 to 270 of
its 2,250 daily flights Monday, the fewest since last Monday, and
hoped to be flying its full schedule by Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be almost there tomorrow (Tuesday),'' Chris Chiames,
an American spokesman, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But the company must still settle the dispute with the pilots
over its acquisition of Reno Air, a small airline in the West. The
two sides are expected to meet Monday, their first negotiations
since Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   About 900 of American's 9,200 pilots were listed as sick Sunday,
down from a peak of 2,400 on Friday but still above the normal
level of 400. As a result, American, the country's second-largest
airline, said it was forced to cancel 552 flights, far below the
peak of 1,170 it canceled on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At airports in Miami, New York and Dallas, there were fewer
angry passengers and shorter lines at the ticket counters of both
American and other airlines, some of which were deluged by American
ticket holders during the sickout.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Sumpter, a hospital administrator in Phoenix, had been
trying to get home for two days without success because her
connecting flight through Dallas was canceled repeatedly. But
Sunday, after American advised her to come to La Guardia Airport,
she got the good news that her flight was finally going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an 8-year-old at home,'' she said, ``so I want to get
back to him.''
</P>
<P>
   At Miami International Airport, American handed out free roses
to passengers while two of its baggage handlers entertained
passengers by singing gospel music, Motown and Frank Sinatra
ballads. ``This has alleviated the stress,'' said Earl Brinkley,
who was playing compact disks to provide the musical background
while his colleague, Larry Branchetti, sang.
</P>
<P>
   Watching were Ernie and Sue Weishaupt, who were waiting for an
evening flight to St. Lucia to begin their honeymoon. When their
original flight from Orlando was canceled, they drove to Tampa. But
the flight there ended up not flying as well, costing them a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't reschedule your honeymoon,'' Ms. Weishaupt said.
``Now on the flight to St. Lucia, they gave us separate seats. Can
you imagine? It hasn't been a good experience.'' Weishaupt said he
was just hoping that the evening flight was for real.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots began returning to work after Judge Joe Kendall of
the federal District Court in Dallas cited the union for contempt
on Saturday and ordered it to set aside $10 million for damages. He
also fined Richard T. LaVoy, the union's president, $10,000 and
Brian Mayhew, its vice president, $5,000. A hearing is scheduled
for Wednesday for the judge to determine how much the union will
pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The union is responsible for the damages these passengers have
suffered,'' he wrote in his sharply worded ruling, referring to the
hundreds of thousands of inconvenienced travelers. ``It is also
clear that the union leadership could care less about these
people,'' he added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   American said in court that the sickout had cost it $40 million.
Wall Street analysts have estimated that the company will suffer
much higher losses by the time the disruption ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The damage to the company has been extensive,'' Donald J.
Carty, the chairman and chief executive of the AMR Corporation,
American's parent, said in a message to employees on Saturday.
``Not just in terms of money, but most importantly in terms of good
will with our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Kendall had ruled on Wednesday that the sickout was
illegal and ordered the pilots to return to work, but American
complained that the union leadership had not complied with the
order.
</P>
<P>
   But after the contempt citation, LaVoy made a personal plea on
the union's hot line on Saturday night. ``We need to get this
airline back up and running at full capacity, and we need to do so
quickly,'' he said. ``Please clear the sick list immediately and
resume your normal schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Though many pilots may have removed themselves from the list,
American's troubles may not be over. Some pilots have said that
they plan to adhere strictly to work rules and many may decline to
fly voluntary overtime, which American depends on to maintain its
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Chiames said that many pilots liked to do extra flying because
it allowed them to earn more money. ``If it is true that they are
not going to do it, then we will have to schedule around that,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
