</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Skipped pit may have proved costly for Wallace, Mayfield
 &HT;    By Al Levine and Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Although both drivers say it didn't affect
their finishes in Sunday's Daytona 500, teammates Rusty Wallace and
Jeremey Mayfield didn't pit during a late caution and it may have
proved costly.
</P>
<P>
   After Bobby Hamilton spun into the wall of the backstretch
during the 173rd lap, nearly all of the race leaders headed to pit
row, except Wallace and Mayfield, who had covered 36 laps on their
tires.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon, who went on to win his second Daytona 500, took
four tires and fuel during the 174th lap, as did runner-up Dale
Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who led 104 of the 200 laps in the race, held his lead
until the 190th lap, when Gordon passed him inside on the
frontstretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the decision was OK,'' Wallace said. ``I still
think the decision was fine. Looking back at it, maybe if I'd had a
little bit more grip in the tires, I might have been able to hold
that bottom line a little bit better. But the car still handled
good. I wasn't having a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield, who led the race twice for a total of seven laps, was
second after 183 laps, but he cut his right, rear tire during the
194th lap and finished a disappointing 20th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Track position is everything in these restrictor-plate
races,'' Mayfield said. ``The tires hadn't shown any wear or
problems, our or Rusty's or anybody else's we knew about. New or
old tires, that thing was cut regardless. We were a lot more
worried about fuel than tires.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield says he isn't second-guessing the decision of his crew
chief, Paul Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd trust whatever Paul Andrews decided, without question,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   NO BULL
</P>
<P>
   Gordon wasn't the only one receiving a $1 million bonus in the
Winston No Bull 5 program. Ray Grimm, a correctional facility
officer from Hagerstown, MD., also received a $1 million bonus
after Gordon won.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't describe how I felt,'' Grimm said. ``It was so tense.
I really couldn't see the whole race from where I was standing.
Until Gordon came across the line, I couldn't stand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimm was part of Winston's ``They Win, You Win'' program, which
pairs five fans with five drivers. But Grimm will share his
winnings with the other four participating fans, who, he says, made
a pact before the race to divide the $1 million, regardless of the
winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a pact and I'll live up to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The No Bull 5 program awards eligible drivers who win one of
five No Bull 5 events _ the Daytona 500 on Sunday; the Las Vegas
400 on March 7; the Coca-Cola 600 in Charlotte, N.C., on May 30;
the Pepsi Southern 500 at Darlington, S.C., on Sept. 5 and the
Winston 500 at Talladega, Ala., on Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   The five eligible drivers in Sunday's race _ Gordon, Mayfield,
Dale Jarrett, Terry Labonte and Jimmy Spencer _ were the top five
finishers in last year's final No Bull 5 event _ the Winston 500 at
Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   The top five finishers from Sunday's race will be the five
eligibile drivers for the Las Vegas 400, and five new fans will be
selected from a national sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   Grimm, by the way, was a longtime Earnhardt fan _ until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   MOVING UP
</P>
<P>
   Bill Elliott of Dawsonville, Ga., made the biggest improvement
Sunday after starting the race in the No. 37 position. Elliott, who
used a provisional to make the field, actually led the race for
seven laps after pitting during lap 123 following a caution.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's plan was to drive conservatively during the first 50
laps, then change only two tires during pit stops. During the first
green-flag pit stop during the 54th lap, Elliott took only two
tires and moved from 32nd place to eighth.
</P>
<P>
   When he took the lead, Elliott jumped from 10th to the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good car,'' Elliott said. ``Whenever we came out and
were leading the race and kind of hanging in there, I said, `Man,
this is gonna be a pretty good day.' Some of the tape blew off the
front and it slowed the car down at that particular time, but we
were working on getting it all back. But, I think, by that time,
the motor laid down a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   ROOKIE WATCH
</P>
<P>
   Two rookies started the Daytona 500 and only one of them was
running at the end. Tony Stewart in the No. 20 Pontiac started on
the outside pole but finished 28th because of a faulty engine that
sent him to the pits for unscheduled stops. He completed 181 of the
200 laps and earned 11 points to take the early lead in rookie of
the year competition. Elliott Sadler in the No. 21 Ford got caught
up in the 13-car wreck on lap 135 and was eliminated at that point.
He got 10 points toward the rookie award.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of smoke there and I just tried to pick a
hole,'' Sadler said. ``I didn't get out and so we totaled the race
car. It's good, tight racing, but sometimes it gets out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckshot Jones, Don Pardus and Stanton Barrett did not make the
field but each earned a point.
</P>
<P>
   HELLO, AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Michael Waltrip hadn't had a top five finish since 1996, the
third-longest streak in Winston Cup at 86 races, before finishhing
in fifth place in Sunday's Daytona 500. Attrition and a pretty
strong No. 7 Chevrolet had Waltrip nearly in position to win over
the final five laps. Afterward, he was dejected instead of ending
his top-five streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was up to me and I didn't do the job,'' he said. ``I should
have kept Kenny Irwin behind me. I felt like I had a really strong
horse and I let the 28 (Irwin) get up under me. It cost us a chance
to win. I have to get that out of my mind and go on to Rockingham
and build on this. What was it like to be up front at the end? It
sucked the last two laps because I was out of it. But up until then
it was pretty fun.''
</P>
<P>
   PULLING UP THE REAR
</P>
<P>
   John Andretti was out of the race after only 25 laps with a
blown engine. ``I was real patient with it and didn't want to get
into any trouble,'' he said. ``I knew if I kept the fenders on it
we'd be there at the end. Running two by two you can't do anything.
Rather than trying to force the issue, like I did a couple of
times, I just said forget it and thought I'd wait until it got
single file and I'd start moving up then. We didn't get that far.
There's not really a whole lot you can do back there when you start
that far back (36th). You have to patient. We were going to let it
come to us.''
</P>
<P>
   DEMOLITION DERBY
</P>
<P>
   There was one 13-car wreck and two cars that hit the wall. Jimmy
Spencer, in the No. 23 Ford, was out after 121 laps when he lost
control and hit the wall at turn 2. Contenders Dale Jarrett, Jeff
Burton and Terry Labonte were the primary casualties of the
dozen-car accident that began when Jarrett went out of control
after being tapped from behind, apparently by teammate Kenny Irwin.
On lap 173, Bobby Hamilton, in the No. 4 Chevrolet, eliminated
himself when he spun and hit the wall on the backstretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like (Irwin) ran over (Jarrett),'' Sterling Marlin
said of the biggest pileup. ``He turned him around in front of all
of us and there wasn't any place to go. We'd run 100 or so laps and
nothing had happened, so you kind of figured it was going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Jeff Burton: ``I just saw (Jarrett) and (Mayfield) make
contact. Once they made contact, (Jarrett) started sliding. He
almost saved it, but you just can't save it when you get in the
corner like that. From there, it's just everybody trying to miss
the wreck and there's just not enough room. There's not enough room
for that many cars that far up in front of the field to miss that
wreck. It was a little, bitty tap. It wasn't a big hit, but it
doesn't take much at these speeds.''
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   The Winston Cup circuit moves to North Carolina Speedway at
Rockingham next weekend for the North Carolina 400. Jeff Gordon is
the defending champion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
