<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5172 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-DAYTONA500-HNS &LR;      02-14 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA500-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The final laps of the 41st Daytona 500 on
Sunday came down to the two men who have dominated Winston Cup
racing in the 1990s.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was Dale Earnhardt, the old master, against Jeff Gordon, the
young superstar of motor sports. For the last 10 laps, the two
biggest names in NASCAR were bumper to bumper with Gordon leading
the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt did everything he could to get his second consecutive
Daytona 500 victory, trying to maneuver his Goodwrench Chevrolet
past Gordon on the final lap.
</P>
<P>
   But the defending Winston Cup series champion did what few
others would have been able to do, blocking the Intimidator on the
final turn and keeping the DuPont Chevrolet in front to win the
event for the second time in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hear anybody say that wasn't an exciting
race,'' Gordon said. ``This is a dream come true for me. To race
Dale Earnhardt down the finish line for the Daytona 500 is just
incredible. He is the best in the business, especially at Daytona.
I had a mirror full out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was on my bumper, and he worked me over big-time. That's
the way he is and shows how bad he wanted to win this race again.
Keeping him behind me was one of the hardest things I've ever had
to do. He did everything he possibly could, but Dale has taught me
lot the last couple of years, and that's how I kept him behind
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Irwin, the 1997 Winston Cup Rookie of the Year, had the
best finish of his career by crossing the line third, just behind
Earnhardt. Mike Skinner, Earnhardt's teammate, also was in the lead
pack and finished fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt waited 20 years to win his first Daytona 500 in 1998,
but Sunday was the fifth time he has finished second.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last 10 laps were pretty exciting,'' Earnhardt said.
``There was some bumping and slamming, and we almost got sideways.
It was pretty physical, and it was awesome just to survive it. We
were happy to get second, but I sure would have liked to be back in
Victory Lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get Skinner with me so we could work together, but
I couldn't. Jeff's car was pretty strong off the corners, and I
just couldn't get there. I just got beat.''
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of more than 200,000 watched Gordon win his third
consecutive Cup event, dating to last season. The 27-year-old
driver also took home a check for $2,172,246, including his third
$1 million Winston No Bull bonus in two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He also made a millionaire out of Ray Grimm of Hagerstown, Md.,
who won $1 million as the racing fan paired with Gordon in the No
Bull promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon took the lead in dramatic fashion on lap 190 when he went
to the inside at the start-finish line to go three-wide heading for
turn 1. Gordon was down on the apron of the track and managed to
get back in line, with Earnhardt in tow, just before the banking of
the turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went about as far as we could before we got back in line,''
Gordon said. ``It was a pretty aggressive move. If we had still
been that low on the turn, we would have been in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who has won three of the last four Winston Cup titles,
has finished in the top 10 in 21 consecutive races dating to last
June at Michigan, and he has finished in the top five in 20 of
those events.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, 47, had not finished higher than third in any Cup
race since he won at Daytona one year ago. The seven-time Winston
Cup champion showed his skill Sunday by overcoming an ignition
problem midway through the race that dropped him back to 20th.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't get up to speed for a while,'' Earnhardt said.
``But we switched boxes and ran better.''
</P>
<P>
   An accident by Bobby Hamilton brought out the final caution flag
of the day on lap 173 and the strategic move that changed the
outcome of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace, who led 104 of the 200 laps, was leading, with
Penske-Kranefuss teammate Jeremy Mayfield third and Earnhardt
sandwiched between them. Gordon and Earnhardt joined most of the
cars on the lead lap and came to the pits, but Wallace and Mayfield
elected to stay on the track.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon and Earnhardt each took on four new tires. Wallace and
Mayfield were in front for the restart while Earnhardt was eighth
and Gordon was 10th. But Earnhardt and Gordon quickly worked their
way back to the front while Wallace and Mayfield were falling back.
With 10 laps to go, it was Earnhardt who pushed Gordon to the
front, and they both passed Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it. I thought I had the thing won,'' said
Wallace, who was making his 17th attempt at winning the Daytona
500. ``I tried to block Gordon, but it was either crash or move
because Gordon was going to come over me.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who finished eighth in the Miller Lite Ford, did not
question his crew's strategy to stay on the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was the right decision,'' Wallace said. ``The only
thing that lost me the race was Gordon got underneath me, and I
couldn't block him off. I just got freight-trained.''
</P>
<P>
   But the decision clearly cost Mayfield, who cut a tire with six
laps to go and finished 20th.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tires hadn't shown any problems with wear,'' Mayfield
said. ``We were a lot more worried about fuel than tires. We went
for track position, which is everything in restrictor-plate
racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon now has won the last two races at Daytona, including the
Pepsi 400 last October. He also has won four of the last five
Winston Cup events.
</P>
<P>
   But beating Earnhardt in a shootout at the end of the Daytona
500 was a victory he will cherish. After they crossed the finish
line, Earnhardt got his car beside Gordon's and bumped him _ a
gentle love-pat gesture of respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dale gave me a little tap, and he waved,'' Gordon said. ``Even
though we battled for the championship in 1995, we didn't have many
tight battles down to the finish of a race. I doubt if anybody in
the grandstands was standing at the end today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
