<HEADLINE>
MEXICANS WELCOME CLINTON, EAGER TO PLEASE A FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERIDA, Mexico _ President Clinton traveled to Mexico on Sunday
for a brief working visit with President Ernesto Zedillo, a trip
that officials described as a friendly stopover aimed mainly at
refreshing the two leaders' cordial relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Zedillo said that during Clinton's 23-hour trip to this
palm-dotted capital of the Yucatan Peninsula they hoped to whittle
away at a broad agenda of pending business, including disputes over
narcotics trafficking and migration.
</P>
<P>
   But the trip seemed mostly intended to please Clinton, two days
after the Senate acquitted him on charges of perjury and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton has been a good friend to the Mexican people
and our government, both in trying times and in good times,'' a
senior aide to Zedillo said. ``We just want him to enjoy his
stay.''
</P>
<P>
   A joint news conference, initially planned for the close of the
visit on Monday afternoon, was canceled after U.S. officials said
Clinton wanted to take no questions from the press, a Mexican
official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a visit more than anything to reinforce the idea that
there's presidential attention to Mexico at a time some people are
saying the Clinton administration has no Latin American policy,''
said Rafael Fernandez de Castro, a Mexican professor who is a
visiting fellow at the Brookings Institution in Washington.
``There'll be a lot of photo opportunities, mostly good-timey
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The two presidents and their wives were to dine together in
private on Sunday night in Merida. On Monday, the presidents are to
have their formal meetings at a restored hacienda outside Merida
before Clinton flies back to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Rebolledo Goot, Mexico's deputy foreign minister, said
modest agreements might result from the meetings, including one
that would increase cross-border airline flights and another aimed
at reducing the deaths of Mexican migrant workers.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials will brief the presidents on Mexico's efforts
to suppress the drug trade. The Clinton administration is due to
deliver its annual judgment on those efforts in coming weeks. The
agenda also includes a review of the North American Free Trade
Agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 2105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990214.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5178 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-NYTCONTENDERS     02-14 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-NYTCONTENDERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIMARY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 TO LEAD NIGERIA FACE OFF IN A BITTER By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast _ Nigeria's dominant political party
struggled to agree on its presidential candidate Sunday, a day
before it is required to submit its choice to an election body and
just two weeks before the elections on Feb. 27.
</P>
<P>
   The People's Democratic Party is likely to produce Nigeria's
next president, who would be the first democratically elected
leader in 16 years in Africa's most populous nation. The party has
dominated local and statewide elections in the last two months, and
the other two parties have so far proven unable to move beyond
their regional bases.
</P>
<P>
   The primaries for the People's Democratic Party, which had been
postponed twice, began this evening in Jos, a city in central
Nigeria. They followed a fierce battle between the two main
contenders, Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo, a former president who was the
only military ruler to give up power voluntarily, and Alex Ekwueme,
a former vice president in a short-lived civilian administration.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins two weeks from now, one thing now seems certain: a
southerner will be the next president of Nigeria, a country long
dominated by generals from the predominantly Muslim north. Obasanjo
is a Yoruba from the southwest; Ekwueme, an Ibo from the southeast.
The candidates from the other two parties are also southerners.
</P>
<P>
   A consensus recently had emerged among northern politicians that
the presidency would be conceded to the south, which has long felt
politically disenfranchised, especially after the presidential
elections in 1993. Moshood K.O. Abiola, a Yoruba from the
southwest, appeared to win the elections, which were then annulled
by a northern general.
</P>
<P>
   But even the apparently simple act of conceding the presidency
to the south has entailed complex strategic calculations in a
country divided by ethnicity, geography and religion. For the
People's Democratic Party, its two main contenders presented their
own weaknesses and strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning, it seemed that Obasanjo was unassailable,''
said Clement Nwankwo, chairman of the Transition Monitoring Group,
which has been monitoring the elections. ``But in the last few
days, we were getting reports that the contest would be extremely
keen.''
</P>
<P>
   As a military man trusted by the north, Obasanjo was viewed as
the front runner as soon as he declared his candidacy last fall; he
is considered the choice of the military elite who belong to the
People's Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   But doubts about his national appeal have increased amid a
widespread anti-militarist mood among voters and his increasingly
clear lack of popularity among his own people, the Yoruba, who have
long been suspicious of his ties to the north.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Ekwueme served as vice president in Nigeria's last
civilian government from 1979 to 1983. Although the civilian
administration was regarded as highly corrupt, Ekwueme maintained a
reputation as being clean. What is more, Ekwueme has the strong
backing of his people, the Ibo, who would likely feel alienated
from the People's Democratic Party if he is not chosen as its
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   By law, all three parties had to submit the names of their
candidates by Monday. The People's Democratic Party's delay in
selecting its flag bearer also apparently stemmed from the party's
desire to give as little time as possible to its rivals, the All
People's Party and the Alliance for Democracy, to mount a joint
attack. These two parties have said they will present a common
presidential candidate against the People's Democratic Party,
although it is unclear whether the agency monitoring the elections
will allow them to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The All People's Party also held its primaries Sunday, in the
northern city of Kaduna. Its leaders chose as their candidate,
Ogbonnaya Onu, a former governor of an eastern state who is little
known nationally; the selection must be ratified on Monday by the
delegations from all 36 states.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance for Democracy already had chosen a former finance
minister, Olu Falae, a Yoruba, as its candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria, which has been ruled by the military for all but 10
years since independence from Britain in 1960, held municipal
elections in December and statewide elections in January. The
presidential elections will be preceded on Feb. 20th by elections
for the national assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The country's military government has pledged to hand over rule
to a civilian government on May 29th, a year after the unexpected
death of Gen. Sani Abacha, whose five-year dictatorship and abuse
of human rights turned Nigeria into an international outcast.
</P>
<P>
   The handover will follow a tumultuous year during which the
equally sudden death of the longtime opposition leader, Abiola,
heightened the country's political crisis. Abacha's successor, Gen.
Abdulsalami Abubakar, defused the situation by implementing a
series of political reforms and by announcing in July that the
military would voluntarily give up power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
