r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-T     02-14 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNHARDT CAN'T GET AROUND A ROADBLOCK NAMED GORDON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Dale Earnhardt looked and sounded like his
old, intimidatin' self all week. He was relaxed, cocky. He walked
with a swagger. He was fast.
</P>
<P>
   He won his Twin 125-mile qualifying race on Thursday and the
International Race of Champions Friday. The familiar bad-guy black
No. 3 Chevy was so fast, handled so well, that Earnhardt took only
49 practice laps all week. Hey, if it ain't broke, no need to fix
it.
</P>
<P>
   The 47-year-old stock-car racing legend hasn't been a factor in
the points race since 1995, but he confidently talked of a second
consecutive Daytona 500 victory and a record-setting eighth Winston
Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me the equipment and get our team in the shape it needs
to be, and I can win races and win a championship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt has the equipment. The team is in good shape. Winning
races seems attainable.
</P>
<P>
   But to win a championship you've got to get around Jeff Gordon,
and that just might be the hardest thing to do in sports these
days.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon won the Daytona 500 Sunday, and took the first step
toward a fourth championship in five years, by refusing to let
Earnhardt get around. Gordon kept Earnhardt in his rear-view mirror
for the final 11 laps, matching The Intimidator move for move,
blocking every attempt to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to keep him behind me was one of the toughest things
I've ever had to do in a race car,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   The final few tense, edge-of-the-seat laps _ which saved a race
that was little more than a high-speed, single-file parade for much
of its 200 laps _ were symbolic of the changing of the guard that
began when Gordon won his first championship by holding off
Earnhardt in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt is the past, North Carolina born and bred with blood
lines that extend to the beginning of the sport. He is the favorite
son of the die-hard fans, who wildly cheer his every move.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is the present, and the future, a
California-by-way-of-Indiana boy, a 27-year-old Jeff-come-lately
who appeals to the sport's newer fans and is a hit in the new
markets, but is roundly booed by the traditionalists.
</P>
<P>
   They boo him, and they don't give him his due. Why does Gordon
win so much? Because, his critics say, Hendrick Motorsports can
afford the best equipment, because he drives for a good team,
because crew chief Ray Evernham is the best in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Why, half the drivers in the garage could win in the No. 24 car.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon did not win Sunday because of equipment, his team or his
crew chief. He won because of good, old-fashioned, Earnhardt-style
driving skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like we gave him the fastest car, and I don't
feel like we gave him a lot of help in the pits,'' Evernham said.
``The last 10 or 12 laps, it was the driver.''
</P>
<P>
   In a race where victory often depends on drafting partners, on
finding a friend to stick with you nose-to-tail to cut through the
wind, Gordon got precious little help. If he pulled out to make a
move, he went by himself.
</P>
<P>
   In stock-car lingo that's called being hung out to dry, and
Gordon looked like a piece of laundry all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've won some championships, they're sure not going to
help you,'' he said. ``It's frustrating. You make a move and think
maybe this guy will go with you, and it's like oh boy, here we go
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, when he finally did get some help, it came from
Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon made a bold move down the front stretch, cutting to the
inside of race leader Rusty Wallace. Mike Skinner, who was running
third, went to the outside and they went three wide.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt ignored Skinner, his teammate, and went with Gordon.
He pushed Gordon to the front, setting up the epic battle over the
final few laps.
</P>
<P>
   The old man tried every trick he knew to get past, tapping
Gordon a couple of times, dropping back to try and break the draft.
But the kid had a few moves of his own, letting off when Earnhardt
did to keep the veteran driver from getting the momentum to make a
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were the longest 11 laps I've ever run at Daytona,''
Gordon said. ``He was setting me up every single lap trying to get
by me.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Earnhardt still had the swagger. He talked about
going to Rockingham next week to ``start on that championship.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that, though, he'll have to get by Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   And that won't be easy to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
