<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HOUSTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON'S SHOOTING SLUMP CONCERNS KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Even when Allan Houston was not being guarded
Sunday, his shooting rhythm looked off. While the Knick assistant
coach Tom Thibodeau fetched the rebounds at SUNY-Purchase, Houston
uncorked 3-pointer after 3-pointer. Instead of the
swish-swish-swish one would expect of a natural jump shot artist
like Houston, he would make a few, then clang just as many off the
front of the rim. The pattern continued during the brief
shoot-around.
</P>
<P>
   The games have been even more telling. Houston is shooting 38
percent (23 of 61) from the field, and he is 1 of 9 from 3-point
range. He is averaging 14.8 points. The numbers take on a glaring
significance after the heel injury to Latrell Sprewell, the latest
player the Knicks hoped would take the scoring burden off center
Patrick Ewing. Sprewell will be sidelined for three to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Latrell being out changes Allan's importance,''
Coach Jeff Van Gundy said Sunday after a sluggish workout by the
Knicks. ``He's our only guy who's a pure shooter on the team. We
need him to be productive.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday afternoon, Houston will look for his former touch
against his former team, the Detroit Pistons (3-2), at Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy said the shortened 50-game season would not afford
Houston, a notoriously slow starter, a lot of time to snap out of
his spell. Even a short-term drop in production could be a
long-term detriment. Especially with Ewing (42 percent) and Larry
Johnson (43 percent) struggling with their shooting. Especially in
a stretch of four games in five days.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy feels Houston is shooting the ball with a flat
trajectory. Houston, who showed signs of his former self with 9
points in the fourth quarter against Chicago last Thursday, said
the solution was to create better opportunities for his talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really feel it's because I'm not getting shots up,''
he said. ``It's just a matter of making them count, and making
shots that are good for me. I'm working in practice on taking shots
that are decisive for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will guard the Pistons' small forward deluxe, Grant
Hill, who is averaging 29.6 points, giving Houston more energy to
exorcise his shooting demons against the club with which he spent
his first three years in the National Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to be lying to say I don't want to play well against
them, but it's not an emotional game for me anymore,'' said
Houston, who admitted to pressing against his former teammates in
the past. In the Knicks' four-game split with Detroit last season,
Houston connected on just 28 percent (14 of 50) of his field-goal
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, who have won their two games to even their record at
2-2, will have far more to worry about than bygone relationships
against Detroit. The Pistons will be hungry after losing two
straight, and they rely on a slashing offense that could land the
Knicks in foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Hill and Jerry Stackhouse (19.8 points) are second and third in
the league in free throws made, with 48 and 42, respectively. The
message is clear to Houston, who has been inhibited by foul woes in
two games and will undoubtedly join the rotation trying to stop the
pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I need to do is not use my hands as much,'' Houston
said. ``Sometimes I bailed out an opponent by using my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   When New York signed Houston as a free agent in July 1996, it
was not for his ability to shut down his man. It was for his
accuracy from the perimeter, which had been a desert for the
grind-it-out Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to fit in with a new team that was stuck in old ways,
Houston averaged 14.8 points in 1996-97. With Ewing out for most of
last season, Houston increased his output to 18.4, then to 21.1 in
the playoffs while Ewing played his 35-year-old body and tender
wrist back into shape.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the team has lost a proven point-maker. Again, Houston
will have to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is when you make up your mind that you're going to
shoot the ball, no matter if you make or miss,'' Houston said.
``That's when you're more effective as a scorer.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
