<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-REDWINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' PLAYOFF BID JOLTED BY A LOSS AND ANOTHER INJURY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first Ranger shot Sunday afternoon, by Brent
Fedyk, clanged off the Detroit goal post and stayed out of the net.
At the other end of Madison Square Garden, the first Red Wing shot
crossed the goal line and lit the red light behind Mike Richter.
From there on, it was just a matter of time, effort and superior
talent before the two-time defending Stanley Cup champions took a
4-2 victory over the Rangers, although the triumph was not secure
until the Red Wings scored into the empty net in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   It was bad enough that the Rangers lost their third consecutive
game on a day when they could have gained ground on their idle
rivals in the Eastern Conference playoff race. But other
developments made it worse, much worse, for a reeling team whose
season could quickly slip away, with five more games in the next
eight days.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Popovic, the big defenseman, who was beaten on the first
goal, by Sergei Fedorov, spent most of the day in a hospital with
blood in his right eye after he blocked a shot with his face. He
went home later, and his injury will be evaluated Monday. The
Rangers are already without Jeff Beukeboom, another defenseman, who
missed his second consecutive game with his second concussion of
the season. Beukeboom is not expected to play against the
Predators, Coach John Muckler said.
</P>
<P>
   On the forward line, Todd Harvey missed the third period with a
fractured right thumb, an injury suffered against Carolina on
Friday night, which was his first game back after missing the
previous 10 with a knee injury. His status is day-to-day, the
Rangers said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Rangers who played, it was a difficult afternoon,
particularly after they fell behind by three goals in the first
period. Richter, who gave them up, was replaced by Dan Cloutier.
Muckler said Cloutier will start in Nashville. Wayne Gretzky, who
went without a point for the third consecutive game, finished with
a minus-3 in the plus/minus ratio, dropping him to a minus-18,
worst on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Leetch, whose three-game goal-scoring streak ended,
attacked the net repeatedly and may have been New York's best
player. He was on the ice for nearly 36 minutes. His reward, in the
closing minutes, was a legal, crunching shot into the boards on a
Kirk Maltby check, a hit that left his teammates trying, without
much success, for vengeance. Petr Nedved, fighting a scoring slump,
created numerous chances for naught. Chris Osgood, the Detroit
goalie, robbed him four times and the cross bar stopped him another
time.
</P>
<P>
   With 29 games remaining in an 82-game schedule, the Rangers
remain in 12th place in an Eastern Conference that will send only
eight teams to the post-season tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Muckler, asked if he thought his team deserved to make the
playoffs, replied, ``Yes, I think we deserve to be in the playoffs
if we can get some wins together. I don't see the other teams _
Boston and Florida _ really setting the world on fire here. We're
six points out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   That much is true. And the Rangers have as many victories as the
eighth-place Panthers, and they have a game in hand on the
ninth-place Bruins.They also have three games in hand on 10th-place
Montreal and are only one point behind 11th-place Washington. And
yet they have lost 9 of their last 12 games and are 6 games below
.500, their lowest mark of the season. And if they make the
playoffs, they deserve a parade, at least from Seventh Avenue to
Eighth Avenue, if any of them are still healthy enough to sit up in
the convertibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no excuses,'' said Adam Graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe tomorrow,'' said Fedyk, who scored one of the Ranger
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't quit,'' said Leetch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fighting for our lives,'' said Cloutier.
</P>
<P>
   He also fought a bit with Slava Kozlov, a Detroit forward. After
they collided, Cloutier put Kozlov in a leg lock and rolled over on
him while other Rangers raced the other way. This came late in the
second period, after Marc Savard's eighth goal of the season cut
the lead to 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   These two elements energized the crowd and set up a tense third
period that got better when Fedyk scored his third of the season to
cut the lead to 3-2 at 4:30. But after Cloutier was pulled for an
extra attacker, Niklas Listrom sank the puck into the empty net.
Yzerman and Petr Klima scored the other Detroit goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
