<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-KECZMER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESERVES MAKING MOST OF VALUABLE PLAYING TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Dan Keczmer didn't get to sun himself in
Southern California last week.
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of his Stars teammates were bonding on a vacation
trip to Newport Beach, Keczmer was busy catching a flight to
Kalamazoo, Mich., returning to Dallas and then flying to Houston _
all so he could play three games at the minor-league level. Not the
kind of stuff a 30-year-old father of two considers fun, but for
Keczmer, there was no disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I'd fly to the North Pole if it meant playing,'' Keczmer
said.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude showed on the ice for both Keczmer and Brent
Severyn on Saturday night. For only the fifth time this season, the
two role players worked themselves into the lineup for the same
game. And for the first time, they played on the same line. The
combination proved electric as the duo played only six minutes but
dished out big hits, dominated control of the puck and sent a sense
of urgency to their teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have that desperation in their game,'' defenseman Richard
Matvichuk said. ``They're out there working hard and trying to
prove something every shift, and that's a great way to play. It's
contagious.''
</P>
<P>
   Severyn, a fighter acquired in the off-season, played in only
his 13th game. Keczmer, a journeyman defenseman who has been
shifted to left wing, played his 20th game. The two typically don't
know if they're going to play until the day of the game and they
have to be ready no matter what. Keczmer, in fact, was told during
pregame warmups Saturday that he would play after Mike Keane's sore
ankle flared up.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, both were ready to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Sevy, we're both in the same position,'' Keczmer said.
``We know whenever we get the chance to come in, we have to play
hard, play smart and play defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we're not going to get a lot of free chances,'' Severyn
said. ``We can't afford to not play well when we get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Combined with center Guy Carbonneau, the Stars' fourth line
played extremely well, helping inject energy into the team when it
lost a two-goal lead in a 40-second span during the second period.
In fact, Carbonneau scored the game-winning goal off assists by
Severyn and Keczmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's exactly what we need from our third and fourth lines,
hard-working play, and they gave us that,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``Desperate or whatever you want to call it,
everyone should play like that.''
</P>
<P>
   With Keane day-to-day on his sore ankle and Hitchcock recalling
young winger Jason Botterill yesterday, it's still up in the air
whether the coach will keep Keczmer and Severyn on the same line.
And while the duo did a remarkable job in a short period of time,
it's difficult enough to get one of them into the lineup on a
consistent basis, let alone two.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this was just one game, and it could change
tomorrow,'' Severyn said. ``We know he has some tough decisions to
make, and we just have to be ready to play when our time comes.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Stars needing more of a physical presence from their
wingers, a couple of journeymen could make it extra tough on a man
who could be controlling the deepest roster in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I have no problem putting them in the game together, even
if it means pulling out some of our other players,'' Hitchcock
said. ``Competition within the team can only make us better.''
BOTTERILL RETURNS The Stars yesterday recalled Botterill from the
Michigan K-Wings of the International Hockey League. Botterill, 22,
played four games with the Stars last season but has not played a
game with them this season. He has eight goals and 13 assists for
21 points with the K-Wings. Hitchcock said he will decide today
whether he will play Botterill against the Edmonton Oilers tonight.
/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
