<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' BOSS NOT AT LOSS IN MAKING ALL THE RIGHT MOVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ If Steinbrenner owned the Rangers, Randy
Johnson or Roger Clemens would be mansion-hunting in the Metroplex
right now. Maybe even both. Steinbrenner has never been one to
finish second in any wild spending spree.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Hicks is The Boss around here, and the Rangers declined
to outrageously overpay for a 35-year-old pitcher with a history of
a bad back, volatile temper and a tendency to quit on his team when
things don't go his way. Nor did they mortgage the farm system or
give away half the team for a 36-year-old pitcher who may still
have it but who also wanted a one-year $27 million contract
extension.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good as far as Hicks owning the Rangers. The man
isn't out of control, at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   His much-anticipated first off-season heading up the Rangers was
not marked by any wild spending sprees, but by the cool
professionalism necessary for a franchise to maintain consistent
success. The old Los Angeles Dodgers, Toronto Blue Jays and Oakland
Athletics were known for just that.
</P>
<P>
   Sanity prevailed. The right decisions were made. General manager
Doug Melvin was allowed to do his job in his usual calm and
meticulous manner.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the shortstop was re-signed, power was added to the
lineup and starting pitching depth was added at a reasonable price.
Remember, Johnson would likely have meant no Rafael Palmeiro and
Clemens ultimately would have cost Rusty Greer, Rick Helling and
Ruben Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   The only sign of unnecessary ownership meddling was the
acquistion of one Heisman Trophy running back who has virtually no
chance of playing in the major leagues. Melvin's protestations
aside, it's hard to believe Ricky Williams would be in the Rangers'
spring training camp if Hicks had gone to Midwestern State
University.
</P>
<P>
   Actually though it could be worse. The Rangers could have Garth
Brooks coming to camp. Imagine a major-league baseball franchise
crazy enough to have a country-western singer hanging around.
</P>
<P>
   The point is the Rangers don't need another Steinbrenner. They
don't need another ego-crazed Peter Angelos or Ted Turner serving
as manager for a day. They don't need an owner who feels it's his
prerogative to hire and fire pitching coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Steinbrenner, taking advantage of the huge financial
advantages in New York, has won four World Series titles, two in
the '70s and two more in the past three years. But both times it
took Steinbrenner getting suspended for two years, allowing the
Yankees' real baseball people to do their jobs properly. The
Yankees did almost nothing in the '80s while Steinbrenner was
allegedly behaving himself.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Hicks has shown no signs of handing out illegal campaign
contributions or consorting with known gamblers, as Steinbrenner
did.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks does want to win a World Series and has conveniently made
that perfectly clear to manager Johnny Oates. But he also does seem
to have a clue.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Schieffer, unlike Tex Schramm or Norm Sonju, has survived
the ownership change. Melvin still seems to have final say in the
baseball decisions. Hicks does know who Mateo, Corey Lee and Kelly
Dransfeldt are and what they mean to the future of the franchise.
He has heard of the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   For all of Hicks' billions and all the financial advantages
offered by The Ballpark, the Rangers aren't going to catch up to
the Yankees by spending as much money as possible. The Yankees win
that battle. Always have, always will.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks needs to make sure the Rangers are spending enough money
in scouting and player development to ensure a viable farm system.
He needs to make sure the Rangers stay strong in Latin America as
well as become a player in the rapidly growing Asian talent market.
</P>
<P>
   He needs to make sure his very-capable manager _ who is as good,
if not better than Joe Torre _ and hard-working coaches don't have
to be fearful for their jobs. He needs to make sure the Rangers
have the best amateur scouts around.
</P>
<P>
   He needs to make sure the home-grown talent stays here and is
not pitching the Florida Marlins or the San Diego Padres into the
World Series. The Rangers, who did the right thing with Helling,
needed to spend more time this off-season talking about Juan
Gonzalez and less about Johnson and Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin knows how to do his job. So does Oates. The Rangers need
an owner not just with billions of dollars in pocket change but who
also dictates the proper philosophy, then lets the right people do
their job.
</P>
<P>
   That's not Steinbrenner's way. But it's the right way. /
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
