<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5199 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BISHOP-TEX     02-14 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BISHOP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOP NOT VIEWED AS NFL PROSPECT BY MANY SCOUTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Michael Bishop finds himself awash in mixed
messages as he prepares to make the transition from college to
professional football.
</P>
<P>
   The runner-up in balloting for the 1998 Heisman Trophy, Bishop
will be at the Fort Worth Club tonight to receive the Davey O'Brien
National Quarterback Award, a trophy bestowed annually to the top
quarterback in college football. Yet few NFL scouts and draft
analysts rank the former Kansas State standout among the top six
prospects at his position in the 1999 NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Check out the top 50 players, as rated by ESPN draft analyst Mel
Kiper, and there are four quarterbacks: Kentucky's Tim Couch (No.
2), Syracuse's Donovan McNabb (No. 5), Oregon's Akili Smith (No.
13) and Central Florida's Daunte Culpepper (No. 23). But no Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sporting News'' ranks Bishop seventh among quarterbacks in
the draft pool, behind the Fab Four identified by Kiper, as well as
UCLA's Cade McNown and Washington's Brock Huard.
</P>
<P>
   Several NFL scouts confirmed that such assessments reflect the
majority opinion within the league, where Bishop is considered too
short (6-foot-1) and too quick to scramble (14.8 carries per game
in 1998) to match the protoype for an NFL quarterback. Most target
him as a third- to fifth-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Bishop said he's been urged to switch positions by
scouts from the Tennessee Titans and Arizona Cardinals. If his NFL
future is dependent upon a position switch, Bishop said he is
willing. But he is counting on some NFL team believing in his
potential at quarterback as much as he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I get there and get the opportunity to play, there's no
doubt in my mind that I'm going to sit back some day and laugh
about all the people who think I can't be an NFL quarterback,''
Bishop said. ``I'll be one of the greatest quarterbacks ever to
come through the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop already has one of the greatest single-season production
jumps of any college quarterback. In 1997, Bishop's first year in
Division I-A after winning consecutive national championships at
Blinn Junior College, he completed 43.4 percent of his passes.
Bishop improved to 55.6 percent last season, throwing for 2,844
yards with a touchdowns-to-interceptions ratio of 23-4.
</P>
<P>
   Combine that with his 748 rushing yards, said Kansas State coach
Bill Snyder, and the numbers suggest a quarterback who has the
tools to succeed in the NFL, where mobile quarterbacks are becoming
more desirable ... as long as they don't disrupt the offense by
running too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of having a quarterback like Dan Marino, who can't
hurt you by scrambling, are endangered,'' said Cowboys' scout
Walter Julif. ``The reason mobile quarterbacks are in vogue is
because of the salary cap. You can't put put together an offensive
line any more without some holes in it. So you'd better have
someone back there who can move.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, a 4.5 sprinter in the 40-yard dash, certainly qualifies
on the mobility scale. He also ranks high in arm strength, work
ethic and intangibles. During the East-West Shrine Game, where he
received 34 of 37 votes to be a team captain, he volunteered to
cover kickoffs. In four seasons as a starting quarterback at the
college level, Bishop compiled a record of 46-3.
</P>
<P>
   But scouts point to his frequent early departures from the
pocket and question his ability to read defenses. Terry Bradway,
director of personnel for the Kansas City Chiefs, predicted
Bishop's draft-day destiny rests in how well he explains his
on-field decisions while reviewing videotapes with NFL coaches
between now and April.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the spring, you get to understand what he knows and what
his thought process is,'' Bradway said.
</P>
<P>
   Some envision greener pastures for Bishop in the Canadian
Football League, where the wider field and less-structured offenses
are more suited to his freelance style.
</P>
<P>
   If Bishop wants to continue in his quest as a quarterback, said
ESPN college football analyst Lee Corso, he ``should go to the CFL
and make $8 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Cowboys personnel director Gil Brandt, who spent a week
with Bishop at the East-West Shrine Game, praised Bishop's arm
strength and leadership abilities. As an athlete, Brandt said
Bishop has the physical tools to shift to cornerback and ``have as
much dominance on the game as any of the top cornerbacks in the
league, other than Deion \RSanders\S.''
</P>
<P>
   But, quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I don't know if he can be an NFL quarterback,''
Brandt said. ``Does he learn 19 different formations and what to do
against 37 different defenses? I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop is convinced he can do it, but would prefer to ease into
the position after spending a season or two learning from a
veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, I'll be ready to explode,'' Bishop said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig James, college football analyst for CBS, said Bishop is
the type of player who would benefit from spending the spring in
the NFL's European training league. Although he identified Bishop
as an athlete with the physical tools to play safety or wide
receiver in the NFL, James said Bishop belongs at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be the best example of a guy you've got to throw out
the standard requirements for being an NFL quarterback ... since
Doug Flutie,'' said James, who was a teammate of Flutie's with the
New England Patriots. ``What both of those guys have is an ability
to win games. Doug just wins, regardless of the situation. I think
the same thing will happen with Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a linebacker's mentality that he's going to have to
throttle down at times. He'll have to learn not to force things to
happen in the NFL, where there are 10 guys around him as good or
better than he is. But he'll be a success for somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as that happens, Bishop said he doesn't mind if he's
taken in the fifth round. Or later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't bother me at all, as long as I get a chance,''
Bishop said. ``When I do, the people that questioned my ability
might look a lot like the people who questioned Randy Moss.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss, lest anyone forget, has a Rookie of the Year award to
remind his critics they were wrong. Bishop, at this point, has a
Davey O'Brien Award that suggests he can't be taken lightly,
either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
