<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAA-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN ALREADY IS A DISTRACTION FOR THE LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has played on five of the last 10 National Basketball
Association champions and has won the league's rebounding title an
unprecedented seven consecutive seasons. On the flip side, he
carouses till dawn, sometimes misses practice and often misses free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   At this tender stage of their championship development, do the
Los Angeles Lakers truly need Dennis Rodman?
</P>
<P>
   While Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant were holding their own
against Indiana Sunday, Rodman, the power forward who could add
considerable intrigue to the Western Conference title chase, was
still mulling whether to sign with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Without suiting up for one game, Rodman is a distraction for a
team that already has a bundle of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're waiting to hear from him,'' said John Black, a Lakers
spokesman. ``I have no idea where he is or what he's doing. There
is no `latest update' or anything. Once we hear from him, then
maybe we'll have something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We would love to have Dennis,'' Magic Johnson said on NBC
Sunday night during the Lakers' 101-99 loss to the Pacers. ``But we
would hope that this thing gets solved soon. It's not good for our
team and it's not good for him if it continues go on like this.''
</P>
<P>
   This is vintage Rodman, milking the moment for all its theater
and running the risk that prospective employers will grow weary of
his antics and decide he is not worth the trouble. But the Lakers
have stayed in the hunt, acting desperate at times in spite of all
their talent.
</P>
<P>
   They can offer him only the veterans' minimum of $1 million,
prorated to $600,000 for the lockout-shortened season. A $3 million
endorsement deal from Converse would help foot the bills for those
raucous parties (a bash over Super Bowl weekend in Miami cost
Rodman an estimated $300,000).
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition might set in motion other transactions over the
next month for the Lakers. Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell could be
sent to Charlotte for Glen Rice, B.J. Armstrong and J.R. Reid.
</P>
<P>
   Rice is currently sidelined because of elbow surgery. In the
last year of his contract, he needs to finish strong to warrant a
huge new deal. Becoming the third option on the Lakers would not
help his cause; he would rather return to Miami, where his wife's
family lives.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, the addition of Rodman would not guarantee the
Lakers a reservation for the finals. He can take pressure off
O'Neal inside by guarding other teams' most burly power forwards
and centers. But does a team of impressionable young players who
are still growing up really need an unpredictable teammate added to
the mix?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he realizes the last thing this young team needs is a
distraction,'' said Derek Harper, the 37-year-old veteran point
guard. ``I'm thinking he's going to come in and work the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an unnamed source that says he's going to come here and
be normal, if he comes here. I just think he's sick of being a
distraction. I think he wants to come in and do the right thing.
I'm really hoping for that. We have a young team. Any distraction
is going to be a cancer for this team. It's Dennis' responsibility
to stay in line.''
</P>
<P>
   What a concept. Rodman, policing himself at 37. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RISKING THE OLYMPICS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Charles Barkley's knee to Latrell Sprewell's heel, the
layoff during the lockout has been deemed responsible for a rash of
injuries afflicting the league. The labor dispute has also been
blamed for, among other things, fan apathy and awful execution on
the court.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another less obvious malady that could be the
lockout's greatest casualty: an Olympic gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   As the USA Basketball selection committee prepares over the next
two weeks to pick a team to represent the United States at the Pan
American men's qualifying tournament in Puerto Rico this July, it
will not take the process lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the boycott by NBA players during the world
championships in Athens last July, the United States failed to
qualify then for the 2000 Games in Sydney, Australia. After
finishing third with a hodgepodge unit of college and Continental
Basketball Association players, the men's team now needs to win or
come in second in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine we would get disqualified,'' said Russ Granik,
the N.B.A. deputy commissioner who heads the selection committee.
``But we're still going to pick our best team and take this very
seriously. The key is winning your semifinal game. You can assume
we won't be sending a college team.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those players who boycotted last summer and are expected
to be selected again: Grant Hill, Gary Payton, Allan Houston and
Chris Webber.
</P>
<P>
   And if the United States somehow gets upset? ``We can blame the
labor dispute,'' Granik said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
REALLY SUITING UP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charles Oakley, perhaps the league's nattiest dresser, took time
out last week from letting the Knicks know how he felt about being
traded to offer up some fashion tips for NBA youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know guys are into the hip-hop stuff, want to wear
jeans,'' Oakley said. ``That's college and high school. When you
get to a level like this, you got to look good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are in love with the hip-hop stuff. Every time somebody
has to go to a function, they say, `I don't have nothing to wear.'
I think every guy should have a suit for every day in the week _
even if they have to rotate them or whatever. At this level, you
should have seven suits.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley also maintained that looking good can help take the sting
away from playing for a team with a lousy record. He wore an
impeccable green tweed ensemble after Toronto's loss to Milwaukee
last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel better, win or lose, once you leave the locker
room,'' he said. ``Hey, you know you gave your best. You have jeans
and stuff, it's a different approach to life. You could be a
millionaire, and you think you don't have to impress anyone with
what you wear. But I always like to look nice.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
K.J. STILL ON THE FENCE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The free agent point guard Kevin Johnson is still deciding
whether to play this season and has yet to commit to the Houston
Rockets, one of several teams interested in his services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 2143EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
