<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-GORDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORDON SHOWS EARNHARDT HIS EXHAUST PIPES AT FINISH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Jeff Gordon's car roared down the front
straightaway toward the checkered flag in the Daytona 500 Sunday,
his Chevrolet a blur as it swerved from side to side. Dale
Earnhardt was nudging the rear of Gordon's car, looking to make one
of his signature bump-and-run moves.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's black Monte Carlo peeked to the inside, then to the
outside of Gordon's Monte Carlo, but there was no extra space on
the track. Earnhardt, last year's Daytona 500 winner, quickly was
running out of time when he made one last attempt to pass on the
inside, only to be frustrated again as Gordon steered onto the
apron.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's decisive block _ a risky move at more than 190 miles an
hour _ kept Earnhardt in his rearview mirror as Nascar's biggest
rivals crossed the finish line 1-2 in front of 185,000 screaming
fans at Daytona International Speedway, ending stock car racing's
crown jewel event in dramatic fashion. Kenny Irwin, driving a Ford
Taurus, was a close third and Mike Skinner, in a Chevrolet, was
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Daytona, on the last lap, that black car is not what you
want to see,'' said Gordon, who claimed his second Daytona 500
victory in three years and drove to his seventh victory at this
2.5-mile, high-banked oval. ``Those were the longest 12 laps of my
life here at Daytona. He was setting me up every lap, trying to get
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's even more special because I beat Dale Earnhardt,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, 47, the seven-time Winston Cup champion who ended a
19-year drought at this race last year, said: ``If I just could
have got to him on the corner, I might have got under him, but I
just couldn't get him. As we came up there and got to racing the
last 10 laps, it was pretty exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, who overcame an ignition problem early in the race,
blamed Skinner for not helping him in the draft, a move that may
have enabled both drivers to pass Gordon in the closing laps.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, 27, tied Richard Petty's modern Nascar record of 13
victories last season, when he won his third Winston Cup
championship in four years. Although 33 races remain this season,
Sunday's victory, which paid Gordon the largest single purse in
auto racing ($2,172,446), has the DuPont team rolling toward a
third straight series title and a fourth over all. Gordon's
winnings included the $1 million Winston No Bull 5 bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace, one of the few Winston Cup champions never to
have won the Daytona 500, was leading the race on Lap 188 when
Gordon, who wound up leading for just 17 of the 200 laps, began his
wild charge. Wallace lost the draft of his teammate Jeremy
Mayfield, who had got edged to the back of the lead pack a few laps
before.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace and Mayfield had made it to the front of the field after
a bold gamble with 25 laps left: they stayed out on the track
during a caution flag when Gordon, Earnhardt and the others stopped
to get four fresh tires. But Wallace, who finished eighth, no
longer had any drafting help from Mayfield and soon became prey
when Gordon, Earnhardt, Skinner, Michael Waltrip and Irwin all form
a freight train behind his Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   In the scramble to pass Wallace, Gordon nearly collided with the
mangled machine of Ricky Rudd, who had been lapped, on Lap 188.
Gordon had to jerk his steering wheel at the last second to prevent
a crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made some moves today I didn't really want to make,'' said
Gordon, who started today's race on the pole. ``I came very close
to letting off the gas. I was way down on the apron and I saw Ricky
Rudd going real slow. I thought to myself, `I hope you see me
coming, Ricky.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Big Wreck, that multicar crash that has become something of
a staple at restrictor-plate races, occurred on Lap 136 when Dale
Jarrett, a two-time Daytona 500 winner, spun into the concrete
wall. The crash took out 12 cars, some of which were possible
contenders. Among the drivers involved were Terry Labonte, Ward
Burton and Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very bad about it,'' said Irwin, Jarrett's teammate,
who may have tapped Jarrett's car from behind and triggered the
crash. ``I don't know if I hit him or not. If I could have made it
not happen, I would have made it not happen.'' Irwin's third-place
finish was his best at Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was the disappointing conclusion to a good week for
Earnhardt, whose 33 victories are more than any other driver. He
won his Gatorade Twin 125 race on Thursday, his 10th straight
victory in the qualifying heats. He also took the checkered flag in
the International Race of Champions on Saturday with a daring,
last-lap pass on Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's race did not go as expected for Joe Gibbs' Pontiacs.
Both of Gibbs' drivers, Bobby Labonte and Tony Stewart, began the
race as favorites, but both were knocked out of contention early
because of electrical problems.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, the runner-up in last year's Daytona 500, pulled onto
pit lane with a loose spark-plug wire on Lap 51 and dropped one lap
behind. He never recovered, struggling with engine trouble for the
rest of the race. It was a disappointing end for the Interstate
Batteries team because Labonte had driven his Pontiac to victory in
a qualifying race on Thursday and started Sunday's race in fourth
position.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte's teammate, Stewart, also in a Pontiac, limped
down pit lane on Lap 116 with engine problems. Stewart, the Indy
Racing League champion in 1997 who left open-wheel racing for
Nascar this season, shocked everyone by qualifying on the outside
of the front row last week.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's race, Earnhardt pulled up alongside Gordon and
bumped him again. This time, the bump was a hardened racer's way of
offering congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was saying this car is going into Daytona USA and
I'm going to put my mark on it before it goes,'' Gordon said. ``I
think we both knew it was a great, exciting race.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 2148EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
