A5211 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX     02-14 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSSES PILING UP FOR MAVERICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ Steve Nash used his hometown as
the backdrop to break out of his shooting slump. But he couldn't
help the Mavericks snap their losing ways.
</P>
<P>
   Nash, who grew up in nearby Victoria, played by far his finest
game as a Maverick, finishing with 18 points and nine assists. But
the Mavericks made an already difficult road trip even more
challenging, losing, 96-92, to the Vancouver Grizzlies before a
crowd of 16,059 yesterday afternoon at General Motors Place.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the hard part of this road trip for the Mavericks, 1-5
after dropping their fourth consecutive game and losing to
Vancouver for just the second time ever.
</P>
<P>
   With the Portland Trail Blazers _ tonight at 9 at the Rose
Garden _ and the Los Angeles Lakers as their next two opponents,
the Mavericks could be looking at some very long faces in the
mirror at the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
   Losing Friday at Denver to start this seven-game, 11-day road
journey, followed by yesterday's dud, did nothing but compound
matters for the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The easy part's over, and we lost,'' center Shawn Bradley said
of the losses to Denver and Vancouver. ``Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going to be a hard road trip anyway. When you dig
yourself in a hole that deep, it becomes a really, really tough
road trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Mack and Shareef Abdur-Rahim stuck the daggers in the
Mavericks yesterday. Mack attempted a team-record 13 3-point field
goals and made eight, also a team record.
</P>
<P>
   Abdur-Rahim added 24 points and three blocks as the Grizzlies
improved to 2-3.
</P>
<P>
   Nash made 7-of-11 field-goal attempts, including 4-of-5 from
3-point range. He was aided by Samaki Walker (14 points, 7-of-9
shooting, seven rebounds) and Bradley, who had 10 points, 10
rebounds and four blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Finley was held to nine points for the second time this
season, and was only 4-of-13 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a win more than anything,'' Mavericks coach Don Nelson
said. ``I thought we played well enough to win and followed our
game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 3-ball beat us tonight, and in some regards that's what we
were giving up, although we wanted to cover Mack better than we
did. We left him open too much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks were down 86-75 with 8:48 left after Bryant Reeves
hit a 17-foot jumper. But Nash drilled a pair of 3-point field
goals, including one from the left corner that left the Mavericks
trailing only 94-92 with 26.7 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   However, 22 seconds ticked off the clock while the Mavericks
were waiting for Doug West (no free-throw attempts for the season
coming into the game) or Tony Massenburg (13-of-17 on free-throw
attempts coming in) to handle the ball. West eventually got the
ball, was fouled with 4.3 seconds left and buried both free throws
to ice the game.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he wasn't discouraged by what happened on the court
_ other than the final score.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to get a win,'' he said. ``But we're doing the best
we can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
