<HEADER>
A5212 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-DAYTONA500-TEX     02-14 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA500-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON WINS DAYTONA DUEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ When Jeff Gordon won his first Daytona 500
in 1997, he had it relatively easy. Gordon only had to blow past
two-time Daytona 500 champion Bill Elliott and then hold off
Hendrick Motorsports teammates Terry Labonte and Ricky Craven to
win NASCAR's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   To win his second Daytona 500 yesterday, Gordon had to
out-hustle Dale Earnhardt _ the defending race champion, master of
the draft and winningest driver at the Daytona International
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Makes for one memorable Sunday afternoon drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when I got here in '93 and '94, Earnhardt is the
man _ and still is as far as Daytona is concerned,'' Gordon said
after nosing out Earnhardt by 0.128 seconds in the Winston Cup
season-opener. ``Especially at Daytona, in restrictor-plate racing,
Dale is so good. When you have that person in your mirror, he's
definitely got you worried.''
</P>
<P>
   After wresting the lead from Rusty Wallace with a brassy
three-wide pass also involving a charged-up Mike Skinner on lap
190, Gordon and ``The Intimidator'' hooked up for 10 riveting laps
around the 2.5-mile trioval. Still fresh in Gordon's mind was
Earnhardt's 33rd and most recent career victory here Friday.
Earnhardt won the opening round of the International Race of
Champions when he put a classic slingshot pass on Mark Martin along
the bottom of the trioval exiting Turn 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was seeing it in my mirror,'' said Gordon, the three-time
and reigning series champion who scored his 43rd career Cup
victory. ``I watched it the other day. He's the master at that. I
saw it coming and tried to do everything I could to block it.
Luckily, I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, who made his IROC move while working the draft with
Bobby Labonte, found himself out of helpers and out of horsepower
against Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying all I could to get to the 24,'' said Earnhardt,
referring to Gordon's DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevrolet Monte
Carlo. ``His car was stronger from the center of the corner off
than I was. I just never could get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, who won a record 10th consecutive Twin 125-mile
qualifying race Thursday, never led a lap yesterday in the No. 3 GM
Goodwrench Service Plus Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we came up there and got to racing in the last 10 laps, it
was pretty exciting,'' said Earnhardt, who had fallen to 20th on
lap 66 because of an ignition-box problem. ``They were bumping and
slamming and bumping and slamming. Anyone who could survive that
last five or 10 laps, it was pretty awesome just to come home and
finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace had the day's dominant car, leading the race three times
for a race-high 104 laps in the No. 2 Miller Lite Ford Taurus. But
a questionable pit-strategy call during the race's fourth and final
caution period and Gordon's bold passing move left Wallace 0-for-17
in the Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon and Earnhardt were among the lead-pack drivers who opted
to pit for four fresh Goodyear tires and fuel after Bobby
Hamilton's spin down the backstretch brought out the caution on lap
175. Wallace and Penske-Kranefuss Racing teammate Jeremy Mayfield,
who were running 1-3 before the caution, stayed out on the track
and wound up 1-2 after Earnhardt pitted.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Pemberton, Wallace's crew chief, opted to set up track
position for the teammates, who had only 36 laps on their tires and
were marginal on fuel mileage.
</P>
<P>
   When the race went green on lap 179, Wallace and Mayfield
remained out front through lap 185, when Earnhardt and Gordon
passed Mayfield down the backstretch and moved into second and
third. With help from Skinner, Gordon moved into second on lap 188
and dropped Earnhardt to fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon then set up the pass of the day through the trioval as it
heads into Turn 1. He dived below race-leader Wallace onto the
apron, only to see the lapped and slow-moving car of Ricky Rudd
looming in his path.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping he would see me,'' said Gordon, who led three
times for 17 laps. ``It felt like I was going 1000 miles an hour,
and I was getting ready to check-up \Rlift off the gas\S. Just as I
got to him, he moved a little bit. And my next thought was, how in
the heck do I move Rusty up so I can get off the apron? It opened
up the last few hundred feet. I got up there, but I didn't make the
pass. Dale helped me get past those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   As Gordon, Wallace and Skinner flew in formation down the
backstretch, Earnhardt chose to go with Gordon over best buddy
Wallace and teammate Skinner exiting Turn 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a tough choice there,'' Gordon, 27, said of Earnhardt.
``I thought he would have gone with the other two long before he
would have gone with me. Maybe he wanted to race me to the finish.
I'm glad he went with me, and I'm glad I was able to race him all
the way to the finish.''  &LR; tagtop:John Sturbin, (817) 390-7408
 &LR; tagbottom:sturb &LR; star-telegram.com /
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 2152EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
