<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5213 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-PUCK-FEDEROV-NYT &LR;      02-14 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PUCK-FEDEROV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDOROV TELLS COACHES TIME IS OF THE ESSENCE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Backstage at Madison Square Garden on Sunday, there
was a meeting of the stars. Sergei Fedorov, the Detroit Red Wings
center, was chatting with running back Ricky Williams, the Heisman
Trophy winner from Texas, who will probably be one of the top picks
in the National Football League draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing watching you guys skate,'' Williams said to
Fedorov.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like football,'' Fedorov said to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   He also seems to like hockey again. Two weeks ago, Fedorov was
not happy. He was being criticized by fans and his coaching staff,
and he was a puzzle to his teammates. Fedorov said the problem with
his production was ice time. If he were given more time, Fedorov
said, he would play the way he did when he won the Hart trophy as
most valuable player five seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Scotty Bowman, who works in mysterious ways, began to give
Fedorov more ice time. Sunday, in a 4-2 victory over the Rangers,
Fedorov played 24 minutes 10 seconds and scored the first goal of
the game and assisted on the last one. His ice time was second
among Detroit forwards to Steve Yzerman, who played 25:11.
</P>
<P>
   In the last four games, all Detroit victories, Fedorov has three
goals and four assists. In Sunday's game, he also won 10 of 16
face-offs, delivered four hits and blocked three shots.
</P>
<P>
   So what did he say to persuade Bowman to use him more?
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't really speak about it,'' Fedorov said. ``I tried to
steer the conversation with him into the ice time. I didn't get a
clear answer. He told me I tried to do too much. I said: `Well,
that's my nature. I used to play a lot. And I'd like to do it
again.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But who knows? Maybe he thought differently. Lately, he's
counted on me a lot more, and I've tried to fulfill his
expectations and make an attempt to bring everybody to the next
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Fedorov complained, he was averaging about 17 minutes.
Now, his time is up to 22 to 25 minutes. Fedorov said this was the
first time he had ever made such public demands and that he hoped
his teammates understood. ``I have a spark in me that gets
everybody going,'' Fedorov said.
</P>
<P>
   Fedorov is in the second season of a six-year contract which
will pay him $38 million. His Detroit critics say he plays
inconsistently during the regular season but concede that he peaks
in the playoffs. Last spring, he led Detroit with 10 goals in the
post-season as the Wings won their second consecutive Stanley Cup.
In 56 games this season, Fedorov has 15 goals and 24 assists.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Fedorov's demand, Bowman replied: ``Not
demands. No, he didn't make any demands. It's a long season.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Lewis, one of Bowman's assistants, said Fedorov's demand
was a ``challenge both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis added: ``When a player asks for more ice time and he gets
it, he has to respond and that's what he did. He puts a lot of
pressure on himself. That's what you want as a coaching staff:
players to put pressure on themselves to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman, the captain and veteran center, has moved to Fedorov's
left wing. He had a goal and two assists yesterday and shrugged off
questions about Fedorov's demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody makes a big deal out of it,'' Yzerman said. ``All he
said is he wanted more ice time. Everybody wants more ice time.
It's not that big a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a quiet guy. He doesn't say much. He has played more
lately. We've gone more with three lines. He's gotten more ice
time, and he has the responsibility to play well. And I think he's
played very well since then.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-14-99 2153EST &QL; 
