<HEADER>
A5218 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-PENSKETEAM-TEX     02-14 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PENSKETEAM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALLACE, MAYFIELD DEFEND STRATEGY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Penske-Kranefuss teammates Rusty Wallace
and Jeremy Mayfield swear they lost the Daytona 500 to Jeff Gordon
on the racetrack yesterday, not in the pits.
</P>
<P>
   At least that was the politically correct corporate answer in
the wake of Gordon's race-winning pass of Wallace _ made on four
fresh tires _ in the NASCAR Winston Cup season-opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the tires had anything to do with it,'' said
Wallace, who surrendered the lead to Gordon on lap 190 after a
three-wide drag race that also included Mike Skinner. ``People keep
talking about that, but I thought it was the right move that we
did. I back my crew chief \RRobin Pemberton\S and all the guys for
that call.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace arguably was wheeling the day's dominant car, having led
three times for a race-high 104 laps in the No. 2 Miller Lite Ford
Taurus. Wallace and Mayfield were running 1-3 when Bobby Hamilton's
spin down the Daytona International Speedway backstretch brought
out the race's fourth and final caution on lap 175.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon and Earnhardt were among the lead pack of 14 drivers who
pitted for either two or four fresh tires and fuel. Pemberton and
Paul Andrews, Mayfield's crew chief, opted to set up track position
for the teammates, who had only 36 laps on their tires and were
marginal on fuel mileage.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace and Mayfield were positioned 1-2 after Earnhardt pitted.
When the race went green on lap 179, Wallace and Mayfield remained
out front through lap 185, when Earnhardt and Gordon passed
Mayfield down the backstretch and moved into second and third. With
help from Skinner, Gordon moved into second on lap 188 and dropped
Earnhardt to fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon then set up the pass of the day through the trioval as it
heads into Turn 1. He dived below race-leader Wallace onto the
apron, avoided the slow moving car of Ricky Rudd and raced
alongside Wallace and Skinner down the backstretch and through
turns 3 and 4. Gordon took the lead for good with drafting help
from Earnhardt through the trioval.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who finished fifth in this race last year, slid back to
an eighth-place result. Mayfield, third here last February, was
relegated to a 20th-place finish after he cut a right front tire on
lap 192 while running seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Track position is everything in these restrictor-plate
races,'' said Mayfield, driver of the No. 12 Mobil 1 Ford. ``The
tires hadn't shown any wear or problems, ours or Rusty's or anybody
else's we knew about. New or old tires, that thing was cut
regardless. We were a lot more worried about fuel than tires.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, meanwhile, found a new way to lose the Daytona 500. The
1989 Cup champion now is 0-for-17 in NASCAR's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels horrible to lose the Daytona 500 like that after I
thought I had the best car and had a chance to win the thing,''
said Wallace, who allowed that fresh tires might have helped his
car hold onto the bottom of the track a bit better.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the only thing that lost me the race was he \RGordon\S got
a fender underneath me, and I went down to block him off,'' Wallace
said. ``We were gonna wreck like crazy going into \RTurn\S 1 if one
of us didn't give.'' /
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
