<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR SHORT ON BIG-NAME TARGETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Oscar De La Hoya established tremendous momentum
with his courageous victory over Ike Quartey here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   And the plan is to build on it.
</P>
<P>
   He'll face capable but limited Oba Carr on May 22 in Las Vegas
and then, ideally, come back with another major fight in September.
</P>
<P>
   One problem, though: There might not be a major opponent for him
to fight.
</P>
<P>
   The public wants to see De La Hoya-Felix Trinidad in what might
be the most compelling and lucrative fight outside the heavyweight
division.
</P>
<P>
   It's not going to happen, at least not this year.
</P>
<P>
   Those close to the negotiations say that rival promoters Bob
Arum (De La Hoya) and Don King (Trinidad) cannot even begin to come
to terms. Arum admitted as much shortly before the Quartey fight.
</P>
<P>
   So who does that leave for September?
</P>
<P>
   Possibly Pernell Whitaker, who fights Trinidad on Saturday in
New York. The catch is that Whitaker is going to have to beat one
of the most feared fighters in the world or at the very least make
a good showing.
</P>
<P>
   At 35 and after a long layoff, is that asking too much of
Whitaker?
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya's camp certainly hopes not.
</P>
<P>
   Although he once said no one would want to see a rematch of the
boring 1997 De La Hoya-Whitaker fight, won by De La Hoya, Arum now
is praying Sweet Pea somehow finds a way to win for lack of another
compelling opponent.
</P>
<P>
   One realistic possibility is Javier Castillejo, the Spanish
fighter who took Keith Mullings' WBC super welterweight title on
Jan. 29. That's an indication of how desperate Arum and Co. are.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that matchup would have going for it is Mexico
vs. Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican fans would love to see one of theirs _ even an American
version _ pulverize a fighter from the mother country. The fight
moniker ``The Second Revolution'' is already being bandied about.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if that's who he fights and it turns out to be a
pay-per-view broadcast, the buy rate could be dismal.
</P>
<P>
   One solution would be to take a chance on one of the 1996
Olympians: junior middleweights Fernando Vargas or David Reid,
assuming one would take the fight. However, don't expect it to
happen. De La Hoya won't fight a junior middleweight of that
caliber until he grows into the division. Either or both of those
fights won't happen for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's this intriguing prospect: Rumor is that highly
regarded IBF lightweight champion Shane Mosley is being considered
for either September at a site to be determined or December at the
new Staples Center downtown.
</P>
<P>
   It makes the mouth water just thinking about it: two of the
top-five pound-for-pound fighters in the world, both from the L.A.
area, duking it out in their hometown. Undoubtedly it would be a
huge event.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact Mosley is desperate for a compelling, big-time
fight raises the chances of it happening.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it's just too hard to imagine a fighter, even
a fighter of Mosley's ability, moving up two weight classes to take
on a talent like De La Hoya. Maybe sometime in the future. Not now.
</P>
<P>
   One more possibility: Quartey again.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya probably wants nothing to do with him after
Saturday's war. When asked about a possible rematch, he at first
responded ``I don't think so'' but later said ``I don't know.''
Certainly, it's not something he wants to jump into right away even
though an immediate rematch would generate considerable interest
and money.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Whitaker, if he gives a credible performance, or
Castillejo.
</P>
<P>
   Not all that exciting, is it?
</P>
<P>
   Fight fans should watch HBO's replay of Saturday's fight before
the Whitaker-Trinidad bout. It might be a long time before De La
Hoya's fans experience that kind of exhilaration again.
</P>
<P>
   Questionable tactics: No one is going to question De La Hoya's
courage after his inspiring performance on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   However, it wasn't a work of art.
</P>
<P>
   The champion didn't do the things that could've made it a much
easier fight: jab and move. He connected on only (begin
ital)eight(end ital) jabs per round, according to computer
statistics, and fought flat-footed.
</P>
<P>
   And what made it worse, he wasn't even particularly aggressive
until the final three rounds. He stood around and waited for
something to happen instead of (begin ital)making(end ital) it
happen much of the fight.
</P>
<P>
   He attributed the lack of jabs and movement to a new proclivity
of his: The desire to beat his opponent at his own game. He did it
against Julio Cesar Chavez in his last fight and he did it again
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of aggressiveness was more difficult to explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was giving him too much respect,'' he said. ``He did
hit hard. I respected that. But I gave him (begin ital)too(end
ital) much respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``... I thought he was going to put on more pressure. That was
our game plan. This guy has good boxing skills and he switched
things around on us.''
</P>
<P>
   One knowledgeable observer put it this way: De La Hoya fought a
stupid fight for eight rounds and smart one for four _ the last
four.
</P>
<P>
   He's going to have to fight 12 smart rounds consistently if he's
going to realize his potential.
</P>
<P>
   Twelfth round: No one who saw it will ever forget the 12th round
of Saturday's fight. It turned a good fight into a great one.
</P>
<P>
   It started with De La Hoya's brilliant left hook that put
Quartey down and climaxed with a non-stop, hair-raising exchange of
punches in the corner that lasted a good 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya landed a reported 41 punches that round (206 in the
fight), an astonishing (begin ital)17(end ital) in the half-minute
of mayhem. At least 10 were solid blows that Quartey somehow
absorbed without going down.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Mitch Halpern seemed poised to stop the fight at that
moment but didn't because Quartey was throwing back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Oscar was going to kill him,'' Clancy said. ``He hit
Ike with left hooks I don't think anyone I know could take and
throw punches back.''
</P>
<P>
   Said De La Hoya: ``I'm surprised he took the punishment. I
thought I had him out. I give him all the credit in the world. He
took some good punches.''
</P>
<P>
   The scoring: Judge Larry O'Connell of England scored it 115-114
for Quartey, judge John Keane of England 116-113 for De La Hoya and
judge Ken Morita of Japan 116-112 for De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News had it 116-113 for De La Hoya. In an informal
survey, the vast majority of boxing writers had De La Hoya winning
a close fight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
