<DOCNO> NYT19990214.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5386 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-SHERIFF-2ndTake-L     02-14 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-SHERIFF-2ndTake-LADN </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: from University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   His desire to enter law enforcement was born from a wish to make
his community safer. He knew he wanted to be sheriff when he
realized he could be more effective than his bosses.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this stage of my life, I have fewer years to live than
before. I'm tired of waiting for solutions to matters like the gang
problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In just seven weeks, Baca has already completed more than 70
inspections and identified problems. Stations need new fax machines
and printers. Others need software upgrades or computer training.
And others need more tools to fight the gang problem.
</P>
<P>
   Many of his meetings with commanders and deputies take place in
restaurants and coffeehouses. So much so that he hopes the
department can afford to buy him a sport-utility vehicle that will
double as an office, complete with fax, phone and computer
connections.
</P>
<P>
   It makes days hard on Sgt. Pat Maxwell, Baca's driver, who
applauds the sheriff's energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he works 16-hour days, so do I,'' Maxwell said. ``But I
can tell you what he's doing has made morale really jump around
here.''
</P>
<P>
   During the two to three hours a day he's in his office, it's all
about business. He keeps his phone conversations short because,
``if they can't get to the point in 15 minutes, it's personal and
wastes time,'' he said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; During Block's reign, the sheriff's headquarters meeting room
contained a series of portraits of former chiefs and high-ranking
department officials.
</P>
<P>
   Baca had them moved to a hallway.
</P>
<P>
   In their place is a series of notes, scrawled in big block
letters, that list departmental issues. The notes will soon be
replaced with wall-mounted easels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those pictures had nothing to do with our mission, and there
was no point for them being here. I want this room to be entirely
about our business, and that's what it now is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Friday, the sheriff met with 41 city managers and
county officials to discuss law enforcement and the county's risk
of lawsuits. The meeting was groundbreaking in that it was the
first time the sheriff, county counsel and the county
administrative officer had met together with this group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sheriff has always been involved, but for years the county
counsel would not meet in this kind of forum,'' said County
Administrative Officer David Janssen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think part of the reason this finally happened is because
Baca has great enthusiasm about his challenges and is thoughtful
about issues. And he's very open about what he's doing, like the
fact he's asking the county for a $100 million budget
enhancement.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; By 2 p.m., Baca heads for a live spot on a popular cable
television talk show with some of the department's harshest
critics.
</P>
<P>
   He's still wearing his black suit. His embroidered shirt cuffs
read ``LDB.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have worn my uniform for this, darn it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Century Communications studio, Baca meets Connie Rice,
among other guests.
</P>
<P>
   Walking out of the makeup room, Baca reaches the set, where he's
hit with questions about everything from his use-of-force policy to
police chases to problems in county jails.
</P>
<P>
   Rice quizzes him about what he'll do to understand and repair
his scandal-plagued jails.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I have taken on `Mission: Impossible' with the jail
system,'' he said, responding to Rice's question. ``But I'm going
to be in the jails walking the line with the guards, and changes
will be made.''
</P>
<P>
   He walks out of the studio and meets up with Deputy Bill Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``So how did I do?'' Baca asked in a rare moment of uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``You did great,'' a grinning Martin replied, patting his boss
on the shoulder. ``Man, you did great.''
</P>
<P>
   Century Communications General Manager William Rosendahl, who
hosts the company's popular ``Week In Review,'' said this was not
Baca's first appearance on the show: He would often show up at
round-tables when Block couldn't make it.
</P>
<P>
   Rosendahl is impressed by his ability to ``let go of the
negativity'' stirred up during the campaign, and his efforts to
open communication with the Board of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he learned through the political process what he was
made of,'' Rosendahl said.
</P>
<P>
   Baca said he surely knows what he's made of. So much so that he
knows when it will be time to retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll quit when I'm no longer able to meet needs assessments.
When my vision is no longer in focus. When I slow down.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will be the time.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
