<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-SHERIFF-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES COUNTY'S NEW SHERIFF EMBARKS ON SWEEPING CAMPAIGN OF
CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Los Angeles County's new sheriff, Lee Baca,
marched toward his new office and gestured at the double doors.
They were propped open.
</P>
<P>
   He greeted his secretary with a wave and entered the inner
office, which his predecessor Sherman Block occupied for 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   That door was open, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Block was concerned about security in here, so he kept these
closed. I ordered them open at all times,'' Baca said, cracking a
smile that broke just for a moment his all-business, all-the-time
demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not as concerned,'' he said. ``Someone might try to come
and shoot me, but I'll be wearing a uniform and a gun -- and I'll
probably shoot them first.''
</P>
<P>
   Pure Baca.
</P>
<P>
   In eight weeks since Baca took the office he won from Block in a
hard-fought election, he has moved quickly to rebuild the
department in his image. The first elected sheriff since 1914, Baca
already is knee-deep in dramatic management changes that include
pruning the top command structure and redistributing the $1.4
billion budget.
</P>
<P>
   He is pushing for a $100 million budget increase from the Board
of Supervisors to hire more deputies and purchase equipment.
</P>
<P>
   He wants badly an inspector general position to look into the
recent rash of deaths among inmates and suspects in deputies'
custody.
</P>
<P>
   He is creating a Deputy Leadership Institute, which would train
everyone in the department to conduct themselves fairly and
responsibly, including dealing with racism, sexism and homophobia.
Ordering that his office doors remain open was a first, easy and
profoundly symbolic fix, he said.
</P>
<P>
   To Baca, the message is priceless: He's no Sherman Block.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Block there was a feeling that managers were unconnected
to line people and that they couldn't trust each other,'' Baca
said. ``That's why I'm flattening the bureaucracy and creating
leadership training for deputies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm also trying to wipe out the feeling that being a deputy
sheriff is just a societal role. The sheriff and his deputies are
one and the same -- all leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Those messages have quickly filtered down to deputies like
Michael Irving, who worked under Block for most of his 10 years as
a deputy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made a huge effort to let everyone know he's here for the
deputies,'' Irving said. ``With his doors open, there's an open
line of communication; and he's frequently in uniform so it brings
him to our level. You didn't have that with Block. Morale has very
much been boosted.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a tough challenge, however. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; During the campaign, Block won endorsements from the
Association for Los Angeles Deputy Sheriffs, representing deputies
and District Attorney's Office investigators, and the Los Angeles
County Professional Police Officers Association, which represents
sergeants, lieutenants and other sworn and nonsworn personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Block also won unanimous support from the Board of Supervisors,
who believed his experience, longevity and history of
accomplishment outweighed the need for new blood.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the sheriff died, his campaign continued and he won
support from heavyweights like Supervisor Mike Antonovich.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Baca has won high marks from Antonovich.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were at a community meeting last week together, and
things are off to a good start,'' said Lori Howard, Antonovich's
assistant chief deputy. ``He's excited that Sheriff Baca wants to
bring a substation to Altadena, and he loves the idea to add 1,000
deputies to the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Antonovich will vote in support of Baca's $100 million
request,'' Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Baca's opponents in the campaign, Bill Baker, said he
remains skeptical about Baca's ability to follow through on
promises, an issue he raised during the race. He predicted during
the campaign that Baca's policies would be a ``perpetuation of
Block's policies with no meaningful reform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been two months in office and it's too early to criticize
him, but he's done a couple of things that are questionable to
me,'' Baker said. ``He has been slamming his shoe on the desk with
the Board of Supervisors for that increased funding, and I think
he's making promises to the rank-and-file that he can't keep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked Lee, and I don't think he's a bad person. I
think he's a little naive.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles attorney Connie Rice, a former director of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People who
started her own law firm, hopes Baca can take on ``Mission:
Impossible'' in fixing the county jail system, which has been
plagued by allegations of fatal inmate beatings, mistreatment of
mentally ill prisoners and overdetention in recent years. Based on
her experiences with Baca, she said she has much hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's highly intelligent, sensible and solves problems. He's
not ideological,'' Rice said. ``He's the kind of leader that steps
into other people's shoes. He understands the challenge of law
enforcement in a complicated society, and he does not wage war on
those he feels are out to get him.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; For the first time in many years, the sheriff is a sheriff in
motion.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Block, Baca spends most of his 16-hour days on the road,
visiting scores of the department's stations and jail facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not lost in the bureaucracy. I'm the most visible sheriff
to people doing the job,'' Baca said. ``I had one deputy tell me he
only saw Sherman Block once, and he's seen me four times in seven
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Hired as a sheriff's deputy to patrol East Los Angeles in 1965,
the 56-year-old Baca rose through the ranks and in 1981 was
appointed captain by then-Sheriff Peter Pitchess. A short time
later he was elevated to the rank of commander, and in 1992 Block
promoted him to chief. A year later, he earned a doctorate in
public administration from University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
