<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5390 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     02-14 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT A MOMENT TOO SOON, BASEBALL IS ALMOST HERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In one of my favorite movies, ``Beautiful
Girls'' (circa 1996), the character played by Uma Thurman, Andera,
is talking to Willie, played with rapt fascination by Timothy
Hutton.
</P>
<P>
   As if to show that she is the coolest, foxiest, hippest female
that Willie and his New England n'er-do-wells have ever set eyes
upon, Thurman impresses Hutton by knowing exactly how many days are
left before pitchers and catchers have to report to spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   Cool.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't get the girl. But I was impressed.
</P>
<P>
   It goes to show, too, that the phrase `` `x' days until pitchers
and catchers have to report,'' has become a staple of the American
winter lexicon. And well it should.
</P>
<P>
   Seasons change. The groundhog does his thing. The President's
Day linen sales come and go.
</P>
<P>
   But if you really want to set your watches, find the date that
pitchers and catchers have to report.
</P>
<P>
   Three days, guys. Three days.
</P>
<P>
   Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Where do we begin to muse about what the next eight months of
baseball have in store?
</P>
<P>
   Do the Rangers have what it takes to be an annual playoff
fixture? Can Mark McGwire juice up a little more and go for 71?
</P>
<P>
   The answers start coming Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there we were. In the jungle just outside Chu Lai. We
had a platoon of VC firing at us from the village just one click up
the road. I was calling in air strikes, when ...
</P>
<P>
   Oops. Sorry. I guess I was having a Tim Johnson Vietnam
flashback.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't that strange? The two tallest tales to be explored and
flogged to death this spring are certain to be Toronto manager
Johnson's bogus tour of Vietnam duty and Yankee pitcher Orlando
Hernandez's questioned dash for freedom through shark-infested
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Strange, because a year ago, if someone had suggested that one
major-leaguer would hit 70 home runs and another 66, that would
have sounded like a tall tale, too.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig called it baseball's ``greatest year,''
and it's hard to argue. An average of 29,000 per game, third
highest in baseball history, walked through the turnstiles. Only a
clunker of a World Series _ the Yankees' sweep of the San Diego
Padres _ soiled baseball's party.
</P>
<P>
   What could the sport possibly do for an encore?
</P>
<P>
   Well, there's Albert Belle. Universally loved, like a bad virus,
Belle takes his act into a true hitter's park in Baltimore. It
bears noting that after the All-Star break last year, McGwire hit
33 home runs; Belle hit 31.
</P>
<P>
   Belle's dual assault _ on McGwire's record and on new teammate
Will Clark's thin patience _ will be worth following, as will all
the Orioles. Baltimore was the only team in baseball last year with
a payroll over $48 million that finished below .500.
</P>
<P>
   So what did owner Peter Angelos do? He spent $120 million on
free agents.
</P>
<P>
   In baseball, alas, that was the unspoken charm of the
McGwire-Sammy Sosa home run chase, that the only people who were
dwelling on the money were the fans hawking the home-run balls.
Fans clearly are weary of hearing that Kevin Brown, he of few
smiles, has signed a contract that calls for $100 million and more
perks than Juan Antonio Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   Don't show me the money. I'm tired of the money.
</P>
<P>
   I'm tired of reading how the Anaheim Angels paid to sign a rag
arm like Tim Belcher, insist Ken Hill will be a solid No. 2, and
still don't know who their everyday catcher will be, yet still
think they have leapfrogged into the favorite's role in the
American League West.
</P>
<P>
   I'm tired of reading about Jerry Colangelo, who spent $119
million in the off-season stocking the Arizona Diamondbacks with
free agents. His lineup figures to include overhyped, overpaid
Steve Finley, Bernard Gilkey, Luis Gonzalez and Jay Bell.
Regardless of how much pitching Colangelo paid for, this is still
Operation Desert Mirage.
</P>
<P>
   I'm also tired of reading about Garth Brooks. If Uma Thurman
tries out for the Padres, though, call me.
</P>
<P>
   I'm tired of reading about the Expos' payroll. I'm tired of
reading about the Dodgers spending $90 million. I'm tired of
reading the phrases ``big market'' and ``small market.''
</P>
<P>
   All I want to read this week is how the pitchers and catchers
are doing. They report this week, you know, guys.
</P>
<P>
   Cool.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
