<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 2/14/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. -- Feb. 14, 1999 -- FBN-UTLEY-2, 2-14
-- The former starting right guard for the Detroit Lions, Mike
Utley, 33, who was instantly paralyzed when he fell on his head
during a game against the Los Angeles Rams on Nov. 17, 1991, with
members of his foundation, which he created after suffering his
career ending injury. Utley who once opened huge holes for Barry
Sanders, now tries to open doors for victims of spinal-cord
injuries who feel shut out from life. (Jeff Topping/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. -- Feb. 14, 1999 -- FBN-UTLEY-1, 2-14
-- Mike Utley, 33, the former Detroit Lion who was instantly
paralyzed when he fell on his head during a game against the Los
Angeles Rams on Nov. 17, 1991, with girlfriend Dani Andersen, a
paramedic, whom he met at the gym where he took his first steps
last December. ``Yeah, I've had my share of adversity,'' he says.
``But that won't stop me.'' Though he is medically defined as a
quadriplegic, he has extensive use of his arms. He drives cars and
boats, scuba-dives, kayaks and even, believe it or not, sky-dives.
(Jeff Topping/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Feb. 14, 1999 -- GANGS REUNION, 2-14 --
Photographer Bruce Davidson, left, and Robert ``Bengie'' Powers,
56, a onetime street gang member, in center photo in 1959, who was
a drug dealer and heroin addict, at a reunion of Brooklyn youth
gang members and Davidson, the photographer that documented their
travels some 40 years ago. The reunion took place at the
International Center of Photography on Fifth Avenue at 94th Street.
(Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) KIEV, Ukraine -- Feb. 14, 1999 -- UKRAINE-CORRUPT, 2-14
-- Pavlo Lazarenko, the former Ukrainian prime minister, now a
member of Parliament, party leader and presidential candidate,
stands accused of laundering millions through Swiss bank accounts.
Lazarenko calls the charges against him ``political harassment.''
``I can absolutely state that I have not violated any law of
Switzerland,'' he says. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MANASSAS, Va. -- Feb 14, 1999 -- SUNKSUB-FOUND, 2-14 --
Paul Tidwell, a maritime researcher, with articles recovered from a
Japanese submarine's wreckage in the mid-Atlantic, some 1,200 miles
west of the Cape Verde Islands. The I-52, a Japanese submarine, was
carrying two tons of gold and other material to Hitler when
American forces torpedoed her in the Atlantic. For decades, the
I-52 was presumed lost forever. Tidwell is now bound for Japan and
plans to return the shoes to relatives of the dead crewmen. (Marty
Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Feb. 14, 1999 -- MISANTHROPE-THEATER-REVIEW,
2-14 -- Uma Thurman, left, as Jennifer, the intelligent, luminous
young movie star, cast against the finely seasoned English actor
Roger Rees as Alceste, in the Classic Stage Company's production of
Martin Crimp's contemporary adaptation of Moliere's
``Misanthrope.'' In transporting Moliere's study of 17th-century
hypocrites and the brooding Alceste's one-man war against them into
the London theater world of today, the work is intent on
outsavaging its dark satiric source. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CANTRALL, Ill. -- Feb. 14, 1999 -- GLOBAL-ECON-I-2, 2-14
-- An Illinois couple organizing their retirement, Mary Jo and
George Paoni are conservative about investing. But Mrs. Paoni, who
has never traveled outside the United States, is in fact invested
in Asia and all over the world, although she does not know it. Mrs.
Paoni's pension fund and stock holdings have made her and her
husband nominal investors in places like Indonesia and Brazil. Such
risks were much rarer before third world nations became ``emerging
market countries.'' (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Feb. 14, 1999 -- GLOBAL-ECON-I-1, 2-14 -- An
Indonesian rickshaw driver named Salamet, 27, has a hard life made
more so by the Asian crisis. Too many competitors -- a byproduct of
Western investment -- has meant a drop in fares and trouble with
rickshaw and other expenses. The crisis which has jeopardized his
son's schooling, is one that has recast thousands of lives and will
haunt a generation in the East just as the Great Depression shaped
a generation in the West. (Stuart Isett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SEATTLE -- Feb. 14, 1999 -- INTERNET-POLITICS, 2-14 -- In
Seattle, a worker strings new cable for a Tele-Communications Inc.
system. A fight over access to the cable lines is taking place amid
a lobbying blitzkrieg, pitting AT&AMP;T and the huge cable company it
is planning to acquire, Tele-Communications Inc., known as TCI,
against local phone companies and an array of Internet competitors,
including America Online and dozens of smaller Internet service
providers. (Larry Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LONDON -- Feb. 14, 1999 -- ROYAL-OPERA-2, 2-14 --
Renovations taking place at the Royal Opera House in Covent Garden.
Until recently the issue has not been how the new opera house will
look, after a $360 million metamorphosis, but whether the Royal
Opera and Royal Ballet will ever perform there. For the last three
years the Royal Opera House has been a soap opera with political,
financial and psychological drama all intertwined. (Jonathan
Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LONDON -- Feb. 14, 1999 -- ROYAL-OPERA-1, 2-14 -- Michael
Kaiser, 45, the executive director of the Royal Opera House, which
has been undergoing a $360 million redevelopment. Kaiser, the
former executive director of the American Ballet Theater, has had
the difficult task of sorting out a number of political, financial
and psychological problems within the organization. ``It does help
to come from the outside,'' says Kaiser. ``My experience with
troubled organizations is that when you are in the midst of all the
problems, everyone is focused on the past. (Jonathan Player/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) JERUSALEM -- Feb. 14, 1999 -- ISRAEL-CULTURECLASH-2, 2-14
-- Protesting what they call anti-religious rulings by the Israeli
Supreme Court, some 250,000 Ultra-Orthodox Jews demonstrating at
the top of a hill in Jerusalem Sunday. A few blocks away, the
Supreme Court held business as usual, although it was ringed by
armed troops. At the bottom of the hill, secular Israelis staged a
counter-rally and cheered fiery pro-democracy speakers. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) JERUSALEM -- Feb. 14, 1999 -- ISRAEL-CULTURECLASH-1, 2-14
-- Some 250,000 Ultra-Orthodox Jews demonstrating at the top of a
hill in Jerusalem Sunday protesting what they call anti-religious
rulings by the Israeli Supreme Court. At the bottom of the hill, in
a counter-rally with a decidedly different flavor, about 50,000
academics, lawyers, kibbutzniks, and devoted secularists waved
Israeli flags, sang the national anthem and cheered fiery
pro-democracy speakers. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Feb. 14, 1999 -- OPERA-CONNECTIONS, 2-14 --
Philip Langridge, left, and John Tomlinson in Arnold Schoenberg's
opera ``Moses und Aron,'' now being given its first Metropolitan
Opera performances. Schoenberg, in his writings, left little doubt
about what the stakes were in this drama. For all his stature as a
highly rational modernist, in his views of artistry he was a
religious Romantic, opposed to what he called ``sterile faith in
science.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Feb. 14, 1999 -- SPRING-DANCE-REVIEW, 2-14 --
Fang-Yi Sheu, vivid in her form-perfect dancing as the frontiere
bride in Martha Graham's 1944 ``Appalachian Spring'' at the Joyce
Theater. Graham's dislocations of the body telegraph states of
emotion, not a description of emotion. ``The thing itself'' is what
she called it. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 14, 1999 -- AFTER-MONICA-MEDIA, 2-14
-- Television crews on the Capitol grounds packing up after the
impeachment trial ended Friday. As the impeachment story winds
down, many journalists are concerned about holding on to their
audiences. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SEATTLE -- Feb. 14, 1999 -- SLATE-SUBSCRIPTIONS-MEDIA,
2-14 -- Michael Kinsley, editor of Slate, Microsoft's online
magazine, at his offices in Seattle. Ten months after deciding to
charge readers $19.95 a year, Slate announced in an e-mail notice
to subscribers that it would now be available free on the World
Wide Web. Kinsley says that the decision is not a setback.
``Obviously, you don't like to reverse course. You try one thing,
you try another. It's a stage in the learning process.'' (Therese
Frare/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
