<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-14 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5400 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-USC-LADN     02-14 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC WRAPS UP BANNER WEEKEND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It looks like the raising of USC's 12th national
championship banner at Dedeaux Field is inspiring the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   At least that what coach Mike Gillespie hopes following the
Trojans' second straight win, a dramatic 5-4 decision over visiting
Texas Tech on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Munson's solo home run with two outs in the bottom of the
ninth followed up a 5-3 win on Saturday, when USC's 1998 College
World Series championship team was honored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be (a boost),'' Gillespie said of the hoopla
surrounding Saturday's pregame ceremonies, which included the USC
band and several departed players from last season, when the school
won its first national title since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to get some of those guys back here who are no
longer with us,'' Gillespie said.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked fourth and ninth by Collegiate Baseball and Baseball
America, respectively, USC (3-5) bounced back with two consecutive
wins over a quality opponent after losing five in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have the band here and all the other guys coming back was
exciting for the younger guys on the team,'' said Munson, the
junior All-American catcher who homered twice Sunday _ a three-run
shot in the fifth off preseason All-American Shane Wright and the
game-deciding solo blast in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The No.13 Red Raiders rallied from 4-0 down to tie the Trojans
entering the ninth and reliever Brandon Roberson (1-1) was
dominant, retiring the first five hitters he faced after taking the
mound in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Munson got ahead of Roberson 2-1 in the count, taking a ball
that was questioned by the Texas Tech battery and dugout. Munson
then belted a changeup over the wall in right-center for his fifth
homer of the season and fourth in the three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1-1 pitch was a little down and out and it was much more
of a pitcher's pitch,'' Munson said. ``The next one was down and in
and a much better pitch to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only downer for USC was the no-decision for starting
pitcher Justin Lehr, the senior transfer from UC Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Making just his fifth career start, Lehr took a no-hitter into
the seventh inning. He lost it on a bloop single by Jon Weber, then
yielded a double and Allen Marshall's three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander was charged with the tying run in the eighth
but his line still included nine strikeouts against just two walks
in 72/3 innings. Steve Smyth (1-1) earned the win with 11/3
scoreless innings in relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good. I was able to get ahead in the count and mix my
pitches pretty well. I didn't do that as well the other night,''
said Lehr, referring to the loss he suffered in relief of the
series opener Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lehr batted for himself and went 3 for 4 with a double. Carlos
Casillas also homered for the Trojans. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
